<SLUG> BC-DESMOND-PFEIFFER-FLAP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORK, WRITERS GUILD ISSUES SCUTTLE `PFEIFFER' SCREENING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICK McGREEVY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Facing objections from the UPN television network
and concerns from the Writers Guild, the Los Angeles Human
Relations Commission canceled a screening and public hearing for
the controversial sitcom ``The Secret Diary of Desmond Pfeiffer.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hicks, executive director of the Human Relations Commission,
said what was intended as an informal, civil discussion about the
television show was being seen mistakenly by some as part of an
effort of government censorship.
</P>
<P>
   That backlash caused Hicks to decide to cancel Friday's
screening of the program's pilot episode, which had been scheduled
before a crowd of civil rights activists at the office of the
Writers Guild of America in West Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just became untenable,'' Hicks said. ``For one, we were
facing legal objections to airing a show that UPN had not decided
whether to broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   UPN representatives did not return calls for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The television comedy, set at the time of the Civil War, has
drawn protests from African-American leaders who believe it makes
light of slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned that the program was racially divisive, the Los
Angeles City Council recently asked the Human Relations Commission
to screen the show and make a recommendation about whether it was
appropriate for television.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said the screening was to include the controversial pilot
episode, which originally included a scene of two hooded men who
had been hanged in England. When African-American activists
complained that the scene appeared to depict the lynching of blacks
while other characters joked nearby, the scene was edited out
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
