<HEADER>
A235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-PARKER-2NDTAKE-N     10-17 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PARKER-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: a story.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parker is also remembered as a driven and dedicated editor who
stayed on at Newsweek even after being passed over twice for the
top job. His enthusiasm was particularly apparent on deadline,
colleagues said, when he was known for making last-minute decisions
and savoring every one of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would daunt most people was thrilling to him,'' said Evan
Thomas, an assistant managing editor of Newsweek. ``The later, the
harder, the better. He was never happier than when we were either
at war or on the brink of war.''
</P>
<P>
   As an editor, Parker's strength lay in asking the right
questions. He grew frustrated when his staff did not work as hard
as he did, and he criticized them for ``leaning on their shovels.''
As a hands-on editor, he was understated; the sum total of his
notes on a story often amounted to a simple line: ``Say better
pls.''
</P>
<P>
   Parker also loved to scoop the competition. In September 1995,
for example, after losing out to Time on the right to excerpt the
memoirs of Gen. Colin Powell, Newsweek obtained an advance copy of
the book and raced ahead with a cover story.
</P>
<P>
   His career was marred by two decisions. In 1983, he pushed
Newsweek to publicize the so-called Hitler diaries. After
bargaining unsuccessfully for U.S. publication rights to the
diaries from the West German photo-weekly Stern, Newsweek ran an
11-page cover story despite questions about the documents'
authenticity. Newsweek's coverage of the diaries included the
observation, ``Hitler's diaries _ genuine or not, it almost doesn't
matter in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   When German authorities later declared the diaries a hoax,
Newsweek ran a second cover story suggesting that the magazine had
played a major role in uncovering the fraud. Parker described the
experience as the low point in his career.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Parker was forced to answer for having guarded the
secrecy of Joe Klein, then a Newsweek columnist, who had vehemently
denied being Anonymous, the author of the best-selling novel
``Primary Colors,'' even as Newsweek published Klein's denial and
speculated about other writers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Parker said he did not consider it a conflict that
his magazine published an item at odds with his own personal
knowledge, although in retrospect, he said that perhaps he should
have killed or delayed the item. ``I don't think it's a conflict,''
Parker said in an interview. ``This is not a matter of national
security. This is more a matter of who shot J.R.''
</P>
<P>
   But Parker's job remained secure. In the wake of the Klein
controversy, Parker's superiors at The Washington Post Co., which
owns Newsweek, vouched for his work. Post Co. chairman Donald
Graham said in 1996, ``If magazine editors were all free agents,
without a second's hesitation I would pick Rick and Maynard'' to
lead Newsweek, referring to the magazine's chairman, Richard M.
Smith, and Parker.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's first marriage ended in divorce.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Susan Fraker, an assistant managing
editor at Fortune magazine; a daughter from his first marriage,
Francesca L. Parker of Beaver Dam, Wis.; two sons from his second
marriage, Nicholas Maynard Parker and Hugh Fraker Parker, both of
Manhattan; and his father, C.N. Parker of Bradbury, Calif.
</P>
</TEXT>
