<HEADER>
A2388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKEES-NYT &LR;      10-17 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGEST TASK FOR YANKEES: NEUTRALIZE PADRES' BROWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Manager Joe Torre carried a thick red binder through
the Yankees' clubhouse Friday, holding it against his hip, like
mother and child. The binder, as thick as any Yellow Pages,
contained the Yankees' scouting report of the San Diego Padres,
intelligence to be used in the World Series that begins tonight at
Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   A section of the report addressed the performances of Torre's
hitters against the San Diego pitchers _ such as Kevin Brown, who
will throw against the Yankees' David Wells in Game 1. Torre could
not have been encouraged by numbers that illuminate Brown's
dominance. Bernie Williams, the Yankees' cleanup batter, has just 4
hits in 17 career at-bats against Brown, for a .235 average. Chili
Davis is a career .170 hitter against the San Diego right-hander,
Tino Martinez .118.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees faced Brown when he pitched in the American League
from 1986 to 1995, before he made improvements. The only regular
with a career average over .300 against Brown is third baseman
Scott Brosius at .409.
</P>
<P>
   ``He throws a sinking fastball at about 97 mph,'' Brosius said
drolly. ``That would make him a pretty good pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, coming off a season in which they won 114 games and
had playoff victories against Texas and Cleveland, are strong
favorites in this four-of-seven-game series; their lineup is
deeper, and they have more depth in their pitching rotation and in
their bullpen. If the World Series extends to seven games, four of
those will be played in the Stadium, where the Yankees are 66-20
this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Brown, who is a sturdy 6 feet 4 inches and 200 pounds and is
a CIA-serious competitor, could be the great equalizer; if the
Padres beat the Yankees and prevent Torre's team from assuming its
place in baseball history, Brown will presumably play a major role.
Brown, perhaps baseball's most durable pitcher, could pitch Games
1, 4 and 7, and in spite of their dubious personal records against
him, the Yankees will probably need to neutralize or beat him at
least once to win this series.
</P>
<P>
   Since he left the Baltimore Orioles after the 1995 season, Brown
has learned how to better control his emotions and has added a
four-seam fastball (which sails high in the strike zone) and a
darting, diving forkball to a repertory that already included a
sinking fastball with stunning movement. He went 18-7 with a 2.38
earned run average for the Padres this season and is 2-1 with a
1.44 ERA in the post-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he'd make a difference,'' said Bruce Bochy, the Padres'
manager. ``I didn't know he'd make this big of an impact over our
year. He's made a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre said: ``Pitchers can dominate a game, no question. We know
Kevin Brown is a good pitcher. Roger Clemens is a good pitcher.
Pedro Martinez is a good pitcher. We just go out and try to do our
thing. Hopefully, if he makes mistakes, we can take advantage of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, Brown has sometimes been his own worst enemy, with
a tendency to try too hard and overthrow after he allows one or two
cheap hits or somebody behind him makes an error.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy with stuff like that,'' one AL executive said, ``a
lot of times something seems to happen to keep him from winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown will be facing the major leagues' most potent lineup: the
Yankees averaged six runs per game and, with their experienced,
patient hitters, they will force Brown to throw strikes. Torre made
two adjustments to his starting lineup that seemed to be a reaction
to Brown. Brosius, who has batted eighth or ninth virtually the
entire season, was bumped up to seventh, to a position where he has
a better chance to drive in runs; and Ricky Ledee, a rookie, was
inserted in the ninth spot and will start in left field to give the
Yankees six left-handed hitters. Against Brown this year,
left-handed batters hit 20 percentage points higher than
right-handed batters did.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy said that Andy Ashby would pitch Game 2 and Sterling
Hitchcock Game 3. He did not announce his starters for subsequent
games, leaving the option to use Brown on three days' rest in Game
4. Torre, on the other hand, is committed to four starters _ Wells
in Games 1 and 5, Orlando Hernandez in Games 2 and 6, David Cone in
Games 3 and 7 and Andy Pettitte in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   Torre acknowledged that he essentially shaped the back end of
his rotation around Cone's needs: the right-hander has sometimes
struggled in cold weather, and by starting in Game 3 on Tuesday,
Cone will throw in the warmth of San Diego. Should the Series go to
seven games, however, Cone would pitch on a late October night in
New York, and the weather could become a factor.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez pitched seven shutout innings against Cleveland in
Game 4 of the American League Championship Series _ and for that he
earned a promotion in the World Series. Pettitte pitched poorly in
his only start in the league championship series, and he is now
also coping with his father's recovery from heart surgery. Pettitte
is in Texas, away from the Yankees, and Torre is not sure when the
left-hander will rejoin the team.
</P>
</TEXT>
