<HEADER>
A2390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-MAURO-DEBATE-COX     10-17 1386
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-MAURO-DEBATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mauro, Bush go face-to-face
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Democratic challenger Garry Mauro, down in
dollars and trailing in the polls, charged at a Friday night debate
that Gov. George W. Bush has been a do-nothing leader as far as
most Texas families are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro urged voters to support Bush if they can think of anything
he has done for them.
</P>
<P>
   In the campaign's only debate, Bush fired back by charging that
Mauro's overall plan is a multimillion-dollar budget buster.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the challenging rhetoric, and an exchange about whether
Bush will be around for four more years if he is re-elected, the
hour-long event maintained a civil tone.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro launched his toughest shot in his closing statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years and nine months, that's how long Governor Bush has
been in office,'' Mauro said. ``I'll ask you if you can think of
anything that he has done in three years and nine months that was
relevant in your life or your family's life, you ought to vote for
him. But if you believe as I that we ought to put Texas families
first, look at my plan.''
</P>
<P>
   White House issues came up twice. Earlier in the day, Mauro
challenged Bush to say whether he believes the impeachment process
should continue. And, at the debate, Mauro said it's time for Bush
to announce if he will run for president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, at or near the top of all lists of potential GOP
presidential contenders, said he still doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have been one of those types of politicians that says,
`Well, no, I promise not to run' and then turn around and run. But
that's not the way I am,'' he said, adding, ``I told the people of
Texas when I said that, if that bothers you when you go into the
voting booth then make that part of your consideration. I
understand the consequences of not making up my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Texans deserve a clearer answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respect Governor Bush's indecision, but when you are running
for the second largest state in the union and when we have such a
unique opportunity in history, I really think Governor Bush ought
to speed up his decision-making process,'' said Mauro, decrying the
possibility of having a ``part-time governor'' more interested in
Washington than Texas. ``He is running for a job most Texans think
is a full-time job. And I'd like to see him let us know if he is
going to be a part-time governor or a full-time governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Elliott, a political science professor at East Texas
State University in Commerce, said there was no clear winner in
Friday's debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody hit it over the fence,'' Elliott said. ``There was some
condescension and some impatience (by Bush) part of the way
through, and I don't know if that was calculated or if Mauro's
responses were getting to him. Mauro tried to put Bush on the spot
on whether he was going to run for president, and I think he might
have scored points with a few viewers on that.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the debate will serve as an important test run for a
possible national campaign, Elliott said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he handled himself pretty well,'' he said, adding that
with Bush's substantial lead in the polls, ``He could stub his toe
a time or two and still get out of it without doing himself
substantial harm.''
</P>
<P>
   And on a Friday night when thousands of Texans were in the
stands at high school football games, Elliott wondered how many
people tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a state contender here, so there wasn't probably
more than a dozen of us watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Champagne didn't bother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched it for ten seconds and switched over to Homicide,''
said Champagne, a government professor at the University of Texas
at Dallas. ``I think I came to the conclusion some time ago that
the debate doesn't really matter, that we already know who's going
to win the election.''
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference before the debate, Mauro said Bush owes
voters a clear statement on where he stands on the Clinton
impeachment question.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to end this impeachment process, time to get back to
doing the business of the United States of America,'' said Mauro, a
longtime friend of Clinton who collected about $1 million at recent
fund-raisers in Houston and San Antonio that featured the
president. ``I was as mad at Bill Clinton as anybody because I
worked hard to get him elected. As a friend, there is nothing he
did that I can't forgive. As a lawyer, there is nothing
impeachable.''
</P>
<P>
   Still struggling to find a wedge issue, Mauro insisted Bush, as
a leading Republican, can have an impact on the impeachment process
the Democrat said has become a ``political circus.'' Bush, through
connections with key Republicans in Congress, can help
short-circuit the impeachment process, according to Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   At the debate, Bush indicated he had no intention of doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm willing to give the president his day in court before I
rush to judgment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's most challenging comments came on Mauro's spending plans,
which include a $6,000 pay hike for all teachers, borrowing $2
billion from the public school trust fund to build classrooms and
other proposals. Bush said the pay hike would wind up as an
``unfunded mandate'' that could force local school districts to
increase taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Commissioner Mauro has made $14 billion worth of promises,''
said Bush, noting that legislative budget writers agree with him.
``We've only got $8 billion worth to spend.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro insisted his budget, which includes ending the sales tax
on motor vehicles, does balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the budget process backwards and forwards,'' said
Mauro, who was elected state land commissioner in 1982. ``My budget
balances.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidates also were asked several questions of particular
interest in the El Paso area. El Paso, for years something of a
political outback, has grown in importance this year as Bush has
worked to capture Hispanic votes in unprecedented numbers for a
Republican. A strong showing among Hispanics would be a feather in
his hat if he decides to throw it in the presidential ring in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Mauro differed on what to do about the Tigua Indians'
casino here. Bush believes the tribe's slot machines are illegal.
Mauro disagrees and wants the state to accept the tribe's offer of
a 3 percent cut. The Tiguas have given Mauro $89,000 for his
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Both declined to back a constitutional amendment to legalize
casino gambling on reservations.
</P>
<P>
   They also differed on the proposed low-level nuclear waste dump
at Sierra Blanca, about 90 miles southeast of here. Mauro said he
would block the dump, which is up for licensing next week at the
Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that Gov. Ann Richards, his predecessor, signed the
bill targeting the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I would ask the commissioner is you make a lot
of noise about this issue relative to me. Why weren't you making
noise when Governor Richards had the issue?'' asked Bush. ``Surely
you weren't playing politics with an issue as sensitive as this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said he has long opposed plans to put the the facility in
inappropriate places.
</P>
<P>
   On two driving related questions, Bush and Mauro agreed the
state should lower from 0.10 percent to 0.08 percent the
blood-alcohol level at which driving is illegal. But they differed
on whether the state should adopt a graduated license system in
which young motorists slowly get more driving privileges _ like
driving at night _ as the gain more experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the law ought to stay the way it is, at first blush,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said his pre-teen children oppose the idea. But he
believes anything that could save lives should be considered.
</P>
<P>
   In closing statements, Mauro, who at times clearly was reading
from notes, stumbled and stuttered while outlining his proposal to
cut taxes on auto and truck sales.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who remained smooth, said in English and Spanish that he
appreciated the support he's received from all Texans. ``I look
forward to being your governor again,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers Juan B. Elizondo Jr. and Dave
Harmon contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
