<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: HONORING HIS FATHER'S INSTRUCTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once upon a time, baseball was full of players like
Tony Gwynn. A player spent his career with one team, no jumping
around, no chasing after the money, putting down roots. There was a
covenant: play hard, play well, and chances are you'll have a home
for a while.
</P>
<P>
   For the last 17 seasons, Gwynn has worn the San Diego Padres
uniform. He has kept up his side of the deal: numerous batting
titles, and Gold Gloves. San Diego has nominally kept its end of
the bargain. The Padres have reached the World Series twice in
their 30 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn has been the anchor of a franchise with a zany past. The
Padres were hastily formed for their first season, 1969. Except for
1984, when they reached the World Series, they have experienced a
succession of blunders, screwy deals and chaos. The Yankees have
Gehrig's farewell address, the Padres have Roseanne Barr screeching
the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a history,'' Gwynn said. ``That's what we're
fighting for here. For us, it's more than just trying to win the
World Series. It's trying to establish history.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly an hour Friday, Gwynn held court in the corner of the
visitors' clubhouse at Yankee Stadium while his son, Tony Jr., 16,
sat and took it all in. He didn't mind sharing his father. They had
a private bonding session much earlier in the morning, before
cameras, pens and pads were there. Gwynn and his son approached the
Stadium and walked in together. In 17 seasons in the majors, Gwynn
had never set foot in the venerable House That Ruth Built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've flown over Yankees Stadium, we've driven by it in a bus,
I had a cab take me _ I was going to Shea and he took me here
instead _ but never been in,'' Gwynn said. ``So it's a big deal to
me to see this place. It's a one-of-a-kind place, the type of place
that sometime in your career, you just hope to get a chance to play
just one game.''
</P>
<P>
   They walked down the left-field line, entered Monument Park,
looked at the retired numbers, the plaques, the monuments. For
Gwynn, Yankee Stadium history made him realize the significance of
this Series for San Diego. Monument Park was a stark reminder of
all that San Diego had not achieved, of the work that still needed
to be done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stuff associated with us is not positive,'' Gwynn
said. ``Here's an opportunity for us to establish something
positive in a huge way. You can't get caught up in it. You got to
focus in on the job at hand. But you also know that how you do in
this series is going to have a big impact on not only a lot of
people in our city, but on the history of this club.''
</P>
<P>
   There were deeper roots and reason that drove Gwynn to walk
among the monuments with his son Friday morning. As he looked and
reflected, Gwynn thought about his father. Charles Gwynn was the
pillar of the community in Los Angeles. He was a popular Little
League and Pop Warner coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about it all the time when I was a kid, about Yankee
Stadium,'' Tony Gwynn said. ``He'd never been there, but he knew
about Mickey Mantle, knew the history. He used to say that the
Yankees were the team of the decade, of the millennium. So walking
back there looking at those monuments, seeing the names, thinking
about the history, I think of my dad. And I think of how he used to
tell me all the time, `You should take your boy with you.' So
having him here is important.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn's father wanted him to play football but supported
him when he played baseball. A lifelong Dodgers fan, his dad wanted
him to play for the Dodgers, but supported him with San Diego. When
the Padres began selling off their high-priced players, his dad
became furious and told Tony he should leave the Padres because
they weren't trying to win.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn thought about the argument they had about his leaving
in 1993. Two days later Charles Gwynn died suddenly. Tony Gwynn
contemplated leaving baseball, but then remembered that his father
had always told him to never give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't a day that goes by that I don't think about how
happy he would have been here since 1994, when we really started
rebuilding this team,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   David Wells predicted that the Yankees would win the Series in
five games. Gwynn shrugged. A team that wins 114 regular-season
games has the right to be confident. The Padres have climbed too
steep a hill to care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I realize who we're playing, what we're going against and how
difficult it's going to be,'' Gwynn said. ``But anything can happen
out there between those white lines. Believe me. I've seen it.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
