<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SEARCH IS NEAR END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Los Angeles Dodgers hope to end their search for
a manager today when they interview veteran Davey Johnson before
the first game of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone spent almost five hours Friday
speaking with former Texas and Boston manager Kevin Kennedy about
the position.
</P>
<P>
   But sources say Johnson is the favorite to get the job. He led
the New York Mets to a World Series championship in 1986 and the
Cincinnati Reds and Baltimore Orioles to division titles during the
past four seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said today's talks with Johnson will be philosophical in
nature, but there is a good chance a new manager could be named on
Monday, the off-day between Games 2 and 3 of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have worked with Davey before and we have had a good
relationship,'' said Malone, assistant GM in Baltimore for the past
three seasons. ``He is a proven winner everywhere he has gone. That
is something we are looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, fired after leading Baltimore to the American League
West title in 1997, has been outspoken about his interest in the
Dodgers position. Despite the club's seemingly limitless resources
due to the new owners at Fox, money could be an issue.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies recently signed Jim Leyland to a
three-year, $6 million contract. The Montreal Expos matched that
figure last week to keep manager Felipe Alou after the Dodgers
offered him more than $3 million for three seasons to come to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Malone has said $2 million per season is too much.
</P>
<P>
   Malone will interview Johnson with new Dodgers farm director
Bill Geivett and assistant GM Ed Creech. There also is a chance
senior vice president and former manager Tom Lasorda will be
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has had trouble with upper management in New York,
Cincinnati and Baltimore. Reds owner Marge Schott and Orioles owner
Peter Angelos are considered difficult to work for, but Malone
conceded Johnson is a ``maverick and very headstrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy led the Boston Red Sox to an American League East title
in 1995 but was fired the next season. He also had the Rangers in
first place in the AL West at the time of the August 1994 strike,
then left to take the Boston job.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who attended Taft High School and lives in Tarzana,
spent several years as a manager in the Dodgers' minor-league
system. He moved on to Montreal as a field coordinator for the
Expos' minor-league operation. There he met Malone, who was GM in
1994-95.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin, like Davey, is a proven winner at every level he has
managed,'' Malone said. ``He did well in the minors and carried
that into the majors. I liked what I heard today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
