<HEADER>
A2396 &Cx1f; tdt-z
b x &Cx13;  &Cx11;  Doyouhavedoubtsaboutthew     10-17 1463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 ,  64, is identified with wide-ranging work on poverty. There was
plenty of schadenfreude as well. The forced sale of Long-Term
Capital Management, the immense hedge fund for the very rich and
powerful that had been built upon the application of Merton and
Scholes' latest formulas, seems to have cost the laureates' their
considerable personal fortunes. (They were among its partners.)
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet a look at the pattern of the prizes of the last four years
shows that the Swedish Academy of Sciences, which makes the award,
has put a great deal of effort into saying something about the
state of modern economics that is interesting, encouraging, and, to
many, persuasive.
</P>
<P>
   I say four years because it was five years ago that Assar
Lindbeck, leader of an older generation among Swedish economists,
retired from the committee that prepares the recommendations for
the prize. He had served as its leader since it began. He was no
stick-in-the-mud; far from it. But he took others with him, and
with their departure leadership passed to the next generation.
</P>
<P>
   Remember, the economics Nobel is a recent invention. Its proper
name is the Bank of Sweden Prize in Economic Sciences in Memory of
Alfred Nobel. The idea was to commemorate the 300th anniversary of
the founding of Sweden's central bank.
</P>
<P>
   The prize was first awarded in 1969, its reception greatly eased
by the long economic boom of the 1950s and 1960s and the sense that
a breakthrough of some sort finally had been achieved by the dismal
science. It joined the five original prizes stipulated in 1895 by
the will of the explosives magnate _ in physics, chemistry,
medicine or physiology, literature, and peace.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the reputation of economics among the general public
has gone mostly downhill. But the Nobel committee was charged with
taking the long view, and for 25 years it carefully charted the
pattern by which economics became its modern self. Within the
profession the committee achieved great authority, working off its
backlog &UR;  &LR; of worthy winners, producing mostly hits and only a few
wheezes in the most political of sciences.
</P>
<P>
   With the general public, too, it maintained credibility,
favoring neither left nor right. In 1974 it split the difference,
dividing the prize equally between Gunnar Myrdal and Friedrich
Hayek.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1980s, however, the committee was caught up in the
ideological battles of the decade, unable to agree about where the
spotlight should be turned. Economics felt itself to have been
progressing rapidly, yet in 1988 and 1989, prizes went for work
done in 1944. Lags between the work itself and its citation in
Stockholm were averaging 40 years _ as opposed to 10 or 12 in
chemistry and biology as and less in physics.
</P>
<P>
   Then Lindbeck stepped down, the composition of the committee
changed, and whammo! Robert Lucas of the University of Chicago was
cited in 1995. Nobody represented better than Lucas the
discontinuous nature of the change that occurred in economics
during the 1970s. With his 1972 paper on the non-neutrality of
money, he had used high-tech math to bring into sharper focus the
role of individuals' expectations in economic life.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, James Mirrlees and William Vickrey were honored. The
fact that they shared the citation seemed to cast the new message
into even sharper relief. Vickery, born in 1914, was an old
fashioned verbal economist, quite brilliant in his day, which
spanned from World War II to the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Mirrlees, on the other hand, born in 1936, was a mathematical
economist whose 1971 article on optimal nonlinear income taxation
was all but indecipherable to those outside the field. And yet
their contributions to the theory of information and incentives
were pretty much the same.
</P>
<P>
   See? the Swedes seemed to be saying: the new high-tech methods
do the same as the old and do it better; they are less ambiguous
and more easily understood and tested. Mirrlees' influence among
his peers was enormous, while Vickrey had been all but forgotten by
the young. As if to underscrore the point, Vickrey died of a heart
attack three days after the award was announced.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the 1997 award to Merton and Scholes. (A third
contributor, Fischer Black, had died the year before.) The
revolutionary Black-Scholes options pricing formula had been
introduced in 1972, generalized by Merton, and shortly therefter
programmed into hand-held calculators used by traders around the
world. It was perhaps the most dominating demonstration of the
practical significance of economic theory ever achieved.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel committee had clearly moved the frontier of
prize-quality work into the era of the Vietnam War. And in this
respect, this year's award to Sen is no exception: ``Collective
Choice and Social Welfare,'' the first of Sen's three books cited
by the committee, was published in 1970. ``On Economic Inequality''
followed in 1973 and ``Poverty and Famines: An Essay on Entitlement
and Deprivation'' in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   In another respect, too, Sen's award is similiar to the others.
His work on the theory of ``social choice,'' on which the citation
dwelt at length, is highly technical. An abstract, almost
philosophical field dealing with collective decision-making, social
choice begins with the propounding of axioms, propositions taken to
be true whose relevance is nevertheless hard to pin down.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike the other bodies of work, Sen's writings lack the
single drop-dead insight that changes the way a particular problem
is perceived and galvanizes other researchers to work variations on
the theme. Instead, his contributions to social choice are
persistently critical.
</P>
<P>
   They point to difficulties of the ``impossibility'' theorem that
is at the core of social choice: how can satisfactory collective
decision-making be impossible when it happens every day? Sen's
writings therefore raise doubts about the significance of the very
activity of which they are a part. Very clever the insights are,
very provocative too _ but they are not the kind of theory-and-tool
building exercises &UR;  &LR; that won the prize in the three previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Sen's Nobel Prize is being described by many senior
economists as a kind of a ``person'' prize, a lifetime achievement
award instead of a matter of depersonalized science. And so it is.
</P>
<P>
   But what a career! Forty years of calling attention to the
plight of the most impoverished members of society in an
astonishing variety of ways, from high philosophy to measurement
economics to pointed empirical work. Sen's work on famines is well
known _ they are man-made events, he has shown, not vicissitudes of
the weather, and they never, ever happen in democracies, where
those who are starving have a political voice. But perhaps the
single most striking result he ever obtained was the case of the
missing women.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of simple calculations relying on research by
others, Sen showed that women generally outnumber men in Europe and
North America. They are hardier and survive better at all ages.
They don't smoke as much and they don't go to war. So even though
around 5 percent more boys are born than girls around the world,
women outnumber men in the industrial democracies.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia and North Africa, however, the situation is reversed.
Even adjusting for lower life expectancies, there were 44 million
``missing women'' in China in 1992 and 37 million in India, of a
total of more than 100 million worldwide _ if the male-female ratio
of Eurpe and America prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Rough treatment all around, Sen found. Worse health care,
less food, little education, fewer property rights, even the custom
of ``hiding'' newborns who are girls. Social inequality outweighted
the natural survival advantages of women in these lands.
</P>
<P>
   It is a perfect example of the Sen style. No wonder every
university wants him. (He taught at Harvard for a decade until
Cambridge University lured him back last spring with the mastership
of its richest college.) His contribution is not so much a tool as
a sensibility. He is a 20th century Jane Austin, richly cultured
himself, whose topic is not the manners of the rich, but the
problems of the poor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
