<HEADLINE>
VAUGHN BENEFITS FROM NON-TRADE TO YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif.)  (Eds: See also BBO-YANKEES, BBO-MATCHUPS, BBO-RHODEN-COLUMN) 
(mk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was the middle of last summer when Greg Vaughn was
flown into New York only to have Yankee team doctors inspect his
right shoulder as carefully as fine print. Something was up.
</P>
<P>
   But for a Californian as laid back as a palm tree, Vaughn was
not overly paranoid about the completion of a deal between New York
and San Diego that had him becoming a Yankee in exchange for Kenny
Rogers. Hours after doctors poked him like a voodoo doll, Vaughn
was hustling back to San Diego to pick up his packed bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a layover somewhere, and I called my wife,'' Vaughn
said. ``She said, `Hey, you failed your physical.' She saw it on
ESPN. I said, `All right, I'll be home in a little while and unpack
my bags.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Padres were stuck with Vaughn, stuck with a player
they wanted to cast off as a $15 million mistake, stuck with a
misfit who could not consistently find his way into the Padre
lineup. These days, the Padres would not shake him for the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Vaughn dropped his bags in a New York hotel room as
a celebrated part of a San Diego team that might not be playing in
the World Series against the Yankees Saturday without the push he
gave his team during his dramatic turnaround season.
</P>
<P>
   Before he cooled a bit, Vaughn's name was inset into this year's
great home run chase. He finished with 50 homers. Still, the
Yankees have not been left wondering what might have been if they
had just listened to the left fielder when he assured them that his
shoulder was OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked out for all those clubs involved,'' Yankees general
manager Brian Cashman said. ``They got a player they got to keep
but they didn't want to keep. We used Kenny Rogers in a later deal
to get Scott Brosius.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greg was a player, at the time, that the Padres made a huge
financial commitment to that wasn't working out, and they tried to
trade a problem for a problem. It didn't work out and maybe that
was the impetus for Greg to turn his career around and get
jump-started again.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But Vaughn's casual nature on the surface did not hint
at any bitterness toward the Yankees as he leaned back in his chair
before Friday's workout at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in trying to throw anything in anybody's
face,'' said Vaughn, who will start in left field after recovering
from a leg injury that kept him out of three games during the
National League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe in taking a negative and trying to make it a
positive. People have asked, would it be extra special to play the
Yankees instead of Cleveland? I don't care who I'm playing, as long
as I'm in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Greg Vaughn against the Yankees or Greg Vaughn
against the doctors here or Greg Vaughn against George Steinbrenner
because they sent me back,'' he added. ``It's the Padres against
the Yankees. I'm pretty laid back, so not a whole lot bothers me,
except when I'm not playing.''
</P>
<P>
   That issue became the bane of his existence in San Diego a year
ago. He was a wallflower on the Padres team, a player who never did
anything particularly outstanding or exciting, nothing to
foreshadow the season he had this year. To explain his revival,
some point to his more relaxed stance in the batter's box, but
Vaughn attributes it to something more simple than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Dick Vitale says: P.T., playing time,'' said Vaughn,
who was stashed behind Rickey Henderson much of 1997. ``I was
playing Monday and Friday last year, and pinch-hitting in between.
I'd never done that. Playing every day, that's the only thing I
asked when I signed that contract. Let me get 500 at-bats and then
judge me. I got my at-bats this year, and everything took care of
itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe everything happens for a reason. With the Yankee
trade, I guess the guy upstairs must have said, `You're a
California boy.' People have asked, `What if you'd been a Yankee?'
and I'm like, `I would have been in the World Series, just like I
am now.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
