<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERS PROPOSE EXPANSION OF UNION'S LUXURY TAX 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three days after the players union proposed a luxury tax on very
high-salaried players as a way of breaking the three-month labor
impasse, the National Basketball Association responded Friday with
a luxury tax proposal of its own that would include the salaries of
many more players.
</P>
<P>
   But while the fact that both sides were now talking about the
same solution _a luxury tax on salaries _ would seem to suggest
some progress, neither the owners nor the union were optimistic
that the latest developments would end the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the union's executive director, dismissed the plan
as a ``masquerade'' by the owners to obtain a salary cap without
exceptions. ``They've taken a step backward,'' he said. Hunter did
not discount the possibility of losing the entire season because of
the way negotiations are going. ``We'll study and analyze it this
weekend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA deputy commissioner, Russ Granik, admitted that the
league's proposal was geared toward discouraging teams from signing
players to exorbitant contracts, but added, ``We can't make any
more deals where the owners take all the risks.''
</P>
<P>
   The public posturing may conceal whether there is room for
negotiation over the next several weeks, and whether a tax system
may eventually lead to the signing of a collective bargaining
agreement and the season's belatedly starting. The first two weeks
of the season were canceled on Tuesday, and league officials have
said another two-week block of games may be eliminated the week of
Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA proposal would tax teams for all contracts signed under
the Larry Bird exception _ re-signing their own free agents for any
amount they choose regardless of the team's salary cap situation _
that exceed the average player salary, which was $2.6 million
during the 1997-98 season.
</P>
<P>
   The league projects that the tax would affect 15 percent of
future contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Using a tax escalation system, a league official said salaries
of $10 million would be taxed 100 percent and salaries reaching $20
million would be taxed 200 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A clause was factored in for current Bird exception players with
huge deals that would prohibit a tax as long as their new deals
were not 5 percent over the current contracts.
</P>
<P>
   The league's plan also includes a provision that says a hard cap
would go into effect if the percentage of league revenue paid to
the players exceeds an agreed-upon level after two years, a
provision the players have said in the past they would not agree
to.
</P>
<P>
   While the league boasted that by the 2001-02 season the average
player salary would be at least $3.1 million, the union contended
the plan will do away with the middle-class salary and exacerbate
the situation of haves and have-nots in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The league proposal was in response to a tax system proposed by
the players on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That plan called for a 50 percent tax on contracts over $18
million with the tax put into a fund that would eventually be
distributed to lower-revenue- generating teams.
</P>
<P>
   The league contended that only two players would be currently
affected by such a tax, and that it would not meet their financial
goals.
</P>
<P>
   If a player received $10 million and had his salary taxed at 100
percent, a luxury-tax system would keep him from making another $10
million that goes directly to a fund for low-revenue teams. ``I
don't think we should get too carried away about the
possibilities,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are awaiting an arbitration decision on Monday by
John Feerick, dean of Fordham Law School, who will rule whether
more than 220 players with guaranteed contracts close to $800
million should be paid during the lockout.
</P>
<P>
   If Feerick rules favorably for the players, the league has
indicated it plans to appeal and tie the matter up in court for
perhaps several months.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if the league wins the decision, Hunter said his
constituency is determined to show resolve in its stalemate with
the owners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0006EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
