<SLUG> BC-BOX-HOLYFIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT ON HOLYFIELD-LEWIS BOUT IS CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain)  (mk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The parties negotiating a proposed undisputed heavyweight
championship bout between Evander Holyfield and Lennox Lewis are
inching closer to an agreement that will have both boxers in the
ring early next year. But after five days of talks on two
continents, it is still not officially done.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Thomas, Holyfield's lawyer, said that Holyfield signed a
contract for the fight on Thursday and was eager to meet Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander has signed and is satisfied with all the terms,''
Thomas said. ``Now, Lennox needs to sign. All this nonsense about
Evander not wanting to fight Lennox is now being exposed for what
it is.''
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation that the fight will take place on March 13
at Madison Square Garden, but Milton Chwasky, Lewis' U.S.-based
lawyer, declined comment when asked about that possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Chwasky said that at this point he did not see any deal breakers
in the contract. Don King, Holyfield's promoter, faxed it to Lewis'
promoter, Panos Eliades, in London and is awaiting a signature from
Lewis. Chwasky said he would read the contract over the weekend
before Lewis signed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've verbally agreed on the majority of the major issues,''
Chwasky said. ``There aren't any minor issues that can't be worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield, 35, is guaranteed $20 million and Lewis, 33, is
guaranteed $10 million. However, there is still a major hurdle that
must be cleared before the fight is made. King must reach an
agreement with HBO Sports, which has the rights to the fight by
virtue of its exclusive contract with Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   The bout would be broadcast on TVKO, the pay-per-view arm of HBO
Sports. There is longstanding acrimony between King and Seth
Abraham, president of Time Warner/HBO Sports. King and Abraham were
once partners at HBO, but they split in the late 1980s. King went
over to Showtime, HBO's main cable rival, but recently he and
Abraham put aside their differences and are trying to hammer out an
agreement to make the fight happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of talk, a lot of good will and a lot of
progress,'' Abraham said. ``But in boxing you always want to be
careful that the chariot doesn't become a pumpkin. In boxing you're
so gun-shy you always sleep with a bulletproof vest.''
</P>
<P>
   With both fighters seemingly on board for the fight, the
pressure is now on King and Abraham to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   This is a risky venture for King, because there are no
guaranteed profits for him. King, the lead promoter for the fight,
can drive the show to profitability. Lack of a guarantee for King
should not be a stumbling block to making the fight, but it is just
not the way he normally does business.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield and Lewis are not major pay-per-view draws on their
own. But together this could be a formidable match, because there
is not another compelling heavyweight championship bout on the
horizon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I'd be surprised if this fight doesn't do a
million pay-per-view buys,'' Thomas said. ``There's been two years
since there was a heavyweight bout that anyone has been excited
about. This is what everyone wants to see.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson, if he gets his license back in Nevada on Monday and
returns to boxing, will do big pay-per-view numbers. But there will
not be a title at stake, and no one is sure how much Tyson has left
in his tank. With back-to-back losses to Holyfield, Tyson has not
won a fight in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evander doesn't have one trait that Tyson has,'' Thomas said.
``People come to see if Tyson will kill someone or if a piece of
someone will get ripped off. But everyone knows that when they come
to see Evander, they'll see a good fight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
