<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A STEP UP, OR IS IT TWO BACK?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If this is progress, the NBA season is in
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   NBA owners agreed in principle Friday to the players' proposal
for a tax system to slow salary growth _ at first glance, a
positive step toward resolution of a 3{-month-old labor dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But the players association immediately rejected the owners'
version of the tax system, calling it worse than previous league
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   As the standoff completed its 108th day, the two sides appeared
as far apart as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears at a quick glance to be a step backward... more
onerous than the proposal we received from them Sept. 24,'' Billy
Hunter, director of the players' association, said of the NBA's
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the week, the union proposed for the first time a tax
system on player contracts. The union's version was a ``luxury'' or
``superstar'' tax, applying only to players making $18 million or
more annually. The tax would be paid by owners as a penalty on
lucrative deals, and the revenue would be redistributed among
cash-strapped teams.
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing to a tax system, the league offered a far
different approach: a tax on every contract signed under the
``Larry Bird exception'' that exceeds the average salary, $2.6
million this past season. The Bird exception allows teams to
re-sign free agents at any price, without regard to the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Because the tax would apply only to contracts signed under the
Bird clause, the NBA said only 15 percent of player contracts would
be taxed.
</P>
<P>
   NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik said owners would try the
tax system on a two-year trial basis, with the proviso that if
salaries continued to escalate, the league would impose its
long-desired hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to try it the union's way, but they have to
agree that if it doesn't work, we then have to try it our way,''
Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   The league called the union's proposal unacceptable, as only two
contracts this past season would have exceeded the $18 million
mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the union's other proposals, it would have increased _
not decreased _ the percentage of league revenue paid to the
players,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the union said the owners' proposal is as bad or worse
than previous calls for a hard salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Though the league said its tax plan would apply to only 15
percent of player contracts, Hunter said it would affect all
contracts and cause 90 to 95 percent of the players to accept the
league minimum salary, currently $272,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be disguised in terms of a tax, but it is in fact a
hard cap,'' Hunter said. ``Our intent was to address the concern of
the superstar contracts, like the Kevin Garnett contract that
everyone points to. The tax they've come back with impacts the
entire system.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, a break in the impasse might still come down to an
arbitrator's ruling due Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Arbitrator John Feerick will be releasing his decision on the
union's contention that 220 players with guaranteed contracts must
be paid during the lockout. The players hope a ruling in their
favor would end the lockout, but the league would appeal such a
ruling in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   The league already canceled the first two weeks of the season
and more cancellations will follow if the lockout doesn't end soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0055EDT &QL; 
