<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   PAKISTAN: Talks With India on Kashmir
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since India and Pakistan conducted nuclear
tests in May, their foreign ministers met in Islamabad to discuss
ways of easing military tensions in the region and resolving their
conflict over the disputed territory of Kashmir. Little of
substance was expected to emerge from the three days of talks, but
a Pakistani spokesman described a productive day of negotiations
while the foreign ministers, K. Ragunath of India and Shamshad
Ahmed of Pakistan, looked on without commenting.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA: American Banned for Criticism
</P>
<P>
   An American professor, Jeffrey Winters, has been banned from
entering Indonesia for allegedly embarrassing its chief economics
minister and implying that he was not clean enough to lead a
national anti-corruption drive. Winters, an associate professor at
Northwestern University, denied that he had accused the
coordinating minister of economy and finance, Ginandjar
Kartasasmita, of being corrupt, saying only that the minister was a
``questionable'' choice to lead the team charged with eradicating
corruption from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: Raul Salinas Murder Trial Near End
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented closing arguments in the case against the
brother of former President Carlos Salinas, Raul Salinas de
Gortari, who is accused in connection with the 1994 assassination
of a prominent politician. In a 1200-page legal brief, the
prosecution charged that Raul Salinas ordered a hired gunman to
kill Jose Francisco Ruiz Massieu, a former state governor, because
of political rivalries between them. If convicted, Salinas faces a
maximum sentence of 50 years in prison. His defense lawyer, Eduardo
Luengo Creel, said prosecutors have not offered any material
evidence linking Salinas to the crime. He has been held in a
solitary cell in a maximum security penitentiary since February
1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
