</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-OREGONST.-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATS HOPE TO SOLVE THEIR IDENTITY CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORVALLIS, Ore. _ Arizona, a two-quarterback team all season, is
seeking to mend a fractured identity.
</P>
<P>
   Within one quarter eight days ago, the Wildcats went from
contender to surrender.
</P>
<P>
   For 51 minutes, they challenged UCLA, now ranked No. 2 and in
the hunt for a national title. But for the final nine, they were a
team in disarray. It was a full and stunning retreat in front of a
Bruins blitz that left the Wildcats with a 52-28 loss.
</P>
<P>
   It would have been one thing if the timing had been reversed. An
early struggle and late comeback might have provided some
consolation for the Wildcats. Then, they could have used the end to
a tough loss as the initial step in renewal.
</P>
<P>
   But, now, the No. 16 Wildcats (5-1, 2-1 Pac-10) enter today's 1
p.m. game at Oregon State (4-2, 1-2) amid uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Was Arizona's last fourth quarter the signal of an imminent
decline, or just a temporary flaw against a superior team? Who are
these guys?
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dick Tomey isn't expecting easy answers today against an
improved program that hasn't been a winner since Nixon was in the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably appreciate winning more than anybody in the
league right now,'' Tomey said of the Beavers, who posted their
last winning record in 1970. ``It will be very hard to take the
game away from them for that reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Tomey expressed no illusions about either Arizona's all-time
record of 18-2-1 against the Beavers or its status today as the
favorite. He believes his Wildcats will have to be better than they
were at their best two weeks ago in a wild, 31-28 victory at
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are more dangerous than Washington,'' said Tomey, who
argued that the Beavers are more tenacious than the Huskies.
</P>
<P>
   The only comparison point be tween the two is Stanford. The
Beavers won at Stanford last week, 30-23. The Wildcats beat the
host Cardinal, 31-14, in their second game on Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   As a guide, the respective Stanford games would appear to favor
the Wildcats. But their rocky fourth quarter last week and signs of
an improving Oregon State create a possible crossroads for both
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're coming in here thinking it's the same Oregon State,''
said Beavers defensive end Inoke Breckterfield, who was a Honolulu
prep rival of several Hawaiian players on the Arizona roster. ``But
they don't know. It's our homecoming, so it's going to be totally
different than we played down there for their homecoming (a 27-7
Wildcats' victory last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll take it to them. If they come half-stepping, they'll
leave losers.''
</P>
<P>
   If Arizona can't add several steps to its running game, defeat
is a distinct possibility. Ninety rushing yards against UCLA
resulted in a one-dimensional, flawed attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything revolves around a good running game,'' said
quarterback Keith Smith, who probably will continue to share time
with Ortege Jenkins. ``We've got to get that going.''
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, perhaps, there have been some questions whether the
Jenkins-Smith rotation was a factor in the loss to UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   Receivers Jeremy McDaniel and Dennis Northcutt are threats
regardless of whether the quarterback is Jenkins or Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toss either of those guys a 3-yard pass and they can turn it
into a 60-yarder at any time,'' Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been growing inconsistency in the running game, a
duty shared by Kelvin Eafon and Trung Canidate, a junior from
Central High.
</P>
<P>
   Different handoffs from different quarterbacks? Different
blocking schemes? The two faces of Arizona? Today's game at Oregon
State might provide a single answer. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
