r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT-AZR &LR;      10-17 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LOCKOUT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA OWNERS MAKE COUNTEROFFER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NBA's owners and players may finally have found some common
ground in their effort to break a labor impasse that already has
cost the first two weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after the players union made a surprise proposal that
would use a ``luxury tax'' to prevent the escalation of player
salaries, the owners made a counterproposal Friday that accepts the
notion of such a tax.
</P>
<P>
   The tax would leave the Larry Bird exception to the NBA salary
cap in effect, thereby avoiding a ``hard'' salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   That exception allows clubs to re-sign their own free agents for
any amount without regard to cap limits.
</P>
<P>
   The tax plan, however, would charge what amounts to a cash
penalty to owners who exceed the salary cap to sign a player under
the Bird exception.
</P>
<P>
   And the owners are insisting on a provision that would place a
hard salary cap in effect if the percentage of league revenues
being paid to players exceeds an agreed-upon amount after the first
two years of the new contract.
</P>
<P>
   However, a significant gulf exists between the tax plan proposed
by the union and the one offered by the owners.
</P>
<P>
   The union plan called for a luxury tax on salaries of more than
$18 million. Last season, out of about 400 players, only Michael
Jordan's $33 million deal and the $19 million of New York Knicks
center _ and union president _ Patrick Ewing, would have been
subject to the tax.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement released by the NBA, the owners'
proposal would tax any contract signed under the Bird exception for
more than the average salary _ $2.6 million last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We analyzed it every which way, and like the union's other
proposals, it would have increased _ not decreased _ the percentage
of league revenue paid to the players,'' said Russ Granik, league
deputy commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, in the spirit of compromise, we have attempted to
fashion a system that uses a tax, instead of a hard cap, even
though we're skeptical about the ability of any tax system to keep
player salaries at a set percentage of league revenue. We are
willing to try it the union's way, but they have to agree that if
it doesn't work, we then have to try it our way.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the league, the new tax would impact about 15
percent of future contracts.
</P>
<P>
   But with more than 190 free agents this summer, the union is
likely to argue that the league's projection is far too low.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, also in the announcement, said the proposal guaranteed
that player compensation will rise by at least 20 percent over the
next four years and that the average player salary will reach at
least $3.1 million by the 2001-02 season.
</P>
<P>
   At stake is about $2 billion in annual league revenue. The
players and league wound up in their current fix after owners
exercised an out-clause in the last collective bargaining agreement
which allowed owners to re-open the contract if player salaries ate
up more than 51.8-percent of basketball-related revenue. According
to owners, player salaries accounted for 57 percent of that revenue
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, hoping to roll back salaries to 48 percent, locked
out the players July 1.
</P>
<P>
   And while both sides have exchanged proposals in recent days,
they also still were waiting for an arbitration ruling by Fordham
law school dean John Feerick.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to decide by Sunday whether the league must pay
those players with guaranteed contracts _ about 220 _ during the
lockout. Players, who have an Oct. 22 meeting planned in Las Vegas,
are scheduled to begin receiving paychecks Nov. 15. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0109EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
