<HEADER>
A2471 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-PREVIEW-AZ     10-17 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-PREVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF 2 SERIES CITIES  
 CAL IS COOL, NEW YORK IS FIERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like most of the San Diego Padres, Ken Caminiti had
never set foot inside Yankee Stadium before the club's workout
Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti and nearly all of his teammates have no idea what
awaits them when the Padres and the storied New York Yankees begin
the 94th World Series tonight.
</P>
<P>
   This will be a series offering as stark a contrast in cities as
conceivable. It will be the laid-back Southern California lifestyle
against the never-enough-time-in-the-day bustle of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Think San Diego, and it's beaches, waves and pina coladas. Think
the Bronx, and it's gangs, police cars and overhead subway tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Padres right fielder Tony Gwynn, who also made his first visit
to the most hallowed stadium in baseball on Friday, got a strong
taste of what awaits him while taking the No. 4 subway from Midtown
to the South Bronx, exiting at the 163rd Street station.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was New York,'' Gwynn said. ``That's the best way I can put
it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a place where subway riders can be treated to anything
from a singing homeless man, who politely asks for donations, to a
near brawl when a mother, holding her infant daughter, defiantly
tells a stranger, ``Back off. Can't you see I got my kid here in my
arms?''
</P>
<P>
   The ugliest type of interaction you could see in San Diego is a
pair of surfers jockeying for a primo wave or someone honking their
horn to be allowed into a lane on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are accustomed to their version of a boisterous
crowd, but the generally well-behaved fans of San Diego don't come
close to the battery-wielding fans who file into Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get chills just thinking about what it's going to be like,''
said Padres catcher/first baseman Jim Leyritz, a former Yankee, who
hit a key home run in the 1996 World Series against Atlanta.
``There's nothing better than going to New York for the World
Series.''
</P>
<P>
   This city has hosted a record 145 World Series games. The
Yankees, who have won a record 23 World Series championships, have
hosted 94 Series games, more than double the next club on the list.
The city among those that have played in a Series that has hosted
the fewest? San Diego, with two.
</P>
<P>
   When the Padres step on the field tonight, they will not only be
taking on the 1998 New York Yankees _ who won a franchise-record
114 regular season games, which could be intimidating enough _ they
must also contend with Yankee Stadium's ghosts.
</P>
<P>
   Every player who walks into Yankee Stadium, no matter how many
times, can't help but think about the great players who have worn
the most famous pinstripes in sports. Just the image of the trellis
hanging from the roof of Yankee Stadium invokes memories of
baseball's most storied franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the first great Yankee club of the early 1920s,
the one that featured Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig and Earl Combs and
heading down memory lane with names such as Joe DiMaggio, Whitey
Ford, Yogi Berra and Mickey Mantle.
</P>
<P>
   Even the recent Yankees _ Thurman Munson, Reggie Jackson and Don
Mattingly _ have fabulous names. In San Diego, the Padres' greats
are named Clay Kirby, Nate Colbert and Gary Templeton, not
necessarily the kind of names that make anyone think of greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't get excited about playing at Yankee Stadium, then
you don't know much about the history of this game,'' Leyritz said.
``There's nothing better than playing in that stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   On one side is a franchise whose alumni list reads like a
``Who's Who'' in Cooperstown. On the other side, there are great
Padres memories like the time then-General Manager Buzzie Bavasi
flipped off the San Diego fans; or the time Roseanne Barr mangled
the National Anthem and topped it off by grabbing her crotch.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget the time then-owner Ray Kroc grabbed the
stadium microphone and offered refunds to every fan in attendance
after an especially putrid performance by the brown and mustard
colored-wearing Padres in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody thinks about San Diego when they think of Southern
California,'' Gwynn said. ``They think about LA, about the Lakers
or the Dodgers. But here we are. I think we've earned the right to
go to the World Series.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
