r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-CARDS-SANDERS-AZR     10-17 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-SANDERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDS WANT EVEN MORE FROM SANDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - If there is a nit somewhere, a football coach
will be the first to find it and pick on it.
</P>
<P>
   Take the Cardinals' Frank Sanders, for instance. All Sanders,
the fourth-year receiver from Auburn, has done is lead the team and
rank second in the NFL in receptions (33) for 326 yards and a
touchdown, and offensive coordinator Marc Trestman offers this
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been solid in practice every week, but his productivity
still is not what we want it to be,'' Trestman said. ``He's getting
catches, but we'd still like to get more out of the catches.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercy, talk about playing to a tough audience.
</P>
<P>
   Trestman, of course, is not being overly critical. He knows
Sanders' fellow wide receiver, Rob Moore, has been hobbling with a
balky hamstring, which has enabled defenses to focus more on
Sanders and create even more problems for quarterback Jake Plummer.
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows that in the past three games _ two wins _
Sanders has contributed 23 catches for 236 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done a great job,'' Trestman said. ``With Rob slowed, we
have had to pick up the slack somewhere, and it has come from
Frank. If Rob is inhibited, or not in the game, everything
constricts, and we don't have the balance in our offense. The
defense can overplay in situations where they normally wouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Create a lopsided field with coverage aimed at
Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Sanders isn't about to cry foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been going on the last two or three weeks has been a
blessing for me,'' he said. ``It's always a disadvantage when you
don't have Rob Moore healthy or on the field. But I won't say it
has been tighter. It's been more in my favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it has been going great as far as Jake and I establishing
good eye contact on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't been lost on Plummer, who will make his 16th start _
officially one full season - on Sunday against New York, where he
threw a 70-yard scoring strike to Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been big,'' Plummer said. ``His production has gone up in
the last five games. I've always felt real confident throwing to
Frank. I have faith in his hands, and he runs very good routes and
always gets open.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's nice to have Rob healthy again. He's had two great
days of practice this week, and we've been throwing deep to him.
Hopefully, we can do that Sunday. It will be nice to have an equal
balance in our offense where we can go to Rob, Frank or Larry
(Centers). It will make Frank even more effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Few probably realize it, but Sanders entered this season with
196 career receptions, the most ever by a Cardinals receiver in
three years. It's an organization, mind you, that has rarely been
shabby at receiver, where wide-outs such as Roy Green and J.T.
Smith excelled.
</P>
<P>
   And for his part, Sanders, who worked feverishly to improve his
quickness in the off-season, believes his best is still to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot different,'' he said. ``I've had to take on a
different role. I'm trying to be more mature and have a better
approach on the field and in the locker room, trying to be a winner
and show it by example and hope the guys will see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``My role, my ideas and my heart haven't changed. But the game
has taken on a new dimension. When I first got here, the tempo was
hard to adjust to, but now I can. I understand you can't just play
this game on heart. In college, you played on emotion for 45 to 60
minutes. Concentration is more important.''
</P>
<P>
   He also knows that during his short career, the Cardinals have
undergone a face lift that he admits to liking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personality of this team is totally different from last
year,'' he said. ``We have a lot of young guys, and new guys, in
key positions. We're not a team with a lot of veterans, but we have
enough vets in key spots to stay on an even keel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of fun, but we work hard. We try to approach
practice like it isn't a drudgery, but don't approach it like the
coaches have to pull teeth to get us to work. We're trying to
improve and have desires and goals that pull us together.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
