<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2480 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZ     10-17 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES COULD BE LAST FOR YANKEE STADIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - All that's missing is the curtain call, a fitting
finish to the season of miracles, a grand crescendo to complete the
renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Take a bite out of this:
</P>
<P>
   You could be watching the last appearance of Yankee Stadium in
the World Series. The place where Gehrig said goodbye, where Reggie
became a candy bar, where little Jeffrey Maier reached over the
railing and became a civic hero. The place where Ruth rumbled,
where Maris humbled, where the owner is spoofed on ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
<P>
   The place where baseball belongs in October.
</P>
<P>
   But even here, history is no match for the stadium game. Even
here, the old building doesn't work. Even here, the owner and the
mayor are pushing for a new palace, a new home for the cell-phone
crowd and the guaranteed revenue stream.
</P>
<P>
   If they can wreck it here, they can wreck it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the bunting, it is one of the numerous backdrops
framing the Fall Classic. There is controversy, a fire lit when
David Wells' guaranteed a five-game victory on Howard Stern's radio
show. There is idiocy, a foot in the mouth from George
Steinbrenner, who objected to Sammy Sosa throwing out the first
pitch. There is a stark contrast of teams, cultures and traditions,
one of which has won 113 World Series games, the other of which is
only 112 behind.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, there is a sense that this is more
coronation than competition, and maybe that's where the magic lies.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, there are separate mojos at work here. There is the
resiliency of the Padres, the jaw-crazy gaze of Kevin Brown, the
uncanny touch of Bruce Bochy. The team that has eliminated a pair
of 100-game winners, a team that will likely parlay this little run
into its own stadium on the water.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, there is the dance with destiny. A World
Series title would mean 125 wins, enough to make a case that this
is the best Yankees team ever. A team built on depth and
versatility, a team literally designed to be slump-proof. But in
the end, they are a team that might be too bland to rival the
Yankees of lore.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, where the corporate makeover of Bilk One Ballpark
continues to grow like stinkweed, there is plenty of reason to pay
attention.
</P>
<P>
   Would you like Bernie Williams in return for the hike in ticket
prices? Would you prefer Kevin Brown? Or maybe you'll be watching a
pair of future Diamondbacks, a decision that would make a good
portion of fans forget about the greed, the arrogance, the inane
comments of Rich Dozier.
</P>
<P>
   Williams could be the best all-around player in baseball. He's
unhappy about his treatment in New York. He has a good relationship
with Buck Showalter. And absurd as it sounds, he might be too
expensive for the Yankees, a team that must re-up with Derek Jeter
and Mariano Rivera, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, meanwhile, is poised to become the richest pitcher in
history. His competitive scowl makes Jack McDowell look like a boy
scout. He has the opportunity to carry the Padres, to become the
premiere arm in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line, there is no bigger stage than New York. And no
baseball facility with more wealth of tradition than Yankee
Stadium, a building clearly in jeopardy now that Steinbrenner wants
new digs on the Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   There are few bastions of pure revelry left in sports. Boston
Garden is gone. Chicago Stadium is a parking lot. The Forum in
Montreal is history. The buzzsaw is on its way to Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The modern era of professional sports can be summed up in one
awful mouthful: The National Car Rental Center, future home of the
Florida Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, there is still sunshine at Wrigley Field. Football
on the frozen tundra of Lambeau Field. Post-season baseball in the
Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   And here we are.
</P>
<P>
   So savor the scene. Expect the unexpected. After all, if this is
the last big dance for Yankee Stadium, you can count on a little
magic, something to remember before they send the ghosts to the
graveyard. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
