<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-PRACTICE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA EXPECTA TIONS TAKE SMALL DIP  
 TALENTED NEWCOMERS PROVIDE HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know you have a successful college basketball program when a
step backward means being in the top 20 instead of the top 5.
</P>
<P>
   This year figures to be a step backward for Coach Lute Olson and
his Arizona Wildcats, who lost three starters from their 1997
national championship team and their 30-win team last season that
came within one victory of being the Pac-10's first undefeated
champion.
</P>
<P>
   UA won't be as dominant on the national scene while its
newcomers mature.
</P>
<P>
   That's the bad news. The good news for the Wildcats, who open
practice at McKale Center this morning, is they have replaced Mike
Bibby, Michael Dickerson and Bennett Davison _ all drafted by NBA
teams _ with a recruiting class judged to be in the top five in the
country. Among the newcomers is forward Richard Jefferson of Moon
Valley High.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of question marks ourselves going into the
start of practice,'' said Olson, entering his 16th season at UA.
``Seven of our 13 scholarship players are new. It's a team the
coaches and fans will have to be patient with.''
</P>
<P>
   But with Jason Terry set to follow Bibby at point guard and
6-foot-11, 217-pound A.J. Bramlett challenged to prove he can be a
dominating big man, the Wildcats are expected to make their 15th
straight NCAA Tournament appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Terry has been one of the strongest sixth men in college
basketball the past two seasons on a guard-heavy team. He is known
for his defense (1.74 steals). During the stretch run to the Pac-10
title last season he also provided instant offense off the bench.
He will need to show that he can run the offense on a full-time
basis and be a floor leader who delivers the ball to the right
people in the right places.
</P>
<P>
   Bramlett was the rebounding leader of the NCAA Tournament when
UA won the national title. He wasn't as dominant during the 1998
tournament run, becoming virtually invisible when the Wildcats were
shown the door in the West Regional Final by Utah.
</P>
<P>
   As Arizona's most experienced big man, Bramlett must stay out of
foul trouble. He has to be a force with his rebounding and interior
defense. Without UA's trademark killer perimeter scoring, Bramlett
also has to be an inside scoring threat.
</P>
<P>
   Olson has openings at Simon's shooting guard spot, Dickerson's
small forward spot, and Davison's power forward spot. Because of
the NBA lockout, Dickerson, Simon and former UA players Damon
Stoudamire and Ben Davis have come back to Tucson and worked out
informally with the Wildcats. Dickerson is taking advantage of the
lockout to complete his degree work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't watch those workouts, but our former players have
come in and given us their feedback on the new guys,'' Olson said.
``They've been optimistic, but until we see them ourselves in a
structured practice individually and in five-on-five work, we have
questions. So we're as anxious as anyone for practice to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's nice that the former players come back and work out
before practice officially opens and talk to the guys about the
expectations in the program and what it's like to play in the
Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   It is going to be a different style team _ bigger and probably
slower with less extended defense _ than Wildcats fans have seen
the past two seasons when Olson could put three or four guards on
the floor together. Now, he can only hope his golf score matches
the makeup of his roster, with lots of 4s across it.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman power forward Michael Wright (6-8, 220), who helped
Team USA to the gold medal in the Junior World Championship, is the
prize of the recruiting class. He is expected to challenge
sophomore Eugene Edgerson (6-6, 221), senior Donnell Harris (6-11,
203), sophomore Justin Wessel (6-8, 211) and freshman Luke Walton
for the power forward job. Edgerson and Harris were valuable role
players on the national championship team. Walton is the son of
basketball Hall of Famer Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Quynn Tebbs will be challenged at shooting guard by
freshmen Ruben Douglas and Traves Wilson, both of whom can swing to
the point to give Terry relief.
</P>
<P>
   At small forward, newcomers Rick Anderson (6-9, 205) and
Jefferson (6-8, 215) will battle. Wessel, Walton and Wilson also
will work at small forward. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
