<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WILL WIN WITH TEAMWORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Yankees will not have Ruth, Gehrig or
DiMaggio in the heart of their order tonight for the first game of
the World Series. Or will they?
</P>
<P>
   The pressure of playing for the most celebrated franchise in
baseball history has undone past Yankees teams. The expectations of
owner George Steinbrenner have turned many high-priced free agents
into mush.
</P>
<P>
   Not this bunch. The 1998 Yankees have embraced the glory of the
past and are bent on adding a little of their own this week.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre said Tuesday _ after the Yankees won their
35th pennant _ that the hardest part was getting here. Believe it.
</P>
<P>
   He was not being disrespectful of their Series opponent, the San
Diego Padres. But the Yankees' blend of pitching, defense and
timely hitting that led to 121 victories create an intimidation
factor that San Diego will not overcome no matter how many times
they pitch Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what anybody says,'' Steinbrenner said after his
team beat Cleveland in the American League Championship Series.
``If the '27 Yankees played this team, they wouldn't stand a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget that the Yankees have outscored the Padres by more than
200 runs or that they have the World Series' only 20-game winner in
David Cone. Forget they won 62 games at home and that their
lifetime Series record is 23-11. This club is much more than
numbers.
</P>
<P>
   That 1927 team of Ruth and Gehrig had 110 regular-season
victories and a four-game sweep of Pittsburgh in the Series. It is
considered the benchmark of Yankee greatness. The 1998 team might
not have any future Hall of Famers; maybe shortstop Derek Jeter or
center fielder Bernie Williams. Instead, they have embodied the
personality of their manager, who has turned the Yankees into
baseball's biggest extended family.
</P>
<P>
   This is a franchise that won the World Series two years ago _
and this year's team is superior to that one because of its
cohesiveness.
</P>
<P>
   From veterans like Cone, Paul O'Neill and Chili Davis to
youngsters Shane Spencer and Jorge Posada, there always seems to be
someone there to pick up a teammate. When first baseman Tino
Martinez went in the postseason tank for a second straight year,
third baseman Scott Brosius countered with a critical three-run
homer and made two spectacular plays at third in last Thursday's
clincher against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, the most impressive thing about them is that if there
is a runner on third and less than two outs, they will always get
the run home,'' Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``Sounds small, but
in baseball that is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's Game 1 starter David Wells owes his entire season to
Torre. After Wells gave up seven runs in less than three innings
May 6 vs. Texas, Torre ripped him for being out of shape and having
poor work habits. It was a side of Torre seldom seen, but Wells
listened.
</P>
<P>
   In his next start, May 12 against Kansas City, Wells settled
down after a rough start and finished strong. The next time out he
pitched a perfect game. Wells enters this game 18-4, with three
more victories in the postseason and an MVP award in the LCS.
</P>
<P>
   He is one of the game's more colorful characters and Torre
occasionally still has to tone him down. When Wells glared at a
teammate for an error several weeks ago, Torre said there would be
no more of that. And this was after the Yankees had already
clinched the AL East with more than a month yet to play.
</P>
<P>
   When Darryl Strawberry went into the hospital to undergo surgery
for colon cancer, every member of the team appeared in a get-well
video. In the two weeks since, which is about two weeks longer than
the average attention span for a big leaguer, Yankees players have
been calling him every day. Strawberry got out Friday and told each
one of them that it was time to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   When Chuck Knoblauch committed a colossal fielding blunder that
cost the Yankees Game 2 of the ALCS, no one jumped in his face. The
New York media jumped on him for a season of subpar play, but this
team doesn't read the papers. Teammates accepted Knoblauch's
apology and moved on _ right into tonight's series opener.
</P>
<P>
   When Williams entered this season without a contract extension
and with free agency looming, the Yankees could have been facing a
Mike Piazza-like disruption. But the focus remained on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Although Williams might leave as a free agent, he won the
American League batting title and with it a Don Mattingly-like
place as a modern Yankees hero.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees inserted Cuban defector Orlando Hernandez into
the starting rotation, players could have resented his new contract
the way they did Hideki Irabu's the year before. Instead, they
embraced Hernandez, who won Game 4 against Cleveland _ probably the
only game they've played this year that could be called critical.
</P>
<P>
   They won't beat the Padres in five games the way Wells predicted
Thursday during an interview with radio shock jock Howard Stern.
But he's close. The Yankees will come back to New York a week from
tonight and wrap it up in six.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
