<HEADLINE>
RETURNERS GIVE NAU CHANCE FOR NCAA RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By GREG CRAWFORD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ When basketball Coach Ben Howland was
interviewing for the job at Northern Arizona University, he
discussed a five-year plan to get to the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his fifth year the Lumberjacks have two Big Sky
Conference championships and a first-ever berth in the NCAA
Tournament, which resulted in a heartbreaking 65-62 loss to
Cincinnati, a No. 2 regional seed last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many people in that room actually believed we
would ever get to the NCAA Tournament,'' Howland said. ``It had
been such a dismal situation here for so many years. It's
encouraging that we've reached that goal, but with any winning
program, we have high expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   As practice begins today, high expectations return. Yet senior
forward Casey Frank sees the accomplishment in a different light.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was more of a disappointment than it was an
accomplishment (losing to Cincinnati),'' Frank said. ``We felt we
were a better team than Cincinnati at the time, and we felt we were
going to win that game.''
</P>
<P>
   NAU's only significant loss from last season is Big Sky
Conference Most Valuable Player Andrew Mavis, which will be some
big shoes to fill. Now playing in England, Mavis averaged 14 points
and finished the season shooting 47 percent from three-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what Coach wants me to do right now is to take Mavis'
spot,'' junior Ross Land said. ``That will be hard to do, but I'm
feeling confident going into this season with two years under my
belt.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Big Sky co-Freshman of the Year made 43.8
three-pointers and and is 23 three-pointers away from the NAU
record. Senior Pat McGrath, who played at the same junior college
as Mavis, will help anchor that position.
</P>
<P>
   Other returners from last season include 7-foot Dan McClintock,
who has been splitting time with Frank for the past two years at
center and gives NAU one of the most intimidating one-two punches
in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The pair showed just how difficult they were to stop last season
during the Big Sky tournament as McClintock was named tournament
MVP playing behind Frank. This season, however, NAU fans may see
the two play side by side.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact of the matter is they are both better than they have
ever been,'' Howland said. ``We have wanted them to play together
in the past, but now I know they have the skills to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior Kawika Akina and junior Rod Hutchings look to be another
difficult duo at the point guard position. Last season, Akina
missed the first six games waiting to be eligible after
transferring from Dixie Junior College and finished the year second
in the conference in steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked about playing them together some even,'' Howland
said. ``Kawika is such a tough, hard-nosed, tenacious defender, he
can guard the two guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Hutchings gives NAU added quickness with great penetration.
</P>
<P>
   Juniors Billy Hix and Andrew Wolthers play the big forward spot
with Hix staring. Hix is NAU's tough inside player and was second
on the team in rebounding with 135. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
