<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-SOMERS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEAVERS DREAM OF BOWL BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In only his eighth month as athletic director at Oregon State,
 &UR; Mitch Barnhart already has accomplished the unthinkable. He was
able to call bowl officials in midseason to lobby for his Beavers,
all the while keeping a straight face.
</P>
<P>
   Barnhart made the calls earlier this week just to let the bowls
know that the Beavers (4-2) would be darn proud to play in a
postseason game for the first time since 1965.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that it's been a long time since we've been in
this position and that we were still out there,'' said Barnhart.
</P>
<P>
   He also emphasized that Oregon State fans, who finally have
something to be excited about, would be anxious to travel to watch
their team play in a bowl game.
</P>
<P>
   Cynics might say that the Beavers are being a bit hasty in their
dreams of a bowl berth. After all, their upcoming schedule is
brutal, beginning with today's game against 16th-ranked Arizona,
then moving on to Washington, California, second-ranked UCLA and
11th-ranked Oregon. And with victories over Nevada, Baylor, Utah
State and Stanford, the Beavers have yet to beat a good team.
</P>
<P>
   But Oregon State hasn't had a record this good at the midway
point of the season since 1968, so forgive the Beavers their
indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time since the late '60s, there is a genuine
level of excitement for the fans,'' Barnhart said. ``People are
jumping on for the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   The Beavers have been in a similar position before, however. In
1988, under  &UR; Dave Kragthorpe, they started 3-2, only to finish
4-6-1. In 1989, they were 4-3-1 and finished 4-7-1. And in 1993,
under  &UR; Jerry
 &UR; Pettibone, the Beavers started 3-3 and finished 4-7.
</P>
<P>
   That's why today's game against Arizona is huge for Coach  &UR; Mike
Riley and his staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've proven we can compete, now we have to get the big
breakthrough win to convince people we're for real,'' Barnhart
said. &QL; 
A simple answer &QL; 
Earlier this week, Oregon Coach  &UR; Mike Bellotti was asked why his
11th-ranked Ducks haven't earned more respect nationally. After
all, they have one of the nation's best quarterbacks,  &UR; Akili Smith,
who leads one of the country's most explosive offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, we're not the biggest media market in the world,''
Bellotti said. ``It's hard not to consider us (as a top team).
We're not only winning games, but we're doing it in a manner that's
fairly convincing. We just have to educate everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Ducks (5-0) want to educate people, they should start by
beating a good team. Of Oregon's five opponents, none has a winning
record now, and together they have a mark of 11-18.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks have a chance to prove they are for real today when
they visit second-ranked UCLA in a game that figures to test the
durability of the stadium's scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams are averaging around 50 points and look similar
offensively. That's no surprise, because UCLA Coach  &UR; Bob Toledo
spent six years as the offensive coordinator at Oregon and was
succeeded by Bellotti.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears a lot of the stuff we used when I was there they've
kept, and a lot of the same things I'm doing here at UCLA,'' Toledo
said. &QL; 
Stormin' in Norman  &QL; 
Two things are non-negotiable to Oklahoma football fans. A chicken
fried steak should be tender enough to cut with a fork. And the
Sooners should win nearly every Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Well, a good chicken fried steak is still common enough in the
state, but victories are another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Since  &UR; John Blake became head coach nearly three years ago, the
Sooners are 8-19. This year, they have a 2-3 mark, including a 34-3
loss last week to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   There is much speculation that this is the final year for Blake,
a former assistant with the Dallas Cowboys under  &UR; Barry Switzer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ``Daily Oklahoman'' columnist  &UR; Barry Tramel made it
clear that he doesn't think Blake is head coaching material. ``Head
coaches must be sharp,'' Tramel wrote. ``Quick thinkers. They must
know what they believe in. They must be leaders. They must be
communicators. Blake is none of the above.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma has used five different quarterbacks this season. Last
week alone Blake made six substitutions involving three of them.
Blake was still waffling as the Sooners were preparing to play
Missouri today.
</P>
<P>
   Blake, who came to Oklahoma with the backing of Switzer, said
the criticism isn't bothering him. ``We've got a lot of pride on
this football team and the coaching staff,'' he said. ``We will
continue to fight. As far as the rest of it is concerned, that's
out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's one thing Sooner fans can cling to: at least their team
doesn't play Nebraska this year. &QL; 
Quick quiz &QL; 
Quiz time: Nebraska Coach  &UR; Frank Solich won five games at Nebraska
before losing one. How long did it take his predecessor,  &UR; Tom
Osborne, to lose a game? Answer below. &QL; 
Calling home &QL; 
The 1-4 Auburn Tigers are off to their worst start in 46 years, but
Coach  &UR; Terry Bowden seems to be holding up well under the pressure.
``When I get up in the morning, I'm more anxious to work on it than
the day before,'' he said. ``Some guys get so wrapped up in it,
they can't function. I'm not one of the them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden said a phone call last week to his father, Florida State
Coach
 &UR; Bobby Bowden, inspired him. ``He told me these things happen, and
if you can't handle it, you can't be a coach.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden signed a seven-year contract last December, and his job
seems safe. &QL; 
Quick kicks &QL; 
Texas running back  &UR; Ricky Williams earned the most votes in the
``Rocky'' ``Mountain News''' latest Heisman poll. Quarterbacks
filled out the remainder of the top five:  &UR; Cade McNown, UCLA;  &UR; Tim
Couch, Kentucky; &UR; Donovan McNabb, Syracuse; and  &UR; Akili Smith,
Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota plays at Ohio State today, where the Gophers haven't
won since 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Flashback:  &UR; Barry Sanders won the Heisman Trophy in 1988. He
scored 39 touchdowns that season to set a Division I record. Only
two other players have scored more than 28 _ Nebraska's  &UR; Mike
 &UR; Rozier in 1983 and Penn State's  &UR; Lydell Mitchell in 1971. Each
finished with 29.
</P>
<P>
   Quiz answer: Tom Osborne also lost the fifth game he coached at
Nebraska. His Cornhuskers were beaten, 13-12, at Missouri in 1973.
The Tigers' defensive coordinator then was a clipboard-toting,
30-year-old by the name of  &UR; Vince Tobin. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Kent Somers can be
reached at 444-8335 or at kent.somers &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
