<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NAU-MONTANA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAU FACES MUST-WIN SITUATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THE ARIZONA REPUBLIC  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Timing is everything, and today's match-up between Northern
Arizona and Montana in Missoula, Mont., might go a long way in
determining the eventual Big Sky champion.
</P>
<P>
   Today's loser likely will be out of the conference race, tagged
with its third loss in four conference games. Cal State-Northridge
(3-0) and Montana State (2-0) will be hard to catch.
</P>
<P>
   It also will be a homecoming for NAU Coach Jerome Souers, who
coached at Montana for 12 years, including eight as the defensive
coordinator. He's trying to remove most of the emotion before
kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a business trip,'' Souers said. ``It has to be that way,
but there is a lot of sentimentality surrounding this. But this
isn't a week to look back for either teams. Both teams need a win
heading into the stretch run.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are improving as a team . . . Montana is a good team that
is capable of exploding on anyone on any time.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the top quarterbacks in Division I-AA, Travis Brown of
NAU and Montana's Brian Ah Yat, could put on quite an aerial show _
if Ah Yat is available. He suffered a back injury a week ago, and
his status won't be determined until shortly before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Brown missed three games with a dislocated elbow, played about a
quarter last week and will get the start today.
</P>
<P>
   Souers said Brown is close to 100 percent, and that a key
element in the game will be the protection he is afforded.
</P>
<P>
   Montana Coach Mick Dennehy realizes that the return of Brown
gives NAU a big boost.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though they have shown improvement every week without him
in the lineup, they are now able to get back to more of the things
that they like do do on offense,'' he said. ``Obviously, that makes
them that much more difficult to defend.''
</P>
<P>
   Defensively, NAU's Afa Faraimo keeps turning in impressive
performances and is being touted for All-America honors at
linebacker. In six games, he has 43 solo tackles, 24 assists, three
fumble recoveries, a blocked punt, 5{ sacks and pass interception. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
