<HEADLINE>
BATES MIGHT START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, ARIZ. - Running back  &UR; Mario Bates won't know until right
before game time Sunday if he will make his first start with the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, who played at Arizona State, worked with the first unit
for the second consecutive day Friday because of starter  &UR; Adrian
Murrell's injured left calf.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing we have to find out is if Adrian is capable of
playing, and if he is, how well he's capable of playing,'' said
Cardinals Coach  &UR; Vince Tobin, whose team (3-3) plays the New York
Giants at Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Bates carried the ball for the first time in last Sunday's 20-7
victory over Chicago and scored on his second and third carries. He
would be backed up by rookie  &UR; Michael Pittman, a fourth-round pick
from Fresno State who had 17 carries for 56 yards against the
Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect them to be gangbusters,'' Tobin said of Bates
and Pittman.
</P>
<P>
   Bates, a fifth-year pro, has 40 career starts. But he has played
mostly on special teams in his first season with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plays are coming,'' Bates said. ``If Adrian is not able to
(play), it changes my role but not how I approach it. I'll be
spending the next (24) hours preparing myself the way I always
prepare myself. You always feel pressure if you're not prepared.
I'll be prepared.''
</P>
<P>
   Murrell said he hopes to play because ``I feel better today than
(Thursday).''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has a lot of confidence in Bates and Pittman, if he
can't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They show when they get opportunities that they can play,''
Murrell said. &QL; 
Still ailing &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback  &UR; Tom Knight will miss his third consecutive game with
a hamstring connector injury. He again will be replaced in the
starting lineup by  &UR; J.B. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't see the full-speed explosion, which is deadly for a
corner,'' said Tobin of Knight. ``You make one false step and it
can cost you a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Second-year pro  &UR; Chris Dishman, who was expected to alternate
with
 &UR; Jerome Daniels at left guard, reinjured his neck in Friday's
practice and also will not make the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I practiced the last two days, and everything was fine,''
Dishman said. ``I never thought a stinger would last three weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Tobin is hopeful both players can use the bye next week to get
healthy for the Nov. 1 game at Detroit. &QL; 
Car trouble &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unlike their NBA friends, Cardinals players aren't locked out.
But their union boss,  &UR; Gene Upshaw, was locked out of his rental
car during a routine visit to the team's Tempe training facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better me than the players, that's for sure,'' said Upshaw,
the executive director of the NFL Players Association. &QL; 
Back home &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murrell was asked if he is looking forward to returning this
weekend to New York, where he starred for the Jets, the other
tenant in Giants Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only because it's a divisional game and it's important,'' he
said. ``Besides, they aren't my fans. Giants fans are a whole
different crowd.  &UR; Dave (Brown, quarterback) has got to be the guy
who's worried, man. I bet he won't take off his helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who started last season as the Giants quarterback before
an injury cost him the rest of the season and his job in New York,
isn't a bit worried about the Big Apple's rambunctious fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take my helmet off . . . but I'm not very smart,'' he
said. ``Actually, it will be good to go home again. I haven't been
there since early July, and it will be good to see my family and
friends again. The crowd reaction to me will probably be mixed.'' &QL; 
Deep thoughts &QL; 
Few of the Cardinals have found success in Giants Stadium, but
receiver  &UR; Frank Sanders has had good days and remembers the 70-yard
touchdown pass he caught from  &UR; Jake Plummer last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started thinking about that the other day,'' Sanders said.
``It's amazing, really. The field is turf _ I don't like turf _ and
it's always cold _ I don't like cold _ but somehow God has blessed
me when I go there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I catch one ball for 9 yards and we win, it will still be
more important to me than having a big day personally.'' &QL; 
Staff writers Tim Tyers and Lee Shappell contributed to this
report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
