<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-OUTDOORS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALLEY ANGLER ON ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society (BASS) decided
to come West with a regional tournament schedule more than a year
ago, almost everyone figured that  &UR; John Murray of Phoenix would be
one of the qualifiers for the BassMaster Classic, the most famous
bass tournament in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Endorsements earned from that tournament can make a winner's
career, providing him stable income for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I finish ahead of John in the final (regional) standings,
I'll go to the Classic,'' said the Valley's  &UR; Greg Hines, who was
one of four regional qualifiers.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble was that Murray never was a factor. He did poorly on
the Delta near San Francisco, finished well at Lake Powell, then
shot craps at Lake Havasu and Elephant Butte Reservoir in New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Murray wondered what happened. He is regarded as perhaps the
best bass fisherman in the West. And his winning record in western
tournaments endorses that belief.
</P>
<P>
   Well, the second year of the Western Region has begun on the
Columbia River in Washington. And Murray definitely is in the
running.
</P>
<P>
   He finished third, won a Ranger bass boat and put himself in a
position to be a front-runner in qualifying for the Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Like stock-car racing, qualifying for the Classic depends on
consistency. Qualifiers don't have to win a tournament, just finish
high in each of the four. Murray has started well, finishing behind
two Oregon anglers who don't figure to do that well when the event
heads farther south.
</P>
<P>
   Murray caught 33 pounds, 8 ounces of bass, all smallmouth. His
nearest Arizona competition came from  &UR; Chris Peebles of Tucson, who
was 18th.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used a conservative approach,'' Murray said. ``I didn't run
all over the river. I got a limit every day at a spot almost
identical to the structure at Roosevelt (Lake in Arizona).''
</P>
<P>
   One of the smallmouth weighed five pounds, which is huge for
that area.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said he found a shelf with a drop-off that had ridges.
That's where the fish were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used Carolina-rigged Zipper Worms and Yamamoto grubs to
catch the fish,'' he said. ``This feels a lot better than last
year.'' &QL; 
Upper dwellings to open &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you've never visited the cliff dwellings of ancient Salado
Indians near Roosevelt Lake at Tonto National Monument, you've
missed an excellent experience.
</P>
<P>
   The lower dwellings, accessible by paved trail, are open
year-round. But the upper dwellings, a three-mile round trip, is
spectacular.
</P>
<P>
   The guided upper-dwelling tours, limited to 15 people with
reservations, begin Nov. 7 on Saturdays, Sundays and Thursdays.
Beginning Jan. 9, the tours will be offered on those three days
plus Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the National Park Service will interpret Sonoran
Desert ecology and the prehistoric Salado people who inhabited it.
The 40-room upper dwelling, occupied from about 1250 to 1450 A.D.,
is one of the best preserved Salado sites. It also offers a
spectacular view of the Tonto Basin below.
</P>
<P>
   There is no charge for the tours, but there is a $4 entrance fee
for vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The climb to the upper ruins is rather strenuous.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, call (520) 467-2241. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be contacted at 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
