<SLUG> BC-FBC-ABNER-HAYNES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABNER HAYNES HONORED BY SCHOOL WHERE HE ENCOUNTERED RACIAL
INDIGNITIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENTON, Texas _ A crowd began gathering around Abner Haynes as
he talked.
</P>
<P>
   He sounded like a preacher, his hands gesturing emphatically as
he talked of his playing days at North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 40 years had passed and instead of his touchdown rushes,
his American Football League days and his many awards, he talked of
a day he always wanted to forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember a couple of guys burned my No. 28 at the student
union,'' Haynes said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not a unique experience as an African-American trying to
integrate North Texas football in the racially turbulent late
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   He thought of the moment Thursday at a reception given by UNT in
his honor because of the sweet irony that moment represents.
</P>
<P>
   His No. 28 will once again hang at UNT, only this time in honor.
Almost 40 years later, Haynes has been invited back to UNT for the
retirement of his number during halftime of tonight's game at 6:35
p.m. at Fouts Field against Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played here, in my wildest dreams, I never imagined
this,'' Haynes said. ``I remember my daddy telling me that playing
here was an honor because I had been given a chance to affect so
many people.''
</P>
<P>
   A fork clinked against a glass, and then all glasses raised in
unison. His proof waited before him in a multitude of faces that
had stopped by to say thanks.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks, said a school cheerleader from back then, for helping to
open doors and minds. Thanks, said Kansas City Chiefs owner Lamar
Hunt, for signing with an upstart Dallas Texans franchise and being
such a classy player. Thanks, said his wife, Lupe Gonzalez, for
always being an inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``To see how many people he touched shouldn't surprise me,''
Gonzalez said, ``but it still does. He has quite a story.''
</P>
<P>
   So, listen. Let Haynes tell his story.
</P>
<P>
   Let him tell of being denied a dorm room, of being showered with
racial slurs by opposing teams, of being in fear during games
because of his skin color.
</P>
<P>
   Then listen as he says, thanks: ``I always have been thankful to
this university for giving me a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He signed with North Texas in 1956, mainly because his father,
Bishop F.L. Haynes, convinced him to. Abner Haynes had wanted to
avoid trouble.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year at North Texas, in a freshman game in
Corsicana, trouble found him.
</P>
<P>
   A riot had started, angry opposing fans trying to attack him.
Haynes left that field with a human shield created by his teammates
as his only protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got on the bus and all of my white teammates were in shock.
They hadn't seen white people act like that,'' Haynes said. ``They
started coming to me one-by-one crying, saying: `Abner, we're
sorry. We didn't know it was like this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said: `You don't have to do this. You ain't them. We're a
team.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His team went 21-9-1 from 1957-59, bonded by both talent and
adversity. Haynes finished with 1,864 rushing yards.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of them, the best one of them, only he wasn't: He
couldn't live on campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to live in the black part of town, and I'd hitchhike out
here every day,'' Haynes said.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't eat in the dorms.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to go to the black part of town and find a cafe, sleep
30 minutes and then start hitchhiking back,'' Haynes said.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Church members would send me little notes with $2, $3 in there
and I started feeling like I wasn't just representing myself. I was
representing a whole lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   He has represented them well. He was selected AFL player of the
year in 1960, his first season, and had an AFL title by 1962. He
finished his pro career with 4,630 yards rushing and 46 rushing
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   The Texans became the Chiefs, and his number was retired with
them. He was honored by the NCAA in 1985 with the Silver
Anniversary Award for living a distinguished life after an
outstanding collegiate athletic career.
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back to where it all started tonight. The university
that once wouldn't feed him was now holding a reception in his
honor, the dorms that wouldn't house him were now welcoming him,
and the crowds that once jeered him will probably be cheering for
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just shows what is possible,'' Haynes said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
