<HEADLINE>
RONNING'S LINE MAY KEEP ROENICK WITH TKACHUK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - A lot of attention has been focused on the
line combination of  &UR; Keith Tkachuk and  &UR; Jeremy Roenick and whether
the two stars can coexist on one line with only puck.
</P>
<P>
   The answer may have nothing to do with them, however, but rather
how well the Coyotes' other top line continues to produce.
</P>
<P>
   If center  &UR; Cliff Ronning and wingers  &UR; Greg Adams and  &UR; Rick
Tocchet keep showing the chemistry they displayed during Thursday's
5-2 rout of Colorado, Roenick and Tkachuk will have no choice but
to try to make it work on their own, along with gritty right wing
 &UR; Dallas Drake.
</P>
<P>
   Ronning said he thinks his line, which produced a goal and three
assists, is a match made in heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some chances in the first game (a 4-1 loss Sunday to
Ottawa), but we weren't really clicking on the passes. We were a
little bit off,'' he said. ``But I felt it was just a matter of
time. All you've got to do is get those guys the puck one time
clean, and they're going to put it in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hoping there's going to be some good things to come. We
enjoy playing on the same line, and we just seem to click. . . . We
want to be able to help our big stars and take some heat off of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronning and Tocchet are simply picking up where they left off
last season, when the duo combined for 46 points (15 goals, 31
assists) during the Coyotes' final 32 regular-season games. The
addition of the veteran Adams, a good finisher with skilled moves,
only figures to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're looking good,'' Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld said. ``When our
other top guns start getting untracked, it's only going to be that
much better.'' &QL; 
Put a cork in it &QL; 
After two games, center  &UR; Bob Corkum already ranks among NHL
leaders, having won 23 faceoffs. He was 12 for 20 against Colorado
and 11 for 17 against Ottawa. And in both games, he was sent out to
take a majority of the critical draws when the puck was dropped in
the offensive zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where you can have your best offensive people
on the ice, but if you lose the draw, it's behind the net or it's
up on the wing and the other team is breaking out,'' Schoenfeld
said. ``I want to make sure we come up with possession on the
faceoff and try to get scoring chances from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go with your gut sometimes. You go with what works, like a
Corkum, who's always a steady guy.'' &QL; 
Opening Night III &QL; 
Because the Coyotes have had three days off between each of their
first three games, all of them on home ice, Schoenfeld said it's
like playing three different opening nights, which is good and bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the length of time we have to play three
games,'' he said. ``To lose (to Colorado) and then have another
three days before the next one (Monday against Boston), you'd end
up driving yourself crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot easier once you're into a
three-games-in-five-nights situation. You go through a little bit
of withdrawal this way.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 0128EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
