<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2492 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     10-17 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES HAVE MORE TO LOSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a cold, damp Sunday night in the South Bronx, seventh game
of the World Series, ninth inning. Moments like this, the New York
Yankees have owned for three-quarters of a century.
</P>
<P>
   So why are the San Diego Padres crouched on the third-base
dugout steps, poised for an on-the-field party while long-faced
Yankees slouch on their bench?
</P>
<P>
   This October, more than any other, was supposed to belong to New
York.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Trevor Hoffman stomping a path to the pitcher's mound
for the bottom of the ninth, about to finish off the Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   This was supposed to be the night New York won its 125th game of
1998, laying claim to the title, Greatest Yankees of Them All.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Fox TV filling the precious minutes between
half-innings with a video jubilee of Kevin Brown strikeouts, Ken
Caminiti backhanders, Tony Gwynn gappers and Jim Leyritz home runs?
</P>
<P>
   This, their second World Series in three years, was supposed to
mark the new Yankees dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   So why is the guy who cues up the postgame ``New York, New
York'' tossing that tape aside, realizing ``One for My Baby'' might
be a more appropriate song to send this Yankee Stadium crowd home?
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks couldn't lose.
</P>
<P>
   So what in the name of Brian Boehringer went wrong?
</P>
<P>
   What happened is that this October, which began as a referendum
on the Yankees, has been taken over by the Padres. By Brown,
Leyritz, Sterling Hitchcock and 65,000 fans in 59,000 Qualcomm
Stadium seats. And now the Padres are about to win their first
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   When they do it, we'll look back and say the Yankees went down
for the same reason the past eight teams with the major leagues'
best regular-season record failed to win it all.
</P>
<P>
   Their bats weighted down by expectations, they stopped hitting.
The 1990 Oakland A's, the '92 Atlanta Braves and the '95 Cleveland
Indians, regular-season leaders and World Series failures, averaged
less than three runs a game against the Cincinnati Reds, the
Toronto Blue Jays and the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it could even happen to the Yankees. By next weekend, we'll
realize the Padres were just the team to make it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Look at how the Yankees beat the Texas Rangers and the Indians
in the AL playoffs. Not with homers but with pitching, winning
games by 2-0, 3-1, 4-0, 4-0 and 5-3. The Yankees had David Wells,
David Cone and El Duque. The Rangers (4.99 ERA, 12th in the AL) and
the Indians (4.44, fifth) couldn't match up.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres (3.63, third in the National League) bear no
resemblance to the Rangers and the Indians. They won playoff games
by 2-1, 2-1, 3-2 (in 10 innings), 3-0, 4-1 and 5-0. Brown
outpitched Randy Johnson and Tom Glavine. Andy Ashby outpitched
John Smoltz. Hitchcock outpitched Glavine and Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres weren't afraid of a little pitchers' duel. So much
for that Yankees advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have David Wells on a season-long roll. The Padres,
by virtue of having finished off the Braves in six games, have
Brown ready to face him in tonight's World Series opener.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the playoffs' hottest starter (0.38 ERA). The Padres
played .600 ball against left-handers like Wells in the regular
season. So much for THAT Yankees advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are playing for a place in history. But seriously,
do even they believe a team with Chuck Knoblauch leading off,
Bernie Williams batting cleanup and Ricky Ledee in left field could
be the greatest Yankees of them all? That rallying cry won't cut
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, meanwhile, are playing for nothing less than the
survival of the franchise in San Diego, for voter approval in
November of a new ballpark. That's a rallying cry to be proud of.
So much for THAT Yankees advantage.
</P>
<P>
   When the Padres win it, we'll look back and say it was because
they were the right team for the right time, because Gwynn couldn't
hit .220 for an entire postseason, because Leyritz might be the
most ungainly specimen ever to fit into Cinderella's slipper, and
because a club with Hoffman in the bullpen really has to play only
eight innings a night.
</P>
<P>
   So we go to the bottom of the ninth. Last chance for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis chases a high Hoffman fastball and strikes out. Tino
Martinez flails at a Hoffman slider and strikes out. Ledee golfs a
soft fly ball to right field.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman throws both fists in the air. Wally Joyner bounds toward
him, arms spread wide. Caminiti glides toward them, his legs
pain-free for the first time in months. The catcher-cam attached to
Leyritz's mask puts the nation in the middle of the incipient
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   In right field, Gwynn has been waiting for this ball for 16
years. He squeezes it. Series over.
</P>
<P>
   Padres in seven.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
