<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NOTEBOOK-ARMIJO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESERT STAR WILL FADE FROM SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Wave bye-bye to the Desert Star Classic at Phoenix
International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   But don't put down the welcome mat just yet for the NASCAR Busch
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we're talking to NASCAR about a Busch race next year,''
PIR President  &UR; Buddy Jobe said. ``We want one. We think it's a
dynamite series. But whether we get one is 50-50 right now. If it
was close to being a done deal, I'd tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Jobe would (wink, wink).
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the only certainty is there will be no Desert
Star event in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The event brought together on one April weekend the NASCAR
Craftsman Truck Series, NASCAR Winston West and U.S. Auto Club
Sprints. Although the truck race was moved to the March 26-28
weekend, where it will share the spotlight with the Indy Racing
League _ the Winston West and USAC sprints disappear entirely from
the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Desert Classic) wasn't losing money, it just wasn't
reaching the potential we always hoped it would,'' Jobe said.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe believes moving the trucks to the same weekend as the IRL
race also will aid the growth of the fledging IRL, whose events at
PIR have been poorly attended.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think moving the trucks to the IRL weekend is a better time
slot for our race fans,'' Jobe said. ``And we also felt if we
combined the two, it would maybe boost up the IRL a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the only cure for PIR's poor IRL crowds would be to
add the rival Championship Auto Racing Teams series to the docket.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry about that, Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Jobe, however, remains adamant that the IRL series was the
direction to go when it was created three years ago by Indianapolis
Motor Speedway President Tony George.
</P>
<P>
   But if that were true, wouldn't fans be knocking down the PIR
door by now?
</P>
<P>
   They're not, but that's another subject for another day.
</P>
<P>
   As far as the Busch Series topic, all NASCAR officials will say
is that the 1999 schedule likely will be released within two weeks,
perhaps as early as next weekend during the Dura Lube 500 at PIR.
</P>
<P>
   If PIR is awarded a Busch date, the race would be held next Nov.
6, the day before a scheduled NASCAR Winston Cup race. A Busch race
also would displace a second Truck Series race held every year at
PIR during its Winston Cup weekend, leaving PIR with one annual
truck race, not two.
</P>
<P>
   A Truck Series official said next year's schedule will be
announced on Friday at PIR.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is we're pushing for a Busch race next
year,'' Jobe said. ``Whether it happens next year is anybody's
guess. But I think they would like to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens, the NASCAR Southwest Tour Series will
return as a support race next year during the Winston Cup weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting next year's IRL and truck pairing will be a Formula
2000 race. But the STAR Mazda series, which appeared this year with
the IRL cars, has been dropped. &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Team Menard has announced plans to participate in all 11 IRL races
next season.  &UR; Thomas Knapp is the new general manager, but who will
replace driver  &UR; Tony Stewart?  &UR; Robby Gordon?  &UR; J.J. Yeley? If I had
a few extra bucks to bet, I'd pick  &UR; Greg Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget today's 1 p.m. Race Against Drugs celebrity event
on a temporary oval track near First and Washington streets in
downtown Phoenix. Drivers will be racing half-scale NASCAR
machines. Indianapolis 500 winners  &UR; Arie Luyendyk and  &UR; Tom Sneva
are two of the participants.
</P>
<P>
   Lealand McSpadden is the newest member of the Arizona Auto
Racing Hall of Fame. It's about time. &QL; 
Mark Armijo can be reached at 602-444-8323 or at
mark.armijo(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
