<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2494 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN     10-17 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY LOSES IN SHOOTOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Everything the Los Angeles Galaxy accomplished the
last six months _ all the goals, all the wins, the level of
dominance never before seen in Major League Soccer -- came crashing
down Friday night in the cruellest manner imaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Another tense showdown with the Chicago Fire turned disastrous
after the final whistle as L.A. watched its season reach an abrupt
end in little more than a crapshoot, their hosts pulling out a 2-1
shootout victory before 32,734 at Soldier Field to nail down a spot
in MLS Cup '98.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Marsch -- the hero of the Fire's victory in the opener of
the Western Conference finals -- and Jerzy Podbrozny converted on
the final two rounds of the tiebreaker to send Chicago up against
D.C. United or Columbus in next weekend's championship game at the
Rose Bowl and leave the Galaxy wondering about what might have
been.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spoils it,'' Cobi Jones said of L.A.'s record-breaking
regular-season campaign. ``It doesn't matter how great a season you
have, if you don't make it to the final and win it, it takes it
away.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a typical Galaxy-Fire battle, defined by defense --
particularly Chicago's -- and determined by the Fire's better
fortune at the finish. ``It's a flip of the coin,'' said L.A.
defender Greg Vanney, who missed his shootout attempt after his
first touch wasn't strong enough. ``You might as well flip a
coin.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how the series has played out all season, with five of
six meetings coming down to the final minutes; this one might have
been determined earlier if not for an inspired performance from
Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman and a pair of posts, which teamed
to keep Chicago from scoring more than once.
</P>
<P>
   Twice shots by Ante Razov cracked into the left post -- once
after slamming off defender Joe Franchino -- but Hartman's best
save turned against him, just like in the opener. It occurred in
the 31st minute, after a long pass from C.J. Brown got caught in
the wind, floating over Robin Fraser and leaving Razov one-on-one
against the goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman dove to push it aside, but Peter Nowak -- following up
the play -- ripped the rebound into the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``C.J. played the ball where I expected he'd play it, but the
wind put it over my head,'' Fraser said. ``These things happen.
Hopefully, they never happen in a big game, but it turned out,
obviously, to be a fatal mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy, which dominated the opener but couldn't penetrate
the Fire defense, pulled even six minutes later when Chicago left
Danny Pena alone in their box. Jones, on the right wing, sent in a
cross and Pena had time to trap it, set it, look up to see his
options and calmly slot it home.
</P>
<P>
   L.A., which had promised a few new wrinkles, offered just one,
sending defender Ezra Hendrickson to the front line in place of
Welton. It didn't lead to much, L.A. managing few chances although
it was the better team in the second half, when it had the wind at
its back. That also meant little: It got off four shots on goal,
none in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some opportunities,'' Jones said. ``They handled us
pretty well, but we broke through their defense a few times, and
there were some lapses on their part that we needed to capitalizde
on and we didn't. We might have been a little out of sync.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't seem so at the beginning of the shootout, although
Jones' first try was stopped when the five-second clock failed to
start. He didn't get as good a touch on his second attempt and
fired wide after racing past goalkeeper Zach Thornton, but Welton's
blast gave L.A. an advantage on the second round. Thornton stopped
the Galaxy's final three attempts, by Martin Machon, Mauricio
Cienfuegos and Vanney.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman also started strong, stopping Nowak and Razov and
forcing Tom Soehn to fire wide. But Marsch chipped him and
Podbrozny's passing shot finished the Galaxy off.
</P>
<P>
   And the Galaxy was left wondering if the better team won.
</P>
<P>
   If you look at the teams, player to player, Jones offered, we
have the better players. But tactically, they were the better team.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
