r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-AZ-AZR &LR;      10-17 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-AZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA MEASURES INCLUDE WATER PROJECTS, ANTI-DRUG EFFORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 and ADRIANNE FLYNN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ States will have temporary veto power over any new
Indian casinos under a massive budget bill that also further
postpones a controversial Southwest border-entry program.
</P>
<P>
   The $500 billion budget also contains new border drug-fighting
money and approval for several water projects in Arizona, including
one labeled ``an environmental disaster'' by a conservation group.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill includes language prohibiting the use of
federal funds to study draining Lake Powell _ a plan once floated
by environmentalists to try to restore the Grand Canyon to its
natural state.
</P>
<P>
   But the foot-thick budget bill, which was agreed upon Thursday
but will not be voted on by Congress until Tuesday, is just as
noteworthy for what was left out.
</P>
<P>
   Omitted was Arizona Sen. John McCain's legislation designed to
create new competition in the airline industry by adding new slots
at airports, along with more air traffic controllers. Also absent
was McCain's companion measure requiring new environmental reviews
before commercial air tour planes could fly over national parks.
</P>
<P>
   The omissions were surprising given McCain's sway as chairman of
the Senate Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am deeply disturbed that the House leadership has killed
aviation competition legislation this session of Congress,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the session, McCain saw his giant tobacco-regulation
bill and his campaign-finance reform bill killed by senators of his
own party.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was not the only Arizonan who sponsored ambitious
legislation that came up short at the end.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz., couldn't move on his victims' rights
constitutional amendment, patterned after Arizona law, and also saw
his bill to ban gambling on the Internet stalled in the House. GOP
Rep. Bob Stump's crusade to impose a stricter burial policy for the
nation's premier veteran's cemetery, Arlington, stalled in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The budget bill, which averted a partial government shutdown,
was cobbled together on the fly as lawmakers sought to return home
to campaign for the election in a little more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Information about the bill was at a premium; staff members at
federal agencies said some elements of the final budget agreement
were scrawled on notepads and still had not been translated into
legislative language.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the federal Bureau of Indian Affairs, for example,
said they had still not seen a copy of the final language covering
new tribal casinos.
</P>
<P>
   However, White House and congressional sources said the tribes
won a partial victory.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Republican senators, backed by the Las Vegas casino
industry and the Christian Coalition, had pushed for a provision to
give states veto power for a year over new Indian casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration argued that Indians need a remedy
when states refuse to discuss Indian gaming. The tribes supported a
plan by Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt for his department to step
in and negotiate gaming agreements directly with tribes when states
decline to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   The battle ended in compromise. Lawmakers finally agreed to
postpone consideration of Babbitt's plan for six months _ which
means states can block new casino plans until then, but perhaps not
forever.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also:
</P>
<P>
   Mandates a delay of 2{ years in an entry-exit documentation
program on both the U.S. southern and northern borders. At one time
during negotiations, the program was to be delayed indefinitely
along the Canadian border but delayed only a year along the Mexican
border. Arizona members charged that was inequitable treatment and
argued for the common delay. Critics say the program, which will
require border crossers to fill out forms to enter or exit the
country, will create border congestion.
</P>
<P>
   Also being delayed, for two years, is a fraud-proof visa. The
cost of the new visas, which will replace standard border crossing
cards, will be higher than Arizona members wanted: $45 for adults
and $13 for children under the age of 15.
</P>
<P>
   Approves the transfer of a Colorado River basin agricultural
water project from the federal government to the Wellton-Mohawk
Irrigation District. The district repaid the government for the
cost of construction and is now taking title from the Department of
the Interior under a negotiated memorandum.
</P>
<P>
   Provides $690 million to keep drugs from entering the United
States, including $90 million to be spent directly on the Southwest
border.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the $90 million is for X-ray machines to detect drugs
hidden in vehicles. It also includes resources to bring three
Blackhawk helicopters out of mothballs for Customs Service patrols,
and $13 million to bring anti-drug technology to state and local
law-enforcement agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Provides funds to continue the Tres Rios effluent reclamation
project in Phoenix and creates language to prohibit federal funds
from being used to study the draining of Lake Powell. The draining
idea was floated in 1996 by the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Provides $15 million for a health center at Fort Defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Provides $4 million to purchase the Bar T Bar Ranch outside
Flagstaff for a park. &QL; 
Jeff Barker can be reached at (202) 662-7264 or at
jeff.barker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
Adrianne Flynn can be reached at (202) 662-7262 or at
adrianne.flynn(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
