A2500 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI &LR;      10-17 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUSKIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARNER LAST CAL HERO AGAINST HUSKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BUD WITHERS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ They were two football teams headed for losing
seasons. California's glory had come the previous year, with a
Pacific-8 co-championship in 1975. Washington, on the other hand,
was a season away from a Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Juxtaposed between those benchmark years was 1976, and an early
November game at Husky Stadium between the Bears and Huskies. In a
meeting of small consequence, the day would boil down to pride and
personal initiative, and maybe that explains why the hero was Bob
Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's married, 43 years old, and has children 14 and 12, and
Warner will drive down from his home in Burlington Saturday to see
if Cal might do it again. The Bears haven't beaten Washington since
'76 _ 15 straight games _ when Warner, as a 6-foot, 220-pound nose
guard, had 19 tackles and was named Pac-8 defensive player of the
week in Cal's 7-0 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a couple of games where I did reasonably well,'' Warner
said, recalling his Cal days, ``but that was probably by far my
best outing.''
</P>
<P>
   Huskies don't much remember that day, nor was there reason to.
Warren Moon, 19 years old then and the UW quarterback, can't recall
it. Washington was 4-4, Cal 3-5, and this was an undistinguished
game that would steer the Huskies toward their only losing season
under Don James.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, they rampaged to the Rose Bowl and started a
streak of winning seasons (21) that hasn't stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Taylor, the late Post-Intelligencer sportswriter, was no
more inspired by the game than the small crowd of 42,932. Taylor's
lead paragraph the next day:
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington and California, a couple of teams going nowhere,
spent the better part of a long, dull afternoon at Husky Stadium
heading in the same direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Warner had grown up in Arlington and played two seasons of
junior-college ball at Everett. At that time, both major-college
programs in Washington were in a state of flux, with Jim Owens
giving way to James after the 1974 season and Jim Sweeney stepping
down at Washington State a year later. So Warner accepted Cal's
scholarship offer.
</P>
<P>
   Warner was in the final month of his football-playing days when
the Bears came to Seattle for a slug-it-out affair by the lake. The
Huskies relied then on the pounding thrusts of 250-pound fullback
Robin Earl.
</P>
<P>
   Moon was a junior not yet popular with Seattle fans. The Huskies
that year completed 44.4 percent of their passes, a depth they
haven't visited since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran out on the field,'' recalls Ralph DeLoach, a Cal
defensive lineman on that team and later an NFL player. ``One of
our defensive tackles ran at the dog (the UW mascot) and kind of
barked at it. The dog ran away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our defensive line was pretty small, but we basically had the
idea that if we stopped Robin Earl before he got to the
linebackers, we had a good chance of stopping him.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was scoreless late in the first half when Washington
mounted four straight first downs and found itself facing
third-and-2 at the Cal 31 with 24 seconds and one timeout left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the whole stadium knew where it was going,'' says Ken
McAllister, a Cal cornerback now in investment counseling in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Earl went straight ahead but came up about a foot short of the
first down. There were still seconds enough for the Huskies to
signal timeout and send on the field goal team.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, however, Moon gathered the offense, reared up and
threw the ball out of bounds to stop the clock, turning it over to
Cal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe what he had just done,'' McAllister said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took heat for that,'' said Jeff Toews, former UW and NFL
guard now living in San Jose. ``That was a tough thing. Of course,
the rest is history.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the play this week, Moon said, ``I don't remember
much about it. I thought it was against Stanford.''
</P>
<P>
   And this was before Moon got knocked out. He was rendered woozy
by a hit in the third quarter and replaced by Duane Akina, now an
assistant at Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Moon re-entered, but the Husky offense went nowhere. The
penetration before the half was Washington's deepest of the game.
And finally, Cal broke the standoff on Tom Newton's 2-yard
touchdown run in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Says Warner of Moon, ``I just remember, at that time the Huskies
didn't utilize him as the throwing quarterback he turned out to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two years later, Moon is still throwing footballs for the
Seahawks. Warner works for a beer distributor in Burlington. And
Cal will try again to beat Washington, with the stakes higher than
they were that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It meant nothing,'' Warner says, ``other than to just play the
game, and for personal pride. For me, I knew I'd have a lot of
people _ parents and family and friends _ that would be there
watching.''
</P>
<P>
   DeLoach remembers what those people saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby Warner,'' he says, ``had the game of his life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
