student who was beaten in the dead of night, tied to a fence and
left to die alone, is mourned at his funeral by 1,000 people,
including many who had never met him. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   BRANDEIS-ANNIVERSARY (Waltham, Mass.) _ As Brandeis alumni and
friends gather this weekend to celebrate the 50th anniversary of
their Jewish-sponsored, non-sectarian university, they are
struggling with the question of how to position their institution
to play the kind of role in middle age that it did in its early
years. By Ethan Bronner. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   VEGAS-ESCORTS (Las Vegas) _ A federal indictment accuses a mob
family of trying to corner the escort service market in Las Vegas
with tactics from murder to high-tech computer hacking. By John
Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SPEND (Washington) _ A day after celebrating a
much-delayed agreement on a final federal budget package, Congress
did not have a budget bill in place to vote on and postponed
Friday's planned action on the $500 billion deal until next week.
By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ The 44 million Americans on
Social Security will receive a 1.3 percent increase in benefits in
January, the government announced Friday. That is the smallest
cost-of-living adjustment since 1987. By Robert Pear.
