<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBITAILLE LIFTS KINGS IN OVERTIME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ A year ago, the Los Angeles Kings and Boston
Bruins were the most improved teams in the National Hockey League,
making their gains by working hard and concentrating on defense.
</P>
<P>
   It became clear Friday night in the Kings' home opener, a 2-1
victory before a sellout crowd of 16,005 at the Forum, that the
formula for the teams won't be any different this year _ the NHL's
offense-friendly rules changes have yet to have much effect.
</P>
<P>
   It took a goal by Luc Robitaille with 2:13 to play in overtime
to break the stalemate, a 40-foot slap shot between the pads of
Boston goalie Byron Dafoe, an ex-King.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, if it hadn't been for a pair of rookies with six
games of NHL experience between them, there wouldn't have been any
goals. The Kings' 20-year-old Josh Green scored his first NHL goal
in the first period, and 25-year-old Finnish rookie Antti Laaksonen
responded in the second for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Stephane Fiset was solid in stopping 22 shots for the Kings
(2-1), and Boston (2-1-1) got nearly as strong an effort from
Dafoe, who made 25 stops.
</P>
<P>
   Kings defenseman Steve Duchesne saved the game for the Kings in
the closing minutes of regulation when he stood in the crease to
block a 10-foot shot by Boston's Sergei Samsonov with Fiset out of
position.
</P>
<P>
   The night began with the now traditional laser-and-fireworks
festivities that mark home openers, with an appearance by former
Kings star Marcel Dionne and the presentation of the Norris Trophy
to Rob Blake thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the game, exactly the sort of defensive struggle that
could have been predicted between the Kings and Bruins. For most of
the first two periods, the Bruins could muster only seven shots on
goal, though they were denied one goal by the length of a skate
blade in the crease early in the middle period.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins entered the game with a two-game shutout streak and
hadn't allowed a goal in the previous 151 minutes, 29 seconds.
Dafoe had started all three games for Boston, posting an
absurdly-low 0.97 goals-against average while stopping 91 of 94
shots.
</P>
<P>
   But the streak ended 10:50 into the game, with the Kings on a
power play after Bruins defenseman Don Sweeney was sent off for
holding Robitaille at 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   The play leading to the goal began with a strong effort by Yanic
Perreault along the left boards to keep the puck in Boston's zone.
Perreault got the puck to Robitaille, who passed the puck to Doug
Bodger at the blue line. Bodger fired a 59-footer at Dafoe, who
made the save with his right leg. Green, left all alone to the
right of Dafoe, pounced on the rebound and slipped it into a
virtually empty net.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes into the second period, it appeared the Bruins had
tied the score on a power play, when Rob DiMaio deflected a
blue-line shot by Darren Van Impe.
</P>
<P>
   But a review of the videotape revealed that just before the puck
entered the net Boston forward Chris Taylor, while tangled with
Blake, had his right foot into the crease, and the goal was
disallowed.
</P>
<P>
   The disallowed goal was the third involving the Kings in the
last two games. In their 4-2 loss at Vancouver four days earlier,
two Kings goals were disallowed, including a late controversial
call that cost them a tying goal.
</P>
<P>
   Given the reprieve, the Kings continued to play solid defense
but mustered little in the way of an attack of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, the Bruins broke through, with a goal off a
faceoff to the right of Fiset. A quick shot from the left circle by
Laaksonen beat Fiset, who appeared to be screened by teammate
Philippe Boucher and Boston's Ken Baumgartner, an ex-King.
</P>
<P>
   With the goal, the Bruins seized the momentum, almost taking the
lead one minute later when Fiset was caught out of position with
Jason Allison alone in front with the puck. Duchesne made the
goal-saving play, knocking the net off its moorings for a
comparatively harmless delay-of-game penalty.
</P>
<P>
   It almost wasn't so harmless, however, because defenseman Sean
O'Donnell's subsequent and needless roughing penalty with 1:01 left
in the period put his team two men short for 32 seconds, a crisis
the Kings were able to survive.
</P>
<P>
   Into the third period the game proceeded, with scoring chances
few and far between. The Bruins got a very dangerous opportunity
midway through the period, when Allison was left alone to Fiset's
right for a 10-foot one-timer. But Fiset calmly swatted away
Allison's shot.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' chance to win in regulation came with 5:14 left, when
Bruins defenseman Dave Ellett, reaching for an airborne puck,
clipped Steve McKenna in the face with his stick and drew a
two-minute penalty.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings were unable to do anything with the opportunity,
and had to wait until the extra period, when Robitaille caught
Dafoe off-guard by firing the puck on a rare outnumbered rush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
