<HEADLINE>
BATTLE OF PHONE GIANTS HAS A LONG DAY IN COURT  
 SHOPPING LIST SAYS DIAPERS; SAVING LIST SAYS CAP AND GOWN  
 INTERVIEWERS GLIMPSE MORE WITH THEIR EARS THAN THEIR EYES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (For release Sunday, Oct. 18) 
(js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the Microsoft antitrust lawsuit lurched toward trial, another
important technology case, consolidating eight suits about local
phone service, received a hearing from the Supreme Court last week.
</P>
<P>
   The complexity of the case _ oral arguments lasted two hours,
twice as long as the court usually permits _ should not obscure its
importance to consumers. The litigation has potentially slowed the
timetable for allowing residential consumers to choose their local
service providers, a step that could save Americans billions of
dollars on their phone bills.
</P>
<P>
   The question is whether the Telecommunications Act of 1996 lets
the Federal Communications Commission set a national structure of
rates that local phone companies can charge for access to their
networks. The government and long-distance carriers say yes. The
regional Bells _ Ameritech, Bell Atlantic, BellSouth, SBC
Communications and U S West _ and GTE would rather have state
commissions do it. A ruling is expected next year.
</P>
<P>
   The case may not have the Microsoft cachet. Still, only about
half of the nation's homes have computers, while almost all have
phones.
</P>
<P>
   _ SETH SCHIESEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shopping List Says Diapers; Saving List Says Cap and Gown
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom holds that boomers are not doing enough to
save for their children's college costs. A recent poll by Louis
Harris &AMP; Associates shows at least some parents bucking that tide.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted for Alliance Capital Management, a
money-management firm in New York, was based on phone interviews
with 1,006 adults. It found that more parents _ 55 percent _ were
saving regularly for college costs than last year, when 46 percent
said they were. They were also starting to save when their children
were younger: an average of 3.8 years old, compared with 5.1 last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because they have more recent experience with college
expenses, the youngest parents were best at saving early: those 18
to 29 years old said on average that they began when their children
were younger than 2.
</P>
<P>
   _ DANIEL M. GOLD
</P>
<P>
   Interviewers Glimpse More With Their Ears Than Their Eyes
</P>
<P>
   Body language, facial expressions, sweating patterns _ all
essential information for evaluating a would-be employee? Guess
again. Susan Straus, a professor at Carnegie Mellon University's
Graduate School of Industrial Administration, says that a job
interviewer can tell a lot more from the disembodied voice than the
live-and-in-person applicant.
</P>
<P>
   After mock interviews between graduate students and company
recruiters _ 29 by phone, 26 in person and 23 by videoconference _
applicants were appraised for conscientiousness, extroversion and
intelligence. ``The validity of interviewers' judgments of
applicants' traits generally was higher in telephone interviews
than in face-to-face or videoconference modes,'' she said. A
possible reason: On the phone, an interviewer cannot make judgments
based on physical stereotypes.
</P>
<P>
   _ CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH
</P>
</TEXT>
