<SLUG> BC-MCWIDOWS-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
 
McWIDOWS GROUP MOST AT EASE JUST SHOOTING THE BREEZE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DENNIS McCARTHY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It's 9 a.m. at the McDonald's restaurant on
Ventura Boulevard in suburban Sherman Oaks, and the McWidows are
checking out a tableful of retired men across the room to see if
there are any new, interesting faces they haven't seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, the McWidows agree. All the usual suspects. All married.
</P>
<P>
   ``How's Iser?'' Sara Roberts asks Dina Sofer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good,'' Sofer says, looking at her husband sitting with the
men.
</P>
<P>
   Dina's the only McWidow who has remarried, but the girls don't
hold it against her. Once a McWidow, always a McWidow.
</P>
<P>
   The only ground rule is that Iser stays over there with the men,
which doesn't seem to bother him too much.
</P>
<P>
   It's been going on this way for years now, even before the '94
earthquake really cemented their friendship, the women say.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, 9 a.m. sharp, the McWidows walk in and order a
cup of coffee, but no food, find a booth and sit down to shoot the
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later, they get up and get on with their own separate,
diverse lives.
</P>
<P>
   They have little in common except their widowhood. Different
political bents, different religions and certainly different
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what makes these morning meetings at McDonald's a
must, the McWidows say. It's like a therapy session and social
outing all rolled into one.
</P>
<P>
   And it all began years ago with one lonely woman looking across
the eating area of a fast-food restaurant and seeing the face of
another lonely woman.
</P>
<P>
   She must have looked pretty forlorn the day Kathryn Goldstein
walked up to her to introduce herself about seven years ago,
Elizabeth Sachs says.
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband, Henry, had been coming to this McDonald's
in Sherman Oaks most mornings from their apartment a few miles
away. He would drive; she would walk for the exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Now Henry was gone, and she was feeling pretty lonely sitting
here all by herself, sipping a cup of coffee in this restaurant
full of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come join us,'' Kathryn said that morning. ``We're an informal
little group. We call ourselves the McWidows.''
</P>
<P>
   Sachs found a smile starting to form on her face, the first
smile she felt coming on in quite a while. The McWidows: What a
marvelous name, she thought. She would love to join them, she told
Kathryn.
</P>
<P>
   That's how it began for her, how it began for all of them. For
Rosemond Demetropoulos, Millie Finell, Marion Kassoy, Sara Roberts
and Dina Sofer. One widow reaching out to another at a fast-food
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friendship'' is the word you hear most from the McWidows, but
what these women have runs deeper than that, much deeper.
</P>
<P>
   Sara could never have made it through those dark days when her
son was battling a malignant brain tumor if the McWidows had not
been there for her, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, there was a note or a card in the mail, a message
on my answering machine, a prayer being offered,'' she says.
``These were women who had been strangers to me only months
earlier, and were now like family, helping me get through one of
the toughest times of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   If any of them misses a couple of mornings, Marion and Millie
say, the phone starts ringing in their homes. ``Are you OK?''
Rosemond will ask. ``Do you need anything?'' Elizabeth will want to
know. It goes on this way for all of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all keep busy and have our own lives,'' Millie says. ``But
that hour in the morning belongs to the McWidows.''
</P>
<P>
   It took about a month after the Northridge Earthquake for them
to find their bearings again. About a month to come back to the
Valley after moving in with their kids or other relatives while
they got over all the shaking and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But once the ground started to settle down, and their lives took
on some sort of normalcy, they began to wander back into McDonald's
again to see if any of the other McWidows had made it back.
</P>
<P>
   They had. One by one.
</P>
<P>
   They hugged and cried, glad to see each other. Missing each
other. It didn't take them long to take up where they left off.
</P>
<P>
   Wandering in every morning around 9 a.m. to order a cup of
coffee, but no food. Sitting in their favorite booth and shooting
the breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, looking over to check out the table where the
retired men sat. Trying to see if there were any new, interesting
faces that morning -- instead of the usual, married suspects.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
