<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: ADD PADRES TO YANKEES' SERIES LORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the Yankees, it's as if the San Diego Padres were
a new theatrical troupe on the other side of the World Series
stage. Some of the new actors are sure to endure in the Yankees'
Series lore.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees having appeared in more than a third of all the
World Series since 1903, their opponents are always as much a part
of Series history as their own October icons: Babe Ruth, Lou
Gehrig, Joe DiMaggio, Mickey Mantle and Reggie Jackson. And now two
or three Padres will have their Series moments, for better or for
worse.
</P>
<P>
   Will a Padre (Tony Gwynn?) torture the Yankees the way the
Pirates' Bill Mazeroski did with his Series-winning homer off Ralph
Terry in 1960?
</P>
<P>
   Will a Padre pitcher (Kevin Brown?) dominate the Yankees as
Johnny Podres did in his seventh-game 2-0 shutout in 1955, the only
time the Brooklyn Dodgers won the Series?
</P>
<P>
   Or will a Padre (almost anyone) be as embarrassed as Dodger
catcher Mickey Owen was in 1941 when he let a third strike get past
him in Brooklyn?
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also offer the possibility of a twist to the Yankees'
usual Series plot. Except for Lew Burdette, a late-season Yankee
rookie in 1950 who won three games for the Milwaukee Braves in the
1957 Series, the Yankees have never had an ex-Yankee haunt them in
the Series, but the Padres have four familiar ex-Yankees: catcher
Jim Leyritz, left-hander Sterling Hitchcock, outfielder Ruben
Rivera and right-hander Brian Boehringer.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, whose three-run homer off Mark Wohlers in Game 4 at
Atlanta turned the 1996 Series, could end up being the first Yankee
Series hero to become a Yankee Series nemesis.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have another ex-Yankee, sort of. Their left fielder,
Greg Vaughn, was traded to the Yankees during the 1997 season but
flunked a physical exam because of a damaged shoulder, killing the
deal. This season he was healthy enough to hit 50 homers.
</P>
<P>
   In winning a record 23 of 34 Series, the Yankees have conquered
eight other National League franchises _ the Dodgers (both in
Brooklyn and Los Angeles), the Giants (both in New York and San
Francisco), the Cardinals, the Braves (both in Milwaukee and
Atlanta), the Reds, Cubs, Pirates and Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Cardinals hold a Series edge on the Yankees, 3-2,
winning in 1926, 1942 and 1964 against losses in 1928 and 1943.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are 8-3 in Series against the Dodgers, 5-2 against
the Giants, 2-1 against both the Braves and the Reds, 2-0 against
the Cubs, 1-1 against the Pirates and 1-0 against the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Padres, who lost to the Detroit Tigers in five games in
1984 in their only other Series appearance, have an opportunity for
their players to be chiseled into Series lore as so many other
Yankee opponents have, good or bad.
</P>
<P>
   Long before Casey Stengel managed the Yankees to seven victories
in 10 Series (including five consecutive triumphs from 1949 through
1953), he was remembered as the New York Giants' center fielder who
hit an inside-the-park home run in the 1923 Series opener at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning of the seventh game in 1926, Grover
Cleveland Alexander shook off a hangover from the night before,
shuffled out of the Cardinals' bullpen at the Stadium, struck out
second baseman Tony Lazzeri with the bases loaded, and preserved a
3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Waner, Lloyd Waner and their Pirate teammates were awed in
1927 when Ruth, Gehrig and the rest of Murderers Row took batting
practice the day before the Series that the Yankees swept.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Root was the Cubs' pitcher at Wrigley Field in 1932 when
Babe Ruth did or did not ``call'' his home run; some say the Babe
pointed to the center field seats, others say he pointed at Root.
</P>
<P>
   Cookie Lavagetto, a Dodger pinch-hitter, broke up Bill Bevens'
no-hitter with a two-out ninth-inning double at Ebbets Field for a
2-1 victory; Bevens had walked two previous batters, one
intentionally.
</P>
<P>
   Don Newcombe lost, 1-0, for the Dodgers in the 1949 opener at
Yankee Stadium on Tommy Henrich's ninth-inning homer.
</P>
<P>
   Willie McCovey drilled a two-out line drive to second baseman
Bobby Richardson in 1962, completing the Yankees' 1-0 victory
behind Ralph Terry in Game 7 in San Francisco with Matty Alou on
third base and Willie Mays on second.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Koufax struck out 15 Yankees for the Los Angeles Dodgers
in the 1963 opener at the Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Barney Schultz, the Cardinals' bullpen ace, fired the fastball
that Mickey Mantle smashed into the upper deck at Yankee Stadium
for a 2-1 victory in game 4 in 1964.
</P>
<P>
   Burt Hooton, Elias Sosa and Charley Hough threw the pitches that
Reggie Jackson slugged for home runs at the Stadium against the
Dodgers in the 1977 finale.
</P>
<P>
   And now, at last, the Padres will be creating their own World
Series moments against the Yankees, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1139EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
