<HEADER>
A2561 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-ABOUTFACE-AR     10-17 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ABOUTFACE-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS ELECTION NEARS, A GOP LANDSLIDE SEEMS UNLIKELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Md., Wash.)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just over two weeks from Election Day, Republicans
are retreating from their hope that the White House scandal will
drive huge gains for their party, while some newly confident
Democrats now are daring to predict that they will even pick up
congressional seats this year.
</P>
<P>
   As a volatile election season enters its final stretch,
strategists in both parties said this week that the environment for
candidates seems to have returned to that of January, before the
scandal broke: Most incumbents are still widely favored to win, and
there are no overarching issues playing to one party's advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Many strategists in both parties agree that, for now, it appears
that Republicans, who hold a thin 11-seat majority in the House,
will pick up no more than a dozen seats there, perhaps far fewer.
These experts also expect that the Republicans will be short of a
net gain of five Senate seats, which would give the party the magic
60 votes needed to cut off a Democratic filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as late August, after President Clinton admitted
that he had had an affair with Monica Lewinsky and misled the
public about it, Republicans and Democrats alike boldly offered
scenarios of how the matter could cost Democrats dozens of House
seats and perhaps five Senate seats.
</P>
<P>
   But now, instead of chastising Clinton, many Democratic
candidates are waiting anxiously for results of a poll being
conducted this weekend for the House campaign of former Rep. Jay
Inslee in Washington state. Inslee is the only Democrat now
broadcasting a television commercial that attacks his opponent for
dragging out the impeachment inquiry. If the poll finds that Inslee
is gaining support, other Democrats may run similar advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as lawmakers who were stranded in Washington forging a
budget deal headed back to their districts to campaign this
weekend, there was great uncertainly _ and a feeling that more
political gyrations lie ahead. Political professionals and
candidates in both parties said they could not recall a year where
there was so much uncertainty over how to proceed so close to the
election _ or over what messages to push in the final days. The
next few days will be critical as candidates scramble to buy their
final waves of television commercials and put in place those
messages for the all-important close of their campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unprecedented in my experience how unsettled the national
environment is two weeks from a national election,'' said Steve
Elmendorf, the chief of staff to Rep. Richard Gephardt, the
minority leader. ``This thing could tip either way.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Brookover, who as political director of the National
Republican Congressional Committee offers a more upbeat assessment
than many in his party, said he expected Republicans to gain House
seats ``in the 10-to-15-plus range.'' His forecast of gains, he
said, was now ``not as big as in that last week in August but
certainly bigger than we ever expected last June.''
</P>
<P>
   Brookover's counterpart at the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee, Paul Frick, said, ``I feel fairly optimistic. What we
know right now is that the same races that we thought were in play
in January are in play today. We haven't had many additions to our
list of vulnerable incumbents.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a significant shift _ at least in expectations. Even
this late in the campaign, some Republican candidates were clinging
to the idea that the Clinton scandal would be their ticket to
Capitol Hill, said Tony Fabrizio, a Republican pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this fundamental belief that this alarm clock is
going to go off and everybody is going to wake up and say, `We
really despise this guy Clinton, and anybody whose been around him
we're throwing out,' '' Fabrizio said. ``It's just not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been forced to re-assess their prospects
because voters have made clear that they want the nation to put the
scandal behind it. And with the hardy economy and no galvanizing
issues to arouse the electorate, the dynamic seems to favor
incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that suggests a status quo outcome involves the
realities of the field this year: There are relatively few races in
which no incumbent is running, usually the most competitive
contests. Prospects for a major shift have also diminished because
there are well under 100 truly competitive House races this year,
probably fewer than than 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that we're holding our own is a real break for us,''
said Jon Hutchens, a Democratic media consultant based in Denver
whose company is handling about 40 races. ``The way this fall
started, we really could have been in a lot of trouble.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
