A2563 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-ABOUTFACE-AR     10-17 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ABOUTFACE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: of trouble.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some Democratic strategists are counseling their candidates to
come up with messages that do not simply attack Republicans for
trying to prolong an impeachment inquiry but meld that notion with
the idea that by emphasizing the scandal Republicans are giving
short shrift to important policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All it takes is one to start a flood,'' Saul Shorr, Inslee's
media consultant, said of the prospect that other Democrats may
follow his candidate's lead and denounce the impeachment
proceedings. ``Republican incumbents who are in marginal districts
with suburban bases outside the South should be concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than wait for the poll results on the Inslee race,
another Democratic challenger, Ralph Neas, in suburban Maryland,
began broadcasting a radio advertisement that castigates Rep.
Constance Morella for voting for an open-ended impeachment inquiry.
Neas has an uphill battle and clearly is hoping that the move will
enliven his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I favor censuring the president but then getting on with the
business of government,'' Neas says in the advertisement. ``The
facts don't justify an impeachment.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a resurgence of confidence, there is no reason for
jubilation among Democrats _ only relief that things do not look
worse. Few Democrats dare to boldly predict, as some did early this
year, that their party will retake the House. And most strategists
on both sides are still expecting Republican gains, but ones that
are more modest than even seemed realistic a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that the dynamics could shift yet again, Brookover said
in an interview on Friday, ``I've never seen a climate where with
17 days to go there's not a clear picture about what you need to do
to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And Hutchens put it this way: ``Here we are, two weeks out, and
no one has a clue either on an outcome or a solid handle on how
you're going to influence that outcome. The vast majority of
campaigns on both sides probably wish Clinton would go to Bulgaria
for a couple of weeks _ at least it would all be less
unpredictable.''
</P>
<P>
   While most candidates are now reluctant to use public speeches
or advertisements to try to turn the Lewinsky scandal to their
advantage, Democrats and Republicans are planning to use the matter
in more discreet mailings and telephone calls and other efforts to
embolden their hard-core voters and get them to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic pitch is that Republicans are unfairly dragging
out the impeachment inquiry; the Republican pitch is to link
Democratic candidates to a president who they say has brought
disgrace to the office and the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Party is about to launch a comprehensive radio
campaign that will be concentrated in black and Hispanic areas. The
advertisements will feature Hillary Rodham Clinton and Jesse
Jackson, who will implore loyal Democrats to vote. ``The
Republicans are hoping you won't bother to vote,'' Mrs. Clinton
says in one commercial. ``I'm Hillary Clinton and I'm asking you to
prove them wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   With recent polls showing a backlash against Republicans
pressing for the impeachment inquiry, the party's candidates are no
longer raising the matter in their commercials. But some
Republicans are still arguing that the scandal could play to their
benefit, particularly in conservative districts in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Significant gains for the Republicans on Election Day would make
it harder for Democrats to turn back any move toward the
impeachment of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to acknowledge it is to ignore the elephant sitting in the
room,'' Brookover said. Like some Democrats, he said the best
option for Republicans may be to talk about the scandal indirectly.
``It's a matter of putting it in people's faces, `This president
has done something wrong,' or alluding to it, `We need to deal with
it so we can move on.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since the party that controls the White House traditionally
loses seats in midterm elections, Democrats are already planning to
declare victory even if they suffer moderate losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``My benchmark is the six-year-itch,'' said Jill Alper,
political director of the Democratic National Committee. She laid
down the party line early by citing the tradition of voters getting
restless with a president and his party after six years. ``Losing
less than 26 House seats and losing less than six Senate seats is a
huge victory for this party,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
