<HEADER>
A2566 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WIS-WELFARE-ART-2TAKE     10-17 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WIS-WELFARE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAWS EMERGE IN WISCONSIN'S WELFARE-TO-WORK PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By JASON DePARLE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE _ In building a bridge from welfare to work,
Wisconsin, perhaps more than any other state, has prided itself on
doing things right. It has spent heavily and pledged lavishly to
give poor families the tools they need, from baby sitters and bus
passes to case managers and community service jobs. On paper, no
state has done more to replace welfare checks with workers'
supports.
</P>
<P>
   But a year after moving from the shelves to the streets,
Wisconsin's celebrated effort bears only an intermittent likeness
to the program of customized employment services outlined in
planning documents and praised from the Oval Office on down. In
practice, even supporters of the program complain that uneven
casework and unresponsive bureaucracies can make services
cumbersome, if not impossible, to use.
</P>
<P>
   Some administrative glitches are inevitable, of course, in an
effort to move tens of thousands of low-skilled, single mothers
into the work force. And despite their frustrations, many former
welfare recipients have achieved a kind of back-door success simply
by walking away from the program to find jobs on their own. Still,
the gaps between generous theory and bumpy practice are noteworthy
here because Wisconsin's ethos _ less welfare, but more help _ has
helped shape a national consensus on aid to the poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we see in Milwaukee isn't what we envisioned,'' said
state Sen. Alberta Darling, one of a half-dozen Republican
legislators who have balanced their enthusiasm for the program's
theory with frequent criticism of its practice. ``There have been
problems from the get-go, with child care and management systems.
We're not demanding enough of the people delivering the services
and there are a lot of excuses on the table that I don't find
acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   Administrative problems were just what the state was trying to
avoid when it privatized the program _ called Wisconsin Works or
W-2 _ in Milwaukee County, which accounts for 87 percent of the
state's 11,000 welfare cases. But despite the effort to import
business-world efficiencies, many of those in the program describe
their caseworkers as distant and distracted figures who neglect to
return phone calls rather than the partners in self-sufficiency
depicted in state manuals. Many recipients find themselves bouncing
between part-time or temporary jobs, suffering income gaps that
planners failed to anticipate.
</P>
<P>
   And the state's offer of subsidized child care, a crucial
support service, has foundered on the confusion between rival
agencies, one public, the others private, whose staffs and
computers often fail to communicate. This year, as many as 60
percent of the child-care placements begun by one agency were
invalidated by another, leaving thousands of bewildered mothers
with no one to care for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Albirta Glenn was left to search for a job on her own, though
she lacked child care and was facing an eviction threat. When
Sheila Baker was laid off, she did not look to her caseworker for
help. ``They don't return phone calls,'' she said. ``I'll find a
job better working with myself than working with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ta-Tanisha Powell had so many problems getting her child care
approved that she left her job to care for her son herself. Indeed,
the bureaucratic foul-ups forced her back on the welfare rolls,
after she had proudly worked her way free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just really frustrated now, ladies,'' she said, in tears
at a recent meeting with the two child care officials who share
authority over her case. ``I've been working for six years and I
never had to deal with anything like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the snags of its start-up year, Wisconsin Works enjoys
broad support. It has cut the rolls by 70 percent in the last year
alone, while producing no sign of the surging deprivation that some
critics feared.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Gov. Tommy Thompson cited the decline in
the number of welfare recipients as compelling evidence of the
program's success. ``I'm extremely happy,'' Thompson said. ``We
expected about 36,000 cases left on the rolls, and we're down to
10,875. It's exceeded any and all expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, a three-term Republican who has staked much of his
reputation on Wisconsin Works, acknowledged that ``we've had some
problems,'' particularly with child care. But he called them
inevitable growing pains during ``the biggest change in social
welfare policy in 60 years,'' and he said he had moved quickly to
fix them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking that into consideration, it's been handled extremely
well,'' Thompson said. ``There should be no apologies.''
</P>
<P>
   J. Jean Rogers, the state official with daily oversight of W-2,
said the agencies were good and getting better with experience and
smaller caseloads. ``It's a matter of, `Is the glass half-empty or
is the glass half-full?''' she said. ``I think the customized
aspects of W-2 have room to grow. But I think there's 100 times
more customized service than there was'' under the old welfare
system.
</P>
<P>
   Darling said Thompson had moved quickly to fix problems once
they were identified. But John Gardner, a member of the Milwaukee
County School Board, argues that the inefficiencies were built into
the program. Each of the five private agencies that run the program
gets paid a flat fee, no matter how many people they place in jobs.
Each serves an exclusive territory where other agencies cannot
compete.
</P>
<P>
   And much like a health maintenance organization, each
theoretically has an incentive to withhold services. The less they
spend, the more their profits rise. ``In theory it's a privatized
model of efficiency,'' Gardner said. ``In reality it's a
politically gerrymandered cartel.'' But while Gardner complains of
``an abysmal implementation,'' he also said the hassles had
prompted many recipients to find work on their own. ``It works
despite itself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson has run experimental welfare programs since first
taking office in 1987. But Wisconsin Works, which went into effect
in September 1997, is by far his most ambitious effort. While every
state is now running a work program, W-2 is unusually bold. It
demands work from everyone who receives state aid, virtually
without exception. To help make that possible, it has financed
thousands of community service jobs, like clerical work at the W-2
agencies, at $673 a month. And it pledges abundant support services
to keep people moving up an earnings ladder. State officials say
the program will spend 45 percent more per person than the old
welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   But administrative difficulties were quick to arise. In child
care, one problem stems from the power-sharing arrangement between
the county workers who used to run the welfare system and the
private agencies that have otherwise displaced them. The private
agencies determine child-care eligibility. The county workers
review the arrangement and pay the child care providers. By leaving
a role for the county workers, the state sought to preserve their
jobs. But the result brought conflicts among cultures, procedures
and computers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of recipients left their appointments at the private
agencies, thinking their child care had been approved, only to find
a later snag. Many child care providers went unpaid, and some began
declining W-2 cases altogether. ``The Milwaukee community is
rapidly losing faith in our ability to make the child care
component of W-2-and thus W-2 itself work,'' Darling and five other
Republican legislators wrote Thompson in July.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Powell's case is instructive. Her problems began in March
when the county stopped paying her son's child care center for
reasons she has yet to determine. ``I went to pick him up, and they
said, `You're not authorized, you can't leave him here anymore,'''
she said. She then left a full-time job as a security guard for
part-time work as a nursing aide.
</P>
<P>
   But when she tried to return to full-time work a few months
later, she found herself in a Catch-22. The private agency
authorized full-time child care. But given her part-time schedule,
the county declined to approve it. ``I tried to call six times,''
she said, ``and I never got called back.'' After her make-shift
baby-sitting arrangements kept falling through, Ms. Powell was
forced to quit. Now she is unemployed for the first time in years
and awaiting a community service job. ``This infuriates me,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Buschmann, who oversees child care for the Milwaukee
County Department of Human Services, said glitches like those arose
in as many as 60 percent of the cases in the program's first six
months. Since then, the county replaced its director of human
services, added staff members and streamlined its procedures.
Though Buschmann said service had greatly improved, he added:
``It's not working well yet. We still have a ways to go.''
</P>
<P>
   While the child care problems are widely acknowledged, the
quality of the broader case management remains subject to dispute.
In theory, the privatized caseworkers are the all-purpose coaches
at the program's heart, routing clients to everything from job
fairs to drug counseling. In practice, many clients describe their
workers as impersonal clerks, urging them to look for work on their
own or warehousing them in group motivation classes that lead
nowhere. Though the program envisioned that each caseworker would
have just 55 clients, a study for the County Board of Supervisors
found some caseworkers with more than 150 clients.
</P>
<P>
   Buschmann, the county official, remains a strong supporter of
the program, but he agrees that it has provided less personal
attention than it advertises. ``Everybody talks that stuff, about
the `individualized approach,' `customer service,''' he said. ``But
in the first year, there was such a drive to move the mass through
the system, you couldn't do that.'' With smaller caseloads now,
Buschmann predicts the individual attention will increase.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Taylor, director of YW-Works, one of the five private
agencies, said customized casework was already on the rise.
``There's a lot more of that going on than people realize,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   William Martin, who runs the largest W-2 agency, Employment
Solutions, said, ``I feel pretty proud about the quality of the
casework.'' But he also said the amount of contact between
caseworkers and clients was ``all over the waterfront,'' depending
in part on ``the ability of the individual to articulate their
needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Crawford, 38, said YW-Works had made an extraordinary
effort to help her, as she faced the break-up of her marriage and
problems with domestic violence. First, it combined her community
service work with several months of psychological counseling. Then
it placed her in a training program to run a plastics-molding
machine. Eight months after joining W-2, Ms. Crawford has a
full-time job with a plastics company, starting at $7.40 an hour.
``They treated me with respect,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Glenn said she received little help when she applied to
her agency in August. At the time she was utterly destitute and
perhaps more troubled than her caseworker knew. Having moved to
Milwaukee three months earlier, she was living in a partly
boarded-up house that was under police surveillance for drug
activity by neighbors. Without birth certificates for her four
young children, she could not enroll them in school. But she says
her caseworker told her to spend 30 days looking for a job on her
own, with little help or supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Pat DeLessio, a public interest lawyer who helped Ms. Glenn
secure a community service job, said her client's case exemplified
the system's laissez-faire approach. ``They should have helped her
get the kids in school,'' Ms. DeLessio said. ``They should have
made sure her shelter was stable. And they should have monitored
her job-search closely.''
</P>
<P>
   Agency officials said they had tried to follow up with Ms.
Glenn, but she had not answered their letters.
</P>
<P>
   With or without customized service, many former welfare
recipients do seem to be working. But the work is often part-time,
low-paying and quick to end. There are no thorough studies of W-2.
But a study of the transition period, by John Pawasarat of the
University of Wisconsin at Milwaukee, found 75 percent of those
hired lost their jobs within nine months. Only 28 percent sustained
projected annual earnings of $10,000 for two consecutive quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baker's seems an illustrative case. Until the transition to
W-2, she had spent 11 years on welfare, giving little thought to
employment. But once she was forced to do community service, she
went out and found a job on her own. She became a dishwasher at the
Bradley Center, Milwaukee's major arena.
</P>
<P>
   But the work is seasonal. And once she found it, her contact
with W-2 essentially ended. Although officially she received ``case
management services'' for six months, Ms. Baker does not even know
her caseworker's name. Her pay stub shows earnings of $3,555 for
the first half of this year, or $483 less than she would have
earned in a community service job. She left the Bradley Center for
a housekeeping job over the summer, then lost it when her child got
sick. Now, once again, she is looking for work on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to work on trying to help people a little more,''
she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1151EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
