<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-LIPSYTE-CO     10-17 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SECRET LOVE FOR YANKS POURS OUT  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Because it was for so long a love that dared not speak its name,
the current outpouring of adoration for the Yankees is almost
poignant. Finally, Yankee fans are feeling secure enough to come
out. People who over the years sneered at the Yankees in public or
at least allowed those who slobbered over the Mets, the Red Sox,
the Cubs, the memory of the Brooklyn Dodgers, to prattle on about
the arrogant, smug, rich, elitism of the Yankees are willing to
identify themselves and flash pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   But why now, not two years ago when the Yankees won the World
Series? What turned the switch, what convinced closeted fans that
their sports cult was as worthy as any other, that loathing the
Yankees is a kind of self-hate? How did they finally come to
realize that their secret passion was really for the democratic
ideal, that rooting for the Yankees has always been about rooting
for meritocracy, possibility, the promise of a country where you
would be judged not on your neighborhood, toys or pedigree, but on
what you did when you stepped up to the plate?
</P>
<P>
   Beats me.
</P>
<P>
   I got this smart in the '50s when there were three teams in New
York, two of which were hypes. The Dodgers supposedly represented
family, neighborhood, earthy pleasures, integration and religious
tolerance. And yet, the subtext, wait till next year, also implied
a willingness to be type-cast as losers. The Giants were cool, the
Polo Grounds a favorite destination for actors and celebrities, and
their fans were insufferable in victory and unavailable in defeat.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees _ mostly according to the Dodger, Giant, Cub and Red
Sox fans who ruled the media _ were supposedly bloodless, cold, the
machine-age-modern-times juggernaut that won because it was more
interested in what went on above the bottom line than between the
white lines, the U.S. Steel of sports.
</P>
<P>
   Incredibly, even after the Dodgers and the Giants left town for
larger profits these myths maintained. In fact, some of the
Dodger-Giant affection was passed on to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone really knew better. The Yankees in their temple to
excellence in the South Bronx represented the chance of being
judged on your batting average. Yankee back-stories _ the Babe was
a throwaway kid, the Clipper was the high-school drop-out son of an
immigrant fisherman, the Mick was escaping the Oklahoma lead mines,
Reggie was an all-American hybrid, Billy was nuts and George was
desperately struggling out of his father's shadow _ were inspiring
to newcomer generations trying to make their own places.
</P>
<P>
   And here we are again, with Bernie, Boomer, El Duque. If the
team needed a sense of the city it represents, nothing could have
been more fitting than Chuck Knoblauch's now-amusing brainlock.
What is more New York than becoming outraged when you are being
wronged although you are absolutely right? This in a city where
honest citizens argue with cops, get handcuffed behind their backs
and almost never get satisfaction because there is no functioning
Civilian Review Board.
</P>
<P>
   This Yankee team has been praised for its collective, adult
play. The team has no overwhelming stars and the manager is an
authority figure with his ego in control. The owner, whose
manipulation, pettiness and fragmentation recalls some of the
city's mayors, has behaved so well that some sportswriters are
going soft on him, urging him not to sell the team and take several
hundreds of millions in profit.
</P>
<P>
   In such an era of good feeling, who wouldn't want to identify
with this team. But even winning the World Series should not be
enough. Now the Yankees must really prove that they are worthy of
the secret love that is not secret anymore. They need to stay in
the Bronx, improve their neighborhood as Steinbrenner promised 25
years ago and fulfill their promise as a positive force.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Bronx Borough President Fernando Ferrer's ``Safe
at Home'' plan seems like the best idea for the club's future. The
$535 million redevelopment of the Stadium and the area is far
cheaper than any midtown Manhattan plan. It includes the luxury
boxes for which Steinbrenner lusts and Yankee Village, a retail
area that would integrate the needs of the team and the needs of
the surrounding neighborhood. Public transportation and highways
would be improved and the Bronx Terminal Market turned into a
waterfront park.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, if the Yankees win the Series, according to reports,
the team's price tag could approach $900 million. Steinbrenner's
potential deal with Cablevision, which owns Yankee TV rights for
the next 12 years, includes incentive bonuses. There are those who
believe that if Steinbrenner, the devil we know, actually sells the
team to a corporate cabal of which Rupert Murdoch is involved, the
Yankees will become arrogant, smug elitists, the Microsoft of
sports. Then it may be time to truly, madly and finally with good
reason, hate them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
