<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-SANDIEGO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSPLANTED NEW YORKERS DUST OFF THEIR OLD YANKEE CAPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By SAMANTHA STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ When the San Diego Padres advanced to the World
Series, Alan Aiello went into his closet, pulled out his
30-year-old Yankee cap, dusted it off and put it on the dining room
table. The next morning, his wife, Gail, an avid Padres fan, put
two San Diego hats next to the relic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make your choice,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For Aiello, who was born in Brooklyn in 1947, a Padres-Yankees
World Series matchup has caused emotional distress and an inner
struggle about whom he is going to root for: the team that is part
of his soul, or the team of underdogs that has grabbed most of the
hearts here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a Yankee fan before I was old enough to walk,'' said
Aiello, who is president of Evergreen Wealth Management and has
lived in San Diego for 28 years. ``At 18 months old, my brother
would take me to Yankee Stadium when he was supposed to be
baby-sitting me in our house. I grew up loving Whitey Ford, Mickey
Mantle, Roger Maris. I was hoping this would never come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have decided only one thing,'' he said. ``My tailor is going
to take half of my Yankees hat and half of my Padres hat and sew
them together.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of this city is showing their colors for the Padres _
Mayor Susan Golding called for a blue and orange day on Friday _
there are many transplanted New Yorkers who have mixed feelings
about the Yankees playing in San Diego for a World Series title.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there is no consensus at the Brooklyn Club, a
group in San Diego whose members must either have been born in
Brooklyn or have attended a Brooklyn high school. Its 10 members
get together and enjoy their favorite New York foods, including
cheesecake flown in from Junior's Restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   A club organizer, 58-year-old Dr. Michael Grossman, has never
been to Yankee Stadium. He was a Brooklyn Dodgers fan at 7 years
old.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about the New York-Padre thing at our meeting,''
said Grossman, a chief executive officer for First Dental Health in
San Diego. ``It's more about being a baseball fan from New York. If
you were a Yankee fan and now live in San Diego, you will root in
your heart for New York. But being a Brooklyn Dodger fan is totally
different. I hated them for moving to L.A. They were the most
traitorous of teams. I want to beat the Yankees because the Dodgers
always wanted to beat the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Sal Rotolo, the new owner of Brooklyn Pizza here won't be
cheering for the home team there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yankees will sweep right through the Padres,'' said
Rotolo, 28. ``Look, it's true you can take the kid out of Brooklyn
but you can't take the Brooklyn out of the kid. I love San Diego.
But the Padres are not the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloria Penner, a local radio talk show host for PBS, grew up in
Bedford Stuyvesant and organized the Brooklyn Club. She attended
games at Ebbets Field in the 1940s with her parents, who loved
baseball. Recently, she moved her 93-year-old mother, Ethel Stern,
out of Brooklyn to a retirement community here. Her mother worked
at the Lord &AMP; Taylor department store in Manhattan until she was
85.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now she says she has two of the best teams in baseball to
root for,'' Penner said. ``When you are born and bred and educated
in New York, which is what I was as a result of the public school
system, from kindergarten to Brooklyn College, New York is
ingrained in your soul, your heart and your karma, and that can
never be extricated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though in San Diego there is a sense of pride for the
Padres, your heart will always be in New York. I am not going to
the game because I am a public person and I can't scream and yell
for the Yankees. I will be at home rooting for the Yankees in
private.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Sobell, a 51-year-old writer who was born in Brooklyn,
grew up listening to the Yankees on the radio with her father.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up binds you to a particular image,'' Sobell said,
adding that she is rooting for the underdog Padres. ``And to me,
the Yankees were special. Before I was 10, it was about sharing the
camaraderie with my Dad and a neighborhood boy, listening to the
voices on the radio, in secret, because we were the only Yankee
fans in the neighborhood. Now, the Padres playing the Yankees
brings me close to the memories of what I did with my Dad, who has
been dead a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Torrence, a history teacher at the La Jolla (Calif.) Day
School, said: ``I want the Padres to win. I'm a diehard Met fan. If
the Padres were playing the Mets, I would be rooting for the Mets.
I was born on the Upper West Side of Manhattan, and we moved to
Brentwood on Long Island. You will find that Yankee fans live in
the Bronx and Manhattan and Met fans live in Brooklyn and Queens.
The Yankees have won enough. Tony Gwynn deserves one.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
