<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For Want of an Ace &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In the four years of their modern resurgence, the Cleveland
Indians have never had a legitimate No.1 starting pitcher. That
missing link may very well be the reason they have not won the
World Series and are not playing the World Series in Cleveland this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We readily admit we don't have one of those dominant Cy Young
marquee guys,'' John Hart, the Indians' general manager, said.
``But we usually have five or six guys who are good. Maybe they're
going to pitch anywhere from 2 to 4. We've done it without a
dominant No. 1 guy. Does that keep you out of the World Series? No.
Does it keep you from winning it? I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   In their four successive forays into post-season play, the
Indians have started Dennis Martinez, Orel Hershiser, Charles Nagy,
Ken Hill, Jack McDowell, Jaret Wright, Chad Ogea, Bartolo Colon and
Dwight Gooden. At times some of of those pitchers were considered
No. 1's, but with the Indians they were past their prime.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we built our club,'' Hart said, ``we built it as an
American League team _ small ball parks, lack of pitching. We built
our club early on around offense. To win and still compete
economically, we thought we would sign starting pitchers that would
be able to keep us in games and hope to develop
front-of-the-rotation starters. Along the line, we tried to sign
some guys, but that didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians pursued Roger Clemens, John Smoltz and Alex
Fernandez as free agents and Pedro Martinez and Randy Johnson in
trades. They still await the arrival of a pitcher of that caliber.
</P>
<P>
   The system they have succeeded in building, Hart said, has
carried the club to four consecutive division titles and three AL
championship series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably not the perfect world, but you kind of have to
deal with what you have to work with,'' he said. ``There's not a
bottomless pit where you can go out and say we're going to have a
star at every position.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Thaw in the Union &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The strong union feeling about players who served as replacement
players in spring training of 1995 during the strike is apparently
thawing. The melting of bitter feelings can be seen in the
post-season shares voted by players on high-finishing teams. For
the most part, based on a survey of club votes, players have
treated replacement players like anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, for example, voted Shane Spencer, the home run
legend, half a full share based on the time he was with the team
during the season. Ron Reed of the Mets automatically received a
full share because he was with the team all season, but Jeff Tam, a
relief pitcher, was voted a share equal to the percentage of the
season he spent with the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Boston players voted pitcher Ron Mahay a one-quarter share as
did the Chicago Cubs with infielder Jason Hardtke. Pitcher Tom
Martin will receive just under half a share based on service time
with Cleveland. Catcher Mandy Romero will get a partial share based
on service time from San Diego and a $3,000 cash award from Boston,
where he was traded June 21.
</P>
<P>
   Among players who were not replacements, Randy Johnson, who
pitched for Houston the last two months, was voted a full share;
Jim Leyritz will receive $10,000 from Boston's post-season players'
pot and about 54 percent of a share from San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   A player automatically receives a full share if he is with a
team from June 1, but the Yankees voted Orlando Hernandez a full
share even though he missed that date by a couple of days. Hideo
Nomo missed by four days, and the Mets voted him a three-fourths
share. The Mets acquired Tony Phillips, Willie Blair and Jorge
Fabregas on July 31, but the players voted Phillips a
three-quarters share and the other two about one-third.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; An Eye on the NBA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The strength of the baseball players union has been its ability
to maintain a solid front among players and, in more recent labor
wars, player agents. Union officials are watching the National
Basketball Association lockout closely and were thus bothered by
the action of an agent in filing an unfair labor practice charge
with the National Labor Relations Board last week against the
basketball players union.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very troublesome,'' Donald Fehr, the baseball labor
chief, said, ``because such agents would not appear to understand
the most basic fact here, which is if there appears to be division
and dissension, there is nothing more reasonably calculated for the
NBA to take a harder negotiating position. They ought to know that
they're not operating in their own best interests or the best
interests of their clients.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say that baseball agents have never disagreed
with the union's bargaining position, but they have always kept
intramural disputes internal and never given the owners legitimate
reason to believe the union would develop fatal cracks.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
