<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-ASSESS-935&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MIDEAST TALKS BUILT ON MUTUAL DISTRUST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Israel)  (mk) 
 By SERGE SCHMEMANN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ The branches of the Wye River that embrace the
sprawling conference center where high-powered Israeli, Palestinian
and American delegations are cooped up for the weekend define their
challenge in elemental terms _ either figure out a way across now,
or tumble into muddy waters in six months' time.
</P>
<P>
   The leap does not seem so formidable in itself. What Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and the Palestinian leader, Yasser
Arafat, are being urged to do by the Americans is essentially to
agree to carry out long overdue obligations under the Oslo
agreement _ the Israelis, to cede another chunk of occupied
territory, and the Palestinians, to crack down on terror and hate.
</P>
<P>
   But a bitter 19-month freeze in the process has left each leader
acutely wary of the step. After all the rancor and international
criticism that the delay has created, Netanyahu must be able to
demonstrate to his critics that the gains in security justify the
loss of time and goodwill and the surrender of more territory.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, Arafat must show an increasingly skeptical public
that he is not simply being made a chump by the Israelis and
Americans, that he is really delivering the promised land.
</P>
<P>
   And as they stand poised on the edge, each leader must overcome
his deep-seated suspicion that the other will just pretend to jump.
</P>
<P>
   In the elaborate secrecy surrounding the meetings, there has
been nothing so far to signal whether progress is being made. There
were idyllic reports on Friday that Arafat, wrapped in his
signature guerrilla outfit, ambled over to the Israeli compound and
sat down on the verandah for a chat with a tieless Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But those familiar with what the two men really think of each
other exclude the chance that the tete-a-tete was evidence of a new
chumminess. Both are masters at political theater, and fully
conscious that such displays of casual contact are what the
Americans want. And if things did fall apart, each could then say,
``I tried.''
</P>
<P>
   If progress is not being made, however, it is not for lack of
horsepower at the Wye Plantation, the Aspen Institute conference
complex on Maryland's Eastern Shore where the negotiators have
gathered.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is scheduled to make his second personal
appearance at Wye Saturday, while Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and the director of the Central Intelligence Agency,
George Tenet, are full-time participants.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is being joined Saturday by his powerful new foreign
minister, Ariel Sharon, and Sunday by his defense minister, Yitzhak
Mordechai. The fourth member of the all-important ``kitchen
cabinet,'' Trade and Labor Minister Natan Sharansky, is there
already, insuring that if any deal is struck, it shall have passed
one major political hurdle already before it comes before the
Parliament on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   That is critical for Netanyahu, because it is certain that
whatever he does, he will have to face a no-confidence vote from
legislators returning from a holiday break.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, given the fury of Israeli politics, Netanyahu
has worked hard to manage the impression of what he is doing at
Wye. When his spokesman, Aviv Bushinsky, slipped out to give
Israeli reporters a briefing, it was to assure them that being at
Wye on Saturday would not violate the Sabbath _ that the Israeli
delegation did not plan to share its Sabbath meal with the
Palestinians, that Sharansky was prepared to read the mandatory
blessings.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has likewise come to Wye with virtually his entire brain
trust, including all his major negotiators, and made sure from the
first day to demonstrate his fealty to the Americans and his
respect for their proposals.
</P>
<P>
   For all the accumulated hazards and hatreds, participants note
that several conditions make the Wye gathering more auspicious than
past attempts to get things moving.
</P>
<P>
   One is President Clinton, who comes to the talks with high
ratings and an understood threat that if this fails, he will not
try again. Unlike last January, the previous time Clinton tried to
cajole the Israelis into a deal, when the U.S. Senate and American
Jewish organizations assailed him for leaning on Netanyahu, and the
Monica Lewinsky scandal had just broken, the president seems to
have full backing from all sides this time.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side, one potentially helpful development is the
promotion of Sharon to foreign minister and chief negotiator. The
veteran hawk is trusted by Israel's right-wing and religious
factions, and thus might defuse the most dangerous source of
opposition to a peace deal _ though, as Israelis were quick to
point out behind his back, he is just as likely to block any deal
he does not like. Netanyahu is also supported by polls that
indicate 82 percent of the Israeli public want an agreement at the
summit, and 57 percent support an additional withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   On the face of it, Arafat appears to be the weakest of the
three. He is sick and increasingly unpopular among the
Palestinians, and the latest Palestinian polls show that a majority
favor violence again. But in these talks he also carries one of the
few tangible aces _ the knowledge that if nothing happens at Wye,
he will proclaim a Palestinian state on May 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That is the deadline set in the Oslo agreements for reaching a
final settlement. And Arafat has declared that if no agreement is
reached by then, he is justified in going it alone, just as Israel
unilaterally declared its independence in 1948. The indications are
that he would get full support from most of the world, and that
even the United States would not stand in his way.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   What exactly is meant by a unilaterally declared Palestinian
state, nobody knows. But neither Israel nor the United States, not
even Arafat, really want to find out, because it would plunge the
region into a totally new, potentially very dangerous realignment.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Netanyahu's preference would be to begin some process that
would put off the deadline, preferably without setting a new one.
At the least, the Israelis would demand concrete assurances that if
they agree to a further withdrawal, Arafat would let May 4 slide.
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat has spent his entire adult life playing with a very
limited hand, and he will not release his solitary ace without some
very concrete assurances that he will get his state at some
specified time.
</P>
<P>
   The mutual distrust extends to every aspect of the talks. The
Israelis demand that their withdrawal be staged, and each slice of
land they cede be accompanied by concrete Palestinian steps against
terror and incitement. Arafat wants guarantees that if he takes
such steps, the Israelis will withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   The sense leading up to Wye was that so complex a deal, which
has eluded negotiators for 19 months, cannot be achieved within 72
hours. That sense has been encouraged by Israeli officials who have
tried to dampen expectations, telling all who will listen that it
is better to return with no agreement than another flawed one.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is certain that however things turn out, all will
claim success and victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each side will receive its pound of flesh,'' wrote one Israeli
commentator: ``Clinton will receive good television minutes, Arafat
will continue to accumulate points at the White House and in the
international arena, and Netanyahu will return home a victor. Only
Dennis Ross'' _ the indefatigable American envoy to the Middle East
_ ``will again pack his suitcases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
