<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal Reserve Cuts Interest Rates Again
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve unexpectedly cut interest rates by a quarter
of a percentage point, taking the unusual step of moving on his own
authority in between the central bank's regularly scheduled
policy-setting meetings.
</P>
<P>
   The move lifted the markets, which had grown increasingly
rattled by the spread of the financial crisis that began last year
in Asia. But it also suggested that the Fed is concerned that the
nation's long economic expansion could be endangered by the growing
reluctance of lenders and investors to provide businesses with
money.
</P>
<P>
   _ By RICHARD W. STEVENSON
</P>
<P>
   Charges in Olympic Bombing
</P>
<P>
   Two years after a pipe bomb exploded at Centennial Olympic Park
in Atlanta, federal authorities charged Eric Robert Rudolph with
the attack, which killed one woman and injured hundreds. Rudolph,
already wanted for his role in a fatal January bombing at an
abortion clinic in Birmingham, Ala., was also accused of two other
Atlanta bombings in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Rudolph has been the subject of a massive manhunt in the dense
woods of western North Carolina, where he has so far eluded
capture.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   Uniting Faith and Reason
</P>
<P>
   In an encyclical marking his 20th anniversary as pope, John Paul
II made a spirited defense of clear, rational thought, criticizing
those who take shortcuts to life's answers or who rely too much on
blind faith. Never ``abandon the passion for ultimate truth,'' he
urged. Philosophers, ``be they Christian or not,'' should ``trust
in the power of human reason.''
</P>
<P>
   He was unambiguous, though, about where that reason should
ultimately lead: to ``the truth of Christ, the one definitive
answer to humanity's problems.'' And he did not address one of
humanity's most divisive issues: abortion.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   FBI Opens DNA Data Base
</P>
<P>
   The FBI opened a national computer data base that holds
identifying information from the DNA of convicted felons. The new
system, which consists of smaller state-run data bases that are
linked by common test procedures and software, will enable DNA from
a crime scene to be compared with DNA from convicted felons in all
50 states.
</P>
<P>
   Crime experts hope the data base will lead to the earlier
apprehension of repeat offenders, including many rapists.
</P>
<P>
   _ By NICHOLAS WADE
</P>
<P>
   American Spy Arrested
</P>
<P>
   A 46-year-old retired enlisted man who had worked in both Army
intelligence and at the super-secret National Security Agency was
arrested by the FBI on charges that he spied for Moscow during the
last days of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   David Sheldon Boone was arrested after he was lured back to the
United States from his home in Germany by agents posing as Russian
spies who wanted him to resume his espionage career.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JAMES RISEN
</P>
<P>
   Prenatal AIDS Tests Sought
</P>
<P>
   Testing for the AIDS virus should be a routine part of every
pregnant woman's prenatal care, a panel of experts from the
Institute of Medicine recommended. Checking for HIV infection need
not be accompanied by extensive AIDS counseling, as now recommended
by federal officials, which some doctors find so burdensome that
they forgo offering tests. Treating infected women with anti-HIV
drugs cuts the risk of transmission to newborns by two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WARREN E. LEARY
</P>
<P>
   Plan to Save the Everglades
</P>
<P>
   The Army Corps of Engineers unveiled a vast plan to fix the
natural plumbing of southern Florida, restoring a more natural flow
of fresh water through the imperiled Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   The program would cost $8 billion and take 20 years. But many
questions remain. Will Congress and Florida's legislature agree to
spend the money? And will the plans to store billions of gallons of
water in huge reservoirs and underground aquifers work?
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NBA Cancels Games
</P>
<P>
   The first two weeks of the National Basketball Association
season were canceled as labor talks slowed to a crawl. The players'
union and the league lobbed verbal grenades at each other in the
dispute, which involves the distribution of about $2 billion in
league income.
</P>
<P>
   Some hope remains in the form of new proposals and a key
arbitration decision due Monday but league officials are weighing
the possibility of canceling more games in another week.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIKE WISE
</P>
<P>
   U.N. Gangs Up on Embargo
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, in a United Nations General Assembly vote, 143
nations favored an end to the American embargo on Cuba. Only the
United States, Israel and Uzbekistan said nay. This year,
Uzbekistan defected _ and some abstaining nations came around _ in
a record 157-to-2 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's official line, as global support nears the
vanishing point, is that ``sanctions are an important foreign
policy tool,'' but one foreign-policy expert is convinced that a
``sanction-happy'' Congress has clung to the embargo ``for domestic
reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   5 Theorists Win Nobels
</P>
<P>
   In a clean sweep of the 1998 Nobel prizes in chemistry and
physics, five professors at American universities garnered a total
of $1.96 million for their masterly applications of the arcane
rules of quantum mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   The physics prize recognized three alumni of Bell Laboratories
for discovering that when electrons are subjected to intense
magnetic fields they behave as if they had been split into thirds.
The chemistry prize went to a mathematician and a physicist for
finding ways to predict the nature of new molecules, including
potentially important pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MALCOLM W. BROWNE
</P>
<P>
   New Insulation for Airlines
</P>
<P>
   First it was airliner seats, then carpeting and other cabin
components. Now the Federal Aviation Administration says it's
airplane insulation that burns too easily and should be changed.
The agency said it would devise a new flammability test within six
months and then require new and old planes to meet it, although it
asked airlines to start work immediately. But they are wary of
spending money to meet a standard that hasn't been written yet.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MATTHEW L. WALD
</P>
<P>
   Big Layoffs at Merrill Lynch
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the nation's largest brokerage firm, sent a
shudder through Wall Street _ and New York City _ when it said it
would get rid of 3,400 jobs, or a little more than 5 percent of its
work force.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the recent turmoil in financial markets, the firm
said it was preparing for tougher times ahead. Merrill Lynch said
the job cuts would save $500 million a year. Other big brokerage
firms and banks are likely to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PETER TRUELL
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Spoils of the Budget War
</P>
<P>
   Schoolteachers, immigrants and the Pentagon emerged as big
winners after Congress and President Clinton reached agreement on
the $1.7 trillion federal budget. Weighty issues aside, some
lawmakers were quietly enjoying their success in slipping into the
huge spending bill several favors to constituents.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott had the duck-hunting season in
Mississippi and five other Southern states extended by 11 days,
over the objections of hunters up north. Rep. Mary Bono, R-Calif.,
got $5 million for a study of how best to clean up the polluted
Salton Sea in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jay Dickey, R-Ark., had $100 million inserted to build a
52-mile interstate highway in southern Arkansas. California
lawmakers prevailed upon negotiators to include $8 million for a
new forest-management program in the Sierra Nevada.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone came away happy. Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J,
failed to prolong a big drug maker's monopoly on the popular
allergy pill Claritin.
</P>
<P>
   And Rep. James Walsh, R-N.Y., wanted to cut the cost of imported
Italian wool to garment makers by $10 million to help offset a
tariff that Canadian rivals do not have to pay. But all Walsh could
wangle was a promise that the Labor Department will study the
issue.
</P>
<P>
   _ By ERIC SCHMITT
</P>
<P>
   The Unbearable Badness of Being
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, bad is good.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Museum of Bad Art, which is housed in a dank,
concrete basement next to the men's room of the community theater
in the Boston suburb of Dedham.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll through the museum's permanent collection tends to
bring expressions of dismay from many visitors, as they pass works
like ``Lucy in the Field With Flowers,'' a portrait of a rather
nasty-looking old woman set against a hideous yellow sky, or
``Sunday on the Pot With George,'' a pointillist vision of a heavy
man seated on a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   The ineffable badness of some of the works, in fact, makes them
all but indescribable.
</P>
<P>
   But the museum's founders say the point of all this badness is
that it's all right, and often even quite interesting, to fail;
that people who only sing in the shower, or paint on Sundays, are
also worth celebrating, simply for their love of making art.
</P>
<P>
   And for a place that celebrates failure, the five-year-old
museum is enjoying marked success. It has put out a book and a
CD-ROM, and its Web site, www.glyphs.com/moba, is well visited.
</P>
<P>
   Its artists are happy too, the founders say, and the submissions
continue to roll in because of the following win-win logic: if an
artist's work is accepted, he can say he has work hung in a museum;
and if it is rejected, he can boast that the world's top authority
on bad art has officially declared him ``not bad.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREY GOLDBERG
</P>
