<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      10-17 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOOTBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIANTS MAY TURN TO CARDINALS' MOORE FOR HELP
</P>
<P>
   One possible answer to the Giants' offensive problems will be
playing at Giants Stadium Sunday. A Giants assistant coach said
last week his team would love to steal Rob Moore from the Cardinals
when the wide receiver becomes an unrestricted free agent at the
end of this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are interested in Moore because they lack a big-play
receiver. Moore has fought a hamstring injury for much of the
season, and Sunday's game is the first for which he will be
completely healthy. Last year he led the National Football League
in receiving yards (1,584), catches of at least 25 yards (20) and
first-down receptions (68). Moore is among the league's top five
wide receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants may have a good crop of young receivers, led by Ike
Hilliard, and it is true that they desperately need a running back
and a tight end, but the team can draft players for those
positions. And with the salary cap increasing for next season, the
Giants will have the cap room to fit in Moore's salary.
</P>
<P>
   Moore recently turned 30, but being that old does not seem to be
a liability for top receivers. Jerry Rice of the 49ers had 391
catches for 6,575 yards from age 25 to 29, and 524 catches and
7,305 yards from age 30 to 34. Some of Moore's top seasons may be
ahead of him.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was the Jets' No. 1 pick in the 1990 supplemental draft
and played with the team until 1994, before signing with Arizona as
a free agent. Moore, who attended Syracuse, still has a home on
Long Island. Sources say he wants to come back to New York, not
only because he likes the area but also because he wants to reunite
with Jim Fassel, the Cardinals' former offensive coordinator who is
the Giants' coach.
</P>
<P>
   Moore has also supposedly said he wants a more stable situation
than the one in Arizona. The offensive coordinator, Marc Trestman,
is Moore's fourth coordinator in four years, and Jake Plummer is
his fifth starting quarterback in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Re-signing Moore is Arizona's top priority. But if the Cardinals
do not sign him, no one should be surprised if he ends up back in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   PATRIOTS RUNNING TO GLORY
</P>
<P>
   It's still too early to judge which team made out better, the
Jets or the New England Patriots, when the Jets gave up five draft
picks to get Coach Bill Parcells and running back Curtis Martin.
Five years from now, the winner will probably be more clear. If the
Jets get to a Super Bowl and the Patriots do not, the draft picks
will have been worth it. If the Patriots do and the Jets don't,
then New England is the winner.
</P>
<P>
   It may be early, but there is a leader _ the Patriots are ahead,
by about a length. The two teams play Monday night in Foxboro,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   New England's front office has proved to be one of the best
evaluators of talent in football, and the Patriots' executives have
used the choices acquired from the Jets well: all five picks
received from the Parcells-Martin defection are still on the
Patriot roster.
</P>
<P>
   The crown jewel has to be running back Robert Edwards, a
first-round selection (18th over all) out of Georgia. The pick used
for Edwards was the one New England got from the Jets for Martin.
That meant that the Patriots took a huge gamble, giving up Martin's
1,266 yards a season for a rookie. The gamble paid off in a big
way. If the Patriots' owner, Robert Kraft, sees Parcells Monday, he
may thank him. Edwards has been so impressive, he is a contender
for rookie of the year (though receiver Randy Moss of the Minnesota
Vikings seems to be a lock).
</P>
<P>
   Edwards is the first rookie since the 1970 NFL-American Football
League merger to rush for a touchdown in each of his first five
games. One more touchdown run and Edwards will pass Alan Ameche
(1955) and Joe Cribbs (1980) for most consecutive games with a
rushing touchdown by a rookie. Last week, Edwards scored twice and
rushed for 104 yards against Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   And to think, Edwards has played running back for only a couple
of years. He went to Georgia as a defensive back, and was moved to
running back as an experiment. In his first game as a runner, he
scored five touchdowns. Experiment over.
</P>
<P>
   His running style is similar to Tony Dorsett's in that he can
combine power with speed in a wink. He is also a good receiver and
excels at beating a linebacker or strong safety playing
bump-and-run coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are 4-1 and they can thank Edwards. His presence
has eased the load of quarterback Drew Bledsoe, who has a rating of
96.9.
</P>
<P>
   Every time the Patriots' front office looks at Edwards, it
affirms the team's decision to let Martin go. In fact, a Patriots
assistant coach remarked with glee that Edwards has 379 yards
rushing, and Martin, who missed last week's Jets game against St.
Louis with a hamstring injury, has 368.
</P>
<P>
   NO CHARGE IN CHARGERS
</P>
<P>
   In San Diego, Kevin Gilbride became the first coaching casualty
of the season, something that had been rumored for weeks. The
reason? Gilbride, several high-ranking Chargers executives said,
had lost the respect of his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of getting better, maybe we were stagnant, or maybe
even regressing,'' said Bobby Beathard, the team's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Several players complained privately to members of the front
office, voicing their disapproval of the team's direction. Those
players said practices were sloppy and there was little team
discipline. Safety Rodney Harrison said morale was terrible under
Gilbride, and a change was welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbride said in a statement he was shocked by the firing, but
he shouldn't be. The Chargers scored only 22 touchdowns in 22 games
under Gilbride, and the rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf had only one
touchdown pass and 15 turnovers. The fact Gilbride was going to
bench Leaf in favor of the journeyman Craig Whelihan also factored
into management's decision to dismiss him, Chargers executives
said.
</P>
<P>
   June Jones takes over as interim coach. Guess what? Leaf is
starting Sunday when the Chargers (2-4) play the Philadelphia
Eagles (1-5) in a game that host San Diego could win. Jones is no
dummy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
