<SLUG> BC-TUCKER-COLUMN17-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Padres good but N.Y. better
 &HT;    By Tim Tucker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Already this month, they've become the first team in
baseball history to eliminate two 100-win teams in the same
postseason. Already, they've won six playoff games in which the
opposing starting pitcher owned a Cy Young Award. Already, they've
outhit the National League's best offense (Houston's) and
outpitched the NL's best pitching staff (Atlanta's).
</P>
<P>
   Now let's see how good these San Diego Padres really are.
</P>
<P>
   The World Series convenes tonight in the Bronx with the
improbable Padres, the NL's third best team during the regular
season but clearly its best this month, facing the New York
Yankees, who won more regular-season games (114) than any team in
American League history. The Yankees are, to say the least,
favored.
</P>
<P>
   But for all that you've heard about the Yankee juggernaut this
season, and for all that you hadn't heard about the Padres until
very recently, here is something that might surprise you over the
next nine days:
</P>
<P>
   These teams are a lot alike.
</P>
<P>
   Both have superb starting pitching, almost invincible closers,
lineups of patient and experienced hitters who rely more on contact
than power, good benches and solid defenses that _ unlike, say,
Atlanta's _ have not melted down in October. And for Game 1
starting pitchers, both teams have a guy with impeccable postseason
credentials and no-hit stuff: the Yankees' David Wells, who threw a
perfect game earlier this season, and the Padres' Kevin Brown, who
had a no-hitter last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have more speed, more millionaires, more history _ a
lot more history, this being their 35th World Series and San
Diego's second. But the Padres have things in their favor, too,
including the only sure-fire future Hall of Famer on the field,
Tony Gwynn, who has been waiting 14 years to get back to the
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't care if no one thinks we're going to win,'' Gwynn
says, ``because we think we're going to win.'' Joe Torre, the
Yankees' manager, believes the Padres enter this World Series much
as his team entered its successful '96 Series against Atlanta _ as
a team widely expected to lose but plenty good enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   In this season that will forever be linked to the home run, it
is interesting, and quite revealing, that only one player on either
of these teams hit more than 30 homers: the Padres' Greg Vaughn,
who had 50. The Yankees have no one who hit more than 28, which
would have ranked fifth on the Braves' team. This Series should
feature baseball in its more subtle splendor. Pitching. Execution.
Defense. Strategy. Smarts.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees win, they will complete one of the most
remarkable seasons in the game's history and perhaps stamp
themselves as one of the best teams ever; if the Padres win, they
will complete one of the most remarkable month in the game's
history.
</P>
<P>
   Says here it'll be a long, low-scoring series, maybe seven
games. Says here the Yankees will prevail because, in the end, the
$16-million-or-so difference in payrolls gives them a few extra
weapons. Anyway, I'm quite sure the Padres, underdogs to Houston,
underdogs to Atlanta, wouldn't want people to start favoring them
now.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
