<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2736 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPAIN-GARCIA-LORCA-AR     10-17 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-GARCIA-LORCA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POET'S SISTER, 87, ACTS TO PROTECT HIS MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AL GOODMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALFACAR, Spain _ For the 100th anniversary of the birth of the
poet and playwright Federico Garcia Lorca this year, his relatives
helped plan dozens of conferences and concerts. Arguably Spain's
greatest literary figure this century, he was executed in the
Spanish Civil War by fascists loyal to Franco.
</P>
<P>
   But one project they did not propose has caused perhaps the
greatest stir: a soccer field a mere half-mile from where
historians say Garcia Lorca was shot dead in August 1936. His body
was never found, but the furor shows that the ghosts of civil wars
live long.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldozers have cleared the ground for the field in this village
of 4,500 people near Granada, carving into a hillside between
Federico Garcia Lorca Park, which commemorates his unmarked tomb,
and a ravine a mile away where some 4,000 leftist opponents of
Franco were killed and dumped in mass graves.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after months of unnoticed work, it seems the soccer field
may never be completed _ thanks to the intervention of the poet's
only surviving sibling, Isabel Garcia Lorca, 87.
</P>
<P>
   A diminutive but indomitable woman, she stepped into the fray
blasting the project as a ``monstrosity.'' She expressed surprise
that the $375,000 field was proposed by Socialist officials, whose
hallmark is to criticize the barbarities of Franco's long
right-wing dictatorship, which ended with his death in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem of sensitivity,'' Ms. Garcia Lorca told a
visitor in her Madrid apartment. ``It's as if they didn't have a
memory.''
</P>
<P>
   Federico, her older brother, was already internationally
acclaimed at age 38 when he was killed. His poems and plays about
his native Andalusia, in southern Spain, and his ``Poet in New
York,'' based on his stay in America in 1929, are widely studied at
universities.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred thousand visitors flock annually to the four
Lorca sites in metropolitan Granada, including the homes where he
was born or did much of his writing and the park commemorating his
death.
</P>
<P>
   But in Alfacar, the Socialist mayor, Juan Caballero, said the
soccer field had been meticulously planned with all the legal
permits and would be largely shielded from view by 3,000 trees and
shrubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, there's no impact,'' the mayor insisted, standing on the
2.5 acres of hard-packed dirt that is the largest patch of level
ground visible on the steep hills at an altitude of 3,300 feet.
``How did they distort something so much?''
</P>
<P>
   Alfacar's present soccer field is on mushy clay that frequently
floods. Experts said the soil a mile up the windy road near the
Lorca park was firmer, and officials deemed the site the cheapest
solution. The five local amateur soccer clubs would play games
there on most weekends and could even use it at night under the
planned floodlights.
</P>
<P>
   But some critics fear that gleeful shouts when goals are scored
would be heard at the park and the mass grave. They say the two
civil war sites should be treated with the respect of a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   ``The countryside is so big,'' Ms. Garcia Lorca said. ``Why does
it have to be there?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider it a veritable affront,'' Isabel Garcia Lorca wrote
this month to Manuel Chaves, the Socialist president of the
Andalusia regional government, which ceded the land for the soccer
field, granted the special permits for its construction, and
pledged a third of the financing.
</P>
<P>
   It was not long before Caballero received the first calls ever,
in his nine years as mayor, from the regional president's office,
summoning him to a meeting in Seville on Oct. 20. As the sunset
cast a brilliant glow on the planned field recently, Caballero, 53,
said he would continue to argue for his pet project, but he
conceded that he was worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're open to any solution,'' he said. ``Our universal poet is
great. Perhaps his fame will prevent this soccer field. If so, we
would accept that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1433EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
