<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT &LR;      10-17 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE MICROSOFT TRIAL BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 18:
</P>
<P>
   When the Justice Department filed its antitrust suit against
Microsoft last May, both sides were hoping for a quick resolution.
But with the trial set to begin Monday, those hopes are gone. The
case against Microsoft has broadened in scope, encompassing new
charges of predatory conduct against big-name rivals.
</P>
<P>
   If these allegations are proved, the courts may well be asked to
consider drastic remedies, including increased regulation or even a
breakup of Microsoft. Many experts worry that such steps could
stifle innovation and enterprise in the nation's most dynamic
business sector.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, and 20 state attorneys general joining
the suit, were right to worry about Microsoft using its monopoly
status to coerce other companies. It is not in the public interest
for any one company to have an Internet chokehold. But it is also
right for Justice to have to prove its case in court. No matter who
wins the arguments in the next couple months, no one doubts that
the case will end up in the United States Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, the core of the case against Microsoft has
been that the company used illegal tactics to try to muscle
Netscape, the maker of a Web browser that is the main rival to
Microsoft's, out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   The focus originally was on Microsoft's decision to combine its
own Internet Explorer browser with its basic Windows software,
forcing anyone who used Windows to take the browser. The expanded
suit argues that Microsoft also used strong-arm tactics against
such other giants as Intel, Apple, IBM and America Online to force
them to use Microsoft products. These tactics, the government
charges, were based on a fear at Microsoft that Netscape's
Navigator browser and Sun Microsystem's Java programming language
might some day supplant Microsoft's dominance with its Windows
operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks in the trial will come in two ways.
</P>
<P>
   First, the government plans to call witnesses from affected
companies, some of whom will be reluctant to testify against
Microsoft. Nevertheless, the government thinks it can get them to
make their complaints about Microsoft public.
</P>
<P>
   Second, there will be plenty of parsing of interoffice e-mails
and other exchanges that the government claims show that Microsoft
was eager to kill off Netscape. In response, Microsoft will argue
that such talk should be dismissed as locker-room bravado, not an
actual business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's main argument is that incorporating its browser into
Windows was designed to improve the basic product. In June, in
fact, a federal appeals court accepted Microsoft's argument that it
has the right to incorporate any software into its system if doing
so offers advantages to consumers. But the court based its ruling
on an earlier consent decree, not on broad antitrust law. The
government has assembled persuasive evidence that Microsoft's
tactics violated prohibitions against using monopoly power in one
area to crush the competition in others.
</P>
<P>
   No one claims this has been an easy time for Microsoft. Besides
the antitrust suit, the company faces strong business competition
and a global recession that could restrict its phenomenal growth.
But as Microsoft looks to expand its reach into Internet commerce,
business software and software for consumer products like cars and
telephones, it is critical to insure unfettered competition.
</P>
<P>
   In weighing the evidence, the courts and the public should
recognize that the Justice Department is not trying to punish one
company for its success but to guarantee that success will be
possible for future innovators as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOTTI-BAIL-2TAKES-NYT     10-17 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOTTI-BAIL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOTTI'S `ORDINARY' BAIL BACKERS PUT PROPERTY AT RISK 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By CHARLIE LeDUFF    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In a modest corner of the Marine Park section of
Brooklyn is a modest home where a modest couple string Christmas
lights in the winter and plant tomatoes in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   You couldn't find better people than Clement and Margaret
Rispoli, their neighbors say.
</P>
<P>
   The street is a picture of postwar Americana. The Rispoli house
is a brick two-story, valued at $185,000, attached to the
neighbor's house, a brick two-story, and so on down the block.
</P>
<P>
   The couple moved onto 31st Street in 1985, and they grew old
there. Mr. Rispoli, who recently had quadruple bypass surgery,
turned 74 last week. His wife suffers from diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're wonderful people,'' a friend next door said. ``They
don't discuss private matters. Whatever ties they may or may not
have, they're good people.''
</P>
<P>
   The ties the friend was mentioning are those to John A. Gotti,
the man the government contends is the heir to his imprisoned
father's throne atop the Gambino crime family.
</P>
<P>
   The Rispolis are among the 35 ``ordinary, common folk of means
and good reputation,'' as Gotti's lawyer, Bruce Cutler, describes
them, who have put up their homes and even a business as collateral
on a $10 million bond so that Gotti could go home to his wife and
children while awaiting trial.
</P>
<P>
   While most of Cutler's description seems to fit this collection
of property owners in Brooklyn and Queens, ``ordinary'' might be a
stretch. Mr. and Mrs. Rispoli, for instance, lost their son-in-law
in a gangland slaying in 1991. And the chairman of the company that
owns the only piece of commercial property involved in the bail
package was indicted _ and ultimately acquitted _ in a 1984 mob
killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to ask yourself, does an ordinary citizen commit
his home or livelihood to one of the most notorious names in
crime?'' said a senior law enforcement official from Queens who has
spent much of his career tracking the Gambino clan. ``Either they
owe a favor or expect a favor,'' said the official, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rispolis moved to their Marine Park neighborhood, the
rumors followed. Neighbors knew they had some connection to the
Gottis by way of a son-in-law named ``Bob Borish or Barish'' or
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   His name, in fact, was Bartholomew Borriello; he was the
henchman of Joseph Gallo, the Colombo family chief, before he went
to work for the elder Gotti in 1985 as a chauffeur and bodyguard.
Borriello, known as Bobby, was married to the Rispolis' daughter,
Susan, and they had two children.
</P>
<P>
   Borriello was killed outside his Bensonhurst home on a cold
spring evening in 1991. He was shot twice in the head and six times
in the body, shattering a jar of tomato sauce he was carrying as he
fell to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3 Borriello was killed on orders of the Lucchese and
Genovese families in retaliation for the 1985 murder of Paul
Castellano, then the Gambino boss, by the elder Gotti, John J.,
according to what former Lucchese underboss Anthony Casso told
federal authorities in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of them are lily-white people, but you would think that
they have given enough,'' a former mob investigator with the Queens
district attorney's office said of the Rispolis and the others who
put up their homes for the younger Gotti. ``Junior's not going
anywhere. But why would this elderly couple put their house in hock
for a guy like this? They gave the father of their grandchildren,
but what did they get?''
</P>
<P>
   Inquiries at the doors of the Rispolis' and their daughter's
Brooklyn homes went unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles from the Rispolis in the heart of Howard Beach,
Queens, lives Christina Agnostinelli, who by way of a cramped
signature offered up her $360,000 home as collateral and granted
her grandson, John Ruggiero, power of attorney.
</P>
<P>
   An elderly widow, and owner of the neat brick and shingle house
on 91st Street, Ms. Agnostinelli did not answer knocks on her door
last week. Her grandson, who had pulled up in a station wagon, said
she was at her vacation home in the Poconos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody that reached out to the family wanted to help,''
said Ruggiero, who investigators say is an associate of the younger
Gotti and son of the late Angelo Ruggiero, a reputed Gambino family
captain.
</P>
<P>
   Friends help friends, Ruggiero said. It's a matter of honor, and
that's what simple people do, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got nothing on him,'' Ruggiero said of Gotti. ``It's
guilt by association. He's Italian and they're trying to make him
out to be a meatball. They're trying to railroad him because of his
family.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his grandmother's association with the Gottis,
Ruggiero said: ``Nothing. She's an 82-year-old lady who stays home
and makes tomatoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Running through the heart of Howard Beach is Cross Bay
Boulevard, a commercial strip of Italian restaurants, bait shops
and vegetable stands. There, on the corner of 158th Avenue, stands
the Ragtime Newsstand Dairy, an unassuming brick delicatessen that
also sells cigarettes and beauty aids. Its owners offered it up as
part of Gotti's bond. Court papers have its value appraised at $2.6
million, the largest contribution.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four owners, Joseph Russo, was at the shop last week.
A thin man dressed in blue jeans and a ball cap, Russo said he knew
the younger Gotti from way back, when he used to buy bubble gum at
his shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it because he should be home with his kids,'' Russo
said. ``That's what it's all about. I've got no problem putting my
business up.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had been approached by the Gottis or their lawyers
or whether he offered his business of his own accord, Russo said,
``I don't know who arranged it.''
</P>
<P>
   Those seen coming and going in the Ragtime over the last 15
years are a Who's Who of Gotti associates, the Queens County
investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the board of Ragtime is John Gurino. Gurino was
indicted in 1984 in a mob murder. At the time, prosecutors accused
Gurino of having ties to organized crime. The man he was accused of
shooting managed to croak Gurino's name before he died, according
to the government. But during the trial, Gurino's little-known
lawyer was able to question the validity of those dying words by
belittling the testimony of the dying man's girlfriend, the last
person to hear him speak.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gurino won an acquittal, and his lawyer, Cutler, won the respect
of the Gotti organization, which made him their top defense
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said, these people are very close to the Gottis as
lifelong friends and neighbors,'' Cutler said of Ragtime's
proprietors. ``They are decent people with no links to organized
crime and they have faith in John Gotti.''
</P>
<P>
   When the senior Gotti was finally convicted in 1992, John
Gurino, now 72, was charged with felony riot, accused of organizing
a 1,000-person rally at U.S. District Courtin Brooklyn, where Gotti
was tried. Seen chanting ``Let's Free John Gotti,'' Gurino
ultimately pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor. Gurino's cousin,
Anthony Gurino, is in prison for obstruction of justice in a
federal case revolving around a multimillion-dollar heroin ring
that involved John J. Gotti's brother Gene.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gurino's wife said he was unable to come to the door
of his home in Howard Beach because he was resting.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of the homes offered as surety are in Howard Beach, a
close-knit, mostly Italian neighborhood, where young men routinely
ask strangers the nature of their business. Heavily developed after
World War II, it is a sequestered village on the north shore of
Jamaica Bay with block after tree-lined block of unremarkable
split-level brick and shingle homes with manicured lawns. It looks
more like Orange County than Queens County.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Gotti's benefactors from Howard Beach live in the same
subdivision in houses that are so similar that it is easy to
imagine them wandering at least once into the wrong home.
</P>
<P>
   In regard to Gotti's bond, they say little.
</P>
<P>
   Ciro and Rose Amoroso, whose son Anthony could be seen regularly
at the Wednesday night meetings at the younger Gotti's social club
in South Ozone Park, referred all inquires about their brick and
shingle home on 85th Street to Cutler, the lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Kaplan, who lives on 83rd Street, also put up her brick and
shingle duplex as collateral. Mrs. Kaplan's son Steven, 30, a
reputed member of Gotti's crew, was arrested along with Gotti in
1990 for hitting two men in a Long Island nightclub whose dates
found Gotti and Kaplan unattractive. The battered men later dropped
the charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known John a long time, and he's a lovely boy,'' Mrs.
Kaplan said before closing the door.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiries at other homes in the subdivision yielded a few ``I
don't know,'' several ``Can't help you, bud'' and, in one case, two
snarling attack dogs.
</P>
<P>
   At the Gotti family home on 85th Street, where Junior spent his
childhood, questions were answered with a polite ``No, thank you.'
</P>
<P>
   Richard DiCasoli, who offered his two-story aluminum-sided house
in Ozone Park as collateral, did not want to talk. Organized crime
investigators said they had never heard of him, until now.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most valuable pieces put up as collateral is the Long
Island house owned by Gotti's sister, Victoria, a writer of
whodunits, and her husband, Carmine Agnello, who according to the
federal authorities became a ``made man,'' or official crime family
member, in 1992. He wanted to help but was not allowed to offer any
of his property as part of the bail package because government
prosecutors questioned the legitimacy of its financing. Victoria
Gotti, however, was allowed to sign over half the value of their
Old Westbury, N.Y., estate, or $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The friends and family wanted him home and have backed it
up,'' Agnello said by telephone from his Bronx-based business, the
New York Shredder Corporation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much I can say. There's a trial, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Then before hanging up, Agnello asked a question of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``How'd you get my number?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
