<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2753 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTIONS-LOTTERIES-C     10-17 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTIONS-LOTTERIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lottery a hot topic in two campaigns
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANETT, Ala. _ At the Happy Stop convenience store, clerk Lynn
Ayers restocks the Marlboro supply hanging over the counter.
There's not a customer in sight as lunch time approaches. When
travelers eventually do stop for a tank of unleaded at 92.9 cents a
gallon, they invariably ask to buy a lottery ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them they can go three miles down the road if they want
to play,'' Ayers said.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road is Georgia, which has raised more than $2.7
billion for education with its 5-year-old lottery.
</P>
<P>
   The Happy Stop sits in lottery-free Alabama, where buying a $1,
state-sponsored chance to become a millionaire has been about as
welcome as the federal government and a losing football team.
</P>
<P>
   But in Alabama and South Carolina, where incumbent GOP governors
once were considered unreachable by Democrats, challengers have
used lottery proposals like rocket fuel. They ignite enthusiasm
with the promise that millions in revenue can be made without
raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Don Siegelman, Alabama's lieutenant governor, proposed a
Georgia-style lottery to fund college scholarships. Trailing in
some polls by double digits, Gov. Fob James has countered with his
own scholarship plan _ one that doesn't rely on a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, Jim Hodges, the Democratic challenger for
governor, also promotes a state lottery and suddenly has made his
race with GOP incumbent David Beasley closer than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're challenging a sitting governor, you have to do
something that elevates you and becomes a negative for your
opponent,'' said Charles Bullock, a political scientist at the
University of Georgia. ``The lottery is an outstanding tool for
doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Happy Stop, Ayers wants no part of a lottery. She used to
work in nearby LaGrange, Ga., and didn't like what she saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``People spent their last dollars on the lottery and let their
kids go hungry just so they could play their numbers,'' Ayers said.
She recounted tales of people spending a fraction of their food
stamps, then coming back to spend the change on Lotto tickets. ``I
stay where there is no lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Alabama has been hemmed in by lottery states Georgia,
Florida and Louisiana. Next door sits casino-crazy Mississippi.
Dollar by dollar, quarter by quarter, potential Alabama revenue
flows out of the state and becomes budget fodder for other
governments.
</P>
<P>
   The lottery tide may be turning, however. Recent newspaper polls
in Alabama and South Carolina showed nearly two-thirds of those
interviewed in each state would vote for a lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Georgia Lottery raised more than $1.72 billion _
up 56 percent over the $1.1 billion raised in 1994, the first
fiscal year for the game. In 1997, more than 136,000 Georgia
students received more than $179 million in HOPE scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   National rankings of quality of public education and quality of
life for children consistently have Alabama among the bottom three
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the parents who thought that college wasn't possible for
their son or daughter because the high cost is crippling, hope is
on the way,'' Siegelman said. ``To those who say it can't be done,
I say it can _ just look at Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   James plays to his socially conservative base when he derides
Siegelman's lottery plan as a ``crap shoot'' and questions the
morality of funding education through gambling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lottery is nothing more than a tax _ and a deceitful tax _
on those who can't afford it,'' James said.
</P>
<P>
   James was born in Lanett 64 years ago. His hometown is typical
of hamlets along the Georgia border from Alabama to North Carolina.
Residents make easy trips to the Peach State for quick dates with
Lady Luck. Five of the top 10 Georgia Lottery retailers are perched
near the Alabama border: two in West Point, two in Columbus and one
in Tallapoosa.
</P>
<P>
   A three-mile drive on U.S. 29 from the Happy Stop in Lanett
brings you to the Oil South No. 8 Texaco in West Point, Ga. The
Texaco is sixth on the Georgia Lottery's list of top retailers.
``We have people from Birmingham, Mobile, Montgomery, Lafayette.
They come from all over,'' said Texaco lottery clerk Cassandra
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is foundry worker Willie Heard, who drops in weekly
from Lanett. Heard makes his way past the shiny metal racks of Slim
Jims and Golden Flake Pork Crackles and the refrigerated quarts of
Coors and Schlitz Malt Liquor to get to the two manned Lotto
terminals in the back of the store.
</P>
<P>
   After Heard buys $15 in tickets _ amounting to $60 a month or
$720 a year _ he heads to a faded gray Caprice Classic in his gray
overalls and oil-stained hat. With two daughters at home, the
oldest 14, he would gladly vote for an Alabama lottery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't afford it but I play it in Georgia,'' said Heard.
Texaco's lottery lines are often eight or 10 deep. Heard said the
woman in front of him spent $70 on tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Heard said his family never has gone without necessities because
of his wagers. ``I want the money. I need the money,'' said Heard,
who won $500 six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Just west on U.S. 29 back in Lanett, the Texaco star is visible
through the plate glass windows of the Greene Super Drug store.
Thirty-year-old pharmacist Pamela Monk, a lifelong Lanett resident,
said she has contemplated moving to Georgia to increase the odds
that her 11-year-old son can earn a college scholarship. Her
friends have thought of moving, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not one of those rich towns. This is not Vestavia
Hills,'' said Monk, referring to a swanky section of Birmingham,
similar to Dunwoody in suburban Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Schools need help and no one wants to raise property taxes, so
why not start a lottery, Monk reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education needs to be the main thing,'' said Monk, a Baptist
who doesn't gamble but invites others to if it pays for schools.
``You've got people who wouldn't otherwise make charitable
donations to education but they might play the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not James is re-elected, Monk is convinced the
lottery is bound for Alabama. ``Oh, it's coming,'' she said.
``You'll get new people in office. The lottery is coming here _ one
way or another.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
