u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-NYT &LR;      10-17 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, THE TALK AROUND BUSH TURNS TO 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``a'' news file.) 
(bl) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush, ahead by as much as 50
points in statewide polls in his bid for a second term, met his
Democratic challenger, Garry Mauro, for their first and only debate
Thursday night, and it did not take long for the talk to turn to
Bush's possible run for the presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jumping on a question from one of the panelists about Bush's
presidential aspirations, Mauro, the state's land commissioner,
said the governor was ``running for a job that most Texans think is
a full-time job and I would like to see him let us know if he's
going to be a full-time governor.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has throughout the campaign, Bush said he had not made up
his mind about running for president in 2000 but he did have some
reservations about how such an intense race would affect his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'll seek the presidency or not,'' Bush said,
counseling Texas voters to ``make that part of your consideration''
when voting for governor on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the consequences of not making up my mind,'' Bush
said. ``I don't think there would be all this speculation going on
if the people didn't think I was doing a good job as governor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the oldest son of former President George Bush, has been
the front-runner for the Republican nomination for president in
many early polls, attracting increased national scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro originally sought a series of debates with Bush, who
eventually agreed to just one, which was scheduled for a Friday
night in the fall, when a significant number of Texas voters are at
high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the exchanges dealt with public education, which has
emerged in Texas as the hottest local issue, as it has elsewhere in
the country. Both promised tax cuts and raises for teachers, though
they differed on the details.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro asked the governor to use his influence to urge
Republicans to end impeachment proceedings against Clinton. Bush
should ``pass the word to Congress that Texans don't want the
circus anymore,'' Mauro said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush responded that he was happy ``to give the president his day
in court before I rush to judgment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1505EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-NYT &LR;      10-17 0390
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGAIN, THE TALK AROUND BUSH TURNS TO 2000 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moving in ``p'' news file.) 
(bl) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
