<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRELAND-NOBEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NOBEL FOR PEACE-IN-PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Oct. 18:
</P>
<P>
   John Hume, a moderate Catholic politician from Northern Ireland,
has been working for peace there for three decades. David Trimble,
the pro-British Protestant who is now first minister of Northern
Ireland, is a more recent convert. Together they helped mold the
Good Friday Agreement that has brought the beginning of
reconciliation to Northern Ireland, and together they were justly
awarded the Nobel Peace Prize on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But peace is by no means assured, and Trimble is right to hope
that the prize is not premature.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel committee pointedly and wrongly omitted Gerry Adams,
perhaps because of his tolerance for terrorism over the years. But
he had the courage and vision to turn Sinn Fein and the Irish
Republican Army away from violence, making the peace deal possible.
A host of others contributed to the accords, including British
Prime Minister Tony Blair; the British government's Northern
Ireland Secretary, Mo Mowlam; the Irish Republic's Prime Minister
Bertie Ahern; President Clinton, and former Sen. George Mitchell,
who led the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for Trimble's caution was evident the other day when
he and his deputy, Seamus Mallon, a Catholic and a member of Hume's
party, visited The New York Times. When the talk turned to
politics, the atmosphere suddenly turned chilly as Trimble and
Mallon skirmished over issues that are crucial to the functioning
of the region's new institutions.
</P>
<P>
   The most important dispute is over how to deal with the IRA's
refusal to give up its weapons. Trimble has said he wants to delay
naming his cabinet _ which would likely include Adams _ until the
IRA begins to destroy the weapons or to turn them over to
authorities. The peace agreement commits all the parties to total
disarmament, and to using all their influence to achieve it. But it
does not state that this must begin before anything else. The IRA,
however, has the obligation to begin. All other parties should
encourage it, by turning over their own weapons and implementing
measures that end Northern Ireland's traditional discrimination
against Catholics.
</P>
<P>
   There is reason for hope. Sinn Fein appointed Martin McGuinness,
its chief negotiator at the peace table, to new talks about
disarmament, a sign of seriousness. Trimble, who would not speak
directly to Adams during the negotiations, has now met with him
three times, alone.
</P>
<P>
   It takes nothing from the achievements of Northern Ireland's
leaders to note that they will continue to disagree as they tackle
the unglamorous tasks of making the Assembly work, setting up
cross-border political bodies and reforming the police and
bureaucracy. ``There's so much work to be done and it's so
mundane,'' Adams warned last week. But that is how peace is built.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
