<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also moved in ``p'' news file.) 
(th) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AN IDEOLOGICAL SECRET? THAT IS THE QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's 2nd Congressional District has long been in
Democratic hands, centered as it is on the university town of
Boulder, northwest of Denver. But when the seat opened up this year
with the retirement of Rep. David Skaggs and Republicans nominated
former Mayor Bob Greenlee, the conventional political wisdom was
that Democrats could no longer take their lock on the district for
granted.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlee did not become mayor of Boulder by espousing hard-right
Republican conservatism. He talked fiscal conservatism and social
moderation, including the right of a woman to have an abortion.
</P>
<P>
   He still says he is a fiscal conservative and a social moderate,
and it appears many voters believe him. By most estimates, he and
his Democratic opponent, state Rep. Mark Udall, are in a dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   But Udall, son of Morris Udall, the former Arizona congressman
and presidential candidate, is buying none of it. He contends that
Greenlee is a secret right-winger who is in ideological synch with
the Heritage Foundation, the Washington-based organization whose
analysts tend to take an unadulterated view of conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greenlee claims to be a moderate,'' Udall said Friday. ``Yet
the central document of his campaign is taken directly from a
right-wing think tank.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Udall, Greenlee not only took the Foundation's
ideas when he drew up his campaign manifesto but lifted many of
them ``word for word'' from the foundation's documents without
giving them credit. Udall then offered two dozen examples, pairing
a paragraph he said came from a foundation document with a
paragraph from a Greenlee campaign booklet.
</P>
<P>
   Typical was this pairing of paragraphs discussing school choice
programs, an education financing approach that Greenlee supports
and Udall opposes:
</P>
<P>
   The Greenlee booklet says, ``Whether in the form of school
vouchers, opportunity scholarships, education tax credits or
education savings accounts, school choice programs offer families
the means to send their children to any local school of their
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation document says, ``Whether in the form of school
vouchers or scholarships, education tax credits and deductions or
education savings accounts, school choice programs offer families
the means to send their children to the school of their choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Udall concluded, ``Greenlee knows he should have acknowledged
how much of this was taken word-for-word from the Heritage
Foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenlee's campaign manager, Sean Murphy, acknowledged that the
foundation was ``a good resource for us.'' But he denied Udall's
charge that Greenlee had been underhanded with both the foundation
and voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Greenlee does not fit neatly into any ideological boxes,''
he said. ``He is in direct conflict with some Heritage Foundation
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   __
</P>
<P>
   ANTI-TAX CAMPAIGN DELAYED, NOT DEFEATED
</P>
<P>
   Up in the northwest corner of Arkansas earlier this year, some
affluent landowners, many empty-nest retirees, grew weary of paying
the state's property tax, the main source of money for public
schools. So they passed around a petition that called for
abolishing the levy and replacing it with an increase in the sales
tax.
</P>
<P>
   They found plenty of support, much of it from well beyond
northwest Arkansas. And shortly they had enough signatures to put
their proposition to a statewide vote this fall.
</P>
<P>
   They also had the hottest political issue in Arkansas in 1998,
one whose antecedents could be traced to Proposition 13, the
citizens initiative of two decades back that capped the property
tax in California.
</P>
<P>
   The Arkansas proposal, because of its basic pocketbook appeal,
has dominated campaign debate like no other cause or race.
</P>
<P>
   Its supporters have argued that it would provide Arkansas
residents with long-overdue relief from a tax that has been raised
over the years to the point of abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the measure _ including most top state officials
and dozens of educators, police chiefs and mayors _ have countered
that it would be a disaster for the Arkansas school system and
ultimately would force the state back into the poverty it has
struggled so hard to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   But as of last week, when polls showed the proposition headed
for passage, such arguments were moot. On Thursday the Arkansas
Supreme Court struck the proposition from the ballot, saying its
supporters had used improper procedures, including forgery, to
gather signatures.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the petition drive, Oscar Stilley, a Fort Smith
lawyer, denied any wrongdoing and vowed to start a new petition
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back in 2000,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AN ANNOUNCEMENT: CANDIDATE HAS BABY
</P>
<P>
   Jane Swift, the Republican candidate for lieutenant governor in
Massachusetts, gave birth on Friday in Boston to a 7-pound 6-ounce
girl, Elizabeth Ruth Hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Swift made political headlines and sparked debates about
parenting in the workplace when she announced last spring that she
was a candidate for both public office and motherhood. Though women
are no longer a rarity in political office, it is still rare to
find a pregnant woman running for office or holding office.
</P>
<P>
   Some social conservatives argued last spring after Ms. Swift's
announcement that a woman's place is in the home, not the
workplace, especially when it comes to having and rearing a child.
Social libertarians countered that today's woman can, and should,
have it both ways.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts were split on whether a pregnant candidate was a
political disaster ``growing larger by the day,'' as one put it, or
``a political advertiser's dream come true,'' as another said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the case, Ms. Swift, 33, a former state senator who is
married to Charles Hunt, a construction contractor, easily won
nomination in last month's Republican primary. And in a campaign in
which parenting in the workplace appears not to be an issue, polls
indicate that she and her running mate, Acting Gov. Paul Cellucci,
hold a slight lead over their Democratic opponents, Attorney
General Scott Harshbarger and state Sen. Warren Tolman.
</P>
<P>
   One thing more: Mother and baby are doing fine.
</P>
</TEXT>
