A2797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOVS-BROTHERS-COX     10-17 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOVS-BROTHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush is leaving no base untouched
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASEE, Fla. _ His famous brother already won a big
election, and is doing so well he's now touted as a possible
presidential contender. Their famous father already held that job.
</P>
<P>
   Now Jeb Bush hopes to carry on the family torch by finally
laying claim to the Florida governorship.
</P>
<P>
   With a political pedigree going back three generations, he's
wasting no time on entry-level offices. He wants to start at the
top in Florida _ and some are already whispering that his
ambitions, too, may not stop at the state line.
</P>
<P>
   But first John Ellis Bush, a Republican and a 45-year-old
millionaire from Miami, son of former President George Bush and
brother of Texas Gov. George W. Bush, must win an election.
</P>
<P>
   That's something he's never done.
</P>
<P>
   He's run only once _ in 1994, when he came achingly close to
toppling one of the most popular politicians in modern Florida
history, ``Walkin' '' Lawton Chiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was devastated when he lost that race,'' said Lance
deHaven-Smith, who works at the Florida Institute of Government, a
public policy think tank at Florida State University.``I think
there's some rivalry there with his brother. I think he learned
from his mistakes. This time he's doing everything he can, leaving
no base untouched.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bush led incumbent Chiles by several percentage points
in the polls going into the final weeks of the campaign. Then
Chiles closed the gap, giving a folksy performance in several
televised debates. Bush lost by 60,000 votes out of 3.5 million
cast, the closest election in modern Florida history.
</P>
<P>
   Now he faces Buddy MacKay, a longtime congressman and Chiles'
lieutenant governor for the past eight years.
</P>
<P>
   This time Bush is leading by 17 points in the polls, and,
barring some last-minute meltdown, he and his brother George _ who
is heavily favored to win a second term in Texas will become the
first brother governors since the Rockefellers _ Winthrop in
Arkansas and Nelson in New York _ in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say Bush has completely retooled his image since his
1994 loss. Then, Bush made no attempt to hide his deep social
conservatism, picking an outspoken born-again Christian legislator
as his running mate and raising his opposition to abortion as a
campaign issue.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, Bush largely ignored black voters, who have
traditionally voted Democratic in Florida. This time, he has
actively courted blacks, telling them he will reach out to their
communities. He helped found a charter school in a poor, mostly
black Miami neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   He has also downplayed his conservative principles, not
side-stepping the abortion issue but not raising it, either. And
his running mate is a middle-of-the-road, no-nonsense rising
Republican star named Frank Brogan, who has already won a statewide
election as Florida education commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, MacKay, 65, has stumbled with a campaign that has yet
to catch fire. He has been hurt badly by an embarrassing rift
created when Democratic leaders passed over a popular black
legislator for a top leadership post.
</P>
<P>
   High-profile Democrats have deserted MacKay in droves, including
the state agriculture commissioner, dozens of county sheriffs and
several key legislators. ``It's been Buddy-come-lately,'' said
Susan MacManus, a political scientist at the University of South
Florida in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay has tried to focus on Bush's support for school vouchers
that would let parents send their kids to private schools with
public money, calling it a ``recipe for disaster'' for minorities
and the poor. He has hammered at Bush's lack of experience and
several questionable business deals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has ignored the attacks. If he wins, Bush will follow in
the footsteps of his brother, father and grandfather, Sen. Prescott
Bush of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Texas, Jeb Bush moved to Miami in the late 1970s,
where a prominent real estate firm quickly offered him a
partnership.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first of what McKay calls Bush's ``silver-spoon
deals.'' Bush was part of a firm that sold water pumps to Nigeria
in a deal that eventually left the U.S. government, which lent
Nigeria money for the pumps, holding the bag. Bush denies any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also served as a director of Ideon, a Jacksonville credit
card services company that went bankrupt after lavish spending by
executives. Bush says he didn't have an active hand in running the
company.
</P>
<P>
   His only government service came in the late 1980s, when he
served as Florida's commerce secretary for 18 months. But that lack
of experience doesn't seem to bother most Floridians. Having
already elected the South's first Republican-majority Legislature
this century, they may give the GOP the governor's chair, too,
erasing another mark that has stood since Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans are very serious about this election,'' said
deHaven-Smith. ``It would really be a watershed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
