u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SHARON-COX     10-17 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SHARON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sharon ``The Bulldozer'' takes enigmatic place at peace talks
 &HT;    By Larry Kaplow
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The ``Blldozer'' rolls into the delicate peace
talks at Maryland's Wye Plantation today.
</P>
<P>
   He is new Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, one of the last
of the founding fathers in Israeli politics and the wild card in
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   At 70 years old, the former general embodies the best and worst
of his country's turbulent history, from bravery and brilliance to
aggression and recklessness.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon is a hefty, part-time farmer, idolized by many in Israel
while he is often reviled around the world. Palestinians call him a
``war criminal'' for two massacres in which he played a part.
</P>
<P>
   Weeks ago, from a lesser cabinet post, he was warning Israelis
that the peace plan under debate would endanger the country's
security. He was a rival to fellow right winger, and boss, Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   But, nine days ago, Netanyahu made him foreign minister,
possibly to pre-empt a Sharon-led opposition. Now Sharon heads to
the peace talks to discuss the same plan he used to oppose.
</P>
<P>
   There, he will likely face Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, the
``terrorist'' Sharon has vowed never to join in a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   What is likely to happen when the two men meet is anybody's
guess just as there is debate about what Sharon wants as foreign
minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to have his fingerprints on the history of Israel,''
said Arye Naor, who worked for former Prime Minister Menachem Begin
when Sharon was a cabinet minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is clearly right-wing, but he is one of the world's great
pragmatists,'' Israeli political scientist David Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon arrives at Wye late, sometime late Saturday or early
today. Some say he wants to distance himself from the results and
others say he simply did not want to miss a 25th anniversary
celebration of the Yom Kippur War, one of his finest moments.
</P>
<P>
   At the talks, President Bill Clinton is pushing a short-term
plan that could restart the faltering Oslo peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Some see Sharon's appointment as a sign that Netanyahu wants an
agreement but fears losing his right wing support. Pull in Sharon,
the theory goes, and the right wing will follow.
</P>
<P>
   Left-wing Israelis worry Sharon will block any more concessions
after this weekend, leaving the process dangerously incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper poll Friday showed that 48 percent of Israelis
support, and 36 percent oppose, the appointment of this
controversial foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis often refer to Sharon as a ``Bulldozer'' for his
single-mindedness in removing obstacles. He also has a record of
expanding Jewish settlement in occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
   He joined Israel's independence underground when he was 17 years
old. Accused of insubordination in 1956, he became a hero in the
1967 Six Day War and the 1973 Yom Kippur War.
</P>
<P>
   In an about-face that makes today's right-wing settlers nervous,
Sharon oversaw the controversial uprooting of a Jewish settlement
in the Sinai Desert after the 1978 Camp David treaty with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   But his daring has led to tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon's 1950s commando forces pioneered Israel's vaunted style
of unconventional warfare. But they also massacred 69 men, women
and children in a raid on a Jordanian village.
</P>
<P>
   His downfall came as defense minister, overseeing the 1982
invasion of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Though he promised limited fighting against PLO bases, the
invasion became a quagmire. More than 17,000 Lebanese were killed
and many Israelis accuse Sharon of deceiving them about the extent
of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   World condemnation reigned down on Israel after Sharon allowed
pro-Israel, Lebanese militias into two Beruit Palestinian refugee
camps. The militia carried out a two-day massacre of more than 700
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon was forced to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Former Israeli politician Michael Bar-Zohar, who fought
alongside Sharon, writes in his memoir, ``Facing a Cruel Mirror,''
``I know that if ever the army of Israel goes to war again, I'd ask
to fight under Sharon. But only under Sharon in uniform. This
excellent soldier is a poor statesman . . . and holds the dangerous
belief that he can change any political situation with military
might.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
