r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRIAD-CAMPAIGNS-KAN &LR;      10-17 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRIAD-CAMPAIGNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAD GROUP RE-EMERGES AS GOP ALLY IN SELECTED CONGRESSIONAL
RACES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With elections just days away, an organization that
influenced the 1996 Kansas congressional campaigns has re-emerged
to boost the candidacies of several dozen Republicans in close
races throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
   The techniques of Triad Management Services, a GOP consulting
firm that collects cash from secret donors and distributes it
through little-known political action committees, was spotlighted
last year by Democrats on a Senate committee investigating campaign
financing.
</P>
<P>
   In its report, the Republican-led Senate Governmental Affairs
Committee found no wrongdoing by Triad. But a campaign finance
reform proposal now bottled up in Congress calls for disclosure of
funding sources behind so-called independent advertising _
commercials not paid for or coordinated by a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Vince Snowbarger, who benefited from Triad support in 1996,
shows up on Triad documents listing Republican candidates in
competitive House and Senate contests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first I've heard of this,'' said Kevin Yowell,
Snowbarger's campaign manager. ``I'm surprised Triad would have us
on any sort of list. I'd still be surprised if Triad does anything
in this district. I hope they don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger's camp has given The Kansas City Star a copy of a
letter dated July 16 requesting that Triad not get involved in his
race this year.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Malenick, Triad president, said Friday that she never
got such a letter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to tell Triad to stay out, not that he can tell me
what to do,'' she said. Donors ``make their own decisions who they
write checks to,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Triad documents highlight 60 House races and six Senate
contests. Snowbarger's 3rd District race is not among 36 House
contests on Triad's top or second-tier lists of Republicans
challenging Democratic incumbents or running for open seats.
Snowbarger is listed among 24 GOP incumbents in tight races.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Todd Tiahrt, a Kansas Republican, also is on that list,
although his race is not considered close.
</P>
<P>
   Snowbarger, a freshman in a close re-election battle with
Democrat Dennis Moore, got help in the closing days of his 1996
race in the form of about $300,000 worth of ads and other
assistance from Triad-affiliated groups.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Triad spent about $1 million in Kansas in the 1996
election, including $410,000 that aided Sen. Sam Brownback. The
Triad connection to Kansas candidates was first reported by The
Star, which disclosed that Brownback's in-laws, John and Ruth
Stauffer of Topeka, donated $37,500 to eight political action
committees selected by Triad.
</P>
<P>
   Within days those committees contributed $36,000 to Brownback,
who was running against Republican Sheila Frahm in the GOP primary.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee
complained that the group used questionable techniques to enable
wealthy donors to skirt campaign laws.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the panel's Republican majority, which focused on
election cash raised by President Clinton and Democrats, especially
from Asian supporters, concluded that Triad broke no laws.
Brownback, who is not on Triad lists this year, was a member of
that committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department reportedly is reviewing the Democrats'
minority report. Triad attorney Mark Braden said he was unaware
that such an investigation was under way.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official committee position was that we didn't do anything
wrong,'' Braden said.
</P>
<P>
   While individuals' contributions to candidates are limited to
$2,000 per election by federal law, donations to nonprofit groups
can be as much as $5,000 per year, Braden said. And donors to
nonprofit organizations do not have to be identified as do those
who contribute directly to a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Malenick said Triad worked for its clients by identifying
Republican candidates in competitive contests.
</P>
<P>
   Triad is affiliated with two nonprofit groups, Citizens for the
Republic Education Fund and Citizens for Reform. In 1996 it
broadcast $3 million worth of pro-Republican issue ads in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But even at this late date, Malenick said, Triad ``has not
developed any issue advertising plans for this election,'' in
Kansas or elsewhere. She said that did not mean it wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Both political parties are closely watching the race between
Snowbarger and Moore. Although Moore was slightly ahead in fund
raising, both sides had collected about $700,000 through September.
</P>
<P>
   In his July 16 letter to Triad, Snowbarger asked that the group
refrain from independent expenditures on his behalf. He said that
while the group's efforts to elect conservative members of Congress
were greatly appreciated, some ads had created ``confusion in the
minds of voters as to who was saying what....''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that the voters of the district hear from the
candidates themselves rather than from outside organizations, no
matter how helpful and well-intentioned the ads may be,''
Snowbarger wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Yowell said Moore was asked to also disavow expenditures by
independent groups. Through June 30, labor had given nearly
$105,000 to Moore, according to campaign expense reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we know why,'' Yowell said of Moore's reasons for not
agreeing to their request.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Esposito, Moore's campaign manager, said money contributed
by unions was not the same as that which came by way of Triad.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the AFL-CIO runs an independent expenditure, they put
their name on it and they disclose their donors,'' he said. ``That
is the issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Esposito also said he was skeptical about Snowbarger's plea that
Triad stay out of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect Triad to spend massive amounts of secret and
unregulated money on negative television and radio commercials in
next two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
