<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-SHELLING-COX-1     10-17 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-SHELLING-COX-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Serbs shell small village soon after extends NATO deadline
 &HT;    EDs: ADDS approximate location of village, statement from Serb
police
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   VRAGOBIL, Yugoslavia _ On Friday as NATO extended its deadline
for Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic to comply with a
U.S.-brokered peace agreement, this small hill village 25 miles
southwest of Pristina was shelled through the night, terrifying
residents and damaging dozens of homes.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces in the area also did not appear to be making any
attempts to withdraw, even though Milosevic has agreed to reduce
the Serb military presence in Kosovo. Buses of soldiers and armored
personnel carriers cruised down the road between Pristina and
Malisheva on Saturday and uniformed soldiers occupied many
buildings along the road. Serb soldiers were also seen spreading
leaves and branches over buried earthen bunkers to make them less
visible.
</P>
<P>
   The peace accord that was signed this week intended to make sure
the Yugoslav president pull his forces out of the strife-torn
province. The Western powers earlier in the week had given
Milosevic until Saturday to comply or face military action. On
Friday, the deadline was extended another 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   The shelling began at about 6 p.m. Friday and continued until 8
a.m. Saturday, said a number of Vragobil residents. One man, who
would only give his first name, Adam, said he counted more than 400
rounds fired during the night. Other residents reported hearing
about the same number of rounds. Perhaps because the village is
nearly empty, no one was injured or killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just after dinner, and I went out to the street, when I
heard this boom, boom, boom,'' said Adam, a man who appeared to be
in his late 50s. The shelling came in clusters early and became
sporadic during the night.
</P>
<P>
   When morning came, the red tile roofs on many houses had shell
holes the size of soccer balls. Other rounds gouged out stones in
the thick masonry walls. In one house, where the residents were
apparently getting ready to go to sleep, rubble and plaster had
collapsed onto once neatly made beds.
</P>
<P>
   Serb officials would not confirm or deny reports of shelling at
Vragobil. In a statement, Serb authorities in Pristina said
</P>
<P>
   there had been several attacks Friday against police by heavily
armed Kosovo separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported an attack by separatists against a police
checkpoint near the village using mortars, grenade launchers and
automatic weapons between 6 and 7 p.m. Friday. Police said they did
not return fire.
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear what would make this impoverished village a
military target, even though there were gun-bearing members of the
Kosovo Liberation Army scattered in the nearby countryside Saturday
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The few civilians who remained in this tiny ethnic Albanian
farming town on Saturday blamed Serb soldiers, who occupy the
nearby town of Malisheva. Residents believe soldiers hidden on
neighboring hills fired 30 mm shells at the houses. The residents
also said they are under occasional attack from snipers.
</P>
<P>
   A few miles away, people in the town of Guribardhe also said
they heard sustained shelling from the direction of Malesheva
during the night. About 25,000 of the 45,000 people who live in and
around Guribardhe are refugees, many from Malisheva.
</P>
<P>
   In Malesheva on Saturday, Serb soldiers in their dark violet
camouflage uniforms were lounging in bombed-out buildings, their
weapons resting on their laps. The town, once a stronghold of
Kosovo separatists, had been severely damaged by earlier fighting
and seemed devoid of any other human life.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of ethnic Albanians have been killed and an estimated
300,000 forced to flee their homes since Serb forces began fighting
Kosovo separatists. The Kosovo Liberation Army also has killed more
than 200 Serb policemen, Serb civilians and ethnic Albanians loyal
to Milosevic's government.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 90 percent of Kosovo's 2 million inhabitants are
ethnic Albanians and most favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   The shelling and other such incidents only serve to reinforce
the fear among refugees that it is unsafe for them to return to
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   With winter just a few weeks off, humanitarian relief workers
are urging displaced people to return home, even if their houses
were severely damaged. ``These people need to get to their homes
soon and get some shelter,'' said Mick Lorentzen of the Kosovo
office of the World Food Program. Lorentzen joined United Nations
High Commissioner on Refugees security officials who visited
Vragobil to inspect the damage. ``I can tell you that this doesn't
help.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
