<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKAMERICA'S EARNINGS SHOCK MAY POSE SETBACK TO BANKING INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: The most significant long-term effect of BankAmerica's
nasty October earnings surprise may be the damage it does to
industry hopes for financial-reform legislation in the next
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Bankers already were smarting from this year's failure to win
congressional approval of legislation that would have allowed
banks, insurance companies and securities firms to merge. This
setback, however, had little to do with political misgivings about
liberalizing the financial marketplace. Rather it resulted from
opposition by a couple of senators objecting to provisions that
would have expanded the Community Reinvestment Act's scope.
</P>
<P>
   Now along comes the BankAmerica debacle to renew fears of
buccaneer banking practices that have provided ammo for opponents
of banking liberalization since the Great Depression's wave of bank
closings.
</P>
<P>
   The BankAmerica shock was its announcement of a nearly 80
percent plunge in third-quarter earnings, resulting largely from
damage generated by volatile global markets. The biggest frights
were a $372 million write-down of a loan to a little-known
investment firm and a $250 million write-down in the value of a
mortgage-servicing portfolio that hadn't been hedged against
declining interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In another unseemly turn of events, BankAmerica found itself
forced to take over a $20 billion bond portfolio from the
investment firm in a rescue observers assume is necessary to
protect a remaining loan balance of about $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   What made this shock even more dramatic was its nearness to the
finalization of BankAmerica's $43 billion merger with NationsBank.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the eclectic nature of the earnings hits, said The
Financial Times, ``reveals serious risk management failures.'' It
also lamented that the calamity becomes ``further evidence (of)
banks' reckless behavior in the bull market.''
</P>
<P>
   This assessment puts the spotlight on how BankAmerica's problems
may pose a new barrier to banking modernization efforts. Hugh
McColl Jr., erstwhile NationsBank chief who heads the new
BankAmerica, is known as a canny banker and extraordinary
dealmaker. Nevertheless, as The Times noted, he failed to ``smell a
rat'' during the transaction's due diligence phase.
</P>
<P>
   How then, reform opponents might argue, can liberalized
post-reform safeguards be trusted to work when the most savvy
industry players were so easily duped while operating in today's
more restrictive environment?
</P>
<P>
   Good question, and as germane now as when the '90s dawned and
the financial industry was emerging from nearly a decade of
widespread bank and savings and loan failures. The debate then
focused on the moral hazard of insuring the deposits of
institutions involved in inordinately risky financial dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Banks still enjoy the same old deposit protection, but since
then nothing has been done to separate the industry's traditionally
conservative role of taking deposits and making loans from its more
freewheeling operations. While it's true the financial marketplace
needs liberation from outmoded Depression-era constraints, it's
just as true that government, under taxpayer aegis, shouldn't be
required to cover high-risk bets made outside of banking's
garden-variety banking functions.
</P>
<P>
   This is a good opportunity to refocus debate on the need to
complement greater regulatory freedom with less government
protection for the industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
