<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2812 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-HOSPITAL-ATTACK-NY     10-17 0410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOSPITAL-ATTACK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN CHARGED IN SEXUAL ATTACK ON 2 FELLOW PATIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 57-year-old patient at a city hospital on Roosevelt
Island was arrested Friday night and accused of sexually molesting
two catatonic women in their beds.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse at the Coler-Goldwater Memorial Hospital walked into a
room where the women were shortly before 8 p.m. and found a man who
was apparently sexually abusing them, police said. She then called
hospital security, who detained the suspect, William Green, until
officers from the 114th Precinct arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Officer George Jensen, a spokesman for the Police Department,
said the suspect and the two women, an 83-year-old and a
45-year-old, were all patients in the hospital's long-term care
program. ``It is for people who cannot take care of themselves,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Regina Lehman, an administrator at the hospital, refused to
discuss the incident. A hospital official speaking on the condition
of anonymity said Green was usually confined to a wheelchair. Jane
Zimmerman, a spokeswoman for the city's Health and Hospital Corp.,
said cases of abuse like the one alleged are infrequent in city
hospital facilities, particularly in those like Coler-Goldwater,
which is a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is more likely to happen in an acute-care hospital because
of the high volume of people coming in and out, but even there this
would be a rare occurrence,'' she said. ``There is no trend here;
this is an isolated incident.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, a man waiting for a CAT scan at St. Vincent's Hospital
and Medical Center in Manhattan was charged with attempting to rape
an 87-year-old woman with Alzheimer's disease.
</P>
<P>
   A nurse walked into the woman's room as the suspect was
disrobing her, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, a woman in a coma was raped by another patient
at Brookdale Hospital and Medical Center, according to police. This
attack was witnessed by a nurse, they said.
</P>
<P>
   In cases involving hospitals that accept Medicaid patients, the
state attorney general's office has sometimes investigated such
incidents. In a highly publicized case in Rochester two years ago,
a 32-year-old comatose woman became pregnant after she was raped at
the Westfall Health Care Center. A former nurse's aide, who had
been fired after being charged with sexually abusing another
physically disabled patient, was later charged in the woman's rape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 1719EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2813 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOGS18-COX     10-17 1460
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOGS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ohio mulls how to manage `megafarms'
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ At the Guggenbiller egg farm just east of Ohio 49
in southern Mercer County, the emerald grass is neatly trimmed,
four tree swings gently sway in the breeze and a boxer named Cindy
greets visitors with a menacing bark.
</P>
<P>
   The only hint that there are 243,000 hens laying 216,000 chicken
eggs each day is the three 450-foot-long sheet metal buildings just
behind the farm house. There are no sign of flies. No smell. No
noise. And no throngs of workers _ four family members run the
entire operation.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the dimly lit hen houses, nine chickens cluck and bob
inside each of the 2-by-2 cages, stacked on shelves in rows that
run longer than a football field. Don Guggenbiller uses an electric
cart to ride up and down the rows, checking on the chickens daily.
</P>
<P>
   Disease control is a concern. Visitors wear plastic bags over
their shoes, white coveralls and hair nets inside the bird houses
to avoid tracking viruses from other farms.
</P>
<P>
   Guggenbiller, his brother and their wives work from 5:30 a.m. to
2:30 p.m. with an automated system that collects the eggs and packs
them into crates. Semi-trucks come six times a week to haul the
eggs away. Feeding and watering is automated and the chicken manure
drops into pits below the cages. Area farmers buy the manure for
fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   This is family farming, with a big business twist. Large-scale
livestock operations are a trend in farming across the nation as
many family farmers expand to survive and to take advantage of
economies of scale. But such huge livestock operations have
attracted criticism. They can pose environmental problems and
people moving to rural areas often don't like the smell and flies
that come with the animal manure.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenbiller brothers contract with Cooper Farms, which
provides the feed and buys the eggs from the Guggenbillers. Cooper
Farms raises 1.5 million turkeys and 50,000 hogs on about 250
farms, mostly in Darke and Mercer counties. It also produces eggs
through contract farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Farms with more than 750 dairy cattle, 1,000 beef cattle, 2,500
hogs, 100,000 chickens or 550,000 turkeys are regulated by the Ohio
Environmental Protection Agency. A manure management plan must be
approved by Ohio EPA before these ``megafarms'' can expand.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio has 107 such megafarms regulated by the Ohio EPA, up from
about 70 two years ago. Darke County is home to 31 of them while
Mercer County has 26.
</P>
<P>
   Such operations have become controversial because of the
potential environmental consequences: flies, rodents, smell and
manure runoff into groundwater sources.
</P>
<P>
   And nearby residents often don't like the idea of living next to
a giant livestock farm, agriculture specialists said. That's
becoming a bigger issue as suburban sprawl gobbles up farmland _
Ohio loses an estimated 100,000 acres of farmland a year _ and more
suburbanites take up residence next to these expanding farming
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper Farms general manager Neil Diller said with suburban
sprawl, it comes down to a conflict between people who want to make
a living in the country and people who want to live in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Darke County, three men recently filed a lawsuit seeking to
stop a hog farm expansion before it even starts. They are asking
the court to consider it a class-action suit and either stop the
construction or order damages of more than $10 million. The suit
alleges that manure runoff could contaminate drinking water
sources, the smell could be offensive and the expansion could drive
down property values.
</P>
<P>
   One of the state's largest chicken operations _ Buckeye Egg _
has drawn the most criticism. Manure discharges and fly
infestations resulted in $228,000 in fines from Ohio EPA _ one
$115,000 fine in 1983 and a $113,000 fine in 1997, Ohio EPA
officials said. (The EPA has issued only two other fines _ totaling
$30,000 _ since it began regulating large-scale farms in the
1970s.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Buckeye Egg . . . they decided they were going to do whatever
they wanted for awhile there,'' Diller said. ``We are the
benefactors to their bad management because people are worried.''
</P>
<P>
   Diller said an operation the size of Buckeye Egg can be
intimidating. ``No doubt about it. Especially if you've never seen
livestock before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Buckeye Egg President Andy Hansen said charges of
mismanagement are false. ``We are one of the best managed
facilities in the world,'' he said. Large-scale operations face
more regulation and public scrutiny so they are better run than
smaller farms, Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Buckeye Egg was not responsible for the violations
that led to the 1983 fine because the company took over the egg
farm involved after the fine was imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Buckeye Egg has 14.3 million chickens in Ohio and plans to add
another 15.4 million once it gets Ohio EPA approval, said EPA
agriculture specialist Mark Wilson. Buckeye Egg's farms are in
Licking County and the tri-county area 50 miles northwest of
Columbus. Ohio is the nation's largest egg producer, in large part
because of Buckeye Egg.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are taking notice. U.S. Senate candidate Mary Boyle
called for a moratorium on ``factory farm'' expansions in Ohio.
North Carolina, Oklahoma and Mississippi have enacted moratoriums
and Colorado residents will vote in November on whether to limit
the size of hog farms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there is inadequate regulation of factory farms.
That's partly why they are growing so fast,'' Boyle said on a
campaign stop in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Boyle's opponent, Gov. George Voinovich, has called for
legislation requiring megafarms to have insect- and rodent-control
plans, giving the Ohio EPA director the ability to consider a
farmer's track record during the permitting process, require
hydrological testing if a new farm will use a significant amount of
water and establish a licensing program for those who manage large
amounts of manure.
</P>
<P>
   The state legislature is also considering bills related to
megafarms, similar to Voinovich's proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's getting to be a very big issue. It's amazing because two
or three years ago, we didn't even talk about this issue. Now, at
just about every House and Senate agricultural committee meeting
the word megafarm is brought up. It's probably at the top of the
agenda as far as agriculture goes as an issue,'' said Kit Fogle,
Ohio Farmers Union legislative director.
</P>
<P>
   At the local level, Darke County Commissioner Richard Graeff
said local health departments should have some control over
megafarms. ``It's all in the hands of the EPA. It's just kind of
difficult to control. So many things are taken out of the control
of the commissioners,'' Graeff said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio EPA issues permits to large-scale livestock operations
after holding public hearings and reviewing manure storage and
disposal plans. EPA officials conduct periodic follow-up
inspections, respond to complaints and require record keeping for
how many tons of manure were spread where and under what
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   But even Diller said the EPA probably does not have enough
resources to keep on top of megafarming issues after permits are
issued.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio EPA agriculture specialist Wilson said, ``We feel we have a
pretty effective regulatory program. We think we are regulating
this industry. That is not to say there can't be improvements.''
</P>
<P>
   Requiring certified livestock managers for farms with more than
1,000 animal units may be a good idea, Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Farmers Union would like to see concentrated operations
the size of Buckeye Egg categorized and regulated as agriculture
factories, Fogle said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Livestock Coalition, however, maintains that existing
regulations are adequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look at the environmental compliance records of Ohio's
livestock and poultry farmers, it is good to excellent,'' said
David White, executive director of Ohio Livestock Coalition and
commodity relations director for the Ohio Farm Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   White points out that the livestock and poultry industry
contributes more than $7.2 billion to Ohio's economy and generates
38,500 jobs. Farmers share the public's concern for water quality
and have been voluntarily using new strategies for manure
management, the coalition says.
</P>
<P>
   White said ``megafarm'' is an offensive term coined by opponents
of expansions. Coalition members prefer ``consumer-friendly farm''
or ``large-scale livestock operation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not only the trend,'' Buckeye Egg's Hansen said of
megafarms. ``They are necessary to feed the people of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
