<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: BERMUDA, N.Y.)  
 SAILOR LOOKS FOR HOME-WATER ADVANTAGE IN BERMUDA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having grown up in Bermuda, Paula Lewin has learned the
idiosyncrasies of wind along her island-nation's waterfront sailing
arena at Hamilton Harbor. With buildings on one side, and a hill on
the other, the breeze gets fluky. But when it comes to yacht
racing, the irregularity can pay off in a favorable lift that bodes
well for the sailor smart enough to see it coming.
</P>
<P>
   That tidbit of local knowledge is apt to work nicely for Lewin,
an unseeded competitor in this year's $60,000 Gold Cup. The
match-racing regatta is celebrating its 50th anniversary, and the
occasion has brought together some of the best match-race sailors
in the world. Among the eight seeded skippers are Peter Gilmour of
Australia, ranked No. 1 worldwide; Chris Law of England, No. 2;
Peter Holmberg of the U.S. Virgin Islands, No. 3; and from New
Zealand, Gavin Brady, No. 4, and Russell Coutts, No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of a lineup, a relative amateur such as Lewin
might seem out of place. But the event tries to mix up competitors,
just to make things interesting. ``I'm not intimidated by it,''
Lewin said in a recent telephone interview. ``I'm ready to step up
to the challenge, and I hope to win. When you get to a higher
level, you can't get frustrated about the people you're sailing
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-person teams will be competing in identical International
One Design sloops. The 33-foot yachts, which are heavier and less
agile than modern grand prix boats, have been used for the Gold Cup
since 1951.
</P>
<P>
   As skipper for the only all-women's crew in a field of 24 teams,
Lewin has more pressure than most. She's no slouch, however, having
reached No. 19 on the world rankings, the highest ever for a woman.
But men's teams with more racing experience will be sweating it out
among the 16 teams at the unseeded level, too.
</P>
<P>
   Take Paul Cayard, a veteran America's Cup skipper and recent
winner of the Whitbread Round the World Race. ``I've got it in my
mind that starting out in the unseeded group will give me the extra
practice that I need,'' Cayard said last week by telephone from San
Francisco. ``But the unseeded round doesn't look particularly easy
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Another unseeded team to deal with will surely be the boat
sailed by Glen Foster of New York. A retired stock exchange
specialist, the 68-year-old Foster has sailed all his life. He has
competed at the world-class level in 6-meter yachts, and regularly
sails a 29-foot Dragon in international regattas.
</P>
<P>
   In the Gold Cup, which Foster last sailed in 1953, he has
surrounded himself with a 30-something crew that includes three top
U.S. sailors: Ron Rosenberg, Morgan Larson and Kevin Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have enough confidence,'' Foster said. ``The others
could outmaneuver us, but then, we may outmaneuver them.''
</P>
<P>
   The round-robin series for unseeded skippers is scheduled to
begin Sunday. The top eight teams will then proceed to preliminary
racing against the eight seeded skippers beginning Tuesday. The
semifinals and finals are scheduled for next weekend .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just hoping for medium air and nothing too hairy,'' Lewin
said. ``These boats are physically challenging because they're so
heavy. I'm used to lighter boats, like the J/22 and J/24, that turn
more quickly. But it will be really good sailing. And if we win, it
would be terrific.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING WAVES
</P>
<P>
   A long-awaited low pressure system provided the 147-foot ketch
Mari-Cha III with the right conditions last Thursday to begin its
attempt at breaking the trans-Atlantic sailing record for
monohulls. The carbon fiber yacht set sail from Ambrose Light off
Sandy Hook, N.J. at 5:09 a.m., New York time, for its 3,000-mile
crossing. The boat, owned by Robert Miller of England, is out to
beat a west-to-east sailing time of nine days 22 hours set last
July by Christophe Auguin of France in his 60-foot sloop, Geodis.
... A dying northerly breeze and light, shifting winds marked the
last day of racing last weekend in the J/44 North American
Championship on Long Island Sound. Winner of the three-day regatta
was Mabuhay II , a J/44 owned by Dr. Eduardo Salvati of New York.
Eleven of the 44-foot sailboats raced from Saturday through
Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
