u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF18-COX     10-17 1767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RELIEF18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refugee relief tied up in web of red tape, danger, sheer numbers
 &HT;    By Bert Roughton Jr.
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GURIBARDHE, Yugoslavia _ Late Saturday morning, the rumbling of
large vehicles just over the grassy hills caused a knot in Ahmed
Gashi's stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Five months ago, Gashi, 32, fled with his wife, three children
and 88-year-old grandmother as the Serb military advanced on their
village.
</P>
<P>
   Fear drove them away then, and fear keeps them away.
</P>
<P>
   At first the family wandered in the open, eating what little
they had carried with them.
</P>
<P>
   In time, they found a vacant block house with a solid red-tile
roof strategically perched on a hillside. From the front porch,
they and another family, also displaced by the fighting, could scan
the valley.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed safe enough, but after a night listening to the sounds
of shelling a few miles away, on Saturday Gashi awoke edgy anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And now there was the rumble of heavy trucks.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, he could make out a white Land Cruiser with a flag rising
from its hood. It was followed by a convoy of eight trucks. His
heart rose. The blue-and-white flag bore the emblem of the U.N.
High Commissioner for Refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain to you what I felt to see this,'' Gashi later
told visitors at the house. ``Those trucks are the only hope for
our children to continue. It is how they hang on.''
</P>
<P>
   With winter coming on, it is a sight he may not see again for
some time.
</P>
<P>
   Interrupted for a few days by the mounting Kosovo crisis,
humanitarian aid trucks again are venturing out from Pristina, the
embattled province's capital.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, convoys organized by the U.N. refugee agency left
the Mother Teresa Warehouse outside Pristina in a dense early
morning fog and headed for two areas where refugees had
congregated. The trucks carried tons of food, clothing and shelter
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, aid planners in Pristina meet to consider more than a
dozen potential sites each in dire need before selecting what they
they think pick one or two.
</P>
<P>
   They are in a race against time. Aid workers must make as many
deliveries as possible in the next few weeks before winter comes.
</P>
<P>
   When the snows fall, the condition of the Kosovo refugees
_particularly the children _ will become dramatically worse, just
as access to them becomes even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   It is a complex and frustrating undertaking plagued by
uncertainty, poor roads, bad weather, land mines, red tape and
tensions that have accompanied the boom of humanitarian aid groups
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you feel like there are so many brushfires, and
we've just got this one fire brigade,'' said Francis Teoh, a new
deputy in the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest challenge is getting a handle on how many
needy people are out there and where to find them.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody knows with certainty how many people have been displaced
by the war. Estimates range from 250,000 to more than 450,000, and
the number seems to change all the time. Teoh is suspicious of the
numbers because displaced people move around so much. Sometimes
monitors don't see them where they hide, and other times they count
them twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest thing,'' Teoh said. ``We must have better
numbers to be able to develop effective plans.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty creates a logistical nightmare. ``You'll get a
report that on one day there are 5,000 people in a place and by the
time you get there, there won't be anybody,'' said Mick Lorentzen,
the director for the World Food Program office here. ``It's hard to
chase a moving target with bags of flour.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's convoy, for example, equipped to aid 13,000 people,
learned on it arrival that there were actually 25,000 displaced
people in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, the 20,000 residents of nearby villages, who have
helped the refugees, have now depleted their own already meager
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, the locals have now joined the rolls of the needy.
``The conditions for both groups now are the same,'' said Bahti
Thaqi, the Mother Teresa Society coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, displaced people in Kosovo are not
defined by most groups as refugees because they have not crossed a
national border. This creates a problem for organizations such as
the various United Nations relief agencies and Care International,
who focus primarily on refugees.
</P>
<P>
   To cope with these technicalities, the agencies have agreed to
structure their aid in a way to care for as many of the people
affected by the war as possible, Lorentzen said. ``They're all in
need, so we figure it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to this the explosion of humanitarian aid groups in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, a half-dozen foreign humanitarian aid groups had
offices here. Now there are more than 30, with each seeking to
develop their own programs.
</P>
<P>
   While no one argues that the need is immense, the flood of
agencies _ some of them relatively inexperienced _ poses
significant issues with coordination and logistics. ``So many
people are, here and more and more are coming in,'' Teoh said. ``We
may have to close the door.''
</P>
<P>
   In Pristina, the organizations are snapping up offices and
installing fax machines, phone lines and computers. They are
staffing up on talented locals, for whom there sometimes is tough
competition.
</P>
<P>
   As it is with human nature, the familiar battles of egos and
politics sometimes color discussions intended to find solutions for
people in profound need for even the basic needs of life. ``It's a
bit disgusting perhaps, but it's a reality,'' said Stephen Pratt,
the Yugoslavia director for CARE International. ``When you're an
aid organization, you have to be dynamic or die.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the organizations so far have been able to work out their
differences, aid workers say. The aid convoys, the single largest
act of cooperation, somehow manage to depart on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Once outside Pristina, Saturday's convoy entered the region
where much of the fighting has been. Almost all villages were
deserted, the fields untended and many of the buildings destroyed.
Dogs and livestock wandered the landscape, free after months
without human supervision.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, there were Serb soldiers, who apparently have
taken up residence in some of the evacuated buildings, particularly
gas stations, presumably because they have stores of motor fuel. On
the black market, gasoline is being sold for about $15 a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   After passing through Malisehva, the convoy left the paved road
and struck out on a narrow jarring path of rock and dirt that
snakes over the hills. In the distance are the snow capped Dinaric
Alps, the jagged mountain range that rises between Kosso and
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most of the shooting has stopped, security remains
an issue for these unarmed convoys. In addition to the sometimes
less than cordial attitude of Serbian police and soldiers, aid
workers worry about traveling through country that at times seems
lawless.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, anti-tank mines have been found buried in roads
like the one the convoy is taking to Guribardhe. Maps showing the
mined roads are updated and circulated frequently among the aid
agencies. Even so, it is a threat that is never far from anyone's
thoughts on these roads.
</P>
<P>
   The suffering at the end of the road is hard for even veteran
aid workers to take. A woman with Care International shed tears as
she spoke to a weeping woman staying with her family in a cramped,
fly infested house across a muddy yard from a dank, smelly barn in
Guribardie.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Sahadete Morina, is with her daughter-in-law and five
grandchildren. Morina has not seen her son, Nevzat, since soon
after they fled their town of Klina Cvrk last summer.
</P>
<P>
   One day, when the family was living in the woods after escaping,
her son was walking, holding the hands of his daughters, 6 and 4,
Morina said, a 2-year-old grandchild on her hip. ``The soldiers got
him, pulled him from his children,'' she said, also telling the
story with her hands.
</P>
<P>
   The two girls stood at her side, listening without emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen him since,'' she said, the tears returning. ``I
think they must have killed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with their bitter memories, the refugees face a hard
future.
</P>
<P>
   For the children, it is particularly dire, aid workers say. Many
of the children who flocked around the aid workers Saturday had
runny noses and fevers. Many still wear the sandals they were
wearing when they left home last summer. Their mothers said many
had diarrhea and poor access to good drinking water.
</P>
<P>
   The 74 refugees living in a schoolhouse nearby get their water
from a muddy well they have dug in the playground. They have been
living for months on the crude bread they make from the flour,
sugar and vegetable oil that arrives when the convoys come. They
also get some rice, pasta and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Meat for most is something between a vague memory and distant
longing. Refugees tended to laugh Saturday when asked when they
last had any meat.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere there were small children and babies. A woman at the
school proudly produced a 6-week-old baby she says she delivered in
the woods before finding this shelter. ``Look how beautiful,'' she
said as she presented the bundled infant to a visitor. But two
women and their babies also have died in childbirth at the school,
which has only the infrequent attention of a doctor.
</P>
<P>
   Life for babies is hard and promises to get even harder when the
extreme cold arrives. While diarrhea is common, diapers are rare.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful of what the winter will bring aid workers want
desperately for the refugees to return to their homes, where they
might stand a better than fighting chance with the weather.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to gaining at least somewhat better shelter, aid
workers are eager for some stability and predictability. Only then
can they develop plans for the winter that make good sense, they
say.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, the fear that drove them from their homes seems to have
subsided little. And each night when they hear the shellings and
gunfire echoing over the hills, they become less inclined to leave
whatever shelter they have found to strike out toward home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will go home only when all the police have left our
villages,'' said Idriz Shabani, whose family is sharing a small
room in a dark, house-filled house, with two other families. ``Only
then will there be any safety for us. Until then, we'll stay and do
what we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
