<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 17:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2828 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-BOHO-LOFTS-900&AMP;ADD     10-17 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BOHO-LOFTS-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: STRETCHING THE LOFT SCENE ONTO STREETS CALLED BOHO 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan Sasson's divorce was so nasty and so prolonged that when it
was finally over, he was, in a sense, homeless _ in an affluent
sort of way. He had an apartment, after the property was divided
up, but it was rented out and he needed the income.
</P>
<P>
   He had no job, because his investment in a chicken-restaurant
franchise had gone bad and had diverted him from his
once-prosperous jewelry business. He had just gone through an
operation to replace a hip. So at the end, exhausted and
shell-shocked, he was taken in by his lawyer's assistant, who let
him stay with her for a few months until he could find a job and
start over.
</P>
<P>
   Now his downtown loft on Broome Street near the Bowery is so
chic, so decidedly hip, with its exposed brick walls, leather
couches and huge restaurant-style stove, that it is impossible not
to wonder: Is this really the home of a man who recently had
nothing, who rented a room in an apartment on the Bowery?
</P>
<P>
   But his possessions _ the table bought for $10 from a homeless
man who was wheeling it down the street, the mirror that belonged
to his grandmother in the Bronx, the bureau he used as a child on
Long Island _ tell the tale of someone who has spent little to
furnish his place.
</P>
<P>
   He renovated it _ as well as the space below that he rents out _
using credit cards and the proceeds from selling the apartment he
had kept. But mostly, he did it by having an idea, and with it, he
has rebuilt his life. At least, his material life.
</P>
<P>
   Sasson, the son of a watchmaker, grew up on Long Island and went
into the diamond business as a young man because it seemed like a
logical thing to do. But on the side, he always played around with
real estate, because he loved architecture and had a feeling for
the possibilities inherent in space. Eventually he owned a few
places on Long Island and two co-ops in a loft building on Bleecker
Street.
</P>
<P>
   After divorcing his first wife, he met a woman, a part-time
model, in a bar, he said. They married and had a son. But in 1994,
after only four years, they broke up, and his comfortable, affluent
life unraveled.
</P>
<P>
   When the divorce was final, and he was living in his lawyer's
assistant's apartment, he began planning his new life.
</P>
<P>
   Because he had a real estate license, he was able in 1997 to get
a job with Citi Habitats, a rental brokerage company that wanted to
expand into sales. He started their sales division, which he still
runs, and he began making a steady income again. He found an ad for
a room to rent in an apartment on the Bowery for $600 a month in a
photographer's loft shared by four people. It wasn't a great place
to visit with his son, but he stayed for four months because he
could pay the rent.
</P>
<P>
   And the location was fateful, not far from the building where he
had had his jewelry business, in a neighborhood he considers ripe
for development, at the eastern edge of SoHo and the western edge
of the East Village.
</P>
<P>
   He began knocking on doors, trying to find space he might
renovate and then rent out, convinced that people who were paying
thousands of dollars a month for large lofts in SoHo would do the
same in a neighborhood some call BoHo, for Bowery below Houston.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the buildings, he said, are owned by people who run the
retail stores below, in some cases third-generation owners whose
families had originally lived on the Lower East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them, he said, do not want to sell their buildings
because they would face enormous capital-gains taxes, or maybe
because they believe the buildings will appreciate far more in the
next few years.
</P>
<P>
   He met the owner of a building on Broome Street near the Bowery,
a building with a retail business on the ground floor but empty
boarded-up space on the two floors above. The owner took him
upstairs. There were no floors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to walk on the joists,'' he said. The ceiling had been
dropped, so it was only seven-and-a-half-feet high. ``I was jumping
out of my skin,'' he said. ``I was so excited to see this.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people would have taken a look at the dark, cavelike space
and walked away. But he figured that if someone opened it up and
put in the right finishes, it could rival any SoHo loft.
</P>
<P>
   He reached an agreement to rent both floors for 15 years, hoping
he could rent out the 2,500-square-foot lower loft for a price that
would cover most of his costs so he could live nearly rent free in
the 1,300 square feet upstairs. The landlord provided new floors,
fixed the crumbling walls and put in plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   Sasson renovated the apartments with the kinds of finishes and
appliances typical of high-end downtown lofts, but in some cases he
used materials that give a similar look but cost less. The counters
in his kitchen, for instance, look like green slate from a distance
but are really laminate.
</P>
<P>
   And he paid attention to the details that people care about,
because they provide character, and people pay for character.
</P>
<P>
   He told the landlord that he wanted brick and not sheetrock on
the walls _ and that it should be old brick, so the place would not
look as if it had just been built.
</P>
<P>
   He salvaged what he could, too, finding an old etched-glass door
in the basement that he stripped and used as the door to a pantry.
He rented out the loft downstairs for $5,600 a month to three men
who work on Wall Street, and in early September he moved into his
new loft, leaving an apartment he had been renting from a friend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Now he is negotiating with other owners of buildings near the
Bowery, hoping to lease more space that he will renovate and rent.
He likes the neighborhood and the architecture; he walks up and
down the streets imagining what the buildings could be if they were
cleaned up, fixed up.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, these streets were part of Chinatown. But many
of the Asian-American tenants have been leaving. Not all, though _
next door to his building is a kimchi factory that gives a distinct
smell to the hallways of his building, but not to the apartments.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood has few services _ ``You can't buy a quart of
milk or a newspaper,'' he said _ but once a ``destination''
restaurant arrives, a place like Balthazar, he is sure the other
retailers will follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The architecture is here, and that's where it all starts,'' he
said, pointing to a building on the Bowery he said was ``as nice as
anything in SoHo.''
</P>
<P>
   He is proud of himself, too, for persevering, he said, and these
days for having a regular relationship with his son, which was
interrupted by the conflict over the divorce.
</P>
<P>
   And financially? ``I'm about where I was 12 years ago,'' he
said. ``I guess that's progress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
