<P>
   SERB CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SHELLING _ VRAGOBIL, Yugoslavia _ On Friday as NATO
extended its deadline for Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic
to comply with a U.S.-brokered peace agreement, this small hill
village was shelled through the night, terrifying residents and
damaging dozens of homes. Serb forces in the area also did not
appear to be making any attempts to withdraw, even though Milosevic
has agreed to reduce the Serb military presence in Kosovo.
(Roughton, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ATTN EDs: Today marks 25 years since the Arab oil embargo of
1973, following the Yom Kippur War. Cox Newspapers foreign bureaus
and Washington will take a look at where the world goes from here
in terms of oil production and consumption, with an underlying
question: Could it happen again? The following are budget lines for
the package, which MOVED Mon., Oct. 12, in both the (i)
International and (k) Commentary categories for use in
Perspective/Opinion/Insight sections:
</P>
<P>
   OIL-EMBARGO _ WASHINGTON _ What ever happened to fuel
efficiency? Today, it seems like every other vehicle on the road in
the United States is a gas-guzzling, four-wheel drive sport utility
vehicle. What, if anything is the government and/or auto industry
doing to conserve fuel? What ever happened to the strategic oil
reserve; and all the dire predictions? We'll also wrap in what it
was like when the embargo first hit, looking at things like
President Richard Nixon's speech telling Americans that their lives
would never be the same. (Mollison, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OIL-MIDEAST _ KUWAIT CITY, Kuwait _ As times get a little
tighter in this oil-rich sheikhdom on the desert, they have even
considered raising the price of gasoline. The oil minister has
noted the irony. ``It looks odd and peculiar that, at a time when
many countries are cutting the prices at the gas stations, you're
increasing it in Kuwait. That's absurd,'' said Saud Nasir Al-Saud
Al-Sabah in a recent interview. ``I don't think this is something
that's acceptable to us now.'' It costs about 50 cents a gallon to
fill up the many large cars that are the preference here. While the
government is removing the subsidies that have kept the price low,
dropping world oil prices have protected Kuwaiti motorists from
seeing any increase at gas stations. Therein lies the problem.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OIL-LATAM _ MEXICO CITY _ After the Arab oil embargo, the United
States pledged to diversify the foreign sources of its oil
supplies. Over the years, more and more imports of foreign oil have
come from the Americas _ from Canada, Mexico, Venezuela and other
Western Hemisphere countries. The Western Hemisphere, in fact, now
accounts for more than half of foreign oil imports. Mexico, which
nationalized its oil in 1938 and is now the world's fifth largest
producer, once sought to limit sales of oil to the United States to
under 50 percent of its exports out of fear of domination. Mexico
is also very dependent on its oil, in spite of attempts to
diversity its economy. So far this year, with falling oil prices,
Mexico has been forced to cut its budget three times.
(Emling/Ferriss, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OIL-RUSSIA _ MOSCOW _ Boomtowns in Russia? Despite its current
economic turmoil, Russia ranks among the world's most fertile
countries in proven reserves of oil and natural gas. Parts of the
former Soviet Union are flourishing as American and other Western
companies scramble to get in on prospecting that could help to lift
Russia out of its economic mess. Off Sakhalin Island in the
northern Pacific and in the Caspian Sea region on Russia's southern
fringe, billions of dollars are being spent on exploration and
drilling. Sizable American diplomatic and technical resources are
at play, too, in the effort to reach the oil in harsh climates and
a politically unstable region. (Holmes, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OIL-ASIA _ BEIJING _ A quarter-century after the last energy
crisis, the price of oil is once again resetting the balance of
power throughout the world _ starting in Asia. With the world
market gorged with cheap petroleum, oil-exporter Indonesia could no
longer support a high standard of living for its masses. The rupiah
collapsed and then the Suharto regime collapsed. Yet what felled
Indonesia has helped ignite China's explosive growth. Until 1997,
China was a net oil exporter, but now it needs more oil if it is to
sustain its 8 percent a year growth path. For now, China continues
to expand its economy, thanks in part to the relatively cheap oil
it imports from Saudi Arabia. Another beneficiary is India, which
like China lacks super-giant oilfields to sustain its growth.
(Kunstel/Albright, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   OIL-DATA _ WASHINGTON _ Information for graphics, including:
snapshot of major oil importers vs oil exporters; Retail Price of
Gasoline in U.S. (trend); World Crude Oil Production (trend); U.S.
Per Capital Petroleum Use (trend); U.S. Strategic Petroleum Reserve
(trend); and a Then and Now List. (Mollison, Cox News Service).
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RELIEF _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The massive relief effort
struggling to get back underway here is being delayed by red tape,
land mines, funding and the sheer scope of the struggle among 50
relief agencies climbing all over themselves for a piece of the
pie. They are being coordinated loosely by the United Nations,
which is in a predicament because its charter forbids it from
providing assistance to ``domestic refugees'' _ those who have not
crossed into another country. There are 550,000 Bosnian Serb and
Croat refugees already here _ some of been here four years _ and
they also pose a problem. (Roughton, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-SHARON _ JERUSALEM _ Israel's newly appointed foreign
minister Ariel Sharon arrives in Washington on Saturday to join the
Mideast summit between Israeli and Palestinian leaders. But what
effect will all the baggage that the controversial former military
commander brings with him have on the summit talks? A newsy profile
of Sharon. (Kaplow, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ELECTIONS-LOTTERIES _ Whether to establish a lottery like
Georgia's is the hottest issue in the governor's race in the two
bordering states of Alabama and South Carolina. A look at which way
voters are leaning and what the gambling debate has done to the
campaigns. (Manuel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   GOVS-BROTHERS _ Last year, Republicans took over both houses of
the Florida legislature. This year, it looks like they'll win the
governor's chair. Jeb Bush is leading Democratic Lt. Gov. Buddy
MacKaye. If brother George W. Bush wins Texas, Jeb would be part of
the first governor brothers pair in U.S. history. (MWilliams,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SPACETV _ What's the biggest story of the century? For veteran
newsman Walter Cronkite there's only one answer: space exploration.
Cronkite covered John Glenn's historic 1962 Mercury mission that
orbited the Earth and now he's come out of retirement to cover
Glenn's Challenger mission beginning Oct. 29. And once again,
television will be the vehicle that informs and inspires when it
comes to travel beyond the hemisphere. Will also look at the
changes in viewer interest and television technology. (Holloway,
Austin American-Statesman). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   Box of network and cable news programming for the launch.
</P>
<P>
   Box of TV comparisons between 1962 and 1998. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   HOGS _ Thirty-five years ago, when the family of Brookville,
Ohio, farmer Pete Dull was ready to sell their hogs, they put the
pigs in a trailer and drove to one of several Dayton
slaughterhouses. But then they closed. So the family began taking
the hogs to a packing plant in Troy. It closed, too. That forced
them to haul the animals to Hillshire Farm &AMP; Kahn's in Cincinnati,
a round trip of over 100 miles. Four years ago, that slaughterhouse
shut down as well. Today, Dull's hogs go to Kentucky and Indiana,
trips that cost him an extra $2.50 or so per hog (he raises about
10,000 a year). That would be bad enough in a robust market, but
pork prices this year are at their lowest level in five years.
(Keilman, Dayton Daily News). 25. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
