<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2832 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     10-17 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNOW THIS: CHAN CHANGES COWBOYS FOR BETTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it was Jimmy and Jerry, egos overflowed at Valley Ranch.
The thermostat was permanently set on chilly.
</P>
<P>
   When it was Gunsmoke and Jerry, there was a San Francisco-like
environment at Valley Ranch. No, not the 49ers. Thick fog.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Chan Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Give it a few years and we all will know how it worked out, but
the early returns do show some dramatic changes at the Valley Ranch
bunker.
</P>
<P>
   With football being the focus once again, that puts the Cowboys
back into the Jimmy era. But without the I-I-I-me-me-me contest
between coach and owner.
</P>
<P>
   And with Gailey proving himself qualified to conduct football
business, when was the last time you heard Jerry hint around about
wanting to coach the Cowboys?
</P>
<P>
   With The Smokester on the scene, Jones could say it and be taken
halfway serious. Which was an embarrassment to both.
</P>
<P>
   With Gailey, Jones doesn't even think it, which happens when the
owner respects his coach as a coach instead of trying to cover up
for a friend and drinking buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Over the long haul, the Cowboys will have success or failure
based on Gailey, the football man. But thus far, the human side has
been intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   It was Troy Aikman, on the last day of training camp in Wichita
Falls, who said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The players are going to respect him and like him, but none us
are really going to know him. Chan is not here to be our friend.
Everyone, including me, is kept at an arm's length.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will all know what he's thinking, good or bad. But we
aren't going to know everything. No one should ever become
overconfident about where they personally stand with Chan. As a
player, you might be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the coaching ``edge.'' Tom Landry had it,
Jimmy had it ... but in a totally different way. Now here's Gailey,
different from both, but probably closer to Landry.
</P>
<P>
   Except there's the other side of Gailey.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in the Carolina game, the Cowboys had offensive
confusion at the end of the first half. What resulted was bad clock
management and bad decisions. Afterward, Gailey, with a smile,
said, ``I blame the offensive coordinator. He really screwed up.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would be Chan Gailey, the head coach's
offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   But Gailey volunteered an additional chapter to the story, one
that most head coaches in the NFL probably wouldn't. Except here's
a case where ego is held in check.
</P>
<P>
   Told that press box second-guessing was extreme due to the end
of the first-half confusion, Gailey replied, ``I'm sure it was, but
that doesn't brother me. Besides, it couldn't have been as bad as
what I got at home. My wife unloaded on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gailey explained that with wife Laurie, they had stopped by the
post-game coaches' reception at Texas Stadium, then departed for a
Sunday evening church service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was kind of pleasant _ we had won the game and
all,'' he said. ``But when we got home, Laurie says, `We need to
talk about your two-minute offense. You've got to do something
about that. It was pitiful.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't too pleased about it myself, but she got all over
me,'' continued Gailey, laughing. ``Laurie is not only the greatest
wife, she's also got a good football mind. Don't ever sit around
her at a game _ she'll tell you what she's thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, there was that time when Gailey was coaching in
college at Troy State _ in fact, it was his Troy State team that
won the small college national championship. During the season,
there was a tense game with Mississippi College.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gotten the lead late, then got the ball back, and
really had the running game going,'' said Gailey. ``The clock was
moving, but I decided to get cute _ I called for a pass. I figured
I'd nail it down right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Except his quarterback was hit, fumbled, and the other team
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to hold on, but our defense saved us, and we won the
game,'' said Gailey. ``In the last few seconds, I'm standing there
on the sidelines all relieved and feeling pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I hear this, `Chan ... Chan.' Laurie had left the stands,
come down to the fence, and she says, `That was the dumbest call
I've ever seen.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Later, we're talking, and I said, `Laurie, you can't say that
in front of the players and the fans.' Her answer was, `Well, I was
just telling you what they were also thinking.'''
</P>
<P>
   So if there's some questionable play-calling in Chicago today,
Gailey said he doesn't have to read about it Monday morning: ``I
will already have heard everything when I get back home Sunday
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, things have changed at Valley Ranch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
