10-17 -- Tony Torrence, foreground, a history teacher at the La
Jolla Day School, and a native New Yorker, along with his students,
is rooting for the San Diego Padres. ``I want the Padres to win.
I'm a diehard Met fan. If the Padres were playing the Mets, I would
be rooting for the Mets. The Yankees have won enough. Tony Gwynn
deserves one.'' (Robert Burroughs/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAN DIEGO -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- BBO-SERIES-SANDIEGO-1,
10-17 -- Alan Aiello, a 28-year San Diego resident from Brooklyn,
N.Y., has a difficult choice to make for this year's World Series.
For Aiello, a Padres-Yankees matchup has caused an inner struggle
about whom he is going to root for: the team that is part of his
soul, or the team of underdogs that has grabbed most of the hearts
in San Diego. ``I have decided only one thing,'' he says. ``My
tailor is going to take half of my Yankees hat and half of my
Padres hat and sew them together.'' (Robert Burroughs/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) UNDATED -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- CT-COLUMN-TRAINMAN, 10-17 --
To connoisseurs of commuting, Travis Ford, a Metro-North conductor
on the New Haven line, is a folk hero, a font of graciousness in
their otherwise rough-and-tumble day. Ford dishes up daily weather
reports, baseball scores, inspirational pep talks and greetings in
a dozen languages to passengers. ``He makes everybody smile,'' says
Mike Imber, a passenger from Westport. It's refreshing to see
somebody who has such a joy for what he does.'' (Thomas
McDonald/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- CALIF-TOBACCO, 10-17 --
Film director Rob Reiner, a lifelong Democrat, is campaigning for
an initiative to add a 50-cent tax to cigarettes in California.
Behind him, a commercial for the initiative plays. Some experts on
smoking say that the additional tax will discourage thousands of
teen-agers from ever lighting up and will encourage thousands more,
including many adults, to quit. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MILWAUKEE -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- WIS-WELFARE-2, 10-17 --
Albirta Glenn, with children Jarkius Person, center, and Dashareia
Glenn, looked for a job on her own while lacking child care. Ms.
Glenn says she received ``little help'' when she applied to
Wisconsin Works, also known as W-2, which accounts for 87 percent
of the state's 11,000 welfare cases. ``My caseworker told me to
spend 30 days looking for a job on my own, with little help or
supervision,'' she says. (Lloyd DeGrane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MILWAUKEE -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- WIS-WELFARE-1, 10-17 --
Wisconsin Works, a program implemented to bridge the gap between
welfare and jobs, helped Michelle Crawford, 38, to work in a
Milwaukee plastics factory. ``They treated me with respect,'' says
Ms. Crawford, referring to the Wisconsin Works program. But despite
certain success stories, many of those in the program describe
their caseworkers as distant and distracted figures. (Lloyd
DeGrane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- TAIWAN-VETS-2, 10-17 --
Nationalist veterans from Taiwan carrying flags and a mock coffin
in memory of a comrade, as part of a demonstration in Manhattan's
Chinatown against Taiwan's government, demanding more retirement
benefits. To date, the campaign has largely swirled in the New York
area, partly because Chinatown holds the largest concentration of
veterans from Taiwan, and partly because veterans elsewhere in the
country live too far from one another to organize effectively. (Vic
DeLucia/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Oct. 17, 1998 -- TAIWAN-VETS-1, 10-17 --
William Wong, 66, in his Chinatown apartment, cannot afford to
inter the ashes of three Nationalist comrades from Taiwan, in boxes
at left. After decades of hiding in the shadows of society's
margins, the Nationalist veterans, many of whom live in New York,
are seeking recognition and have demanded more retirement benefits
from Taiwan's government. ``I miss my friends. Some day, I'd like
to be able to bury them with the proper respect,'' says Wong. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
