<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2845 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-COMMERCIAL-REAL-2T     10-17 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COMMERCIAL-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: THE VORNADO TORNADO SLOWS DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Steven Roth, chairman of Vornado Realty Trust, hit
New York's office market like a whirlwind last year, buying Bernard
Mendik's portfolio of 4 million square feet of Manhattan properties
for $650 million as Mendik Co. was preparing to become the city's
first real estate investment trust.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came as a surprise, because Vornado was best known as
the operator of suburban shopping centers.
</P>
<P>
   But having decided to move into the Manhattan office market,
Roth went on a tear, spending an additional $1.7 billion to acquire
such properties as the building known as One Penn Plaza, which
occupies most of the block bounded by 33rd and 34th Streets and
Seventh and Eighth Avenues.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Vornado bought all or the large majority of the
ownership positions in 20 buildings in the city including most of
the buildings on both sides of Seventh Avenue between 31st and 34th
Streets. The company has said it plans to transform the area into
the urban equivalent of an entertainment-oriented shopping mall,
with Macy's at 34th Street and Penn Station-Madison Square Garden
complex serving as anchors.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, Roth has been less active. Since announcing an
agreement to acquire the 1 million-square-foot building at 770
Broadway at Eighth Street and a smaller structure in June, little
news has flowed from Vornado's headquarters in Saddle Brook, N.J.
Last week, the company did announce that Mendik, who had been
co-chairman of Vornado, had resigned to pursue private interests
and said that it had acquired some property from Mendik's partners
for $104 million.
</P>
<P>
   Some real estate executives have speculated that the steep
decline in the price of Vornado's stock (the name comes from a fan
company taken over by Roth's predecessor as a tax shelter) have
made it impossible for the company to issue operating partnership
units, which eventually convert into common stock, to pay for
properties.
</P>
<P>
   Vornado's stock, which reached almost $50 a share earlier this
year, has been trading recently in the vicinity of $30 a share.
Most REIT industry shares have, of course, taken a pounding in the
stock market in recent months. The argument is that if a REIT meets
an owner's price with the devalued stock, it will be perceived to
have overpaid if the stock price rises to what the REIT managers
consider a ``normal'' level.
</P>
<P>
   Roth does not appear much in public. Indeed, he proclaims in
Vornado's annual report that ``we will continue our policy of
almost never talking to the press.''
</P>
<P>
   But Roth did appear at a recent state-of-the-market meeting
organized by Insignia/ESG, the current corporate form of the old
Edward S. Gordon Co.
</P>
<P>
   At that meeting, Roth conceded that his company's acquisition
pace had slowed considerably in recent months. But he said that the
ability to pay was not an issue because the company had over $1
billion available to finance purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, he said, is that owners' expectation of what their
properties are worth have become overly inflated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just gone through a period of participating at
auctions held by institutions,'' he said, ``and we have been coming
in third and fourth. The pricing is wrong. That is why we have not
bought a building in six or seven months.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the big numbers involved in the company's entry to
the Manhattan office market, he said, Vornado's cost basis for its
buildings is $175 a square foot in a market where new construction
costs from $400 to $450 a square foot. Noting that many of the
properties were occupied by tenants with rents below the current
market rate, he said that the company would be supplied with
increasing cash as the leases expired and rents moved up toward
market levels. ``We have $30 space in a $40 market,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As the rents roll over, he said, they will add $130 million a
year to Vornado's cash flow over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said the suspicion that some aggressive buyers overpaid for
property was reflected in the capital markets. In the early 1980s,
he said, interest rates were high, but lenders were willing to
finance all of an acquisition. ``You could borrow 105 percent of a
piece of real estate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that rates had generally declined from that period until
now, but that lenders were willing to finance only a smaller part
of a deal. ``The rates are low, but you can't borrow more than 60
percent of the cost of an asset,'' Roth said. ``My theory is that
the lenders suspect that the value of the buildings will go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth described the debt markets as being ``in chaos,''
apparently referring to the market for commercial mortgage-backed
securities, where as much as $20 billion in loans has piled up
awaiting sale. He said the lack of debt financing would choke off a
lot of new building.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he told the group of real estate brokers and
executives, in a time of economic uncertainty caused largely by
events in Asia and other overseas markets, ``for the first time
real estate's not the bad guys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people have a stunningly reasonable amount of debt,'' he
said, ``and there are almost no defaults in real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the recession was preceded by a wave of real
estate development, particularly in Manhattan. As a result, many
developers could not fill their properties with tenants at rental
rates anticipated in their financial projections. Some defaulted,
losing the buildings to lenders, who absorbed losses when they were
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, tough times can also provide buying opportunities,
Roth noted. That's what he did in 1980, gaining control of Vornado
and its valuable real estate, as the Two Guys retail chain the
company was then operating faded. He repeated the trick later in
the decade, taking control of Alexander's Inc. and its real estate
as the retail operations became unprofitable.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Although Vornado has extensive exposure to the retail market,
with 59 shopping centers with 12.4 million square feet of space as
of the end of last year, Roth said he ``lost faith in retail as an
investment in the mid-1990s.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The retail market is saturated and the retailers are mature
and non-differentiated,'' he told the real estate group. ``They are
all selling the same products. Retail is going to get murdered in
the next recession.''
</P>
<P>
   Although best known for its shopping centers and, more recently,
for its incursion into Manhattan, Vornado is a broadly diversified
company. Roth said he seeks to invest in ``fortress'' or
``franchise'' properties whose very size or unique position in an
industry protects them from competition.
</P>
<P>
   One example, he said, is the company's 60 percent interest in
Americold Logistics, which operates 80 refrigerated warehouses,
with 394 million cubic feet of space. The company accounts for 25
percent of the refrigerated public warehouse space in the country
and Roth said anyone buying a frozen turkey in this area was
getting a bird that probably spent some time in one of those
warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Another is the Merchandise Mart in Chicago, a
5.4-million-square-foot building that Vornado bought in April for
$630 million. Roth said the facility was the major trade show
building for the furniture industry and that 65 percent of all the
contracts for office furniture are signed there annually.
</P>
<P>
   Roth may have something similar in mind for the fortress he has
assembled along Seventh Avenue in the Penn Station area. The
properties, which include the 1,700-room Hotel Pennsylvania, had
largely been individually owned. Roth had remarked in a previous
interview that ``there is a lot you can do when ownership is
concentrated in one strong hand.''
</P>
<P>
   He told the real estate group that he expected the trend toward
public ownership of real estate to continue, but at a slower rate
than that of the last few years because of the dip in REIT stock
prices and unavailability of public capital. Because REITs are
required to pay out 95 percent of their income to shareholders in
dividends, they have little in the way of retained earnings and
must return to public markets to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
   Roth said that real estate companies considering adopting the
REIT structure would just have to accept the fact that stock prices
fluctuate in unpredictable ways. ``Our stock dived six months ago
when the business was never better,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said that there was at least one way in which running a
public company was not that much different from the
family-controlled real estate companies, which are a hallmark of
New York real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public companies have to deal with analysts and family
companies have to deal with cousins,'' Roth said. ``And they are
both pains.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
