<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON JOINS TALKS BETWEEN NETANYAHU, ARAFAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUEENSTOWN, Md. _ President Clinton flew to a secluded Maryland
conference center Saturday in an attempt to salvage Mideast peace
talks and preserve one of the few major foreign policy successes of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Skipping his 25th reunion at Yale Law School, Clinton joined
most of his national security team here as Israelis and
Palestinians continued to bicker about antiterrorist measures.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential scholars and Middle East specialists said that the
four-day summit is a risky move for Clinton because the chances of
failure are great and even a successful agreement between Israeli
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian President Yasser
Arafat is likely to be small. Any accord that is reached could be
endangered by a new violence in the Mideast.
</P>
<P>
   With congressional elections just 2 1/2 weeks away and
impeachment hearings looming, ``It's important that Clinton not be
seen as out of the loop, that he shows he is working for peace in
the Mideast, not relaxing at Hyannisport or Jackson Hole or
Hollywood,'' said Douglas Brinkley, a presidential and diplomatic
historian at the University of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had put Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright in
charge of the day-to-day mediation at this conference, which is
supposed to conclude Sunday night. But the president canceled a
campaign appearance in St. Louis Friday night to be on hand and
decided to visit the conference center Saturday in order to goad
both sides into making concessions. Clinton might join the talks
again Sunday, and the White House said another round of
negotiations might be added tomorrow if there is no resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than any other foreign policy undertaking Clinton has
made, this one is a test of his leadership,'' said Wayne Owens, a
former Democratic congressman from Utah and former member of the
House Foreign Affairs Committee. ``These talks are especially
significant because of the current cloud over Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House hopes that the Israelis will agree to give up 13
percent more of the West Bank in exchange for Palestinians'
agreement to pursue terrorists more vigorously. But unlike many
high-profile international conferences, this time the outcome has
not been agreed to in advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing has happened yet at the talks that is going to make
this easy on Clinton,'' said Stephen Cohen, vice chairman of the
Center for Middle East Peace and Economic Cooperation. ``He's
definitely showing that he's still president.''
</P>
<P>
   If these talks are important to Clinton, they are equally
important to Albright. She has tried to avoid the fate of her
predecessor, Warren M. Christopher, who immersed himself in the
morass of Middle East politics.
</P>
<P>
   Just over a year ago, Albright said she would not ``tread
water'' while waiting for progress in the peace process. In another
attempt to prod the Israelis to withdraw from more West Bank
territory, Albright threatened in May to reveal details of the
negotiations that Netanyahu had wanted to keep secret. But the
White House prevented follow-through on that threat.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, Albright's tough image has been tarnished as
diplomatic muddling followed her tough talk about Iraqi dictator
Saddam Hussein and Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's major achievements overseas have been in forging a
peace accord in Ireland, halting the carnage in the Balkans, easing
a dictator from Haiti, dismantling ``loose nukes,'' and making
free-trade pacts.
</P>
<P>
   But massacres in Yugoslavia's Kosovo province have cast a pall
over the Balkans peace deal while Haiti has returned to its former
poverty and corruption despite tens of millions of dollars of aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's essential that Bill Clinton try to build on his modest
foreign policy successes over the last six years,'' Brinkley said.
``Trade policies and nuclear disarmament are not what presidents
are remembered for. War or peacemaking are what people remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after noon, Clinton arrived in his Marine helicopter at
the 1,000 acre former ranch on the banks of the Wye River near the
Maryland shore. The president had a light lunch with Albright and
other US participants at the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton held an 80-minute meeting with Arafat in a library, and
the two then took a five-minute walk with Arafat through the
retreat, which used to belong to the president of Steuben Glass
company. Continuing to seek support from Middle East leaders,
Clinton called Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak from a secure phone
at the operations center the White House set up on the grounds of
the conference center.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of the autumn day, Clinton sat outdoors and
talked with Netanyahu. The White House made clear their
conversation was ``informal,'' because observant Jews are not
supposed to work on the Sabbath, which ended at sunset.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists were kept 20 miles away, at a community college,
where they were given only bare-bones details of the president's
schedule. White House spokesman Joseph Lockhart characterized the
third day of talks as ``constructive'' and said Clinton will join
Sunday ``if he feels he can play a constructive role.''
</P>
<P>
   Trying to prevent the kind of battle of rhetoric common at
Mideast talks, the White House has demanded silence from the
spokesmen of Arafat and Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Material from the Associated Press and Reuters was used in this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
