<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2855 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--NBAPLAYERS-HNS &LR;      10-17 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--NBA </SLUG>
 PLAYERS-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Players try to make ends meet
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Checkmate.
</P>
<P>
   That's what NBA owners might hope for as the league-imposed
lockout drags on toward Nov. 15, which is when the first paychecks
are due the players.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides _ the players' union and the owners _ await the
ruling from John Feerick, dean of the Fordham University Law
School, on whether NBA teams must pay the guaranteed contracts to
approximately 220 players during the lockout. Feerick's decision,
which is expected Monday, will be a huge bargaining chip for the
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Should the union prevail, the owners no doubt will consider
making the players work for their money. But should the owners win,
they could hold the union hostage until the reality of the
financial crunch sets in.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Feerick) rules in favor of the owners,'' said
Washington forward Tracy Murray, ``it's going to kill the (morale
and position of the) players.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is probably what the owners hope for.
</P>
<P>
   Checkmate.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more to the point, paycheckmate.
</P>
<P>
   The owners gambled by canceling not only the preseason, but the
first two weeks of the regular season as well. The lost games
represent a ticket-revenue loss of well over $50 million to the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``That tells me that they mean business and they're scared to
death of some of the contracts that have been signed in the last
couple of years,'' said Chicago's Steve Kerr, the Bulls' union
representative. ``So they're willing to play serious hard ball to
force us into a bad deal where down the line they will more than
make up for the $50 million they're blowing off.''
</P>
<P>
   Anticipating financial hardship, union executive director Billy
Hunter has been working on a mechanism to provide financial support
to players if they are forced to miss paychecks. According to a
union spokesman, they have a $10 million war chest and some $25
million due them from licensing payments and bank credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've set up lines of credit with two major banks to make
money available, especially for our free-agent players, in
November,'' Hunter said. ``We've also been promised financial
support from the other unions in pro baseball, football and hockey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been making the rounds since last season urging players
to save money because we knew there'd be a good chance the owners
would lock us out again. The response from the players has been
positive. They believe in what we're trying to do and they fully
support leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Johnson, the Rockets' player representative, is one of
many players who worked for the veteran's minimum last season and
does not have a guaranteed contract for this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order to put food on the table, we've got to make money,''
Johnson said. ``If we don't win it (the ruling,) our backs are
against the wall. We're in the process of trying to establish a
line of credit to help guys. There are 100 some odd guys that
played at the minimum salary, and a lot of guys count on that
check.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2856 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXY-LBPT     10-17 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY CONTEMPLATES FIRE DAMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As Major League Soccer's third season kicked off seven
months ago, Danny Villanueva, the Los Angeles Galaxy's president
and general manager, spoke about what would constitute success for
his club in the coming season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MLS championship is at the Rose Bowl, and we want to be
there,'' he said. ``Anything less than that would be failure.''
</P>
<P>
   When MLS Cup '98 kicks off next Sunday afternoon, the Galaxy's
only role will be as spectators, but in the wake of their
elimination from the championship race, he was forced to rethink
his position.
</P>
<P>
   After a campaign in which L.A. set MLS records for wins (24),
points (68) and goals (85), scored at least five times in eight
games, notched seven shutouts and allowed just one goal 13 times,
opened the season with nine successive victories and dominated
every opponent but two the Chicago Fire, who advanced to the title
game with Friday night's 2-1 shootout victory at Soldier Field, and
their likely foe, D.C. United Villanueva had to redefine success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing can wipe away the torrid, record-setting pace that we
gave this year,'' he said. ``I'm very proud of this team. They
essentially rewrote most of the records in this league. That's what
makes being eliminated so difficult to take. When you have perhaps
the best sustained effort in this league's short history, any way
of being eliminated shootout or otherwise is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a phenomenal year for the Galaxy, who embodied Coach
Octavio Zambrano's dynamic attacking sensibilities, playing MLS's
most attractive soccer while also leading the league in defense:
</P>
<P>
   They overcame the loss of captain Dan Calichman, their spiritual
leader, to a broken leg in May, with second-year defender Steve
Jolley emerging as a force in his presence as L.A. ran away with
their second Western Conference regular-season title in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   They got an MVP-caliber season from Cobi Jones, who finished
second in the league scoring race with 51 points (18 goals, 13
assists) despite missing eight games while on World Cup duty, and
had two others among the top seven scorers No. 3 Welton, with 45
points (17, 11), and No. 7 Mauricio Cienfuegos, with 42 (13, 16).
Three others reached double digits in assists: Martin Machon (14),
Carlos Hermosillo (12) and Clint Mathis (10).
</P>
<P>
   They played superb defense, with veteran Robin Fraser anchoring
a unit that surrendered just 44 goals despite Jolley's inexperience
and a platoon system at work at both outside positions.
</P>
<P>
   And they saw the emergence of nearly a half-dozen future stars,
including Jolley, second-year goalkeeper Kevin Hartman
(league-leading 22 wins, second-best 1.38 goals-against average)
and rookies Mathis and Joe Franchino.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could never be a failure when the team accomplishes the
things we accomplished this season,'' Zambrano said after Friday's
loss. ``I'm proud of the guys, and I can't be proud of something
that's a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy overcame adversity Calichman's injury; the continued
troubles of Eduardo Hurtado, who in April was shipped off to New
York/New Jersey; the early impact of Hermosillo's addition in June
on the attack, in which Welton's production almost ceased but what
they provided was excellence. With Cienfuegos directing a fluid
attack that could strike from any place at any time, they destroyed
nearly every team in the league at least once, with only two-time
champion D.C. United and the defensive-minded Fire able to avoid
falling under their spell.
</P>
<P>
   None of that was any consolation following their loss Friday
night. They had endured disappointing finishes in their first two
seasons, watching a 2-0 lead disappear in the final minutes of an
overtime loss to D.C. in the '96 final, then getting swept by an
inferior Dallas Burn side in the first round of the '97 playoffs,
and weren't prepared for another early demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything short of winning the championship this year was going
to be a disappointment,'' said Fraser, the Galaxy's captain in
Calichman's absence. We've already been to a championship game,
we've been ahead in the final game, we've lost a good-sized lead in
the final game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may sound like we had lofty aspirations, but I think we did
well enough throughout the season that we had the right to have
these goals. Does it make this season a failure? Who's to judge?
Anything short of winning is unsatisfactory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0222 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
