<SLUG> BC-FBC-PENNST-PURDUE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN STATE CUTS OFF PURDUE AT THE PASS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By RON DICKER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATE COLLEGE, Pa. _ Penn State did not do anything fancy to
stop Purdue's Drew Brees and his band of receivers Saturday. Sticky
man-to-man coverage and a persistent rush were all the Nittany
Lions needed. With occasional bursts from its offense, Penn State
rolled over the Boilermakers, 31-13, before 97,034 at Beaver
Stadium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Brees was 39 of 57 attempts for 361 yards and 1 touchdown _ a
far cry from the 494- and 522-yard efforts of the previous two
weeks. He was intercepted once. Penn State is 5-1 over all and 2-1
in the Big Ten, and Purdue is 3-4, 1-2. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions (No. 12 Associated Press and No. 24 in the New
York Times computer ranking) played with five or six defensive
backs at times, but their mission was simple: Stop the run and
limit the damage Brees could inflict with his short slings while
punishing him on longer-developing plays. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked as Purdue rushed for minus-12 yards, and
Brees did not have a completion over 19 yards. The punishment was
provided by defensive end Courtney Brown, who sacked Brees 3 times
for a loss of 28 yards. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions' offense, while still the weak link, had its
moments. The freshman tailback Eric McCoo ran for 163 yards on 18
carries and caught a touchdown pass. Fullback Aaron Harris showed
improvement in his comeback from a torn anterior cruciate ligament,
plowing for two touchdowns. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kevin Thompson completed 15 of 24 for 196 yards and
a touchdown. But he also missed receivers sprung from the
Boilermakers' confused secondary, and he threw two interceptions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCoo, of Red Bank, N.J., was the pleasant surprise. Cordell
Mitchell looked uninspired in the first quarter, so Penn State
Coach Joe Paterno inserted McCoo, who began paying immediate
dividends with 5- to 8-yard runs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   McCoo set up the game-icing touchdown with a 77-yard scamper
late in the third quarter. Purdue had crept within 21-13 on Brees'
12-yard touchdown pass to Gabe Cox. On the next possession, McCoo
escaped off-tackle, putting Penn State at the Purdue 15. Harris put
the contest away with a 9-yard reception, a 4-yard run and a 1-yard
plunge for the touchdown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Penn State stymied Brees from the start. With the Boilermakers
rotating receivers as if they were changing hockey lines, the
Nittany Lions would simply add or subtract a defensive back. Brad
Scioli sacked Brees on a third-and-long to stop the Boilermakers'
first drive, but Purdue got the ball right back when the Penn
State's Bruce Branch fumbled on the punt return after being rammed
in the stomach by Eric Haddad. Rocco Figgio recovered at the Penn
State 39, and the Boilermakers settled for a 32-yard field goal by
Travis Dorsch. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions responded by marching 96 yards for a touchdown
_ with considerable help from Purdue. A face-mask penalty on third
down, a pass interference and an offside in another third-down
situation, pushed the Lions to the Purdue 1. Kevin Thompson surged
into the end zone behind center Eric Cole to help put Penn State
ahead by 7-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions earned the next score on their own. Mixing short
passes by Thompson and 7 rushes of 49 yards by McCoo, Penn State
covered 80 yards in 11 plays. McCoo capped his handiwork by
plucking a Thompson screen pass at his shins and racing 12 yards
for the touchdown. The Lions led by 14-3 with 8 minutes 35 seconds
left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
