<HEADLINE>
PANTHERS NEED MORE THAN MORAL VICTORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE FISHER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good choir boys don't necessarily make good football players.
</P>
<P>
   Good football players don't necessarily make good choir boys.
</P>
<P>
   So how come it took the Carolina Panthers so long to understand
that the fact that their Ericsson Stadium headquarters in
Charlotte, N.C., sits at the right hand of Billy Graham (Parkway),
doesn't mean they do?
</P>
<P>
   Says one prominent ex-NFL coach, backing my thesis that
Carolina's holier-than-thou approach to building a football
organization was destined for failure: ``You look at their
first-round picks over the years and you think, `Maybe they should
have concentrated more on just football.'''
</P>
<P>
   But to a public starved for athletes as role models, it all
sounded so good. From the game-day rules of the stadium (no
smoking, no celebratory removing of shirts, no nothing) to the
re-inventing-the-wheel approach to football purity, the Panthers
sincerely seemed to think they had all the answers.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the moral Panthers defeated the ``felons'' from
Dallas in a playoff game, the victory was offered as proof that God
was on Carolina's side.
</P>
<P>
   But since then have come disasters of almost Biblical
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kerry Collins, a franchise lynch pin, is a
psychological disaster who parties too hard, has caused racial
division in the locker room and who lost the respect of his
teammates long before last week's infamous ``My heart's not in it''
announcement. The Panthers don't win home games. There have been
attitude problems. There have been drug and alcohol problems.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Carolina has experienced exactly the same sort of
behavioral difficulties that plague any company employing 50 or so
millionaires in their early 20s.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is still buzzing about Deion Sanders, and isn't it odd,
given the general public's disapproval of Deion's flamboyant ways,
that it took more than just his quietly unparalleled shutting down
a third of the field to get him noticed?
</P>
<P>
   People keep saying that what the Cowboys cornerback accomplished
Sept. 21 in New York was a once-in-a-lifetime thing. But actually,
it's merely the latest episode in a pro football career that will
hopefully be properly honored five years after it's over with a
hall of fame induction. Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Against the Giants, Deion became the first NFL player since 1954
(Jack Christiansen, Lions) to return a punt and an interception for
touchdowns in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders is the first player since the 1970 merger to
triple-threat his way to an interception, punt return and
50-yard-plus reception in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders has eight interceptions returned for touchdowns, second
all-time, and has 19 career touchdowns, the most in history for a
non-offensive player.
</P>
<P>
   Conclusion: Voters would have to invent a reason to not make
this guy a first-ballot Hall-of-Famer right around 2006 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Give the management of the New Orleans Saints credit for being
realists.
</P>
<P>
   After a 3-0 start, coach Mike Ditka's Saints are a loss to
Atlanta today away from slipping to .500.
</P>
<P>
   Ditka has his eyes on NFC West foe San Francisco. ``Until we
beat the 49ers,'' he says, ``we can't say we're making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   General manager Bill Kuharich has his eyes on the rest of the
NFL. ``We realize,'' he says, ``we're a lot like 20 or 22 teams,
not one of the elite.''
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans is at Atlanta today, and oddly, underscoring
Kuharich's view, it's the only game of the weekend featuring two
teams with winning records.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a rubber match for old Cowboys cronies Mike Ditka and
Dan Reeves, who are 6-6 in head-to-head matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to both of them quite a bit,'' says their mentor, Tom
Landry. ``But I stay out of it this week.''
NUMBERS GAME
1.2 _ Vinny Testaverde is saying all the right things about doing
whatever quarterback job _ backup, starter, whatever _ Jets coach
Bill Parcells demands. But don't kid yourself: Vinny is happy he's
starting today against New England, if only because if he plays 45
percent of the Jets snaps, he receives a $1.2 million bonus.
TRIVIAL PURSUIT
</P>
<P>
   What makes rookie quarterback Ryan Leaf's verbal and physical
conflicts with San Diego media members so odd is his Washington
State major _ Broadcasting. QUOTABLE
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Drew Bledsoe has the same agent (Leigh Steinberg),
same college (Washington State) and same physical attributes as
quarterback Ryan Leaf. And the Patriots star has some advice for
the Chargers' maybe-future star. ``If he's going to go through the
emotional swings that he seems to be going through now and for his
whole career,'' Bledsoe says, ``he's going to have a heart
attack.''
CHECK OUT. ...
</P>
<P>
   There are two Los Angeles groups and one Houston group preparing
expansion presentations for NFL owners at a meeting scheduled for
Oct. 27 in Kansas City, Mo. With Cleveland entering the league next
year as the NFL's 31st team, a 32nd team would provide eventual
scheduling balance. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue says a franchise
could be awarded by March. Houston businessman Bob McNair is behind
the Texas bid; NBA star Shaquille O'Neal might be a part of the
Hollywood group, led by Mike Ovitz, that is battling for control of
a Southern California franchise.
AFC BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   Something for Oakland Raiders fans to feel good about: Maybe the
problems in Philadelphia suggest Oakland has a keeper in coach Jon
Gruden, who supervised these same Eagles on offense last year and
had them ranked fifth in the NFL. Something for Raiders fans to
feel bad about: Since when is Gruden old enough to drink or drive?
... Buffalo quarterback Doug Flutie, today making his first NFL
start in nine years, swears he's not kidding: When the NFL discards
him (again), he'll go back to the CFL (again). ... Brace
yourselves, Jets fans: Your next three games are Patriots, Falcons,
Chiefs, with a combined 12-4 record. ... Pittsburgh's running back
of record today is Richard Huntley, but I predict Jerome Bettis
(knee) will be tough to keep on the bench once the game starts. ...
Second-year back Antowain Smith (130 yards in last week's victory
against Indianapolis) is a bright spot in Buffalo. And in this era
of selfish jocks, it's notable who Smith thinks deserves some
credit. Says Smith: ``Most guys wouldn't have taken me under their
wing like Thurman did. I really respect him for what he's done for
me.'' Yes, Thurman Thomas has become a teacher. ``This is my 11th
year,'' Thomas says, ``and I was a starter for 10 years. It's been
very easy for me to help him. I recognize talent, and Antowain has
talent.'' ... A big day for San Diego's Natrone Means? The Eagles
have allowed three backs to gain 100 yards _ in first halves. ...
How to measure bad coaching: Cincinnati is 3-7 after bye weeks. How
to remember that sometimes numbers prove nothing: All three of
those victories came against the supposedly well-coached Steelers.
... The Jaguars have won 21 of their past 26 games and 17 of their
past 19 home games. ... Ravens running back Errict Rhett hasn't
been allowed in the lineup. Scouts say it has everything to do with
his inability to handle their blitz pickups. ... Ex-Bills coach
Marv Levy is getting the Vince Lombardi Symbol of Courage Award for
his public fight against prostate cancer. ... Not that Colts GM
Bill Polian doesn't have the magic touch, but his three teams over
the years _ Buffalo, Carolina and Indy _ are 3-13.
NFC BUZZ
</P>
<P>
   If I'm a player, I don't especially want Kerry Collins as my
quarterback right now. But if I'm a GM in New Orleans, rolling the
dice on a 26-year-old who, two years ago was touted as being a Troy
Aikman Junior? In a second. It's why Jeff George keeps getting
hired, why Rick Mirer just got a nice new contract in Green Bay.
These guys are too tough to find to throw them on the scrap heap at
26. ... Jerry Rice needs one catch today against Indianapolis to
tie Art Monk's NFL record of consecutive games with a reception at
183. ... The Buccaneers got their bye week at the right time for
quarterback Trent Dilfer, who has quietly been playing for a month
with a slightly separated shoulder. ... Folks in Green Bay are
whispering that runner Dorsey Levens might not make it back at all
this season. ... Scouts say Minnesota's linebacking has been so
good with Dwayne Rudd and Ed McDaniel starring that ex-Cowboys
player Dixon Edwards is only the third best of the bunch. ... I
guess nobody is belittling the Vikings for building an unbeaten
record against patsies anymore, eh? ... Giants tight end Alfred
Pupuna, a native of the island of Tonga, says his touchdown
celebration includes him pretending to rip the top off a coconut
and drinking its milk. ``A kava,'' corrects Pupuna. ... Until the
49ers signed him recently, punter Reggie Roby was running a gourmet
cookie business in Cherry Hills, N.J. ... Quarterback Brad Johnson
might return from injury next week, and the Vikings insist he'll
regain his job no matter how brilliant Randall Cunningham continues
to be. ... Bill Clinton's second most famous former intern? Saints
tackle Willie Roaf, who served as a seventh-grade page in the
Arkansas State Capitol under then-Governor Clinton. ``Yeah, what
President Clinton did was wrong,'' says Roaf. ``But it's been known
for years that he chased skirts.'' ... An 8-8 team winning a
division? It could happen in the NFC East this year, and it's
happened before. Twice. The 1978 Vikings and the 1985 Browns were
.500 champions. ... Speaking of which: ``People had written us
off,'' Lomas Brown says of a time when the Cardinals were 0-2 and
had been outscored 71-24. ``But in this league, things can change
in a hurry. It can still turn back in an ugly way, but right now,
we're riding a high horse.'' Arizona is 3-3. Still, in the NFC
East, it's more like kicking a dead horse. ... With three, Emmitt
Smith already has one more 100-yard rushing days this season than
he had in '97. ... Green Bay's Brett Favre threw 16 interceptions
all of last season. He's thrown nine in the past three games.
</P>
</TEXT>
