<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS DISCOVER NEW LINE OF SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith's resurgence has made national headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Garrett's play in place of injured quarterback Troy Aikman
has been inspiring. And cornerback/wide receiver/punt returner
Deion Sanders has simply had a prime-time season.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Cowboys (4-2) prepare for today's matchup with the
Bears (1-5) at Chicago's Soldier Field, team owner Jerry Jones has
not been fooled by gaudy statistics, end-zone dances and glamour
positions.
</P>
<P>
   He said the difference this season has been the improved play of
the offensive line, which has given up only seven sacks and has
powered the offense to 367.7 yards per game, fourth in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my mind, our offensive line is as responsible for our
record as anything else,'' Jones said. ``That's where we had the
most glaring problems heading into the season. Where we've ended up
singing the blues around here is when we haven't been able to move
the football. We are moving the football because of the offensive
line.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys haven't been singing the blues through six games in
1998 largely because of the work put in by Jones in the off-season.
After 1997's 6-10 debacle, Jones the offensive line the team's top
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Ravaged by injuries and inexperience, the line woes were
considered the root of the team's problems last year, when the
Cowboys surrendered a seven-year high 39 sacks and the offense
finished 20th in the league.
</P>
<P>
   The two certainties on the line were Pro Bowl right tackle Erik
Williams and Pro Bowl guard Larry Allen, who moved to left tackle.
Guard Everett McIver came from Miami via free agency to replace
Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Aging veteran guard Nate Newton (6-foot-3, 318-pounds) lost more
than 50 pounds and came into the season in the best shape of his
career. The Cowboys drafted behemoth Flozell Adams (6-7, 335), who
has since replaced the injured McIver.
</P>
<P>
   Add the experience gained by center Clay Shiver, now in his
second-year as a full-time starter, and the result is a deeper,
younger and more talented group.
</P>
<P>
   Bears coach Dave Wannstedt sees the difference. He expects the
Cowboys to pound at his defense with Smith, the NFC's leading
rusher with 529 yards. The Bears rank 25th in the league against
the run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their offensive line is playing about as well as it's played
the past three years,'' Wannstedt said. ``Emmitt looks like he has
a lot more confidence \Rthat\S his guys are going to block
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Shiver and Newton also credit the improved play to Cowboys coach
Chan Gailey's new offense. Shiver (6-3, 294) struggled in the power
blocking schemes the Cowboys used last year. He said Gailey's
offense is based on zone blocking, which is more suitable to his
athletic skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``My confidence and comfort level is better and I'm able to get
out and run more to use my athletic ability,'' said Shiver.
</P>
<P>
   Newton said Gailey's unpredictable and creative schemes also
help with pass protection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense helps us by having different drops for the
quarterback and moving him around to different positions,'' Newton
said. ``We never have the quarterback sitting in one spot so the
defense can't key in on us. It gives us the advantage of doing
different things to the defensive linemen.''
</P>
<P>
   Newton, a 13-year veteran, tried to downplay the performance of
the offensive line, which is starting to draw some comparisons to
the dominant Cowboys lines of a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything yet,'' Newton said. ``We got to win
four or five or six games in a row. That's when you can gauge an
offensive line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
