<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS' LUCK MAKES ROBINSON GROWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The Kings defeated Boston in their home
opener on a Luc Robitaille overtime goal Friday night, but after
the game coach Larry Robinson did not look appropriately happy.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he'd almost have preferred a well-played loss to the
somewhat lucky victory the Kings had gotten, a win they'd gotten
despite being outplayed for most of the final 30 minutes of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   So on Saturday morning, Robinson briefly addressed the issue
with his team, telling his players that some of them needed to work
harder.
</P>
<P>
   And while he didn't name names, he did say that he was pleased
for the most part with his defensemen, and couldn't complain much
about the line of Robitaille, Yanic Perreault and Josh Green, which
has produced all six goals for the Kings (2-1) in the first three
games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   That would seem to leave the trio of Jozef Stumpel, Glen Murray
and Vladimir Tsyplakov as chief culprits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like to center guys out,'' said Robinson, whose team
plays host to the Colorado Avalanche (0-4) at 5 this afternoon.
``People that aren't working hard and aren't playing well should
know without being told. So you address it in generality. You know
what they say: If the shoe fits, wear it.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Stumpel, Murray and Tsyplakov produced 68 goals and
191 points and finished 1-2-3 on the team in scoring. But through
three games this year, they have yet to score a goal, and only
Tsyplakov has so much as an assist.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuses for why we're not scoring,'' Murray said.
``Well, there is one: We're not working hard enough, plain and
simple.... We might be pressing a little bit and thinking too much
offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson responded, ``Pressing? I wish they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said he'd like to see a greater defensive commitment,
which would be followed by more chances offensively. He'd like to
see more of his forwards getting scoring chances around the net. He
said only three players _ Green, Robitaille and Sandy Moger _ had
chances from the key scoring areas in Friday's victory.
</P>
<P>
   And he said the Stumpel line has gotten into the bad habit of
staying on the ice too long during many of its shifts, sometimes
for twice as long as they should.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few times they got caught a minute and a half, a minute 20
seconds,'' Robinson said. ``They just kill themselves. You can't
stay on the ice. I don't care who you are. To stay out that long,
your legs just build up with lactic acid and the next thing you
know you can't move, and you just ruin yourself for your next
shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray said: ``We've got to cut our shifts down. Maybe we've
been staying out there a little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Robinson said he may make slight alterations to his
forward lines. One possibility would be to have Green play with
Stumpel and Murray, and to have Tsyplakov play with Robitaille and
Perreault. ``I'm not afraid to move my lines around,'' Robinson
said. ``But then I could start with them and 10 minutes into the
game move them back.''... After tonight's game, the Kings hit the
road for a five-game Eastern swing beginning Wednesday at Florida.
Robinson said he was uncertain whether the two Kings who have yet
to appear this season _ defenseman Garry Galley and forward Roman
Vopat _ would play tonight, but he said if they don't, they will
play on the trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
