<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZR-BUDGET-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Oct. 18. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286. 
 
DAILYLIFE (undated) _ Researchers are providing the first
wide-angle view of America's daily rat race, and you're likely to
spot yourself in the picture. The most common causes of stress
aren't muggings, traffic tickets or money woes, but the little
things that add up each day: burning dinners, hunting for parking
spaces, running late, dealing with rude neighbors. And lot of the
strain comes from the very same people who enrich our lives _
friends, relatives, children, co-workers and spouses. Called the
National Study of Daily Experiences, the project's 11,000 telephone
interviews with 1,500 people in 48 states _ mostly people at
mid-life _ chronicle loss, danger, disappointment and frustration,
along with simple pleasures and unselfish service. By MAUREEN WEST.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. 
 
HMO18 (Undated) _ Across the state, Arizonans are studying
materials perplexing enough to give even scholars a headache: their
employee benefits packets. Which health plan to select from an
alphabet soup of possibilities: HMO, PPO, POS? Which insurer to
choose? What happens if you are given only one choice? Now is the
time for many of the 1.2 million Arizonans covered by HMOs to do
their health-care homework as their employers offer the annual
chance to change benefits or choose new plans. By JODIE SNYDER.
Story will move in the ``A'' category. 
 
LECKIE (Paradise Valley, Ariz.) _ George Edward Leckie, former
deputy chief of staff to then-Gov. Fife Symington, and a key player
in political and legal struggles that preceded Symington's
downfall, is dead at 57. Leckie, an outgoing businessman often
accused of overreaching and intrigue in connection with his
government service, died at a Paradise Valley home Thursday after a
long battle with cancer. By CHARLES KELLY and AMY SVITAK. Story
will move in the ``A'' category. 
 
FORENSIC (undated) _ Cookie Jacobson's body could tell a lot of
tales. That is, if investigators find the right parts and if the
body hasn't decomposed too much. ``An awful lot's going to depend
on what they find, how long it's been dead and how much it's
decomposed,'' said Walter Birkby, a retired University of Arizona
anthropologist and director of the Human Remains Identification
Unit in Tucson. By JUDI VILLA and RICHARD RUELAS. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. 
 
MISSING (undated) _ A 10-month mystery into the disapperance of a
Peoria mother and her daughter ended tragically Saturday when the
woman's skeletal remains were identified. Police are investigating
as a homicide. By RICHARD RUELAS. Story will move in the ``A''
category. 
 
STARS (undated) _ Sun Dance Kid vs. Ben Hur as Robert Redford
stumps for Steve Owens, the Democrat, and Charlton Heston campaigns
for J.D. Haywroth, the Republican incumbent COngressman for the 6th
District. By ALEXA HAUSSLER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. 
 
MONTINI-COLUMN (Undated) _ I'm not outraged because Matthew Shepard
was a gay man who got murdered. I don't understand the candle-light
vigils or the pompous political pronouncements or the sad-looking
bunch of Hollywood actors protesting on the Capitol steps because
Shepard was gay man who got murdered. It only cheapens his death.
Or the deaths of others. By E.J. MONTINI. Story will move in the
``A'' and ``K'' categories.
