A2884 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-COLORA     10-17 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-COLORADO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO HAND TECH FIRST LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ Texas Tech's perfect start to the 1998 football
season ended with an imperfect thud yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The 22nd-ranked Red Raiders buried themselves in a flurry of
first-quarter turnovers and ill-timed penalties. No. 19 Colorado
never let them resurface, striking for just enough big plays to
carve out a 19-17 victory at Folsom Field.
</P>
<P>
   Tech (6-1, 3-1) lost despite a 443-290 edge in total offense,
ending the school's fastest start in 22 years and dropping the Red
Raiders out of first place in the Big 12 South Division. Colorado
(6-1, 3-1) remains one half-game behind pacesetters Kansas State
(6-0, 3-0) and Missouri (5-1, 3-0) in the North Division.
</P>
<P>
   The Buffaloes did little offensively. Colorado failed to cross
the line of scrimmage on 37 of 69 offensive plays. During the
course of building a 13-10 halftime lead, 28 of the Buffaloes'
first 31 snaps netted a combined 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The other three plays proved huge, however. A 59-yard pass from
quarterback Mike Moschetti to Marcus Stiggers followed a Tech
fumble and led to a field goal. A 22-yard scramble by Moschetti
provided the impetus for a 36-yard touchdown march, set up by a
Tech interception. A 21-yard scamper by Damion Barton allowed
Colorado to turn a botched quick kick from the Tech end zone into a
19-yard field goal by Jeremy Aldrich.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did all the things you're not supposed to do if you're
going to beat a good football team,'' said Tech coach Spike Dykes,
whose team lost the turnover battle, 3-1, and gave Colorado three
pivotal first downs with personal-foul or pass-interference
penalties. ``This game was supposed to determine if we were
contenders or pretenders. I guess we're pretenders. We've had our
one-night stand in the Top 25.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be determined today by poll voters. But the Red
Raiders did not enhance their chances to extend their stay in the
national rankings by squandering a solid defensive performance.
</P>
<P>
   The offense rolled for 273 yards in the first half but managed
just 10 points because of three first-quarter turnovers in Colorado
territory. Matt Tittle threw an interception into triple coverage
at the Buffaloes' 1-yard line. Jonathan Hawkins lost a fumble at
the Colorado 24. Rob Peters' pass was tipped twice and intercepted
at the Colorado 44 and returned 20 yards to set up the Buffs' first
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one we let slip through our fingers,'' Peters said.
``We had our chances but didn't do what we needed to do to win. It
makes you sick.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado defense stiffened after halftime, forcing Tech to
punt on four consecutive possessions before the Red Raiders moved
80 yards in the final two minutes for Peters' 1-yard touchdown
sneak with 26 seconds remaining. Darrin Chiaverini's onside-kick
recovery sealed the victory for the Buffaloes, who gave themselves
a 19-10 cushion by moving 91 yards to set up Aldrich's fourth field
goal with 2:50 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   During the drive, Colorado converted two third-and-10 situations
and consumed 8:37 of the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think anyone could do that to our defense,'' Dykes
said. ``That drive really took the wind out of our sails.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge will be bouncing back for Saturday's meeting in
College Station against No. 10 Texas A&AMP;M, a contest that could
decide the South Division title.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurts, but we're not going to roll over and die,'' said
defensive end Montae Reagor, who had nine tackles and two sacks.
``The only way we were going to win the South was to beat A&AMP;M, so
that hasn't changed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the perfect record has disappeared. Tech will learn later
today if its Top 25 ranking will disappear along with it. Extra
points Tech receiver Donnie Hart (seven catches, 97 yards) failed
to catch a touchdown pass for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Dykes, on his decision to try a quick kick that Peters booted
only 27 yards, leading to a Colorado field goal: ``It sounded good
at the time, but we obviously hadn't worked on it enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech had five plays of 20 yards or more, a season high against
the Colorado defense.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
