A2895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-Padres-Moores-HNS     10-17 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-Padres-Moores-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Padres owner Moores puts winning, `family' ahead of finances
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ John Moores, Houstonian and owner of the San Diego
Padres, arrived a few hours early at Yankee Stadium for Saturday's
opener of the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   John Moores, baseball fan, tagged along.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually I'm a fan-owner, rather than the other way around,''
Moores politely corrected.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the former Bellaire and University Houston alumnus,
software-magnate/philanthropist turned West Coast baseball owner
has plenty to cheer about with his Padres making just the second
trip to the World Series in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   And Moores is soaking up every moment.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday afternoon as the Padres went through workouts, Moores
and club president-CEO Larry Lucchino walked around the
center-field area at Yankee Stadium, admiring the monuments
honoring some of New York's baseball legends.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, he arrived for only his second in-person World
Series game _ wearing a brown leather jacket, Padres polo shirt and
baseball cap _ taking time to mingle with players, fans and
reporters on the field during pre-game workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been kind of paralyzed,'' Moores said. ``I really haven't
left the hotel because I almost can't think about anything else. We
came out here for batting practice (Friday) and went out to the
legends area. I got out there and was a little choked up. That's
like going through a sacred ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife (Becky) and I have just gotten absolutely consumed by
all this. Buying the Padres was the smartest and luckiest thing
I've ever done in my life. I'd do it again in a heart beat.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when the business side of sports is so visible, Moores
is a throwback, a man revered by his players and front-office
staff.
</P>
<P>
   To get an idea of what the people around him mean, Moores
chartered a jet and brought about 150 employees to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Making it to Atlanta for the National League Championship Series
was a big deal, Moores thought. But the Big Apple? For the World
Series? Against the storied New York Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   Moores, who saved the Padres from ruin when he purchased the
club in December 1994, still hasn't fully grasped the 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had this feeling in my life,'' Moores said after
the Padres wrapped up the NLCS in Atlanta. ``For me to be a part of
this is mind-boggling. I never thought something this grand could
happen. It's too good a story to tell.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody had told the story before the season, everybody
would have died laughing.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, the Padres finished last in the NL West. They were
10 games below .500.
</P>
<P>
   This year, San Diego claimed a second division title in three
years, won a club-record 98 games and then played the role of giant
killer with playoff-series victories over the 102-win Astros and
106-win Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody's laughing anymore.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the Padres' rise to the top of the NL even more
special for Moores is how they have accomplished it. While the
Yankees have the second-largest payroll in baseball, San Diego is
13th and plays in one of the smaller markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represents the big market,'' Moores said, referring to
Yankees owner George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the guys that have to recycle the aluminum cans to make
ends meet. We're like country cousins. We're a little nervous being
in the big city. I've never seen so many cars before. This is a
fairy tale for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it's almost too good to be true is because it's the
best baseball year of my life, of anybody's life, as far as I can
tell. There's been a renaissance of interest in baseball. This
season certainly illustrates that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story has a fairy-tale quality about it because we're such
a small market. We are the mother of all small markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Moores, whose heart first belonged to the Astros when he grew up
with Nolan Ryan and Terry Puhl as his favorite players, fulfilled a
lifelong dream in 1994 when he bought the struggling Padres, who
had alienated fans with unpopular, salary-slashing trades.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately upon his arrival, he OK'd a 12-player trade
with the Astros that brought third baseman Ken Caminiti and
outfielder Steve Finely to San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Moores also was instrumental in the trade with the Florida
Marlins that landed ace righthander Kevin Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have the best owner in baseball,'' manager Bruce
Bochy said. ``When he acquired our ballclub, he allowed us to
acquire the type of players that would not just make us competitive
but contenders, and I think all the credit goes to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty lucky to have an owner like John Moores.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres finished 70-74 _ third in the NL West _ in 1995, his
first year of ownership, but it was then that Moores was hooked. He
liked what he saw and the Padres lived up to expectations the
following year with their first division championship since they
advanced to the World Series in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   There is renewed interest in baseball in San Diego after the
Padres drew 2.5 million fans this season. And the future is bright,
if voters OK a pending ballot initiative that would mean a new
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about getting to the World Series,'' said
Moores, who until last year had never attended a World Series game.
``Only after the first year did it dawn on me that we potentially
had the talent to get there. We had a pretty good season in 1996
and the (St. Louis) Cardinals beat us in three straight games in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew from the start this year we had a chance to do
something special. Baseball is such a funny game and such a long
season. You don't know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For business purposes, the Padres' success would make an owner's
eyes _ and wallet _ light up. For John Moores, baseball fan, seeing
his family win seems almost more important.
</P>
<P>
   That's what separates him from other owners in baseball, and
maybe all of sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always joke around saying we are a family,'' the Padres'
Jim Leyritz said. ``John Moores takes that to heart. That is one of
the biggest things I have seen since I have been here.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really takes his ballclub _ granted I own you guys, this is
my team _ but at the same time he makes everything perfect for your
family. He really cares about every individual.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
