u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MUONEKE-HNS &LR;      10-17 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MUONEKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas' Muoneke vows to exceed all expectations
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ Starting over.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday night, just after midnight, never-been dribbled,
yet-to-be-shot basketballs were rolled out onto the court at the
Frank Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   Every year there is a first day of practice, providing the
basketball season its official beginning. For the University of
Texas men's basketball program, that first organized workout
signified more than the beginning of a season, it was the beginning
of an era.
</P>
<P>
   The Rick Barnes era.
</P>
<P>
   But for junior Nnadubem ``Gabe'' Muoneke, the first dribble and
jump shot at the season's initial practice meant more; more than
the official start to the season or the program's ushering in of a
new era under a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Midnight Mania practice for Muoneke is the day his college
career started over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited about playing,'' Muoneke said. ``In the previous
two years, I was hopeful, but I didn't have high expectations. Now
I've made it 100 percent clear to myself that what happens to me is
up to what God has planned for me and what I do with it. I'm
thankful for the opportunity to play this year. That's all I need
is an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't bother me that people don't imagine me doing well.
I guess it'll be a big surprise when I do. It's the same with the
team' we're not expected to do well, so we'll have to surprise
people as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke has had his moments in two college seasons, but he has
had a nondescript career. He was in the starting lineup for most of
his freshman year, shooting 53.6 percent from the floor and
averaging nearly six points in 15 minutes of playing time per game.
</P>
<P>
   Last season he was expected to shine, but though he started 30
of 31 games, he was unhappy. His scoring average rose to 10.4
points per game, but his shooting accuracy dropped to 43.1 percent
and he never found his normally solid stroke from 3-point range
(26.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
   For Muoneke, recognized as one of the state's top recruits when
he left Cypress Falls after leading the Greater Houston area in
scoring and rebounding his senior year, the subpar play was
disappointing.
</P>
<P>
   That is why the Texas High School Coaches Association All-Star
Game Most Valuable Player views the arrival of Barnes to replace
Tom Penders as his chance to start over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't come to Texas to be a mediocre player, I didn't come
here with a mediocre status,'' Muoneke said. ``Coach Barnes is
expecting me to do well. He basically said, if I don't do well,
it's my fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him it was important for me to give glory to God and he
told me, `To give glory to God, you have to take what you're
blessed with and work harder with it, not be satisfied that you
have it.' He didn't give me an option, I have to work hard every
day and play hard every night.''
</P>
<P>
   Few question Muoneke's talent or his desire. At 6-7 and a solid
250 pounds, he is a difficult defensive assignment _ too big for
smaller players to handle and too quick for bigger players to keep
up with.
</P>
<P>
   And to call him competitive would be an understatement. An
emotional fire burns within Muoneke whether he is playing before a
packed house at the Drum or a pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I want to do is win,'' Muoneke said. ``People may be used
to 18-20 wins a season, but I don't like that. I don't think fans
at Texas should be satisfied with 18 wins and the Sweet 16. Why?
Why can't we beat everybody else?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you accept mediocrity and you think I'm crazy because I
don't, then fine, I'm crazy. But I have no desire to go out there
and play 30 games, win 18 and be happy. I don't like losing. If
losing doesn't bother you, why do you play?''
</P>
<P>
   The new atmosphere might have increased Muoneke's enthusiasm for
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got me excited because he's so excited about getting
going,'' Barnes said. ``Gabe's got great potential. He's proven to
me that he wants to be a worker and he wants to learn everything he
can about the game. I think he really wants to be a student of the
game. I think he's really committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing I want to see Gabe do is be consistent. I
want him to know he's bringing it every day and every night.
Certainly we're going to need him to be a real presence for us on
the boards. I want to see him be a complete player.''
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke points to a productive basketball summer, something he
didn't have last year when he spent much of the time visiting
relatives in Nigeria, as helping him improve his play, especially
his midrange game.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke says he and the Longhorns will be ready when the season
tips off, thanks to the effort of strength and conditioning coach
Todd Wright, another new staff member.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in better basketball shape than we were in the past,''
Muoneke said. ``Last year we could go for a long time, but not hard
for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditioning will be important for the Longhorns, who have only
eight scholarship athletes and return just four players _ Muoneke,
Kris Clack, Chris Mihm and DeJuan Vasquez _ who saw significant
playing time last season.
</P>
<P>
   And that 14-17 season was filled with turmoil and ended with
several player transfers and a coach's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that is the past,'' Muoneke said, ``Right now everything
starts over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
