<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-EASTNOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Money matters for Pittsburgh Penguins
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   East Conference
</P>
<P>
   Money Matter$
</P>
<P>
   Things have started to settle down a bit for the Pittsburgh
Penguins, who now have declared bankruptcy as often (twice) as
they've won the Stanley Cup. The team is close to finalizing
agreements with former star Mario Lemieux (who is overdue $28.6
million in deferred salary) and Fox Sports Pittsburgh (which is
renegotiating broadcast rights). Majority owner Roger Marino also
lent the team $2.5 million (at eight percent interest) so the Pens
could make Thursday's $200,000 payroll, and in the words of Jaromir
Jagr, ``I'm happy about that.'' But the Penguins, who have lost
$37.5 million in the last two years, are hardly woe-free. The
latest legal entanglements: (1) Mayor Tom Murphy has opened an
investigation into whether the Penguins owe Allegheny County
$900,000 in ``amusement taxes,'' causing the team to issue a
statement, ``Heavy-handed tactics such as these aren't going to
keep the Penguins viable in Pittsburgh''; (2) and on that veiled
threat to move the team, the county has filed a lawsuit saying
Marino has shopped the team in recent months to four cities _
Houston, Las Vegas, Kansas City and Oklahoma City. The Penguins
also have made no headway in their attempt to reduce their rent by
$4 million a year at the Civic Arena. In related news, the team won
its first two games.
</P>
<P>
   New Yech, New Yech
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of public-relations woes, it can't please league
officials in New York that the area's three teams all are having
problems. The Rangers, Islanders and New Jersey Devils were a
combined 1-7 one week into the season. The Rangers, outscored 13-3
in their first three losses, have seen general manager Neil Smith
make all the wrong moves. Madison Square Garden the other day
chanted, ``Let's Go Yankees.'' Things are worse on Long Island,
where star forward Ziggy Palffy remains unsigned and in his native
Slovakia and the Isles drew only 11,457 for their home opener. The
fans who showed up chanted, ``Bring back Spano,'' a reference to
John Spano, who attempted to buy the team but later was convicted
of fraud charges. The Islanders won the Stanley Cup four times in
the 1980s but have failed to make the playoffs the last four years.
``I spent 20 years there when it was as good as it gets,'' said
former GM Bill Torrey. ``I hate to see this happen.'' The Devils
don't have the off-ice problems. They're just struggling with
first-year coach Robbie Ftorek, who is trying to open up a team
that has been accustomed to a defense style under Jacques Lemaire.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Boston goalie Byron Dafoe gave up only three goals on 94 shots
in the first three games of the season, with two shutouts. He faced
34 shots in a 3-0 win over Colorado. ... The Bruins are upset with
schedule makers for subjecting them to a seven-game road trip after
two home games to open the season. ... Buffalo forward Miroslav
Satan did not have a normal signing when he came to terms on the
eve of the season opener at Dallas. He was pulled off the plane by
coach Lindy Ruff on the tarmac because he had forgotten to sign his
contract. The deal was closed in an airport office. ``First time
I've done that,'' said GM Darcy Regier. ... Carolina coach Paul
Maurice benched starting goalie Trevor Kidd (six goals in 15 shots)
and replaced him with Arturs Irbe, which helped the Hurricanes gain
a 2-2 tie with Dallas Thursday. Too bad nobody noticed. Carolina
drew only 5,351 in Greensboro after selling only 8,195 tickets for
the home opener.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
