<HEADER>
A2899 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHL-FEATURE18-COX     10-17 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-FEATURE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Is all he can do enough?
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Several years ago, a successful insurance salesman
from Waycross wrote a motivational book entitled, ``All You Can Do
Is All You Can Do but All You Can Do Is Enough.'' The superfluous
cover didn't dissuade the buying public. Even Norman Vincent Peale
gushed: ``This book really motivated me!''
</P>
<P>
   Now the question: Can Art Williams inspire left wingers and
goalies as well as he did Peale and term-life clients? The
Georgia-bred multimillionaire, who only five months ago purchased
the Tampa Bay Lightning, caused the first tremor of the young
season when he fired the Esposito brothers _ GM Phil and assistant
GM Tony _ only two games into the season.
</P>
<P>
   Williams admits, ``The timing was horrible.'' Against his better
judgment, he had given Phil Esposito a year to fix one of the
league's saddest franchises. Two months into his ownership, he knew
it was a mistake. Esposito, who founded the franchise and paved the
way for the NHL's mass expansion in the Sun Belt, feuded with coach
Jacques Demers over personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about it for three months,'' Williams said. ``A lot
of times you make a decision, then you talk yourself out of it.
Finally, I just woke up one morning and said, 'That's it.' When you
see something not working, you've got to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no shortage of things to do. The Lightning has been
every bit the nightmare for the NHL as the Clippers have been for
the NBA. On the ice, the franchise had one playoff appearance in
six years and finished a league-worst 17-55-10 last season. Off the
ice, absentee ownership in Japan ran the team into the ground with
budget constraints. The team lost more than $10 million last season
and alienated fans.
</P>
<P>
   Average attendance has dropped every year since 1994, when it
peaked at 20,986. Last year, the Lightning drew 13,886; this year's
home opener, 11,753. That's 3,000 less than last season's opener
drew, but Williams said, ``They gave away 5,000 tickets. I won't be
dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams estimates the Lightning will lose $10 million to $15
million this season, but his checkbook will survive. He started the
A.L. Williams Company in Norcross in 1977, and 12 years later had
sold $300 billion in life insurance. He sold the company to
Primerica in 1989 in a deal that reportedly earns him up to $35
million annually for 20 years. He is wealthy enough to have donated
over $70 million to Jerry Falwell's Liberty University.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is more adept at football, having played quarterback at
Cairo High School, attended Mississippi State on a scholarship and
coached at Kendrick, Appling County and Thomasville. He attempted
to buy the Tampa Bay Buccaneers a few years ago but was outbid. He
admits to being a novice at hockey, having seen one Atlanta Flames
game and a Lightning game just before the purchase, but it isn't
difficult to analyze the home team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a total disaster here,'' Williams said. ``It was a
last-place hockey team and a bankrupt organization. We've got a
giant sales job here. But it's exactly what I was looking for. I
wouldn't have bought the team unless I had something to do. I
wanted something to turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   He already has expanded the coaching and scouting staffs and
plans to be aggressive in free agency. He said, ``I plan to be here
for the long haul. I told the commissioner (Gary Bettman) I'll be
here for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
