<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    League rule changes fail to increase scores
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So much for a scoring boom.
</P>
<P>
   The rule changes that NHL commissioner Gary Bettman hoped would
increase goal production in the league haven't had the desired
effect. In fact, scoring is down.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it's early, and players still are getting accustomed to
the larger areas behind the net and smaller goal crease. But
through the first six days of competition, only 134 goals were
scored in 30 games, an average of 4.47 per game. That's down from
last year's average 5.8, which was the league's lowest in 32
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, 30 games had yielded eight shutouts. Of the four
games Wednesday, two were shutouts, including the second of the
year by Boston's Byron Dafoe.
</P>
<P>
   Moving out the goal lines two feet from the end boards was
intended to create more skating and passing room behind the net,
where Wayne Gretzky reinvented the game. But even Gretzky said, ``I
just don't think two feet changes the spectrum of the game a whole
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers update
</P>
<P>
   So you want the luxurious life of an NHL general manager? This
was Don Waddell's itinerary last week for his first major scouting
trip as the Thrashers' architect.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday: Travel to Windsor, Ontario, for a junior-league game.
</P>
<P>
   Friday: Detroit, for Red Wings' title banner unveiling and game
against St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday: Plymouth, Mich., for another juniors game.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday (afternoon): Calgary at Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday (night): Back to Plymouth, Mich., for a juniors game.
</P>
<P>
   Total: five games in four days.
</P>
<P>
   Waddell will catch a few more NHL games over the next two weeks,
then leave for Austria on Nov. 2 for a juniors World Championship
qualification tournament, during which he will see nine games in
three days.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing will beat that trip to the juniors World Championship.
It runs Dec. 26 to Jan. 4. The site: Winnipeg.
</P>
<P>
   The understatement from Thrashers assistant GM Les Jackson:
``It'll be cold.''
</P>
<P>
   STORM CLOUDS
</P>
<P>
   There was early panic in Raleigh when the Carolina Hurricanes
blew a 4-1 lead in the opener, were tied by Tampa Bay 4-4, then
lost to expansion Nashville 3-2. Dating back to the franchise's
original home in Hartford, the team has gone six straight seasons
without making the playoffs _ not an easy feat in the
playoff-friendly NHL. Six years is the longest active playoff
drought and ranks fifth on the all-time list. Following are the 10
longest:
</P>
<P>
   Team _ Start _ End _ Seasons
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey _ 1979-80 _ 1987-88 _ 9
</P>
<P>
   Washington _ 1975-76 _ 1982-83 _ 8
</P>
<P>
   Boston _ 1960-61 _ 1967-68 _ 8
</P>
<P>
   Detroit _ 1971-72 _ 1977-78 _ 7
</P>
<P>
   Carolina _ 1993-94 _ (Active) _ 6
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh _ 1983-84 _ 1988-89 _ 6
</P>
<P>
   Chicago _ 1947-48 _ 1952-53 _ 6
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia _ 1990-91 _ 1994-95 _ 5
</P>
<P>
   Colorado _ 1988-89 _ 1992-93 _ 5
</P>
<P>
   N.Y. Rangers _ 1951-52 _ 1955-56 _ 5
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey was the Colorado Rockies until 1982-83
</P>
<P>
   Carolina was the Hartford Whalers until 1997-98
</P>
<P>
   Colorado's non-playoff years came as the Quebec Nordiques.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   New NHL director of operations (read: sheriff) Colin Campbell
promised to crack down on intentional hits to the head this year,
and so far he's keeping his word. Colorado winger Keith Jones was
suspended two games and fined $1,000 for checking Buffalo's Curtis
Brown in the head Monday. Jones drew a roughing penalty in the
game, though Brown was not injured.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Penguins owners Roger Marino and Howard Baldwin are not
inaccurate in their assessment that the 37-year-old Civic Arena
(a.k.a., The Igloo) makes it difficult to generate revenue. But
they were the ones who accepted a deal for $12.9 million in
renovations in exchange for extending their lease to 2007. So who
has sympathy now that they're screaming for a new arena?
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEY ABCs
</P>
<P>
   Many feel one of the top forward lines in the league this year
will be Dallas' trio of Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Jere Lehtinen.
A line consists of a center, a right winger and a left winger. Each
team generally dresses four lines, with one (usually the fourth)
generally known as ``the checking line'' because of its defensive
skills. Top scoring lines in history often have had nicknames, like
the French Connection (Buffalo's Gilbert Perreault, Richard Martin,
Rene Robert), the MPH Line (Chicago's Pit Martin, Jim Pappin, Bobby
Hull) and Production Line (Gordie Howe, Ted Lindsey, Sid Abel).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
