<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL-WESTNOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Avalance losing games; game schedule for Japan nixed
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Western Conference
</P>
<P>
   Look out below
</P>
<P>
   Now, Colorado's nickname really is appropriate. The Avalanche,
only three seasons removed from the Stanley Cup, dropped their
fourth straight game at Phoenix, 5-2, after leading 2-0. And it's
not a good sign when a first year coach (Bob Hartley) already is
blaming ``bad bounces.'' Colorado GM Pierra Lacroix is not about to
admit that parting with coach Marc Crawford and hiring Hartley was
a mistake. But there are signs that he is getting ready to shake
things up. Scouts from at least six teams attended a game against
Boston, fueling speculation Lacroix is ready to deal. It's clear
that team chemistry, which created problems for Crawford, remains a
problem for Hartley, who may or may not be qualified to pull things
together. The Avalance remains one of the league's most talented
teams (Patrick Roy, Peter Forsberg, Joe Sakic, et. al.) but that
has meant as little this year as it did last, when the team was
bounced in the first round of the playoffs. ``When (Phoenix) scored
their second goal, it was like, 'Here we go again,''' said Adam
Foote. ``When things are sour, things are sour. But this is
ridiculous.'' The biggest problem? The Avalanche is 1-for-22 on the
power play.
</P>
<P>
   Sayonara
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt that the NHL is shelving its two-year
Tokyo experiment, they were laid to rest this week. League
officials confirmed there will be no regular-season games in Japan
next season and said the next international experience probably
will be an exhibition or two in Europe in the 1999-2000 season. The
two games between San Jose and Calgary drew crowds of only 8,500 at
the Yoyogi Sports Center, perhaps because tickets were as high as
$180. Players and coaches complained about the jet lag and
inconvenience _ even the Flames, and they gained a win and a tie in
the two games. Sharks center Bernie Nicholls was the most vocal
critic, saying, ``To me, it's another stupid thing (commissioner
Gary) Bettman has come up with.'' Bettman, in fact, didn't even
make the trip, instead sending vice president Steve Solomon. Sharks
coach Darryl Sutter offered one alternative to games in Tokyo: ``It
wouldn't be a bad idea if both teams went to Hawaii, split the
games and laid on the beach and told the league we went to Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly ...
</P>
<P>
   Nashville's 12,000 season-ticket holders include Garth Brooks,
Amy Grant, Reba McEntire, Vince Gill, Lorrie Morgan and Deanna
Carter. Quoth coach Barry Trotz: ``We're going to be the best in
the league in something. We're deep in anthem singers.'' ... Ottawa
management let the players spend a week-long retreat in Banff,
Alberta, leading up to the season opener. Maybe that's why the
Senators opened the year with wins over Colorado and Phoenix _ the
first 2-0 start in franchise history. ... Flames No. 1 draft pick
Rico Fata signed his first NHL contract when the team was in Tokyo.
``I'm going to be the answer to a trivia question,'' he said. ...
Anaheim's loss to Washington dropped the Ducks to 0-6 in season
openers. ... The Blackhawks asked Sammy Sosa to drop the ceremonial
first puck at the United Center. ``But I can't skate,'' he said.
The Blackhawks cleared up the misunderstanding. ... Economic
fallout: The Edmonton Oilers couldn't afford to re-sign free-agent
goalie Curtis Joseph (who signed with Toronto for four years and
$24 million) so they replaced him with Bob Essensa, who will make
$450,000 this year, the NHL's lowest-paid starting goalie. ...
Vancouver general manager Brian Burke insists he will trade holdout
forward Pavel Bure but continues to turn down offers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
