<HEADER>
A2902 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-MAJORLEAGUE-NOTES     10-17 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-MAJORLEAGUE-NOTES18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Free agents may offer needed aid for Braves
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the Braves want to get better, the free-agent
market this winter will offer some interesting choices.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the club desperately needs some help in the
outfield, and both Brian Jordan and Bernie Williams are available.
</P>
<P>
   Williams might be too expensive, and the Braves already have a
good center fielder in Andruw Jones. But Jordan would make a lot of
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who played for the Falcons, lives in Atlanta in the
offseason and has told some of his St. Louis teammates privately
that he would like to play for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts love the way Jordan plays the game, but injuries,
specifically his bad back, have been a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Another player who could help the Braves is versatile B.J.
Surhoff. While Surhoff, a college teammate of Walt Weiss, is not a
star, he consistently hits 20 homers and drives in 80 runs a season
and can play several positions.
</P>
<P>
   At second base, the Braves could go after Roberto Alomar, who
will be very expensive, and some baseball people think his career
is on a downward turn. In addition, umpires as a group continue to
remember the spitting incident from two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors continue that the Braves will make a play for Milwaukee's
Fernando Vina, who could be a perfect fit as a leadoff hitter. The
Brewers would love to have Ryan Klesko.
</P>
<P>
   But the most intriguing free agent out there for the Braves is
probably Kevin Brown. Even with its starting-pitching riches, the
Braves remember that Brown was he main force stopping Atlanta from
going to the World Series the last two seasons. Brown's home is in
Macon.
</P>
<P>
   How could the Braves fit in Brown? Well, they probably would
have to deal one of their top three starting pitchers. The problem
is that Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and John Smoltz all can block
trades because they have been in the majors for 10 years. But don't
be surprised if Braves general manager John Schuerholz at least
calls Brown's agent, Scott Boras.
</P>
<P>
   In the bullpen, not much is on the market, meaning the Braves
probably would have to make deals to improve there.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Chipper
</P>
<P>
   Not much was heard from Braves third baseman Chipper Jones in
the League Championship Series. The reason is that manager Bobby
Cox told Jones to shut up, and the player typically the most
interviewed didn't even come out of the training room after games
when reporters were around. Cox was upset with some of the things
Jones had said that made it into the Gotham tabloids about the city
of New York. But that censorship by Cox might be an example of one
of the Braves' problems. They have been described as a club that
shows little emotion, and Jones and Tom Glavine are breaths of
fresh air, usually not holding back when things are not going well.
After Cox shut Jones up, the third baseman had a terrible series.
</P>
<P>
   In the '90s
</P>
<P>
   This decade the Braves have been the winningest team, with a
record 822-570, followed by the Yankees who are 753-638. But if the
Yankees win the World Series, they would have two world titles to
Atlanta's one and put themselves in position to take away the
Braves' label of ``Team of 90s.'' Still, Yankees manager Joe Torre
has a lot of respect for the Braves. ``It's tough to get all the
way to the World Series,'' Torre said, ``so I respect what Atlanta
does every year. The Braves are picked every spring to get there,
and every October they are playing with an opportunity to win the
World Series. That is really something.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   The oldest living major-leaguer is 107-year-old Chester Hoff,
who played for the New York Yankees when they were called the
Highlanders. Hoff lives in Daytona Beach and pitched in just 23
major-league games, with a 2-4 record and a 2.49 ERA. ... Word is
that Braves first baseman Andres Galarraga will play winter ball in
his native Venezuela. ... The Mets are expected to make
soon-to-be-free-agent Mike Piazza a seven-year, $98 million deal.
... Word out of Baltimore is that Braves assistant general manager
Dean Taylor continues to be in the running for the Orioles' GM job.
... The Cardinals want to deal for Reds shortstop Barry Larkin. ...
Look for pitching-needy Cleveland to make a hard run at Brown.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   The all-star free-agent team:
</P>
<P>
   RHP - Kevin Brown
</P>
<P>
   LHP _ Randy Johnson
</P>
<P>
   Reliever _ Jeff Montgomery
</P>
<P>
   C _ Mike Piazza
</P>
<P>
   1B _ Rafael Palmeiro
</P>
<P>
   2B _ Roberto Alomar
</P>
<P>
   SS _ Royce Clayton
</P>
<P>
   3B _ Robin Ventura
</P>
<P>
   OF _ Bernie Williams
</P>
<P>
   OF _ Brian Jordan
</P>
<P>
   OF _ B.J. Surhoff
</P>
<P>
   DH _ Jose Canseco
</P>
