</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BISHER-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Only one way to tell story of Ga. Tech comeback
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is not a story that will write itself, if there
ever was one. There are so many ways to tell this one, but it has
to have a beginning, and an ending. It began with Homecoming
folderol, lovely autumn day, browning turf, sun sparkling bright,
but Georgia Tech had a tough foe to hoe. Coaches who cherish their
job don't usually schedule one like Virginia for Homecoming, No. 7
in the poll and unbeaten.
</P>
<P>
   They're still dancing down on the field at Bobby Dodd Stadium,
harkening back to the days when it was Grant Field and football was
in full flower. The band is blasting forth, anybody who can find a
partner is dancing. Goalposts are down at one end, now the other,
and a cheer goes up from the crowd gathered round, like a mob in
the French Revolution, and they go marching off with the crossbar,
triumphant in their glee. It has been announced that the Saturday
Catholic mass will be delayed until the end of the game. Priorities
are in order.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it all came down on the shoulders of a 5-foot,
7-inch sophomore named Todd Braverman, a walk-on from Ft.
Lauderdale. ''He etched his name in Virginia lore against
Clemson,'' it reads in a press release, when he kicked a field goal
that won the game in the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   That was at home in Charlottesville. This was in downtown
Atlanta, in the pressurized zone of the accursed enemy.
Twenty-seven seconds showed on the scoreboard. Georgia Tech led,
41-38, after a comeback that would make Napoleon look like a piker.
A field goal from 54 yards would tie it. Overtime. Tech called
time-out, the old ''freeze'' maneuver, and Braverman walked about
all by himself.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the whistle, the snap, the kick. It was short, no
matter how much, but short, and the world of Georgia Tech erupted.
It was a moment that would freeze in the minds of all who had eyes
and ears, and heart. It was all heart, for if you look at the
statistics, Virginia beat the blazes out of Georgia Tech. But as
George Welsh, the wizened Virginia coach said, ''when you give 14
points to your opponnt, they will generate their own offense.''
</P>
<P>
   When last seen, he had concluded the obligatory handshake with
George O'Leary and was walking slowly, glumly toward the Wardlaw
Building, sanctuary of visiting teams, surrounded by blue uniforms,
like a prisoner being led to his execution. It had been a day to
remember and forget.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia had come crashing out on the field, scored two
touchdowns within 30 seconds in the first quarter, and it was not
looking good for the home side. Even worse in the early third
quarter, when Thomas Jones, a hard-to-tackle running back from Big
Stone Gap, Va., tore loose on a plain off-tackle play and didn't
stop until he had covered the 65 yards between him and the end
zone. He's a ball-carrier as fine as you want to see. The score
became 38-17, out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Then came one of those gifts. Nate Stimson, a defensive lineman
from West Palm Beach, tackled a fugitive Aaron Brooks, the
quarterback, he fumbled, Delaunta Cameron, from Arlington, Va.,
picked up the ball and huffed and puffed 34 yards for a touchdown.
The comeback was on. Virginia never scored again, and when Joe
Hamilton hit Dez White on a crossing pattern for 54 yards and a
touchdown, and the Tech quarterback dived in for a two-point
conversion, the final score was written.
</P>
<P>
   It was the same, as irony would have it, as the great confict in
Charlottesville in 1990, when Georgia Tech trespassed on Virginia's
lawn.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers were enjoying their only tenure as No. 1 in the
USA, but Scott Sisson kicked a field goal at the end that put away
such dreams. Georgia Tech was on its way to a national championship
at the time, but you know that story.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
