</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-VIRGINIA18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yellow Jackets come from behind to sting Virginia
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   That's what No. 25 Georgia Tech pulled off in the Saturday
evening twilight in coming back from three touchdowns behind to
knock off No. 7 Virginia 41-38 in front of a giddy sold-out crowd
of 46,018 at Bobby Dodd Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Braverman's 54-yard field goal attempt came up short with
21 seconds left to leave the scoreboard locked at 41-38, the same
score Tech used to dash Virginia's national championship hopes in
1990. Tech keeps open its own ACC title hopes, its most realistic
shot since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets (5-1, 4-0 ACC) host FSU this Saturday with
the ACC title there for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by as many as 21 points throughout the game, the Yellow
Jackets kept finding reasons to live. In the first half it was a
69-yard touchdown pass from Joe Hamilton to Dez White and a 54-yard
punt return by Charlie Rogers. In the second-half it was Delaunta
Cameron's 34-yard fumble return for a touchdown, an NCAA record
fifth fumble return for a touchdown this season. That one set off a
roll of 23 unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   Tech closed a 38-17 Virginia lead to 38-33 with 8:13 remaining
on a 35-yard pass from Joe Hamilton to Dez White.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets then stopped Thomas Jones on third and
inches, the ACC's leading rusher who had 209 of Virginia's 273
rushing yards to that point, when Jesse Tarplin and Justin
Robertson converged on the back. That set up a 46-yard touchdown
pass from Hamilton to White again, on third and 7 on a quick strike
which White turned into a touchdown by flying by defenders across
the field and into the right corner of the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   A two-point conversion run by Hamilton gave Tech a 41-38 lead
with 4:40 left.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's defense, which had been bullied for the first three
quarters found a way to stop Virginia in the last 4:40. Twice
Virginia quarterback Aaron Brooks converted first downs on 9-yard
runs. But on second and 10 from Tech's 24, defensive end Nate
Stimson got in his face and forced him to try to unload a pass. He
was called for intentional grounding and Virginia had to go to
Braverman on fourth and 23 with 27 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia's defense couldn't get a grasp on the Tech offense like
it's had against the rest of its opponents this season, but used
three turnovers including an uncharacteristic pair of Joe Hamilton
interceptions, to helps its offense to 21 points and the lead for
all but the last 4:40.
</P>
<P>
   If Tech's defense thought the Boston College loss was
embarrassing, try allowing 31 points and 371 yards in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Jones, the ACC's leading rusher with a 107-yard average,
had 118 yards on Tech in the first half. He was averaging 7.4 yards
every time he carried. His backup Antoine Womack averaged 7.3 yards
a touch and had 51 yards of his own in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia had taken a pair of turnovers on Tech's first two
possessions and turned them into touchdowns to set the stage for a
game of catch-up for the Yellow Jackets. The first came following a
Hamilton interception by Antwan Harris at the Tech 42. From there
the Cavaliers used eight running plays and a 2-yard run by Jones
for the 7-0 jumpstart.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Virginia was in the end zone again. After
Anthony Poindexter forced an Ed Wilder fumble, Brooks hit Terrence
Wilkins on a crossing route for a 28-yard touchdown and a 14-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia took its biggest lead 21-3 on an 86-yard drive
highlighted by a 29-yard completion to the wide open fullback
Anthony Southern and some more hard running by Jones and Womack.
Keeping those guys in mind, Tech's defense blew a goal-line play,
allowing quarterback Brooks to walk into the end zone around the
right end.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later Hamilton hit Dez White, who juked cornerback
Dwayne Stukes downfield and scored a 69-yard touchdown to cut
Virginia's lead to 21-10. The Tech fans celebrated loud but not
long as they noticed Hamilton writhing in pain back downfield due
to a punishing hit he took from linebacker Byron Thweatt and
another Virginia defender from the backside. He would leave the
game with a sprained knee.
</P>
<P>
   With Hamilton in the locker room getting his knee wrapped Tech's
defense ''held'' for the first time all day, forcing a Todd
Braverman 45-yard field goal. The Yellow Jackets then held again,
this time for real. And Charlie Rogers jumped on the opening in the
game and up the middle on Virginia's punt return team. A burst and
a couple moves later Rogers was gone for a 54-yard touchdown and
Tech was back in it, 24-17.
</P>
<P>
   But Virginia snatched back the momentum on the very next play
from scrimmage. Brooks found receiver Kevin Coffey down the right
sideline with his defender Jamara Clark a good 5 yards to his side.
He completed the pass for what became a 68-yard gain before Jason
Bostic chased him down from the other side. Four runs later
Southern was in the end zone standing up and untouched to give
Virginia a 31-17 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Hamilton back in, Tech's offense didn't get much. A
pair of Clark interceptions is all that prevented the Cavalier
offense from more. By the end of the first half, it was those two
touchdowns Virginia got in the first eight minutes that separated
Virginia from Tech 31-17.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
