<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-HUMMER-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eagles pay homage to their past by returning to summit
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   STATESBORO, Ga. _ Saturday was as beautiful as any good ol' day
Georgia Southern has ever lived. Four national championship flags
grew large in the cool breeze. A fine mob marched from tailgates to
Paulson Stadium benches, spilling over onto the grassy banks at
every corner of the field. The unbeaten Eagles were riding the
football thermals again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Great weather, great crowd, two great football teams. What
else would you want to do in Statesboro?'' said Paul Johnson, the
round-faced wind beneath Georgia Southern's wings. Not a card he
could play during eight years assistant coaching at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Southern is a pocket power again. Ranked No. 2 in
Division I-AA entering the day, the Eagles piled on third-ranked
Appalachian State 37-24. Thursday, top-ranked McNeese State
suffered its first loss. Logic demanded that the winner here would
move into the penthouse vacancy with the next poll.
</P>
<P>
   In case you might be wondering Georgia Southern's ultimate
motives: ``We want to put up our own (championship) banner on the
pole,'' said quarterback Greg Hill, from whom all offense flows.
This day, the option attack chose to gain 494 yards and go over 30
points for the 10th straight time at home.
</P>
<P>
   This was one of those big ``since'' games.
</P>
<P>
   First time since the start of the 1991 season that the Eagles
will have earned the No. 1 ranking.
</P>
<P>
   Biggest crowd _ a throaty 20,353 _ since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   First victory over Appalachian State since '94, after suffering
three straight defeats.
</P>
<P>
   First Georgia Southern runner since ever to go over 100 yards
seven straight games. Redshirt freshman Adrian Peterson didn't stop
Saturday until he reached 216 yards and two touchdowns. He's at
1,193 yards for a season that is but seven games old.
</P>
<P>
   The renaissance in Statesboro is based on the ability to move
the football relentlessly. The Eagles may not claim any great
defensive honors, save cornerback Earthwind Moreland's secure place
on every All-Name team. Their job is to get off the field as
quickly as possible so that a dangerous, many-pronged offense can
take the stage. The tone was perfectly set Saturday when with their
first possession, the Eagles went 64 yards in 15 plays for the
first in a series of touchdowns. ``Let's put it this way,'' said
guard Mark Williams, ``if we do what we're supposed to, we can't be
stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   This is how Georgia Southern would return to the days when a
campus ditch gained the name Beautiful Eagle Creek, and it was
worshipped like the Ganges. The school in the pines is ready to
write some new fables.
</P>
<P>
   Watching it all amid the umbrellas in an end zone patio area
were a couple solitary figures, both important symbols to Georgia
Southern. One an American eagle, the other Erk Russell, the former
head-butting, Uncle-Fester-on-Creatine coach who started all this.
As to which was balder, it was impossible to tell.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose coaching odyssey has taken him from Statesboro to
Honolulu and back, leads this revival. Until he arrived last season
on the heels of a 4-7 1996, Paulson Stadium attendance had been in
slow, steady decline since the start of the decade. It is now
spiking upwards again. An old feeling is familiar again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go toward the future, but you don't want to fight
the past,'' said Johnson, an assistant here under Russell in the
mid-'80s. ``There are several of us on staff who know how it felt,
and we want the players to know what it was like.'' This fine
afternoon, Johnson's bunch stepped smartly backward to the future.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
