<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ADVANCE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    It's Falcons vs. Saints _ with meaning
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There will be a little more on the line this afternoon
in the Georgia Dome than the locals are accustomed to, and if the
Atlanta Falcons beat the New Orleans Saints for the seventh
straight time, there will be even more pressure. A new kind of
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons (4-1) are tied with the 49ers for first place in the
NFC West, and the Saints (3-2) are one game back. The Falcons have
won 10 of their last 13 games, and are beginning to get national
media exposure. Not only that, but people are talking about coach
Dan Reeves' squad as one with serious playoff aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   There's a very good chance the Falcons will sell 60,000 tickets
or more, giving them their biggest crowd since 1996, when they sold
58,760 for a game against the Steelers. The San Francisco game had
the most tickets sold last year with 53,378.
</P>
<P>
   Given all the fuss lately, and the Falcons' six-game winning
streak against this division rival, one can't help but wonder about
the danger of overconfidence among the home team.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count on it, said second-year tight end O.J. Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   ``That might happen. Look at San Francisco up in Buffalo a
couple weeks ago (an upset win by the Bills).'' he said. ``But I
don't think we're at that stage yet. Maybe if we were 11-1. All
this is new for this team, new for this organization. I don't think
it's a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the Saints are ranked last in the NFL in total
defense, giving up 378.6 yards per game, and 281.4 passing yards
per game. That's also worst in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves is convinced the Falcons need to be concerned about
the Saints' blitzing defense (17 sacks), and he's well aware that
New Orleans has a plus-nine turnover ratio, tied for second-best in
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The fact Saints coach Mike Ditka has made a move at quarterback,
naming two-time former Falcon Billy Joe Tolliver the starter over
Danny Wuerffel, almost doesn't matter to Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than San Francisco, they're the best team we've
played,'' he said. ``They're extremely active on defense, and
they've struggled at quarterback and still won three games.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka made the move partly because he fears the Falcons' pass
rush, which has 13 sacks in the last 14 quarters after starting
with just one in the first six quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want a little more mobility against a good
pass-rushing team,'' Ditka said. ``Danny had trouble with them last
year (Atlanta had 16 sacks in two games against the Saints in 1997,
including 10 in the first meeting when Wuerffel started). Danny
holds the ball a little longer than Billy Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditka is returning to the site of one of his career low points.
He was so despondent after a 20-3 loss in Atlanta last year that he
talked about quitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all go through those little things in life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not very rational after that game in Atlanta last year.
I went through a period where I was questioning myself more than
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
