<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOB-FOSSE-FEST-2takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFINING FAMED CHOREOGRAPHER-DIRECTOR BOB FOSSE NO EASY STEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Fill in the blank: Bob Fosse's choreography is
known for being extremely ...
</P>
<P>
   Dark? Erotic? Humorous? Theatrical?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, to all of the above. But what about classy?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I'm so glad you said that,'' Gwen Verdon exclaims. ``Most
people don't spot that; they just see sex and eroticism and
sensuality and bumps and grinds. He had great elegance.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he did -- not that Fosse had anything against bumping and
grinding, either.
</P>
<P>
   It was his unique way of fusing dissimilar traits -- sensuality
with sophistication, sardonicism with joy, funkiness with wit --
that Verdon and several other longtime collaborators are seeking to
commemorate with ``Fosse: A Celebration in Song and Dance.'' The
Broadway-bound musical, which includes numbers from ``Cabaret,''
``The Pajama Game,'' ``Chicago,'' ``Pippin'' and ``Damn Yankees,''
among others, opens Wednesday at the Ahmanson Theatre, where it
will play through Dec. 6 en route to its Jan. 14 Broadway premiere.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, ``Fosse'' is a kind of family reunion, uniting
members of the late choreographer-director's extended (and densely
intertwined) personal and professional lives.
</P>
<P>
   Verdon, Fosse's third wife, was perhaps his pre-eminent
interpreter, winning Tony Awards for ``Can-Can,'' ``Damn Yankees,''
``New Girl in Town'' and ``Redhead.'' She's listed as the new
show's artistic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Reinking, who co-conceived ``Fosse'' along with Richard
Maltby Jr. and Chet Walker, was one of Fosse's greatest proteges
and his close companion of many years. She's sharing choreographic
duties with Walker, who first approached Fosse with the idea of a
revue based on his work in 1986, a year before Fosse died at age
60.
</P>
<P>
   For once, the phrase ``labor of love'' seems more than just a
cliche here. Even when communicating by phone, it's impossible to
miss the immense affection those who knew Fosse best still feel
toward this complex, demanding and singular American artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a wonderful time in my life, and it's very gratifying
to see that he entrusted me with so much belief in me,'' Reinking
says of her years spent working with Fosse on shows such as
``Dancin' '' and the 1979 feature film ``All That Jazz,'' the
thinly disguised biopic that Fosse directed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a remarkable gift and one that I've always been
grateful for, and it's also wonderful to be doing this again and to
have the chance to experience it again,'' Reinking adds.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the most striking behind-the-scenes tribute is that
Reinking, 47, and Verdon, 73, have worked together to honor a man
whose love they once shared. (Though Verdon and Fosse eventually
separated, they never divorced and stayed close friends as well as
creative partners.)
</P>
<P>
   ``To see them now -- they have such respect for each other,''
says ``Fosse'' cast member Valarie Pettiford. ``They love each
other, and it's a beautiful thing. And it's because of their love
of Bob.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortuitously, ``Fosse'' is arriving at a moment when its
inspiration's stock is higher than ever. A wildly successful
revival of the noir-ish musical ``Chicago'' is touring the country.
``Cabaret,'' another show Fosse choreographed, also enjoyed a
successful Broadway revival starring Natasha Richardson last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most significantly, Fosse's sultry, insinuating
choreographic style, and the often cynical material that attracted
him, seem suddenly in step with the times. Much as Paddy
Chayefsky's ``Network'' looks even more prescient now than it did
in 1976, the mordant, post-Watergate satire of ``Chicago'' now
serves as a bracing, ice-water antidote to the politics of
Monicagate.
</P>
<P>
   But it would be a mistake, the show's creators say, to
overemphasize any one aspect of Fosse's work. The man who admired
Bertolt Brecht and Kurt Weill's moral starkness also helped stitch
together Sid Caesar's brilliant, quick-change clowning in the Neil
Simon musical ``Little Me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He not only liked heavy-duty stories but he also liked light
stories like `Damn Yankees,' '' says Reinking. ``He employed a
broad spectrum of feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Verdon says that, in addition to such choreographers as Agnes de
Mille, Jack Cole and George Balanchine, her husband was greatly
influenced by the stylized movements and archetypal characters of
medieval commedia dell'arte, as well as by such great burlesque
comedians as Burt Lahr and W.C. Fields. Fosse himself had started
out performing in burlesque theaters as a Chicago youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still remember W.C. Fields walking behind Mae West and
just missing the train of her dress,'' Verdon says. ``There was an
economy and elegance about humor; it was not just four-letter words
and making fun of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Fosse maintained an edge of playfulness,
both on stage and off, Verdon says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob used to dance in supermarkets, because he loved all that
(piped-in) music,'' she says. ``He'd take a cart and go dancing
down the aisle. Our daughter loved it; I'd take another aisle. And
he'd always wear hats. He loved props.''
</P>
<P>
   (2ND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
