<SLUG> BC-FBC-VAUNION-MOREHOUSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virginia Union wins 21-7, sends Morehouse to 0-8
 &HT;    By Seth Coleman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the eighth straight game, Morehouse was
overwhelmed by a stronger opponent as Virginia Union defeated the
Maroon Tigers 21-7 Saturday before a homecoming crowd of 10,000 at
B.T. Harvey Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   For Morehouse (0-8), the opponents change but the result remains
the same _ a valiant effort falls short against stronger,
experienced teams. But Panthers head coach Willie Bailey didn't
think it was a total mismatch. He thought coming in to the contest,
Morehouse had a decided edge in quickness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew that there was no use running outside on them because
they are so much quicker than we are,'' said Bailey, whose Panthers
move to 5-2 overall, remain 3-2 in the CIAA. ``But we thought we
could run straight at them. I'll tell you one thing, they may not
have won any games yet, but they give you one hell of a fight for
four quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had success moving the football as the Panthers, who
will travel to Norfolk State next week for a key CIAA matchup,
rolled up 386 yards of total offense _ 251 on the ground _ while
Morehouse amassed 243 total yards. Andre Braxton led the Panther
rushing attack with 84 yards on 19 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The game was also a duel between two freshman quarterbacks,
Virginia Union's Jasun Thompson (cq) and Chivarlrik Daughtry from
Morehouse. Thompson was 9-of-14 passing for 135 yards and two
touchdowns, while Daughtry, who evaded several sacks by a strong VU
rush, was 11-of-22 for 122 yards and the Maroon Tigers' lone
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
