</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-VANDERBILT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Bulldogs `back on track'
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia took the first step toward erasing the
memory of last week's bitter loss to Tennessee, rolling 31-6 over
hapless Vanderbilt in Saturday's homecoming game in front of 83,911
fans at Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs improved to 5-1, including 3-1 in the SEC, ahead of
this week's road date at pass-happy Kentucky. Vanderbilt fell to
0-6 and 0-4 in the SEC, moving closer to the program's first
winless season in its 109-year history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really good to get back out there and get a win,''
Georgia linebacker Orantes Grant said. ``It gives us back our
confidence and gets us back on track.'' Georgia won despite using
starting quarterback Quincy Carter for only the first quarter.
Carter, a freshman from Decatur, bruised his left (non-throwing)
shoulder in the 22-3 loss to Tennessee last week. He completed
3-of-6 passes for 62 yards and two touchdowns, to Champ Bailey and
Tony Small.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could become very difficult for (Carter) to play if he
continues to get hit,'' Georgia coach Jim Donnan said. ``He got
hurt in the first quarter last week, then played the rest of the
game. He was able to practice all week without getting hit, and
then got hit only once (against Vandy). I expect him to be at
full-strength next week.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Commodores stacking the line of scrimmage to stop
Georgia's running attack, Carter and backup Jon England both called
audibles for ``tunnel screens'' to Bailey, who turned the quick
slants into scoring receptions of 29 and 44 yards. Bailey finished
with 159 all-purpose yards, including five catches for a
career-high 130 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're bringing that many people, there's nobody in the
middle to cover him,'' center Jonas Jennings said. ``Once Champ
gets past the first level, no one can catch him.''
</P>
<P>
   England, a junior who lost the starting job to Carter in
preseason, completed 6-of-12 attempts for 96 yards in the most
extensive action of his college career.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs' running game also improved. Highly regarded
freshman Jasper Sanks finally saw action and led all Georgia
players with 57 yards on nine carries, including a 28-yard burst.
Georgia finished with 222 rushing yards, its highest total on the
ground since gaining 289 in the season opener against Kent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt good to get out there,'' Sanks said. ``I was a little
nervous on the first few carries, but now ... I'm ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs outgained the Commodores by only 12 yards, yet
Vandy scored just once, and that was against the Bulldogs' second-
and third-teamers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to worry about anything they did against our
defense,'' Donnan said, ``because there were guys out there that I
didn't even know were on our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's get-well game turned into a special-teams nightmare
for the Commodores, who lost to the Bulldogs for the fourth
straight time. Georgia scored on a blocked punt and scored after
another botched punt and a fumbled kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia took a 17-0 lead after Vanderbilt's Lew Thomas, a
freshman from Westlake High, fumbled a kickoff, which Dogs strong
safety Earl Chambers recovered at the Vandy 31. Carter needed only
two plays to find Bailey for his first score.
</P>
<P>
   When Vandy attempted to punt with about 11 minutes left in the
opening half, punter Joe Webb dropped the snap. When he picked it
up and tried to punt, Georgia cornerback Glenn Ford blocked the
kick, catching the ball in the air and returning it 46 yards for a
touchdown. Junior Hap Hines' extra point made it 24-0 with 10:31
remaining in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he bobbled it, I thought I had a chance,'' Ford said. ``I
just took off. I blocked, I caught it and I returned it. Coach
Donnan was telling us we needed to create more turnovers. We were
able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford, a senior from Columbus, became the first Bulldog to block
a punt since Trey Sipe stuffed one against New Mexico State in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   The Commodores had botched another punt earlier when Webb
fumbled a high snap. The Commodores recovered, but the Bulldogs had
possession and drove in for a 44-yard field goal by Hines, their
first points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Vandy's only score came late in the third quarter on backup
quarterback Greg Zolman's 36-yard pass to redshirt freshman Adam
Ditto of Kennesaw's Harrison High.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
