<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JONES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE CALLS JONES SETTLEMENT OFFER UNACCEPTABLE  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Paula Corbin Jones Saturday demanded that President
Clinton pay her $1 million as part of a $2 million package she
would receive to drop her sexual misconduct lawsuit against him,
but White House advisers quickly described the proposal as riddled
with insurmountable problems.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' much-awaited final counteroffer and the swift White
House reaction ended a month of intense settlement negotiations in
which both sides briefly appeared close to ending the four-year-old
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent end of negotiations means that the lawsuit that
helped bring the president to the brink of impeachment will now
remain alive in the courts as Clinton deals with a formal
impeachment inquiry in the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not formally reject the offer Saturday
night, but advisers made it clear that the president would not
participate in the package Ms. Jones had proposed. The other $1
million was to come from Abe Hirschfeld, a New York real estate
magnate.
</P>
<P>
   Both Ms. Jones and Clinton had strong reasons to reach a
settlement. Clinton and his advisers had believed that ending the
lawsuit would make it easier for him to deal with Congress because
many of the accusations he faces stem from the Jones matter.
</P>
<P>
   The House is considering, among other things, whether he lied to
Ms. Jones' lawyers when he testified under oath in a deposition
last January that he had not engaged in ``sexual relations'' with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   While a settlement of the lawsuit would not help Clinton in
strict legal terms, he and his advisers believed it would make it
more difficult for Congress to move against him for behavior in a
lawsuit that no longer existed. He would also be more free to
reverse himself and admit he lied in the deposition. Such an
admission while the lawsuit existed would place him in greater
jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   For Ms. Jones, a settlement would mean she would be guaranteed
some money after years of litigation.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the negotiations, Clinton and Ms. Jones seemed
fairly close, the lawyers involved said, with only $300,000
separating them. Ms. Jones asked for $1 million in September and
the White House countered with $700,000.
</P>
<P>
   But the situation became clouded in recent days as the cast of
lawyers and advisers in Ms. Jones' camp increased. At one time Ms.
Jones had a single lawyer representing her, but this weekend, there
were at least six sets of lawyers in her camp dickering over
Hirschfeld's $1 million offer and what to demand of the president.
</P>
<P>
   Her lawyers now have lawyers. And Ms. Jones has a new lawyer
whose sole job is to represent her to her other lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   One White House official said that it was not reasonable to
expect Clinton to come across with $1 million because he had
explicitly rejected that figure before. To do so now, the official
said, would make it harder for the president to argue that his
contribution did not amount to an apology, because it could be
viewed as demonstrating how desperate he was to make the lawsuit go
away.
</P>
<P>
   The White House also did not want to have anything to do with
Hirschfeld's offer. Yet another problem is that Joseph Cammarata,
who formerly represented Ms. Jones, has insisted that he receive
something like the first $800,000 of any settlement to pay for his
legal costs. Cammarata has asserted that a federal trial judge has
approved such an arrangement, although it is far from clear that
she has done so.
</P>
<P>
   Cammarata has hired a lawyer to represent his interests.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschfeld has balked at any arrangement in which Cammarata and
his partner, Gilbert Davis, would take such a large slice.
</P>
<P>
   A scheduled argument for next Tuesday in St. Paul before an
appeals court panel has served as a kind of deadline driving the
negotiations. Ms. Jones is asking the appeals panel to reinstate
her case, which was dismissed April 1.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ms. Jones seemed influenced the most by William
McMillan, a California lawyer, to help her deal with her lawyers.
McMillan is the husband of Susan Carpenter-McMillan, who has served
as an adviser, friend and spokesman for Ms. Jones. The McMillans
became involved as well the last time settlement negotiations
seemed on the brink of success, in September 1997, when Cammarata
and Davis withdrew from the case in disgust.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones' new set of lawyers agreed to take the case if Mrs.
Carpenter-McMillan ended her role as an adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Jones charged in her suit that in 1991 when Clinton was
governor of Arkansas and she was a state employee, he had her
summoned to his hotel suite in Little Rock and made a crude sexual
advance.
</P>
</TEXT>
