<HEADLINE>
MORE SAINTLY BEHAVIOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Ditka and Bill Kuharich may not win the Super Bowl trophy
this year in New Orleans but they should be in line for the Sister
Teresa Aid to Homeless Quarterbacks Award.
</P>
<P>
   When Ditka and Kuharich claimed disgraced ex-Carolina
quarterback Kerry Collins on waivers last week, it brought to two
the number of lost souls they've imported at that position in the
past year.
</P>
<P>
   Just last November it was Ditka's Saints who signed Billy Joe
Hobert a month after he'd been fired by the Buffalo Bills for
admitting he didn't have a clue what his team was trying to do
against the Patriots during a 33-6 loss in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   Hobert told the Buffalo media the next day that he had never
even looked at the game plan and thus was baffled once he found
himself in the game after a shoulder injury had finished starter
Todd Collins for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Hobert threw two interceptions and often looked like a guy who
had no idea what he was supposed to be doing, which turned out to
be exactly the case. When an embarrassed and dejected Hobert made
his unethical work ethic public, he was fired, and many felt he
would never work again in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   A month later, however, Kuharich and Ditka brought him to New
Orleans and in less than two months he had become their starting
quarterback. Hobert has now been lost to a season-ending injury and
the Saints are trying the same route again, agreeing to bring in
Collins a week after he allegedly went to Panthers head coach Dom
Capers and said the unthinkable: He said he didn't want to play
anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Or did he?
</P>
<P>
   That's what Kuharich, the Saints' president, general manager,
and chief operating officer, needed to find out before his team put
a claim in on Collins after the Panthers were unable to trade the
former No. 1 draft choice for a pair of socks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to do a Paul Harvey,'' Kuharich said Friday. ``I
needed `the rest of the story.' It was very strange, so I just
thought there was more to it than was being reported. They had just
offered him a contract extension a few weeks ago worth $25 million
for six years. So something was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The three questions we needed to answer before we brought
Kerry here was (1) what kind of football player is he. That was a
no brainer. (2) What really happened in Carolina. (3) How would it
effect our team. The last one was what I was most concerned
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuharich said he talked with no one ``in the Panther family''
about Collins because they might have been in an emotional
situation that prevented them from seeing the forest for the trees.
He also didn't talk to Collins's agent, Leigh Steinberg, until
after the Saints had claimed him because he wanted to avoid the
mist of the best spinmeister in the game.
</P>
<P>
   So he talked with the man who made Collins the fifth player
taken in 1995's draft, Colts president Bill Polian, as well as two
of his own players, safety Chad Cota and wide receiver Eric
Guliford, who both played with Collins in Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   He came away believing that the stories about Collins having a
drinking problem or suffering with the manic depression that has
been found in his family were, at best, overblown and that the day
Collins went to see Capers was one filled more with
misunderstanding than with a desire to stop playing football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's only concerned with what happens here, but I was a
little more interested in trying to see what happened up there
because I've learned perception is not always reality,'' Kuharich
said. ``Chad had a lot of good things to say about him. Polian
thinks a lot of him. We liked him coming out of college and a big
factor was he's only 25 and has already had success in this
league.''
</P>
<P>
   That success came when Collins and a stiff defense combined to
lead the Panthers to the NFC Championship game in 1995. Although he
has struggled since, both on and off the field, Collins was a Pro
Bowl selection that year and Kuharich understands that in a league
that lacks enough quarterbacks to go around, if you can get a Pro
Bowl one for nothing, what's the risk?
</P>
<P>
   ``He comes here with a clean slate,'' Kuharich said. ``Kerry
basically has an 11-week evaluation period. We would not have
traded for him because basically we don't believe in trading with
teams within our division. But there was no risk claiming him. He's
a free agent at the end of the season but if we like each other I
think he'll want to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   What Kuharich and Ditka liked was an NFL arm, experience as a
starter, and, surprisingly, toughness.
</P>
<P>
   Collins had shown that last year when he came back to play with
his jaw wired after Bill Romanowski shattered it in preseason, but
it had come into question when Capers said he had asked out of the
lineup saying his heart was no longer in football.
</P>
<P>
   That story was seconded by backup quarterbacks Shane Matthews
and Steve Beuerlein, who claim that Collins said as much to them in
a quarterback meeting following his session with Capers. But when
Collins got to New Orleans, he denied it, saying there was a
misunderstanding of his feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard three different stories,'' Kuharich said. ``I heard
his heart wasn't in it. I heard he told Capers if he felt the team
was 0-4 because of him, he should sit him down. And I heard he was
upset about all the free agents they signed for big money in the
offseason before they got to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware of the talk about him. I know there have been
stories about a drinking problem and depression but we've got a
good support system here. If he shows signs of that, we can support
him. But I won't prejudge problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think maybe he doesn't like being the person out front
and that's tough for an NFL quarterback. I believe that's more of
the situation and I think we have the coach who can handle that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kuharich believed it enough to agree to pay the final $746,058
of the $1.153 million Collins was to earn this season and take his
chances that a former Pro Bowl quarterback can yet return to that
form in a new city.
</P>
<P>
   He particularly believed all of that after watching Collins pass
during the Panthers' loss to Atlanta two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a string of a dozen throws that were as good as anyone
in the league,'' Kuharich said. ``If you saw this one seam route he
threw, you'd say, `What's the risk?' There's such a lack of
quarterbacks today and here's a guy who was a No. 1 pick for a
reason. He showed against us and other teams in the past the skill
he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Adding Collins to a locker room that already had Hobert might
lead some to think Ditka and Kuharich had decided to open the Boys
Town of the NFL. To others it might just seem dangerous business.
But to Bill Kuharich and Mike Ditka, it was something much simpler
than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we're the home of lost souls,'' Ditka said. ``I know
there's angels everywhere. Maybe we're going to be his guardian
angel. I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   If they are, the Saints could end up being a devil of a team in
a year or two with a lost kid named Kerry Collins at quarterback
backed up by another one named Billy Joe Hobert.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   If  &UR; Jerry Rice  &LR; is to be believed, there is one guy worth
keeping an eye on Monday night when the Jets have the ball: wide
receiver  &UR; Keyshawn Johnson &LR; . ``He's a good guy and he has a lot of
confidence,'' says Rice. ``There's nothing wrong with that. The
thing I like about him is he's a playmaker. He's going to be around
for a long, long time.'' ... Rice happens to be a bit of an expert
on quarterbacks, as well, and here's his opinion of the apparently
ageless  &UR; Steve Young &LR; : ``The ball has exploded downfield this year.
I like to test him at times. I try to sprint hard downfield and
outrun the football. So far, he's been putting the ball out there
and I have to utilize my extreme burst to get to the ball, so he's
looking better than ever.'' ... Rice could tie  &UR; Art Monk's  &LR; NFL
record for consecutive games with a reception Sunday. Monk had
receptions in 183 straight games. Coincidentally, the last time
Rice didn't make a catch was on Dec. 1, 1985, in a game against the
Redskins, Monk's team, at RFK Stadium. To give you an idea of what
that record means, the next closest active player is Dallas's
 &UR; Michael Irvin  &LR; with 114 and then Minnesota's  &UR; Cris Carter  &LR; with
104 ... When Cincinnati quarterback  &UR; Neil O'Donnell  &LR; used a faked
spike to freeze the Steelers' defense last Sunday and throw a
game-winning touchdown pass to  &UR; Carl Pickens  &LR; as time was running
out, not everyone was fooled. Safety  &UR; Carnell Lake  &LR; reacted and ran
to cover  &UR; Darnay Scott  &LR; when O'Donnell yelled, ``Clock, clock,'' as
he came to the line. Unfortunately for Pittsburgh, the rest of the
defense did not react, which is probably why Lake is a consistent
Pro Bowl player ... Speaking of Pittsburgh, that city is on
schedule to open both a new baseball park and a new football
stadium in 2001. Both will be built within the shadow of Three
Rivers Stadium. How come a city like Pittsburgh can build two new
stadiums faster than Massachusetts can build none? ... Denver
running back  &UR; Terrell Davis  &LR; is finally resting Sunday because the
AFC West has a bye. He should need it, because he hasn't been
resting much. Davis is averaging 144.2 yards a game, a pace for
2,307 yards. That would break the record of 2,105 set by  &UR; Eric
Dickerson  &LR; in 1984 ... No wonder the Philadelphia Eagles are mired
near the bottom of the NFL standings. In 1995, the Eagles decided
not to trade for Jacksonville quarterback  &UR; Mark Brunell &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has
the Jaguars undefeated at 5-0. They also got rid of both  &UR; Bubby
Brister  &LR; and  &UR; Randall Cunningham  &LR; in recent years. Brister and
Cunningham this morning are the top-rated passers in the AFC and
NFC, respectively, although Brister technically does not have
enough attempts to qualify. They're also a combined 11-0 with
Denver and Minnesota, respectively. So the combined record of
unwanted ex-Eagle quarterbacks is 16-0. And what of Philly's
quarterbacks?  &UR; Rodney Peete  &LR; has the only win. Over winless
Washington, we must add ... Speaking of the Deadskins, you can't
blame Patriots secondary coach  &UR; Ron Lynn  &LR; if he's of a mind to say,
``I told you so.'' That's because Lynn was fired as the Redskins'
defensive coordinator after the 1996 season despite inheriting a
defense that was 26th in the NFL in 1993 and improving it to 18th
by 1995. In his final season in Washington, that defense allowed
nearly a touchdown less per game than the one he inherited. Yet he
was blamed for the Redskins' failure to make the playoffs and
fired. Lynn has been a defensive coordinator in the NFL since 1986,
rebuilding bad units into competent ones in San Diego and
Cincinnati before going to Washington. He was particularly
excoriated for being unable to improve the 'Skins run defense but
his replacement,  &UR; Mike Nolan &LR; , &UR;  &LR; did little better last season
(142.2 yards a game under Lynn in 1996, 138.8 in 1997 with Nolan).
This year Washington is 0-6 and its rushing defense is 28th in the
NFL despite paying more than $57 million for free agent defensive
tackles  &UR; Dan Wilkinson  &LR; and  &UR; Dana Stubblefield &LR; . Washington has
allowed an average of 163.2 rushing yards, has forced only three
turnovers, and, worst of all, is dead last in the league in points
allowed per game (31). Maybe Lynn knew more about defense than the
guy who fired him.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Stubblefield claims one reason he signed with the Redskins
instead of with his old friend  &UR; Ray Rhodes  &LR; and the Eagles was that
the facilities were so shoddy in Philadelphia. ``As far as the
weight room goes,'' Stubblefield said, ``I know some players with
bigger ones in their houses. Ray took one look at my facial
expression and knew he had no chance to sign me. I love Ray dearly,
but not that dearly.'' ... Last Sunday at Foxboro Stadium, there
was a ruckus in the crowd in front of the press box that had a new
twist. The instigator was not some sot in the seats but Kansas City
Star sports columnist  &UR; Jason Whitlock &LR; . When security personnel saw
several fans standing up in front of the glass windows that enclose
the press box and tapping on them, they came to quiet the unruly
parties only to find that Whitlock had been holding up hand-drawn
signs designed to irritate the locals. One said, ``Drew Bledsoe is
gay!'' Another said the Patriots stunk, but in stronger language. A
third said it was warm in the press box, which considering the
damp, rainy weather was galling. The security people apprised their
counterparts inside the press box, who confiscated the signs, and a
protest was lodged with Whitlock's boss by the Patriots' PR staff.
The case has reached both the league and the Pro Football Writers
Association. Although the Star has not announced any disciplinary
action, Whitlock's column did not appear in the paper this week ...
Although there has yet to be a breakout day, Patriots line coach
 &UR; Paul Boudreau  &LR; believes the long-chastised running game is
rounding into shape in front of rookie  &UR; Robert Edwards &LR; , who has
gained 94, 97, and 102 yards the past three games. ``The efficiency
of your running game is more important than your average per run,''
Boudreau said. ``Are you moving the chains? People get wrapped up
in yards per carry but if you're averaging 4 yards a carry but
don't get it on third and 2, what does it mean? I'd rather get
those 1- and 2-yard gains when you need them. The other numbers
will come if you stick with it.'' Boudreau said one of the things
he likes most about Edwards is that a good run or a bad one doesn't
change him. ``If he's had a success or a failure on a play, he
doesn't change,'' Boudreau said. ``He's always the same.'' ... When
the new Cleveland Browns appear in the Hall of Fame game next
August in Canton, Ohio, a huge ticket crunch is expected. It won't
help much, but the Hall has made 3,750 tickets available to the
Browns. Normally, each NFL team gets 450.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
