<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-SWEENEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEART WASN'T IN IT, SO SWEENEY GOT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; There wasn't a single moment, an instant Tim Sweeney could
point to that told him it was time to quit. Sweeney, who retired
from professional hockey a week ago at the age of 31, said it was a
gradual process.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, a Weymouth native, played for nine pro seasons. He
began in 1989-90 after four years at Boston College, spending a
year in Salt Lake of the International League. In 1990-91, he split
his time between Calgary and Salt Lake before joining the US
Olympic team. He played 11 games for Calgary that season before
signing as a free agent with the Bruins in 1992. He played mostly
in Providence in 1992-93, and from there, his career took him to
Anaheim, back to Providence and Boston, and then to the Rangers'
organization last year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Sweeney said he saw the writing on the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of snowballed when there was less and less interest in
my services,'' he said. ``I could've gone to a training camp on a
tryout, but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Turning down an IHL offer that was worth more money but would
have required his family to move, Sweeney accepted a deal to return
to Providence, but his heart wasn't in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought when it came down to it, I could go to Providence,
play well, and maybe get an NHL deal,'' he said. ``But I thought,
`If they didn't sign me all summer, are they really going to sign
me now?'''
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, what made up his mind was his lack of
enthusiasm in Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't do it,'' he said. ``I don't always show it, but I'm
an emotional guy. Hockey isn't a 9-to-5 job. If I can't play with
the passion and emotion you need to play, I'm not going to be
successful. I played emotionless games. The thing that got me was I
didn't care if I played a bad game. I can't play hockey that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on his career, Sweeney laughed and said, ``It's
been nine long years, to say the least.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rocky career. I spent some good years in the NHL
and some years in the minors. I just couldn't find a niche to be a
regular in the NHL. There were a lot of things involved. I felt my
luck was starting to run out. Providence seemed like the best fit.
It's a tough position for a guy my age. The AHL is basically a
development league. I was playing with guys who were 10 years
younger than me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney is exploring his options. He joked that all of his
friends have been in the working world for 10 years and he'll be
picking their brains to figure out what to do next. For now, he's
just getting used to the idea of his hockey career being over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only been a couple of days,'' he said. ``I don't know how
I'm going to react. But I can tell you, I'm not feeling a lot of
stress right now. Right now, it feels like the right decision. A
month from now, it might not feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of defenseman  &UR; Mathieu Schneider  &LR; on Broadway
increased the Rangers' payroll to $41.64 million, one of the
league's highest. Schneider, who was traded to New York last week
from Toronto for defenseman  &UR; Alexander Karpovtsev  &LR; and a
fourth-round pick in next June's entry draft, was thrilled to back
in the city in which he was born. ``I heard rumors for a while,''
he said. ``I knew New York was talking to us, Carolina was. I think
in the back of my head, I always wanted to come here. This is home.
I hope I can help us get going in the right direction. I've
stressed to (general manager)  &UR; Neil  &LR; ( &UR; Smith &LR; ) that this is where I
want to be for the rest of my career.'' ... The Penguins' financial
problems continue. Not only did they file for bankruptcy, but
Pittsburgh Mayor  &UR; Tom Murphy  &LR; has asked for an investigation into
whether the team's co-owners,  &UR; Roger Marino  &LR; and  &UR; Howard
Baldwin &LR; , &UR;  &LR; could be criminally charged for collecting amusement
taxes and not turning the funds over to the city. Pittsburgh
officials believe the city is owed $900,000 in taxes collected from
last season. In an even more bizarre development, the Penguins won
a backruptcy judge's approval for an emergency loan of $2.5 million
so they could meet their payroll. The source of the loan was
Marino, who plans to charge the team 8 percent interest on the
60-day note. Marino has said the club has lost $37.5 million over
the last two seasons. Murphy is said to be upset that Marino
shopped the Penguins to Houston, Kansas City, Oklahoma City, and
Las Vegas. That prompted both the city and Allegheny County to seek
a court order barring relocation discussions before the team's
lease expires in 2007. Former Penguin  &UR; Mark Recchi &LR; , &UR;  &LR; now in
Montreal, said  &UR; Mario Lemieux &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who sued the club for money he was
owed and has since settled, apparently wasn't the only player
shortchanged. ``There's an agenda there,'' Recchi said. ``I think
the guy wants to move the team. There are seven or eight guys that
are owed money there, not just Mario.'' ... Speaking of financial
messes, New Jersey coach  &UR; Robbie Ftorek  &LR; said he saw plenty of them
during the 1970s when he played in the World Hockey Association.
``I never missed a paycheck and I played for some teams with
financial problems,'' said Ftorek, a Needham native. ``The NHL is a
lot more secure than the WHA was. In the WHA, when teams had
financial problems, that made the guys on that team play better
because if the team disbanded tomorrow, you wanted to make sure you
would get picked up.'' ... New Lightning owner  &UR; Art Williams  &LR; is
nothing if not a hands-on guy. Last week he fired both  &UR; Phil  &LR; and
 &UR; Tony Esposito &LR; , &UR;  &LR; promoting coach  &UR; Jacques Demers  &LR; to GM as well as
bench boss. When his club played the Islanders and lost, Williams,
who is a former football coach, didn't mince any words. ``I talked
to the team Tuesday night,'' he said. ``In football, you run 120
plays a game and four or five will decide the game. Looks to me
like we got too many players on this team that take too many plays
off.'' Williams said that game was only his fourth or fifth, and
that he didn't really know hockey but was going to learn it ...
Flames defenseman  &UR; Phil Housley  &LR; said his reputation for being
selfish and a defensive liability is a mystery to him. ``I don't
know if I ticked someone off when I was younger or what,'' he said.
``Every player who plays the game is going to have a media
perception where there are positives and negatives. I can't figure
it out; I actually think that I am a pretty good guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   New Blackhawks coach  &UR; Dirk Graham  &LR; was asked what had changed
since he took over for  &UR; Craig Hartsburg &LR; . ``Personally, I think all
of us coaches are overrated,'' he said. ``We don't have a lot to do
with the outcome of the games.'' ... On Friday night, at Detroit's
home opener, the Red Wings were reunited with coach  &UR; Scotty
Bowman &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is recovering from knee replacement surgery. Bowman
was scheduled to undergo a checkup late last week, which was likely
to determine whether he returns behind the bench or calls it a
career. The players said they were looking forward to spending time
with Bowman, whom they hadn't been around since mid June. ``I'm
sure he's going to be as sarcastic as ever and I'm sure we're going
to hear something about the outstanding preseason we had,'' joked
forward  &UR; Kris Draper &LR; , &UR;  &LR; ``but he deserves to be here. He's a huge
part of the reason why we have won two Stanley Cups.'' ... It's
likely that defensemen  &UR; Gary Suter  &LR; (offseason elbow surgery) and
 &UR; Marcus Ragnarsson  &LR; (broken thumb) will miss tonight's home opener
in San Jose against the Bruins. They are both skating, though, and
appear close to returning ... Country music has embraced the hockey
team in Nashville. Reportedly,  &UR; Garth Brooks  &LR; is a friend of
Predators coach  &UR; Barry Trotz &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and last Wednesday the entire team
was supposed to dine at  &UR; Barbara Mandrell's  &LR; home ... After
starting the season 2-0, the Leafs took a little side trip to the
resort of Banff, Alberta. Included in the three-day stay was
hiking, bowling, and bird-watching ... Former NHL dean of
discipline  &UR; Brian Burke  &LR; was in town for the Bruins' opener against
the St. Louis Blues. Burke has traded the headaches of the league
job for that of general manager of the Canucks. He said he will
trade disgruntled forward  &UR; Pavel Bure  &LR; when and if the right deal
comes along. The other problem is trying to come to terms with
Group 2 free agent  &UR; Bryan McCabe &LR; . ``I told him,'' said Burke,
``either wake up or go get a good TV set.'' ... WEEI's  &UR; Ted
Sarandis  &LR; recently worked an AHL game for Fox Sports New England
with former Bruin assistant coach  &UR; Cap Raeder &LR; . Sarandis was very
impressed with the new Lowell club, which has 14 players who spent
time in the NHL last year, among them former Bruin defenseman  &UR; Dean
Malkoc  &LR; ... 98 days to the All-Star Game.
</P>
</TEXT>
