<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2921 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BO     10-17 1868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-TYSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPLIT DECISION ON TYSON IS OMINOUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Don King believes the Six Wise Men from Boston will rue the day
they ever met Mike Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   King knows Tyson as well as anyone in the world. He has promoted
him for more than a decade and spent many hours dealing with
Tyson's problems, the bulk of which have been of his own making. So
when he read the former heavy-weight champion's rantings in a
nine-page Playboy interview, he saw nothing unusual. King had heard
it all before.
</P>
<P>
   What he wonders now, on the eve of a relicensing hearing for
Tyson in Las Vegas Monday, is whether the Six Wise Men at
Massachusetts General Hospital who concluded that Tyson was not at
significant risk to repeat the kind of ring behavior that led him
to bite off a chunk of Evander Holyfield's ear saw that Tyson. If
they didn't, he says, they will soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's Tyson, brother,'' King said. ``Those psychics (sic)
over in Boston better go back and cover their ass. Their
credibility goes down the toilet if they didn't do the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's on a self-destruct course. I love him but I don't want to
get blamed for it any more. I never would have let him do that
interview.''
</P>
<P>
   King is no longer in a position to control such things, because
Tyson has filed a $100 million lawsuit against him, charging King
with stealing his money and violating their promotional agreement.
He has a new armada of lawyers, advisers, and enablers around him,
all of whom portray King as the cause of Tyson's problems. He is
broke because of King, they say. He is suspended because of King,
they say. He is not what people in boxing thought he would become
because of King, they say.
</P>
<P>
   King and the Six Wise Men know better than that.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ronald Schouten, Dr. Thomas Deters, Dr. David Henderson, Dr.
Barry Jordan, Dr. David Medoff, and Dr. Jeremy Schmahmann are six
of the world's most highly trained psychologists and neurologists.
They gathered for four days in Boston last month to evaluate a
convicted rapist, occasional cannibal, and professional
prizefighter to see if he was sane enough to be let loose in a
boxing ring with someone trying to punch him in the nose.
</P>
<P>
   They concluded, according to a report filed with the Nevada
Athletic Commission, that Tyson suffers from ``a constellation of
neurobiological deficits.'' They said he had problems with anger,
impulse control, depression, and self-esteem, he is pessimistic
about the future, is socially isolated, and suffers from ``an
increased risk of impulsivity and poor judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   They said he expressed a wish to harm two of the doctors when he
grew frustrated or embarrassed but did not act on those desires,
which you may conclude was a good thing both for the doctors and
for Tyson. Dr. Schmahmann concluded, ``It was this evaluator's
clinical impression that this incident did not reflect Mr. Tyson's
intent to intimidate but rather that it was an expression of a
fantasy in reaction to the frustration of this evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson told the doctors he had no one in his life that he trusts
despite the presence of a wife, four children, enough attorneys to
open an international law firm, accountants, bodyguards, and
assorted hangers-on.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors ``strongly recommended'' weekly ``if not more
frequent psychotherapy sessions'' to help him manage his anger and
bouts with depression.
</P>
<P>
   Two said they were ``unable to predict whether or not Mike Tyson
will lose control of his behavior in a future boxing match. He
exhibits neurobehaviorial and emotional deficits that make him
susceptible to this but are by no means predictive of it.''
</P>
<P>
   After all that, they concluded the obvious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the opinion of the evaluation team that Mr. Tyson is
mentally fit to return to boxing, to comply with the rules and
regulations and to do so without repetition of the events of June
28, 1997,'' they wrote.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same guy who told Playboy, ``I know I'm going to
blow one day. But I'm going to make sure that when I blow, my kids
are fine. There's not much more of this (expletive) I can take. I'm
going to blow one day. I try very hard, I'm doing a very good job,
sir. I'm doing a very good job. I'm just really angry these days.
Really, really angry. This whole year has been a total retrospect
of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Six Wise Men know a guy with problems but the ability to
cope with them. Don King knows the guy who says ``I'm going to blow
one day.'' What the Nevada Athletic Commission has to decide now is
which one they'll be sending back into a boxing ring.
</P>
<P>
   The bet is they'll try to push and bait Tyson to see if he
explodes. If he doesn't _ and anyone who has seen Tyson con people
over the years, as I have, believes he won't _ he'll get his
license and fight in Las Vegas Dec. 5 in a triumphant return to the
ring that will earn everyone around him millions, including the
IRS. If he doesn't get the license, he'll fight somewhere else
because he needs the money and so do the people around him.
</P>
<P>
   What that fight will earn Tyson is suspect, since he owes so
many people. He owes the government millions in back taxes, he owes
several million (some say $7 million) to Irving Azoff, one of his
new advisers, he owes that armada of lawyers and accountants, he
owes his hangers on, he even owes the Six Wise Men.
</P>
<P>
   If the net from his first fight in 15 months doesn't make him
blow, maybe nothing will, but as New Jersey Athletic Commission
executive director Larry Hazzard watches the circus from afar, he
is both sympathetic and smug toward the commission that once
promised it would decide Tyson's fate in less than a day after he
withdrew a license request in Hazzard's state under pressure and
returned to the scene of the original crime, Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marc (Ratner, executive director of the Nevada Commission) is
a friend of mine, but the thing I'm laughing about is Nevada was a
little angry when Tyson came to New Jersey first,'' Hazzard said.
``They said they wouldn't be like New Jersey. They'd decide that
day. We're still waiting. This guy isn't as easy as he seems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd hate to see Mike Tyson be the tragic figure of our times
but no matter which way he turns, it seems to be drama after drama.
I hope he comes back and fights and does well. I hope he gets his
license back and nothing else happens. But until he leaves boxing
he's always going to be hustled. You feel it in the pit of your
stomach. Everybody who says they're there to help him is getting
paid. Who's there to help Mike Tyson? Come on. Look at the reality
of Mike Tyson.''
</P>
<P>
   King has seen that reality up close. Maybe the Six Wise Men
have, too, but in their reports, each pointed out somewhere that
Tyson was responding to Holyfield's head butts and the referee's
refusal to do something about them when he became enraged and bit
Holyfield's ear off. One said such overzealousness happens in most
contact sports from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe if the Six Wise Men understood boxing as well as they do
mental health they would have known that is fiction. Tyson was an
initiator, not a victim, of head butts. It was his head that came
forward time after time, not Holyfield's.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson has done that all his career, and most of his opponents'
responses have been to retreat and get clipped with a left hook.
Holyfield, however, does not retreat. He comes forward, and because
of his refusal to cower from a charging Tyson, they clashed heads
repeatedly and Tyson got cut. In boxing's world, Tyson cut himself
and he knows it.
</P>
<P>
   He just can't admit it. Isn't that half his problem?
</P>
<P>
   This is a guy who says in Playboy that one thing he'll never do
is commit suicide over his troubles because ``it's not my fault I'm
this way. Write a letter to God. `God, why did you bring this black
convict into the world? Why did you do that, God?' He's the reason
I am what I am. Blame the big boy. Blame God.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson ends up following the pattern his first trainer and
father figure once claimed is true of all of us, God won't be
blamed for what Tyson does next.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy born round don't die square,'' Cus D'Amato used to say.
</P>
<P>
   Six Wise Men in Boston better hope D'Amato didn't know more
about the kid he raised than they do about the man he became.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   King and Holyfield signed a bout agreement to take on World
Boxing Council champion  &UR; Lennox Lewis  &LR; in February, finally ending
two years of stalled negotiations for a unification heavyweight
title fight. But nothing is final in boxing until the fists fly,
and problems still exist. As usual, they're on the side of the guy
who keeps claiming everyone is afraid to fight him. Holyfield
agreed to accept $20 million for the fight, which was his original
asking price. Lewis's side has said it will fight for $8 million,
but it's really $10 million because King is buying out Lewis's
promoter's end from  &UR; Dino Duva  &LR; and  &UR; Panos Eliades &LR; . Problem is,
the original agreement included a clause that made Lewis's
promoters responsible for up to $1 million in losses if the
pay-per-view show bombs, and they're balking at that now since they
won't be in charge. They claim that's Time Warner's problem, since
it announced last summer in London that it would put up the
necessary purses to make the match. Time Warner believes it did so
with the assurance that both sides would cover some of the
potential downside if sales lag. King believes it's all baloney,
just another way for Lewis's people to talk big but carry a small
stick. So where do things go now? All sides were negotiating over
the weekend, and it's likely the thing will be resolved, because
after all the talking Lewis's people have done the past two years,
they'd look as phony as  &UR; Howard Cosell's  &LR; toupee if they let $1
million kill the promotion. But King has also said publicly that he
wants no options on Lewis yet Lewis's people claim the first
contract they received after making a verbal commitment to the
fight included a three-fight option. That, too, must go to make the
fight, and fair enough. It's time for both sides to stop arguing
over every nickel and dime and either make the fight or shut up and
move on because, frankly, fight fans are tired of hearing about it
and never seeing it ... HBO's most recent ratings indicate that
boxing is on the upswing in a big way. It has had five straight
double-digit ratings with four different headliners, and its
``Boxing After Dark'' series continues to win its Saturday time
slot against ``Saturday Night Live'' and the  &UR; Howard Stern  &LR; show
...  &UR; Lou Savarese &LR;  is still being held as a possible opponent for
Lewis if the Holyfield fight can't be made. Meanwhile, it seems
likely that Holyfield's World Boxing Association mandatory defense
vs.  &UR; Henry Akinwande  &LR; will be ignored by the organization because
of Akinwande's inability to pass a test for hepatitis B ... How do
you know Tyson will fight somewhere Dec. 5? Cable operators are
holding the date open, for one thing, and under the terms of his
deal with the IRS, he must fight by Dec. 31 or face foreclosure
proceedings on many of his properties.
</P>
</TEXT>
