<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2922 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RIVALRY-JETSPATRI     10-17 1577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RIVALRY-JETSPATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS-PATRIOTS RIVALRY IS REFUELED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ Glenn Foley understands New England fans and
New York players very well and knows how friction must rub the two
into heat, but most of all, he remembers Tuna Bowl I last September
in Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday night game, wasn't it?'' asked the former Boston
College quarterback, now with the Jets. ``Most of all, I remember
it was wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley speaks in that Philadelphia-New Jersey accent of his youth
_ much closer to New York's than Boston's _ but he also speaks of
New England fans whom he grew to know at BC.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England fans are great, they're the most unique people in
the world up there,'' he said. ``And I remember that night, they
were raucous and wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets and Patriots, Patriots and Jets, Bill Parcells and Bob
Kraft, traitor or genius, chef or grocery-shopper, New England and
New York, too close to each other for comfort, the twain so seldom
meeting, too much, too difficult, too different, too many chips
earned over too many lifetimes on too many shoulders. New York is
big; New England thinks it's better.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know them and they know us,'' said Foley. ``We line up
pretty well against each other, and we just go out there and wrack
them and frack them, just to see who's standing at the end. Awww,
it was electric that night. That was one of the most electric
stadiums I've ever been in.''
</P>
<P>
   The only comparison, Foley said, ``is like being in Yankee
Stadium for a playoff game. I went to a playoff game the other
night and you have this electricity in the place, electricity that
you feel as a player and electricity that you don't get in other
stadiums. I've always loved that electricity in Foxboro Stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley remembers New England fans pelting him and Parcells and
the other Jets with verbal abuse ``and you'd think, seeing I played
in Boston, that they'd give me a break, maybe be a little kinder
toward me. But I had those enemy colors on and it was like, `We
don't care who you are.' Everything goes. They're cursing and
screaming at you. Aww, I loved it. It was great. It's one of the
best places in the world to play.''
</P>
<P>
   So this longest of weeks for Glen Foley, the week he was
benched by Parcells, was made even longer because New York's next
game is in New England. Monday night. And Foley _ along with his
dream of once again quarterbacking in Foxboro Stadium _ will be on
the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the game that I had the star next to on the schedule
even before the season,'' said Foley. ``So it's tough that way on
me. Real tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Byars aware
</P>
<P>
   A New York writer was asking Keith Byars if he had noticed a
greater maturity in Patriots quarterback Drew Bledsoe this season
and the former Patriot demurred, saying that he had seen the
Patriots play ``only a quarter or so of the Denver game and a
little bit last week against Kansas City.'' He said he did not have
enough knowledge to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But when Byars was asked about his memories from Tuna Bowl I,
the words poured forth.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, Byars wanted to say, ``I'm still friendly with a
lot of the guys up there and we already said a lot of things to
each other during the offseason to take care of this week'' when
Patriots and ex-Patriots might deem it wiser not to speak to each
other. ``We've been jabbing back and forth during the offseason.''
</P>
<P>
   Byars said he and New England tackle Bruce Armstrong did some
jabbering. ``Me and Bruce go at each other a lot,'' he said. ``And
Chris Slade, Slade's always saying, `Man, when you were in Miami
we'd beat you,' and `You better be glad you were on our team.' But
now, we're foes again and Slade and I'll be jabbering at each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Byars tried to say Monday night ``will be just another game _
for the most part. I don't have any animosity in my heart toward
anybody in the organization up there. But this is a game we just
have to win. It's a division game and we can't fall behind any more
than we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Byars expects Patriot fans to boo him, ``but I'm not going to
take it personally. I like those Patriot fans but, remember, the
game is for 60 minutes and, in 60 minutes, they might find some
reason to boo me. I can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``New England holds somewhat of a special place in my heart
because I was one of the guys who helped them, and they helped me,
get to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Patriots, and former Patriots coaches, are everywhere in
the Jets' complex at Hofstra University, and this situation causes
an identity crisis on all sides _ players and media alike. Ask
Byars about Tuna Bowl I and he replies, ``It was a fun game to
play, and a great game to win,'' and he says that while sitting in
a New York locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``That game was probably as close as you can get to a playoff
game in the regular season,'' recalled Byars of New England's
overtime victory. ``The buildup and the hoopla _ all this in Week
3, and I'm saying, `We still have 13 weeks to go.' You know, `Calm
down.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was overhyped, but, as it turned out, it was a
good experience for some of the young guys on the team, the ones
who didn't go to the Super Bowl. They learned what a crazy week can
be like. You know, pressure similar to a Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   And Byars added, sitting in that Jets locker room, ``It was a
great learning experience for both teams, us and the Jets.''
</P>
<P>
   That identity crisis again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this one as being just as big,'' said Byars, ``but being
that we're at each other for a third time, it might die down a
little bit. It can be old news after a while, you know. I mean, how
much can (Patriots fans) say they hate a guy?''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches' perspective
</P>
<P>
   That ``guy'' himself, Bill Parcells, said he doesn't expect this
game to be as overhyped as last year's. The Jets' coach said he
senses that ``it's not as big as it was last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why, really, so much was made of last year's
game. I really don't,'' Parcells said with a straight face. His
return ``was newsworthy, but it's not relevant,'' he added. ``I can
tell this year is much less. This year, it's about the players
playing in the game, and that's the way it should be.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the first question to Pete Carroll about
Parcells this season came after weeks of camp, five weeks of
exhibition games, and untold gatherings with the media. The
question came on Thursday, Sept. 3, prior to the Patriots opener
against the Broncos, when a Denver beat writer asked the Patriots
coach about the former Patriots coach. Carroll momentarily was at a
loss for words, saying, ``That's the first time I've been asked
that since last year,'' and then he gave a bland answer.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after speaking more of his mind to a Newark
Star-Ledger sportswriter about Parcells (``He's full of it''),
Carroll quickly backtracked, telling Jets beat writers, ``The
rivalry has enough going for it and enough to it that I'm not
commenting on any of that stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets safety Victor Green, never a Patriot himself (there are
actually some of those in the New York locker room), was asked
about the return of Curtis Martin to Foxborough, added to the
return of Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be like a bomb,'' said Green with a laugh. ``Something's
going to go off. But it's going to be a good one, you know? What
with Parcells and a lot of guys who played for Bill with the
Patriots, just that itself, and last year started something, and
along with it being a Monday night game, it'll be a lot of hype.
It's going to be a game to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   Green said the atmosphere won't be too much for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like games like this,'' said the Jet. ``I like playing in
games like this, what with national television, and playing against
your big rival. But we can't let it being a Monday night, and all
those guys playing against guys who used to be on their team, keep
us from doing our thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive lineman Mike Gisler _ yes, another Jet who once was a
Patriot _ was on the New England side of the rivalry last year. And
when asked what his most vivid memory of Tuna Bowl I was, Gisler
responded, ``That we won _ in the end. And then that blocked kick
we had just before the end (of regulation).''
</P>
<P>
   That identity crisis again.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, said Gisler, ``I remember that there was a lot of
hype for a game that was crucial for that time of year, but not
critical. Guys (on the Patriots) took it differently. Some guys
were hyped up and some guys couldn't care less. But I think
everybody felt that excitement in the air. You know, it was our old
coach and obviously there were guys here who had left New England
and gone there. So, I remember there was a greater sense of
anticipation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gisler, like Martin, like Byars, said he was looking forward to
going back.
</P>
<P>
   He has talked to his former teammates on the New England
offensive line, such as Max Lane and especially center Dave
Wohlabaugh, ``and right now neither Dave nor I are saying a whole
lot. You know, you have to be careful what you say. But normally,
we talk about how each of us is playing _ we play a lot of the same
teams _ and I'll see something on film that he's done and he'll see
our game on film and we'll talk about personnel on other teams.
He'll give me pointers about how to play them and I'll give him
pointers.''
</P>
<P>
   But not this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
