<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIER PICKY, AND IT PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Monday night, Bill Parcells will get to see some of
the groceries he wasn't able to shop for. They are mostly Bobby
Grier's groceries, though some of them came courtesy of Parcells,
who upon leaving the Patriots also brought them valuable draft
picks in compensation.
</P>
<P>
   At draft time, Grier took some criticism from draft gurus and
scouts who said he didn't make the best of a great situation. But
those who gave Grier average or below-average grades may be
reconsidering.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Grier recommended to Patriots owner Bob Kraft
that he hire Pete Carroll, who has emerged as a very good coach,
finishing 10-6 in a tumultuous first year and losing in the second
round of the playoffs by 1 point.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll's team enters Monday night's nationally televised game
against the Jets at 4-1, with a four-game winning streak and on the
heels of a near-perfect 40-10 win over the Kansas City Chiefs, whom
many selected to be in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Grier, the Patriots' vice president of player personnel, seems
to have made some wise draft choices, as well. Running back Robert
Edwards is off to an excellent start. The other No. 1 pick, Tebucky
Jones, may get some playing time soon, while second-rounder Tony
Simmons, a receiver from Wisconsin, is scheduled to get his baptism
in the pro ranks, taking over for the injured Vincent Brisby.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Chris Canty, last year's maligned No. 1 pick, is
starting and has improved; free safety Chris Carter is now in the
nickel and dime packages; three huge offensive linemen have become
true backups, able to come into games and play; fullback Chris
Floyd has been impressive on special teams and is being used more
to spell Tony Carter; Brandon Mitchell is in a regular rotation at
defensive tackle; and Greg Spires, who has showed excellent
quickness as a pass rusher in camp, recorded his first sack last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years, Grier has drafted decent players who have
made contributions and appear to be on the upside, working toward
becoming starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage we've played five games,'' said Grier. ``The
thing I wanted to see was them to develop and come along and be
ready to play. It might happen a lot sooner than we expected. They
were going to play sooner or later, and to me that's what matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought Simmons would take a while, but we thought he'd
come along quicker and he did that in camp. We know he has
tremendous hands and tremendous speed. The thing he had to learn
was route running. There are certain routes you don't want him to
run, but there are some he runs very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier defends his pick of Jones and doesn't agree that he is
behind schedule. He said he never thought Jones would be ready to
start the season as the right corner, against the big receivers in
the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (hamstring) injuries really slowed him down,'' said Grier.
``In our rookie minicamp he really started to come. I think we wore
him down in that first camp, when he had the first pull. We brought
him back and he had the other pull, so the injuries have set him
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, Tebucky's situation is very similar to Ty Law's when we
drafted him. It took Ty about seven games to break into the lineup.
To be honest it's happening a lot sooner than we expected in both
cases. I'd like to see it happen if he's ready. If he's not ready
to play _ regardless of size of receiver _ he'll just get
frustrated. He'll determine when he's ready himself by how he
performs in practice. In the last week and a half, he's had great
practices.''
</P>
<P>
   Grier says the situation with Carroll has turned out even better
than hoped. Grier and Kraft knew they had lost one of the greatest
coaches in NFL history, so anyone they brought in would pale by
comparison and be put under microscopic scrutiny. Carroll has
handled it well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the team has taken Pete's character in terms of
defense,'' said Grier. ``We're much more aggressive. Sizewise we
might be the same. We're quicker and more aggressive. That's the
big difference. For Pete's system and what he wants to do, this is
what works for us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
