<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2924 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      10-17 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Scheduling presents a different headache for NBA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
So, you think the NBA has problems now.
</P>
<P>
   Just wait until the lockout ends. That's when the problems
really begin.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, when the league gets down to the business of doing
business, there will be issues to address. Players will have to be
signed, trades will have to be made and when all that is finished,
the league can get on with its schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But what will that schedule look like?
</P>
<P>
   Television and travel commitments dictate games will have to be
picked up from whatever point in the season the schedule resumes.
That means there will be an imbalance in the total number of games
and the division of home and road games for teams throughout the
NBA.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets, like every other NBA team, play 82 games _ 41 at
home and 41 on the road. When the league canceled the first two
weeks of the season, the Rockets lost seven of those games, three
at home and four road games.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers, who also had seven games lopped off
their schedule, lost five road games, including much of their only
East Coast swing.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland lost eight games, four each at home and on the road.
Minnesota, which is trying to build itself into contention, had
only six games erased, four of which _ road games against Phoenix,
Seattle and the Lakers and a home game against New York _ would
have been hard to win.
</P>
<P>
   Former Laker Nick Van Exel, traded to Denver before the lockout
went into effect, tried to look at the bright side of the scrambled
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might be good for us,'' said Van Exel, whose Nuggets lost
six games. ``We might only play two games, be 2-0 and make the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So it might work in the Nuggets' favor. The fewer games, maybe
the better for us. That's what I'm banking on.''
</P>
<P>
   He was joking, but Van Exel touched on a serious point _ an
imbalanced schedule could have a large impact on playoff seedings.
</P>
<P>
   One idea being bandied about is a 56-game schedule, in which
each team plays another twice, on a home-and-home basis, which
would represent a big sacrifice in home-game revenue for the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   But putting together a longer season would be difficult,
according to NBA deputy commissioner Russ Granik.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we really don't have a lot of
flexibility,'' Granik said. ``Most of our arenas are booked most of
the time so you really can't make up any of the games.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look at it, these two weeks, while you might be able to
make up a game here or there, or make some adjustments if we
somehow made a deal within the next week or so (it would be
difficult to make up the games).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't lose every single game (in the canceled two
weeks), you're going to pretty much lose most of them. That means
we probably have lost about one-twelfth of our regular season and
that amounts to about $85 million in lost players' salaries. I
don't think that will ever be made up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can make up a game here or there, you might make up a
few dollars of it, but for the most part, I believe it is lost.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer? Nobody's quite sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the main thing is that they're going to have to come
up with some sort of arrangement where everybody plays 75 games, 62
games or whatever,'' said San Antonio's Avery Johnson. ``Whatever
it is, everybody has to play the same number of games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they have to give every team an ample amount of time
to get their rosters filled in a way that it can be competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' Robert Horry offered one solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I can see them doing is (reviewing the schedule to see)
where sometimes you're going to play teams four times, they might
trim that down to three,'' Horry said. ``Say you've got a Jan. 15
game against the Timberwolves, and you're scheduled to play them
four times (even with the shortened schedule).
</P>
<P>
   ``They could cancel that game. They could take the remaining
four-game series and make them three-game (series). That way they
can try and get the schedule evened out. I guess that's the only
thing they can do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
