<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2929 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-FIRSTLOSS-     10-17 0527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-FIRSTLOSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS BLAME MISSED CHANCES, NOT RULINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE _ They were hard-luck losers to the Los Angeles Kings
Friday night, dropping a 2-1 overtime decision in their final visit
to the Great Western Forum.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson learned for the Bruins? There were two, really. The
first is that the video replay officials giveth and they taketh
away. In Colorado last Wednesday, Chris Drury was in the crease for
an Avalanche goal that would have cut Boston's lead in half. The
goal was nullified and the Bruins went on to win, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Kings, the Bruins had two goals disallowed, both in
the second period. Rob DiMaio's was disallowed because Chris
Taylor's left skate was in the crease. It was Taylor's brother Tim
who had his left skate in the crease to nullify P.J. Axelsson's
overtime goal against Washington in last season's playoffs. The
Capitals went on to win the game and the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``That crease rule,'' said DiMaio, shaking his head. ``It always
seems to include our line for some reason. It's a frustrating rule
sometimes. It's great when it goes your way and it's awful when it
doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Allison's goal was not allowed because defenseman Steve
Duchesne intentionally dislodged the net as Allison was shooting.
According to Allison, the officials had blown the whistle before
the puck went into the net. If that's the case, it appears they did
so in error. The rule states that the whistle is supposed to be
blown after the offending team gains possession of the puck. That
never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Lesson No. 2: If you play lousy for the first two periods and
then well in the third, chances are those 40 minutes of lethargy
will come back to haunt you.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Pat Burns took a ``you-can't-cry-over-spilled-milk''
philosophy regarding the result, the Bruins' first loss in four
games this season. Next up are the Sharks tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (Don) Sweeney's pass gets on (Sergei) Samsonov's stick,
we're talking victory,'' he said. ``They picked it off, (Luc)
Robitaille shot the puck, they won the game. Don't point fingers,
don't blame anybody, that's the way it is. On to the next town.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a bitter disappointment for goalie Byron Dafoe, who has
been the team's best player so far. Dafoe said he was jazzed up to
play his former team and he held the Bruins in it for two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no momentum in that game either way,'' he said.
``The second period, we had two goals disallowed and we couldn't
seem to get anything going out there. It's just unfortunate,
Robitaille gets a break down the wing and puts it in the net. If we
get one break, we win the hockey game, but we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe said he wasn't sure what happened on Robitaille's goal,
scored from long range with 2:13 remaining in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grant (Ledyard) kind of tried to block it,'' he said. ``I
thought it was a little bit of a two-on-one, maybe a two-on-two, so
I might have been cheating a little bit. I was surprised that Luc
shot it but he put it in the corner, right where it had to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
