<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-QUALIFYINGSCHOOL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUCH WORK TO DO BEFORE SCHOOL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   They know about amateur greatness, but not professional
happiness. And that did not change at the recent LPGA Tour
Qualifying School.
</P>
<P>
   Kelli Kuehne was the most notable failure during the proceedings
at LPGA International in Daytona Beach, Fla. _ but she had company.
Marisa Baena met with disappointment, as did Silvia Cavalleri and
Vicki Goetze-Ackerman, but Kuehne is the name that jumps out.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Kuehne was a two-time US Women's Amateur champion
who left the University of Texas early, carrying a bagful of Nike
money and riding a wave of claims that she was the female Tiger
Woods. One year ago, Kuehne was finishing tied for fifth at Q
School to gain her Tour card in her first try, proof that she was
as good as advertised, supporters said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kuehne, 21, is probably looking at the Futures Tour,
thanks to a 74-78-76 in Daytona Beach, a poor finish to an
uninspiring rookie campaign. She played in 24 LPGA Tour events in
1998 and missed the cut 13 times. With just $39,831 in earnings,
the youngster from the golf-rich family in McKinney, Texas (her
brother Hank recently won the US Men's Amateur and older brother
Trip lost in the 1994 final to Woods) was forced back to Q School,
where pro golf continued to humble her.
</P>
<P>
   Baena, for one, can relate. She lost to Kuehne in the 1996
Amateur final and is a former NCAA champion. After this year's
Amateur, Baena said she was leaving the University of Arizona to
turn pro and Q School figured to be the first step of a promising
career. Not quite, for the charismatic player from Colombia shot
75-67-75-78 at LPGA International and earned only non-exempt status
for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   That's the category into which Cavalleri and Goetze-Ackerman
fall, too.
</P>
<P>
   Cavalleri, the Italian who surprised the experts by winning the
US Women's Amateur at Brae Burn CC in West Newton in 1997, matched
par just once in four rounds at Q School after tuning up on the
European women's circuit this year.
</P>
<P>
   As for Goetze-Ackerman, it seems so long ago that she was the
rage. There were US Women's Amateur victories in 1989 and 1992
(over Brandie Burton and Annika Sorenstam, no less) as well as an
NCAA championship while she starred at the University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But amateur accolades have not turned into professional dollars
_ Goetze-Ackerman has been 82d, 77th, 56th, and 95th on the money
list, and when she plummeted to 171st this year ($12,049 in 24
events), it was back to Q School.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after shooting 72-75-74-76, Goetze-Ackerman, though only
26, is staring at a professional comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Given her taste of success, that may seem upsetting, but if
Goetze-Ackerman should need comforting, perhaps she can seek out
another former US Women's Amateur winner _ Laura Baugh. She will be
44 next May, but the mother of seven is still chasing the
professional success that she once seemed destined for.
</P>
<P>
   At Daytona Beach, Baugh shot 69-72-74-75 and _ like Baena,
Cavalleri, and Goetze-Ackerman _ gained non-exempt status for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   For  &UR; Geoff Sisk &LR; , the scenario is clear-cut: win the Nike Tour
Championship and earn a PGA Tour card. The 33-year-old Marshfield
resident heads out Monday for Semmes, Ala., and the final event of
the year, which is reserved for the Top 50 on the money list (Sisk
is 35th at $70,694).
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of highs, but a lot of lows,'' said Sisk of
his first full year of playing pro golf since the 1991 Hogan Tour.
``It's been frustrating and your patience wears thin. Looking back,
I don't think I budgeted my time well enough and I got tired at the
end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, though he had a strong tournament in Moreno Valley,
Calif., two weeks ago, shooting three rounds in the 60s to finish
tied for fifth. He then had a chance to end a five-week stretch on
the road and spend time with his wife and 10-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   But it's back to business this week, and while the $54,000 top
prize would vault him into Top 15 territory (and earn him a coveted
PGA Tour card for 1999), Sisk is setting sights on a more realistic
goal. ``If I play well, I could get into the Top 25,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That may not sound like much, but to golfers like Sisk, Top 25
carries a precious prize _ an exemption into the final stage of PGA
Tour Qualifying School. ``Avoiding that second stage would be a big
deal,'' said Sisk. ``That's such a grind.''
</P>
<P>
   As it stands, Sisk has secured his Nike Tour card for 1999 and a
spot in the field for the second stage of Q School.
</P>
<P>
   Sisk's good friend and roommate on the Nike road,  &UR; Kevin
Johnson &LR;  of Pembroke, finished 62d on the money list and is tuning
up for another go-round at Tour School. Johnson will tee it up at
the Country Club of South Carolina during the first week of
November.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   With Woods, there's always something to report. Word is out that
he has extended his association with IMG but dumped  &UR; Hughes Norton &LR; 
as his agent. A graduate of the Harvard Business School, Norton is
given credit for putting together Woods's blockbuster deals with
Nike and Titleist, but apparently his relationship with the golfer
soured in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Norton was not in Scotland for the recent Dunhill Cup, but the
golf world certainly had to take note of Woods's debut at St.
Andrews. It was, to say the least, overwhelming, and if it was any
indication of what is to come in 2000 when the British Open returns
there, they can probably start inscribing his name on the Claret
Jug.
</P>
<P>
   In weather that ranged from perfect to horrendous (in other
words, typical British Open weather), Woods was near-flawless. He
was 14 under in four trips around the Old Course, a whopping seven
shots better than his nearest competitor, which happened to be his
good friend  &UR; Mark O'Meara &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   Granted, it was team competition and the field was not
deep, &UR;  &LR; but Woods showed both immense power (he drives the par-4s at
9, 12, and 18) and the deft touch needed to negotiate the mounds
and swales that distinguish the sacred grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the only glimpse you got of the Dunhill Cup was Woods
burying his head in his hands after missing a 4-footer for birdie
at the 18th hole. It resulted in a stunning upset loss to  &UR; Santiago
Luna &LR;  as Spain shocked the US team, 2-1, and led the media to do
what they generally do _ treat Woods's miscues too harshly. As if
he's the only golfer who ever missed an important 4-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The bogey at 17 and the three-putt par at 18 were probably the
only shortcomings in his marvelous 72 holes at St. Andrews (for
comparison,  &UR; Ernie Els  &LR; was even par in those same four rounds).
The image of Woods on that 18th green should not overshadow this
reality: If he is on his game, no one will challenge Woods at St.
Andrews, where the driver can stay in his hand all day.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   You think they have some kids who can play a little down there
on Cape Cod?  &UR; Bob Kingman  &LR; can vouch for the amount of talent. He's
the golf coach at Barnstable High School, and last week a unique
dilemma fell into his lap: Three members of his team went to Las
Vegas to take part in the Oldsmobile Scramble, a wildly popular
national event that pairs a club pro with three amateurs.  &UR; Jesse
Schectman &LR; , &UR; Tyler Gold &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Pat Rogers &LR; , &UR;  &LR; playing with  &UR; Mike
Boden &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the first assistant at Hyannis Golf Club, had earned their
spot in qualifying last month, but the decision to go to Vegas was
not an easy one. Kingman told the boys there was a good chance the
MIAA would take action against them, though the coach conceded he
did not object to their decision to go. ``There's certainly a lot
of benefits,'' said Kingman. ``There are college coaches watching
and there's not much recognition at the state level. I'm a firm
believer in taking advantage of everything you can.'' It meant
replacing his third, seventh, and eighth players. No problem, not
when the pool of juniors numbers 250 at Olde Barnstable Fairgrounds
alone. Kingman brought up  &UR; Josh Coffey &LR; , &UR; Lucas Tierney &LR; , &UR;  &LR; and  &UR; Tim
Moynihan  &LR; from the JV and what happens? Moynihan, a sophomore,
shoots 37 for medalist honors and leads the team to victory over
New Bedford. Then, in the next match, Kingman's club remained
undefeated by dealing Silver Lake its first loss. The only blemish
for Barnstable is the news handed down by the MIAA earlier in the
week _ Schectman, Gold, and Rogers can play in the remaining
matches, but not in the State Championship Oct. 29 ... Speaking of
Cape golfers,  &UR; Michael Carbone  &LR; of Brewster and  &UR; Kenneth Lewis  &LR; of
Dennis, along with  &UR; Hans Sherman  &LR; of Chestnut Hill, were honorable
mentions to the annual American Junior Golf Association
All-American team ... Thirty lucky souls who this year made the
ultimate golf shot, the hole-in-one, were to get a chance at $1
million in the second installment of a Dunkin' Do-nuts promotion.
Held Saturday at the Easton Family Golf Center, the event featured
three shots for each player from 165 yards; the payoff goes from
$50,000, to $100,000, to a cool million on the third round. The
group of players included  &UR; Todd Obuchowski &LR; , who made arguably the
most talked-about ace of this or any other year. At Beaver Brook in
Haydenville, Obuchowski overshot the 116-yard fourth hole, but his
ball hit a passing car driven by  &UR; Nancy Bachand &LR;  and ricocheted
back into the hole. The bizarre shot earned him a guest spot with
 &UR; Jay Leno  &LR; on ``The Tonight Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   When  &UR; Frank Vana Jr. &LR;  failed to make it into match play at the
recent US Mid-Amateur Championship, it sealed MGA Player of the
Year honors for  &UR; Justin Peters &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who is a fifth-year senior at the
University of Nevada-Reno. Peters won the Horn-blower Memorial in
May, was low amateur in the State Open (where he finished fifth),
and qualified for the US Public Links Championship ... The first
MGA Senior Player of the Year award was won by  &UR; Ed Fletcher &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
is getting better with age. He won the New England Senior Amateur
two weeks ago at Metacomet, then came back a few days later to win
the MGA Senior Championship at Eastward Ho! ... Lewis earned Junior
Player of the Year honors ... Longtime MGA official  &UR; Ray
Bump &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who deserves most of the credit for bringing the USGA
Public Links Championship to Massachusetts (Stow Acres) in 1995, is
recuperating at Braintree Hospital Rehabilitation. Few have
championed the public player's cause more ardently. Cards and well
wishes would be appreciated ... As it did to alleviate
oversubscription to its Four-ball Championship, the MGA has taken
steps to allow more players a chance at the coveted State
Mid-Amateur Championship. Next year, two qualifying rounds will be
held in September, pushing the championship back to early October.
The age limit will be dropped from 35 to 30 (it is 25 for the
national Mid-Am) ... The MGA also announced that all of its events
in 1999 will be spikeless ... The 64th New England Intercollegiate
Golf Championship tees off Monday at New Seabury in Mashpee, with
48 schools represented. The University of Rhode Island is favored
to repeat its 1997 title;  &UR; Bill Link &LR;  of Holy Cross is the
defending individual champ ... Prestigious honors went to Boston
College students  &UR; Matthew Kelly &LR;  and  &UR; Pat Dunn &LR;  at the recent
annual meeting of the Francis Ouimet Scholarship Fund. Kelly, a
senior, was presented the first Eddie Lowey Award for the top
Ouimet Scholar who is also a caddie, while Dunn, a junior who stars
for the BC team, was named the first winner of the Billy Maich
Award.
</P>
</TEXT>
