<HEADLINE>
KWAN LEFT OUT IN COLD AT SKATE AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Why is Michelle Kwan being kept out of next week's Skate
America event in Detroit? Because the International Skating Union
is trying to keep Olympic-eligible skaters from deserting the Grand
Prix circuit for the ISU's own easy-money open events.
</P>
<P>
   Kwan, who has already won two opens against pros this fall and
skated in a third in San Jose last night, hadn't signed up for this
season's Grand Prix, which was already hurting because Tara
Lipinski, Chen Lu, and Surya Bonaly all have turned pro. The
reason: Kwan's programs weren't ready and she wasn't sure which
Grand Prix events she'd be assigned. So when Kwan wanted to defend
her Skate America title, which she has won thrice, the ISU turned
thumbs down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really looking forward to being there,'' Kwan said.
``But life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Skate America still has a bunch of marquee names: former US
champ Nicole Bobek, world medalist Maria Butyrskaya, three-time
world champ Elvis Stojko, and current title-holder Alexei Yagudin.
But it's silly of the ISU to punish the only top female star who is
staying eligible for the next Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the US Figure Skating Association scrubbed the
three-year, million-dollar contract it had with Lipinski after the
Olympic gold medalist ducked the Daytona Beach open earlier this
month. Lipinski hasn't competed against Kwan since Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Skaters have to do what's good for them,'' Kwan shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Add Bonaly to the list of skaters for this week's ``Evening With
Champions'' benefit at Harvard's Bright Center, which includes
Yagudin and fellow world champs  &UR; Elena Berezhnaya  &LR; and  &UR; Anton
Sikharulidze &LR; , &UR;  &LR; plus former Olympic gold medalist  &UR; Oksana Baiul
 &LR; and silver medalist  &UR; Paul Wylie &LR; . Bonaly will skate Saturday night
only. For tickets call 617-493-8172 ... At least the US men's
basketball team won't have to go to Guadalajara next summer to
qualify for the Olympics. The Mexican organizers backed out after
the government couldn't subsidize the event, so the international
federation is looking for a new venue. If FIBA wants to make sure
the Americans make it to Sydney, it'll give them home (or at least
Canadian) cookin'. The larger issue for USA Basketball is who'll be
on the team. The NBA lockout cost the Yanks the gold medal at this
summer's world championship and deprived them of an automatic
Olympic bid. Should they stick with the Dream Teamers? Or go with a
guaranteed, but lesser, melange of overseas pros, CBAers, and
collegians? USA Basketball will ponder the decision at next month's
annual meeting ... Look for the USOC to outsource its drug-testing
program in the future to boost its international credibility. ``We
think we have a very good doping control program, but we're the
only country in the world to have to do the testing ourselves,''
says executive director  &UR; Dick Schultz &LR; . ``Other countries look at
us and say it's like having the fox in the henhouse with the
chickens.'' ... Los Angeles, which hasn't hosted the US figure
skating championships since 1954, will stage the 2002 event, which
will double as the Olympic trials. Site will be the Staples Center,
which opens next autumn and will house the Lakers, Clippers, and
Kings ... That familiar face on the halfpipe this winter will be
former Olympic luger  &UR; Duncan Kennedy &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who has gotten serious
about snowboarding after giving up sliding. Kennedy, who retired
from luging last winter after brain-stem bleeding made him dizzy
and nauseated, has quit as coach of the US junior luge team to
indulge his fascination with the slopes.
</P>
<P>
   ___ &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Auspicious start for Brookline's  &UR; Dan Weinstein &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who grabbed a
silver medal at the recent World Cup short-track speedskating meet
in Saratoga Springs. Weinstein, who made the Olympic team at 16
last winter, ended up fifth in the overall standings ... Plenty of
frequent-flier miles this fall for Wellesley attorney  &UR; Paul
George &LR; , &UR;  &LR; the US representative on the International Olympic
Committee's evaluation commission checking out sites for the 2006
Winter Games. George, who was the US chef de mission at the Nagano
Games last winter, is making three trips to Europe, where all the
bidders are ... Yes, the  &UR; Elfi Eder  &LR; who is Grenada's one-woman ski
team is the same woman who won the 1994 Olympic silver in slalom
for Austria. Eder, who sat out last season because she was feuding
with her federation, went country-shopping and ended up in the
Caribbean ... US women's field hockey coach  &UR; Pam Hixon &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who
resigned recently after five years at the helm, was a victim of
unrealistic expectations. Though the federation believed that the
Americans should have done better than eighth (of 12) at last
spring's quadrennial World Cup after winning bronze in 1994, the
team was still in post-Olympic rebuilding mode after losing more
than half of a squad that had been together for six years. With
another year to develop the newcomers before the Pan American Games
(the next qualifying opportunity), odds are Hixon would have gotten
the team a ticket to Sydney ... Encouraging performance by
comebacking former champ  &UR; Lance Armstrong &LR; , &UR;  &LR; who placed fourth in
both the road race and time trial at the recent world road cycling
championships in the Netherlands. ``I think I can win again,'' said
Armstrong, who was diagnosed with testicular cancer two years ago.
Armstrong posted the best finish for the Americans;  &UR; Mari Holden
 &LR; was seventh in the women's time trial.
</P>
</TEXT>
