<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3014 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BARNHART-COLUMN18     10-17 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BARNHART-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Taking a look inside college football
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the other guy gets 600 yards, has his offense on the field
for 30 more plays, and you still win the game, there are reasons.
Bob Casulo, Georgia Tech's special teams coach, was celebrating one
of those reasons after Saturday's 41-38 win over No. 7 Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching special teams isn't glamorous work, but if you do it
long enough, you'll eventully have your moments to shine. Casulo
and his troops had several sterling performances Saturday evening:
</P>
<P>
   _ Charlie Rogers, who returned a punt 54 yards for a touchdown
and set up a field goal with a 21-yard return. All total, the
senior from Cliffwood, N.J., returned six punts for 117 yards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Georgia Tech's kick coverage teams, which held Virginia to
just 9 yards on two punt returns and just 30 yards on two kickoff
returns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Punter Rodney Williams, who averaged 45.4 yards on five kicks
(with a long of 54), and boomed several kickoffs deep into the end
zone.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Yellow Jackets kickoff return team, which had five chances
for 96 yards.
</P>
<P>
   _ Field goal kicker Brad Chambers, whose 47-yard field goal in
the fourth quarter was his career-long.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line: All those return yards gained (213 on punts and
kickoff returns) and returned yards saved by good coverage add up
in a game like this.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew our guys had a chance to play a big part in this game,
and boy did they play great tonight,'' Casulo said. ''I can't tell
you how proud I am of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Rogers, whose work kept Tech in the game while the defense
struggled: ''There's all kinds of ways to win games and we knew our
return teams were going to have to step up,'' he said. ''And we
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those most appreciative of the work of Casulo's Crew was
head coach George O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ''Special teams were huge for us tonight,'' he said. ''When
you're struggling to stop people, you have to get it done in other
facets of the game. I really like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others sights, sounds, and observations from Tech's memorable
victory:
</P>
<P>
   _ The comparisons to Georgia Tech's win over Virginia by the
same score in 1990 were many. That game, played in Charlottesville,
Va., was also the last time Tech fans tore the goalposts down after
a victory. Tech students, so excited that the Jackets had knocked
off the No. 1 Cavaliers, broke into a closed Bobby Dodd Stadium and
ripped down the goalposts. Then they started a bonfire on campus.
The goalposts, which cost about $7,000 each, were last seen at a
fraternity house.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton may never know how close he came
to being pulled from Saturday's game. Hamilton came back after
sitting out a series with a slightly-sprained knee in the second
quarter but it was clear the junior was hobbled. Once Tech fell
behind 38-17 in the third quarter, O'Leary began thinking about
getting Hamilton off the field. ''If we couldn't get back into the
game, I wasn't going to let him stay out there and get beat up,''
O'Leary said. But six minutes later Delaunta Cameron returned a
fumble 34 yards for a touchdown and Tech had new life. And so did
Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   _ It won't become official until Monday morning, but expect ESPN
to bring its College Game Day show back to the state of Georgia for
the second time in two weeks. Next week's game with Florida State
is a 7 p.m. telecast on ESPN. The Game Day set will be down in the
southwest corner of Bobby Dodd Stadium. Chris Fowler, Lee Corso and
Kirk Herbstreit were in Athens on Oct. 10 for the Georgia-Tennessee
game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trailing by three in the final seconds, Virginia drove to the
Tech 24 and had a chance to win or tie. Coach George Welsh wanted
to just run the ball and take what would have been a 41-yard field
goal and overtime. But Welsh got talked out of it in favor of
taking a shot at the end zone and the win. Quarterback Aaron Brooks
was sacked and was called for intentional grounding, essentially
taking the Cavaliers out of field goal range. Todd Braverman was
short on a 54-yard attempt.
</P>
<P>
   _ Among the questions Virginia fans will be asking today: How
does a nationally-ranked defense get beat on third-and-13 with a
35-yard touchdown pass and then, just a few minutes later, get beat
on third-and-seven with a 54-yard touchdown pass?
</P>
<P>
   _ Said more than one Georgia Tech player late Saturday night:
''Can you imagine where we'd be if we hadn't lost to Boston
College?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
