<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3047 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOORE-COLUMN18-COX     10-17 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-COLUMN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech showed refusal to quit
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just like that, Georgia Tech isn't totally back to the
days of Bobby Dodd, but the football gods are suggesting that the
Yellow Jackets are a Florida State victory shy of those of Bobby
Ross.
</P>
<P>
   Here we are, three games and a miracle into the ACC season for a
Tech team that has done nearly everything right on this side of its
Boston College fiasco, and nobody sits higher in the conference
than this absolutely resilient bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not Virginia. In fact, the Cavaliers are joining the
rest of us in wondering how Tech rose from oblivion Saturday at
Bobby Dodd Stadium to capture one of the wildest victories during
its 106 years.
</P>
<P>
   This made no sense. One moment, Tech was resembling the
loveliest of patsies along the way to going easily to Virginia. The
next, there were nearly 46,018 screamers tearing up the place with
the mightiest burst of glee around here over a football game since
... well, since Tech shocked Virginia by this same 41-38 score
eight years ago along the way to a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to say, because I've never felt this way in
my life,'' said Tech defensive tackle Nate Stimson, describing his
thoughts, those of his teammates and those of the many who ripped
down both goalposts and cheered deep into the gorgeous October
night.
</P>
<P>
   No way this should have happened. Virginia's Thomas Jones rushed
for 207 yards, mostly without resistance. When he wasn't making
Tech's defense look pathetic, everybody else on Virginia's offense
was. Quarterback Aaron Brooks completed pass after pass with only
air covering his receivers.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia finished with 600 yards overall to Tech's 370. And,
with many among Tech's homecoming crowd thinking of tipping out
during the third quarter for an early dinner, Virginia led 38-17.
</P>
<P>
   We're talking three touchdowns. That's what Tech needed during
the game's final 19 minutes, just to tie their seventh-ranked foes,
and Tech did better than that.
</P>
<P>
   Tech won, because this isn't the same Tech bunch that flinches
at the sight of a big opponent in a big game. Tech won, because
coach George O'Leary wouldn't let the Jackets quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very professional locker room at halftime,'' said
O'Leary, whose team not only trailed 31-17, but barely showed a
pulse outside of Rodney Williams' mighty foot on kickoffs and
punts. ``I just told them to concentrate on the three things that
we weren't doing in the first half. I was referring to effort,
enthusiasm and execution.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech eventually went three-for-three in those categories, and
then Tech won, because Tech has a group that doesn't want to quit.
Even after Jones tried to shove a dagger into the heart of the
Jackets' comeback thoughts with a 65-yard sprint to the end zone
for that 38-17 lead, Stimson foreshadowed great things to come for
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   On Virginia's next possession, Stimson sacked Brooks for a
6-yard loss on third-and-6. Then came Virginia's next possession,
when he forced Brooks into a fumble that Tech's Delaunta Cameron
scooped up and returned 34 yards to push the Jackets closer to
their miracle.
</P>
<P>
   They'll need another miracle next week, when sixth-ranked
Florida State comes to town.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
