<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3099 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      10-17 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY CRIME IS A HATE CRIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I'm not outraged because Matthew Shepard was a gay man who got
murdered.
</P>
<P>
   I don't understand the candlelight vigils or the pompous
political pronouncements or the sad-looking bunch of Hollywood
actors protesting on the Capitol steps because Shepard was a gay
man who got murdered.
</P>
<P>
   That only cheapens his death.
</P>
<P>
   Or the deaths of others.
</P>
<P>
   In the town where I live, 15-year-old Renelyn Simmons, a
cheerleader, and 16-year-old Andre Bradley, a football player, were
shot dead as they walked along 41st Drive on their way to a pizza
parlor.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not outraged because Renelyn was a cheerleader who got
murdered; or because Andre was a football player who got murdered;
or because they were teenagers who got murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Also here, Laura Munoz, a mother of six who'd suffered through
years of domestic abuse, was murdered one night after she tried to
escape from her own house but couldn't find room in a
battered-women's shelter.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not outraged because Munoz was a woman who got murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen local children died at the hands of their parents last
year. They'd done nothing but be born into the wrong families. They
could not have been more innocent.
</P>
<P>
   It's not what makes victims different that's important. It's
what makes them the same. It's the murder.
</P>
<P>
   Murder is the outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Any murder. All murders. &QL; 
ANOTHER KIND? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. House or Representatives decided to go out on a limb
and pass a ``non-binding'' resolution last week condemning the
brutal killing of Universityof Wyoming student Shepard as
``unacceptable and outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   As if the people we elect to run the country and write the laws
believe there is another kind of murder.
</P>
<P>
   One that is acceptable and not outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   After Matthew Shepard's death, President Bill Clinton said,
``Congress needs to pass our tough hate-crimes legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   As if there is no law to punish Shepard's alleged killers, who
sit in jail accused of murder.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that I don't believe in hate crimes; it's that I don't
believe in any ``other'' type of crime.
</P>
<P>
   In the age of political correctness, we've developed the idea
that killings can be typed and sorted, divided, subdivided and
arranged into tidy categories.
</P>
<P>
   Some, we declare, are more hateful than others, worse than
others. &QL; 
CAN IT BE LESS BAD? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But if it's worse that someone like Matthew Shepard is killed
because he was gay, then it must be less bad when someone like
Laura Munoz is killed because she was in an abusive relationship.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Ask anyone who knew her.
</P>
<P>
   Ask her family.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the families of any of the five other women across the
Valley who police say were murdered during a three-month period
this year by boyfriends or husbands.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the families of Renelyn Simmons and Andre Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Every murder is an outrage. Any excuse for it is outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   A person run over by a drunk driver is no less dead than a
person done in by a terrorist bomb.
</P>
<P>
   A person killed in a drive-by shooting is no less a victim than
one shot during a robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Or a person murdered over an insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   It would be no less a horror if Matthew Shepard died during a
convenience store robbery, or because he didn't belong to the right
gang, or because he accidently cut someone off on the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   Or because, like Robert ``Mike'' Poduch and Hans Hummel, he
chased a suspected shoplifter out of a Wal-Mart store.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if the killer hates gays, or hates not owning
a TV set, or hates his wife, or just hates the idea of getting
caught.
</P>
<P>
   It's not important to define a hate crime. It's only important
to hate crime. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981017.0269 </DOCNO>
