<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3107 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LECKIE-AZR &LR;      10-17 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LECKIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SYMINGTON AIDE GEORGE LECKIE DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 and AMY SVITAK  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Edward Leckie, former deputy chief of staff to then-Gov.
Fife Symington, and a key player in political and legal brouhahas
that preceded Symington's downfall, is dead at 57.
</P>
<P>
   Leckie, an outgoing businessman often accused of overreaching
and intrigue in connection with his government service, died at a
Paradise Valley home Thursday after a long battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   To the end, Leckie remained loyal to Symington, who left office
last year after being convicted of bank and wire fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was an extremely close friend and a highly valued
adviser,'' Symington said by phone from New Hampshire. ``He's been
a part of our family for years. Ann and I will miss him very
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Connelly, Leckie's lawyer, said Leckie's relationship
with Symington remained warm though they went through difficult
times together.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said he, too, was glad to have known Leckie.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Leckie was a gentleman and my friend,'' Connelly said.
``He knew what the word loyalty meant.''
</P>
<P>
   In May 1997, Connelly won an acquittal for Leckie on federal
charges that Leckie leaked confidential information to the late
John Yeoman, Symington's accountant, to rig a bid for a $1.5
million state contract.
</P>
<P>
   That contract, for a cost-cutting program called Project SLIM,
went to Yeoman's accounting firm, Coopers and Lybrand. Yeoman was
killed in a car crash shortly after he and Leckie were indicted in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The indictments of Leckie and Yeoman were seen as giving federal
prosecutors leverage to get them to testify against Symington, but
neither did. Connelly said the pressure on Leckie was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government wanted him to co-operate and point the finger
and he said `That's not me and there are no fingers to point,' ''
Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   Though Leckie was acquitted in the criminal case, he earlier had
agreed to pay a $25,000 settlement in the SLIM matter after an
Arizona Attorney General's Office investigation turned up evidence
that he and Yeoman had exchanged vital bidding information.
</P>
<P>
   Coopers and Lybrand, which agreed to pay the state a $725,000
settlement acknowledged ``a grave appearance of impropriety.''
However, neither the firm nor Leckie admitted wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Coopers later agreed to cooperate with federal prosecutors in
the Symington case, and to pay $2.275 million to end the
investigation into its role in the bid-rigging scandal as well as
its work for Symington's real estate business.
</P>
<P>
   Leckie was born Dec. 24, 1941, in Champaign, Ill., to Robert
Fulton Leckie and Olive Harriett Brunskill.
</P>
<P>
   In his resume, he listed himself as a 1963 graduate of MacMurray
College, Jacksonville, Ill., with a bachelor's degree in government
and economics.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he attended Vanderbilt University Law School for
two years, and graduated from the Loyola University Graduate School
of Business with an MBA in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   His business career took him around the country _ to
manufacturing companies in Chicago, Hollywood, Fla., Detroit, and
Mesa. He also owned businesses in Tucson and Clinton, Okla.
</P>
<P>
   And he served as president and trustee of Phoenix Country Day
School, trustee for Hospice of the Valley, and director of the Mesa
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But his business career had its ups and downs. When he went to
work as finance chairman for Symington's first campaign for
governor in 1989, Leckie's business enterprises had been ailing. In
a deposition taken that year in connection with a lawsuit involving
several of his businesses, Leckie said he hadn't had an operating
company or a job since 1987.
</P>
<P>
   After Symington won a runoff election in 1991, Leckie was
installed as his deputy chief of staff. In that position, he was
often the subject of controversy.
</P>
<P>
   He allowed the $3.4 million Governor's Office budget to run $1
million in the hole, forcing layoffs and belt-tightening to avoid a
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   He also improperly billed a state fund $1,336 for a Hawaiian
vacation with his girlfriend, paying the money back only after he
was called to account. And he listed himself as working when he was
on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The Project SLIM affair, which led to Leckie's indictment, put
Symington's administration under a cloud when rumbles about it
surfaced two years after Leckie left the administration in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   When Leckie left Symington's service, however, the governor
lauded the job he'd done, saying Leckie revitalized Project SLIM,
solved problems at the state Lottery, and contributed to economic
development efforts.
</P>
<P>
   After the resolution of the bid-rigging case against him, Leckie
worked as a business consultant.
</P>
<P>
   And he periodically appeared at Symington's trial last year on
fraud charges, offering Symington moral support. On Sept. 3, 1997,
Symington was convicted of multiple counts of bank and wire fraud
in connection with his real-estate development business. He is
appealing those convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew George as a very loyal friend of Fife's,'' said Terence
Lynam, an attorney for Symington. ``I remember how supportive he
was during the trial. Considering his own health situation and the
fact that he had gone through a trial himself, I thought it was
great that he was being so supportive of Fife. I thought he was a
wonderful guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynam recalled that Symington resigned immediately after the
verdict and had dinner that evening at his east Phoenix home with
family attorneys and a few friends, including Leckie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very tough evening, but George got up and toasted
Fife and Ann and said he was pleased to be their friend. It was
very warm and moving.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of his death, Leckie had been undergoing treatment
for a cancer that was found in his mouth and lymph nodes in 1996.
Shortly after that diagnosis, doctors removed part of his palate
and three upper lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of Leckie's, public relations man David Hans Schmidt,
said the cancer continued to spread throughout Leckie's body,
despite recent treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Leckie is survived by a daughter, Jeanne; a son, Bryce; a
brother, Jim; and a sister, Mary Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Services will be held at 3 p.m. Tuesday, at Saint Barnabas on
the Desert Church, 6715 N. Mockingbird Lane in Paradise Valley. &QL; 
 &UR; Republic writer Jerry Kammer contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
