<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISSING-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHONE CALL ENDS THE WAITING FOR MOM, GIRL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ribbon on the door Saturday was the color of mourning, no
longer the bright yellow of waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The ribbon's hue, and the family's mood, changed after
authorities confirmed their worst fears: that bones in the desert
had been identified as those of 28-year-old Tammy Meier.
</P>
<P>
   Her remains were spread over a quarter mile north of Phoenix,
intermingled with her daughter's. The remains of Chelsey Gragg, 9,
were identified last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the hard part,'' said Billie Gragg, Chelsey's
grandmother, ``changing our yellow hope ribbon to black.''
</P>
<P>
   The discovery crushed Gragg's father, Eddie Gragg, the
ex-husband of Meier, who had refused to the end to believe the pair
was dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had hope the whole time,'' said Gragg. ``Then we got the
phone call and it took that hope away.''
</P>
<P>
   Meier leaves behind three children. Bailey, 2, and Nick, 9, are
staying with the Gragg family. T.J., 7, lives with his father.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Gragg said Nick understands what happened to his mother
and sister. But she hasn't explained the murder to her youngest
grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   ``She used to ask a whole lot . . . `Where's Mommy?' And I had
to tell her Mom is at work. `Where's Chelsey?' `Chelsey's at
school.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nick broke down and cried when he was told that the bodies of
his mother and sister were found in the desert.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you remind him of it, he'll still cry,'' Billie Gragg said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you tell him your mother and sister are gone? How do
you make it easy?'' asked Eddie Gragg, as his son lounged barefoot
next to him on a bench. ``I'm trying to not have him left with the
anger feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   The mother and daughter disappeared Feb. 4 after a dentist's
appointment. Their van was found in a grocery store parking lot on
Feb. 11. And the family went on several search missions in the
desert surrounding Phoenix, at times following directions from a
psychic from Show Low.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand I was within five minutes of where they was. I
just didn't go far enough,'' said Irene Moody, Meier's mother, who
came out to Phoenix from Marshall, Mo., several times to search.
</P>
<P>
   A hunter last weekend discovered the remains just west of
Interstate 17 and New River Road. Authorities said they weren't
sure if the bodies had been buried or left in the open.
</P>
<P>
   Gragg said he at first thought Meier went out of town just to
get away for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``But time passed, and no phone call. She wouldn't have left
Bailey like that,'' he said, as Bailey stood at his knee eating
bologna out of a Tigger bowl. ``So we figured something was
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Meier moved to Phoenix with her family in 1986, her mother said.
The family moved back a few months later, but Meier wanted to stay
to finish high school.
</P>
<P>
   She met Eddie Gragg and had two children with him, which also
kept her in Phoenix, despite what her mother said were desperate
pleas to get Meier back to Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   She divorced Gragg in 1991 and had a string of boyfriends, most
of whom didn't get her mother's approval.
</P>
<P>
   The family was pointing fingers at a ex-boyfriend of Meier's who
is an ex-convict. The Maricopa County Sheriff's Office would only
say it has strong investigative leads, but would not name them.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 Maricopa County Sheriff's Office homicide detectives
and posse members combed the desert looking for additional remains
and evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``She planned on moving back to Missouri in March. But she
didn't make it to March,'' Moody said. ``We have a big enough home,
my husband and I, that we could have accommodated her and the four
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have been no problem.'' &QL; 
 &UR; Richard Ruelas can be reached at 444-8473 or at
richard.ruelas &LR; pni.com via
 &UR; e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
