<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOSTER INJURY COULD HAVE BEEN WORSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ UCLA freshman tailback DeShaun Foster is
expected to miss 2-3 weeks with a sprained medial collateral
ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had torn it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Foster suffered the injury with nine minutes left in the second
quarter. After catching a screen pass and running to the Oregon 8,
he was hit from the side by a Ducks defender. He grabbed the knee
immediately, then was helped to the sideline. He watched the second
half in street clothes, sitting on the training table with injured
receiver Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still had Keith (Brown) and Jermaine (Lewis), and I was
hoping they'd get the job done,'' Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown rushed for a career-high 101 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Foster will have an MRI on Monday to determine the extent of the
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the information I have now, I think he'll be out 2-3
weeks,'' said Dr. Gerald Finerman, UCLA's team physician.
</P>
<P>
   Miami stuff: UCLA and Miami will play at 11 a.m. (PST) on Dec.
5, the Bruins announced Saturday. The game will be televised by
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Drew and a prayer: If it seemed strange for a reserve
quarterback to play receiver with 22 seconds and 58 yards to go,
consider this: UCLA's Drew Bennett is 6-foot-5 and has a 38-inch
vertical jump. He can dunk a basketball any-which-way and is one of
the Bruins' best athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the coaches inserted Bennett into the ``Hail Mary''
lineup, and he practiced the play once.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm supposed to use my vertical to jump up and get it,'' he
said. ``But (the Ducks) didn't guard me. I was all by myself. I
didn't have to jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett caught Cade McNown's pass at the 4, but Chris Sailer
missed the ensuing field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Bouncing back: McNown's week started with a scathing headline in
the Daily Bruin: ``Bruins Win Despite McNone,'' a reference to his
10-of-24 performance against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It ended with 395 yards passing and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a little upset,'' offensive coordinator Al Borges said
of the criticism. ``But in the final analysis, he kept it in
perspective. He's learned to live with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in action: Defensive end Kenyon Coleman played his first
game since injuring his knee Sept. 19 against Houston, and he did
not miss a beat. He forced two fumbles, recovered one, and had one
tackle-for-loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw the ball on the ground and the crowd started cheering,
so I figured it was a fumble,'' he said of his second recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Cornerback Marques Anderson and linebacker
Brendan Ayanbadejo led the Bruins with eight tackles. Ayanbadejo
also had two sacks in overtime.... UCLA had a season-low three
penalties.... The Bruins are 12-0 when they score at least 40
points under coach Bob Toledo. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
