<HEADER>
A3120 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FORENSIC-AZR &LR;      10-17 1381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORENSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LANDFILL MAY GIVE UP VITAL CLUES IN MOM'S DEATH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDI VILLA  
 and RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cookie Jacobson's body could tell tales. Or it could be
unreadable.
</P>
<P>
   Even if investigators find her corpse under layers of trash at a
dump they plan to search, they may never be able to tell how she
died.
</P>
<P>
   Proving murder, forensic scientists say, will depend on whether
they find the right parts, and whether those parts haven't
decomposed too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on how much of her is left,'' said Dr. Laura
Fulginiti, a forensic anthropologist with the Maricopa County
Medical Examiner's Office.
</P>
<P>
   And though Jacobson's body might have tissue, only bones remain
of Chelsey Gragg, 9, and Tammy Meier, 28, whose skeletons were
found in the desert north of Phoenix last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, when you're dealing with skeletal remains, you
do have to have some sort of fracture to indicate some type of
trauma,'' said Sgt. Dave Trombi, of the Maricopa County Sheriff's
Office, speaking of the remains of the mother and daughter, who had
been missing eight months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there any other means of death, strangulation, or anything
that has to do with tissue, when you're down to skeletal remains,
that's difficult to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, in many cases, dead bodies can provide clues to a
person's demise, anthropologists say. Tissue and bones, even
partial ones, often can reveal if a person was shot, stabbed,
strangled or poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   And they can reveal whether trauma occurred before or after
death.
</P>
<P>
   In Jacobson's case, that means investigators may be able to
determine if injuries to the body were caused before or after
death.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobson's body will be far from an ideal case.
</P>
<P>
   Her body would likely have been crushed by garbage trucks,
rolled over as many as 400 times by bulldozers. If it is in the
landfill it has been amid rotting trash for more than a month.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobson, 49, disappeared Sept. 21, and police are convinced she
was killed by her son, Aaron, 16, and thrown in a garbage
container, which was then picked up and hauled to the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Jacobson told police that he found his mother dead in her
bed and, fearing he would be blamed for her death, he and his
sister, Laura, 13, disposed of the body. The siblings were arrested
and released Oct. 1 after prosecutors said there wasn't enough
evidence to hold them. &QL; 
BLOOD IN TRASH BIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Tempe police found blood in a recycling bin and a
garbage container behind the Jacobson home, and announced that they
would search the Butterfield Station Landfill, southeast of
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But ``in a month's time, you could lose a lot of tissue,'' said
Walter Birkby, director of the Human Remains Identification Unit in
Tucson. ``Whenever you're missing your soft tissue, that's when
you're going to wind up in trouble identifying a cause of death.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because knife and gunshot wounds don't always penetrate
into the bone, leaving most of their bruising evidence in the
tissue. Tissue is also where investigators would find evidence of
poisoning or a drug overdose, investigators say.
</P>
<P>
   Soft tissue decomposes first, said Dr. Charles Merbs, an
anthropologist at Arizona State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The better preserved, the better the chances of coming up with
evidence,'' Merbs said. ``If you don't have the soft tissue, you're
losing all the evidence that is only in the soft tissue.'' &QL; 
CRUSHED, RECRUSHED &QL; 
Assuming Jacobson's body is in the landfill, it was compacted in a
standard garbage truck carrying four to six tons of waste.
</P>
<P>
   Then, at a transfer station, it was crushed again and loaded
into a trailer hauling 25 tons to the landfill. At that point,
garbage has been squeezed to 70 percent of its original volume.
</P>
<P>
   At the landfill, 100,000 pound bulldozers with six-inch blunt
spikes on their wheels, roll over the garbage throughout the day.
At the end of the day, six inches of fresh dirt are placed over the
flattened garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Landfill officials have already cordoned off a 3,500-square-foot
area that's 13 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   After a month, the body could range from moderately decomposed
if it was buried deep enough to pretty skeletonized.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a dry place, sometimes the body is well-preserved,'' said
Dr. Henry Lee, forensic pathologist for the Connecticut State
Police, who testified in the O.J. Simpson trial. ``Sometimes, the
body is mummified if its really hot weather.''
</P>
<P>
   With tissue, gunshot or stab wounds could still be visible. Medi
cal examiners can also run tests to determine poison or drug
overdose.
</P>
<P>
   With only a skeleton, as in the Chelsey Gragg and Tammy Meier
case, the work is tougher. If only Jacobson's skeleton is found in
the dump, and the bones show injuries, investigators will have to
determine which injuries were caused by her killing and which by
the crushing bulldozers. &QL; 
MARKS FROM WEAPONS &QL; 
Sharp instruments, such as knives and hatchets, would leave very
distinctive marks in the bones, different from marks left by a
bulldozer or a trash compactor.
</P>
<P>
   However, distinguishing a blunt-force trauma from one inflicted
by a compactor would be more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much blunt force trauma that can be inflicted in
the landfill,'' Fulginiti said. ``You've got heavy trucks rolling
over them. You've got other garbage. You've got compacting.
</P>
<P>
   ``But bone reacts differently (to injury) if it's still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, when the body is injured, the body automatically
shoves blood towards the injury to help it heal. This causes
discoloration and bruising that won't be evident if the person is
already dead and the blood flow stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries that happen to the bones after death ``look very
white,'' Fulginiti said. The bones also become hard and brittle
after death.
</P>
<P>
   Fulginiti equates it to breaking a green stick versus breaking a
dry, dead stick. The dead stick will break in a distinctively more
jagged pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Even harder to determine will be if Jacobson died of suffocation
or strangulation, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Manual strangulation often causes blood vessels and capillaries
to rupture and can be detected in the ligatures of the neck.
Evidence also can be picked up from the eyes. However, this
evidence may also have been lost in decomposition, Birkby said.  &QL; 
`YOU HAVE TO BE LUCKY' &QL; 
Depending on how hard a person was strangled, there might be a
broken hyoid bone, located in the neck at the base of the tongue,
but Merbs said it would probably take a strong adult to break that
bone.
</P>
<P>
   Suffocation would be nearly impossible to prove, Merbs said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That wouldn't show any evidence at all unless you had a
complete, well-preserved body,'' he said. ``You have to be lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   And finding a completely intact body isn't likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, if a body is dismembered or chopped up, that's
another problem because it could be everywhere,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The skull, several experts say, would be one of the most
valuable pieces of evidence to find. This is because the head would
provide positive identification, and also it is the area most
likely to have sustained trauma in a murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's different if you find the skull and you have a bullet
hole in it,'' said Phoenix police Detective Mike McCullough. ``You
don't need a whole lot more. But the skeleton isn't always enough.
When you're unsure, the skeleton may not have everything you
need.''
</P>
<P>
   It's anybody's guess whether Jacobson's skull would have
survived the repeated crushing at the landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of it like an egg,'' Fulginiti said. ``It's really hard
to break an egg, except in certain ways. The skull is the same
way.'' &QL; 
TORSO IS VALUABLE &QL; 
The torso, including chest, thorax and abdomen, also would be
extremely valuable because experts could examine the ribs and the
vital organs. There might even be enough there to run toxicology
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Arms and legs are only helpful to determine if there was a
struggle, Fulginiti said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, finding anything in a landfill is ``sporadic,'' said
Fulginiti, who participated in the 1996 landfill search for the
body of a 13-year-old Ahwatukee boy. Brad Hansen was never found.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like luck of the draw,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
