<SLUG> BC-RAC-SANTAANITA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVER CHARM BEATS FREE HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA _ They ran the first mile of the Goodwood Handicap
together for old times' sake Saturday, Silver Charm and Free House
rarely separated by more than half a length, the two gray colts
reliving '97 Triple Crown memories as 20,000 fans at Santa Anita
roared their approval.
</P>
<P>
   Then sentiment took a back seat to cold-hearted thoroughbred
tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   In the space of a few strides on the turn for home in the
1[-mile race, Silver Charm put away his one-time rival and set his
sights on a new rival.
</P>
<P>
   His powerful, 2{-length victory, under a perfect ride by Gary
Stevens, not only settled the best-in-the-west debate but earned
Silver Charm a shot at Horse of the Year front-runner Skip Away in
the Breeders' Cup Classic at Churchill Downs on Nov.7.
</P>
<P>
   If Silver Charm beat Skip Away, whom he hasn't faced before, he
would get some votes for racing's top award.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll supplement to the Breeders' Cup,'' owner Bob Lewis
declared in the winner's circle, meaning he'll put up the $480,000
necessary to enter the Classic, whose $4 million base purse will
swell each time an unnominated horse like Silver Charm is entered.
``I wouldn't be so bold and pretentious as to say we're going to
win. But we're going to have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm was scheduled to fly to Kentucky this morning. It's
at Churchill Downs that he won the Kentucky Derby last year.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, Silver Charm and Free House were two very fast peas
in a pod, facing each other in six consecutive races from February
to June '97. Silver Charm won three, Free House two, and Touch Gold
beat them both in the Belmont Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   But they hadn't met in the 16 months since then, each missing
most of the rest of '97, each coming back to score major victories
in '98. Their reunion Saturday shaped up as the highlight of the
Oak Tree Racing Association season.
</P>
<P>
   Score Quick, an 11-1 shot in the six-horse Goodwood, tried to
upstage them and led most of the way. Stevens and Free House jockey
Chris McCarron fought a positional battle in second and third and
Stevens got the edge by angling Silver Charm to the outside in the
first turn.
</P>
<P>
   When Free House went for the lead, he was wedged between horses.
When Silver Charm attacked on the outside at the top of the
stretch, he was in the clear and home free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little surprised we got by Free House as easily as we
did,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   The final time, 1:47.21, made this the second-fastest Goodwood
of the '90s.
</P>
<P>
   Free House finished second, 2{ lengths in front of Score Quick.
</P>
<P>
   !arrow!The undercard:!off! Gold Land, rested for the past two
months, extended his vacation into the first half-mile of the
Ancient Title Handicap before accelerating from last place to a
three-quarter-length victory under Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   The victory, at 5-1 odds, probably will send the 7-year-old to
the $1 million Breeders' Cup Sprint, trainer Neil Drysdale said.
</P>
<P>
   The filly A.P. Assay, a stablemate of Free House, held on for
second. Favored Kona Gold finished fifth in the 6-furlong race,
timed in a fast 1:08.50.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Alex Solis won aboard High Drama and Secret Advice R. N
to become the 87th jockey to reach the 3,000 victories mark....
Solis rides Neil Drysdale-trained Hawksley Hill, a 6-5 morning-line
favorite, in the five-horse Oak Tree Mile on turf today....
Measuring the marquee value of Silver Charm and Free House: Santa
Anita attendance, 20,102, was up 30 percent from last year's
Goodwood, won by Benchmark.... Fourth-race winner Lexington Beach
collapsed and died while galloping out on the backstretch. As
always, a necropsy will be performed.
</P>
</TEXT>
