<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-17 23:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3125 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-     10-17 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BLOW A 2-GOAL LEAD BUT EARN A POINT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ The Pittsburgh Penguins may be bankrupt, but you've
got to give them a little credit. They are undefeated in three
games, the latest being a 3-3 tie with the Rangers Saturday night
in the Igloo.
</P>
<P>
   And the Penguins earned their point in the standing the hard
way, overcoming a two-goal deficit late in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rangers also earned their point while ending a four-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Playing their second game in two nights and their fifth in nine
nights, they fell behind by 3-2 early in the third period, but tied
it at 13:35 of the period on Todd Harvey's second goal of the
night.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh took the lead at 5 minutes 35 seconds of the third
period on a power-play goal by Kevin Hatcher. It was set up by
Jaromir Jagr, the third assist of the night for the Penguins
captain. Harvey scored on a rebound when the Rangers had a two-man
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey helped set up the game-tying goal by drawing a penalty
against Jiri Slegr, who chased him down the boards and elbowed him.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored the first goal of the game _ and took their
first lead of the season _ at 10:32 of the first period, when Todd
Harvey sent a rebound shot past Tom Barrasso, who made the initial
save on Adam Graves' high slap shot. Barrasso remained in the game
for about a minute after that, but then left with a strained groin
and was replaced by Peter Skudra.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey had been the Rangers best player in a 2-1 defeat in
Madison Square Garden against the Devils on Friday night. Obtained
from Dallas in a trade last season, Harvey is the ``heartbeat of
the team,'' according to Coach John Muckler, because he provides
the youthful vigor the Rangers have lacked for several seasons.
Back in the Rangers' lineup was the rookie center Manny Malhotra,
who was a healthy scratch Friday night. Mike Richter, who sat on
Friday in favor of Dan Cloutier, started Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins, who had a two-man advantage for 1:17 midway
through the first period, had an excellent chance to tie the score
with Jagr orchestrating the attack. But several shots were wide and
one hit the post.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a feud between their two co-owners and a recent
declaration of bankruptcy, the Penguins started the season 2-0 with
victories over the Islanders and the Devils. This, their third
game, was their home opener, and there were only a few empty seats
in the high rows.
</P>
<P>
   Not in a Penguin uniform for for the second consecutive season
is Petr Nedved, the center who remains a Group 2 free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, who once employed Nedved, are interested in him.
Neil Smith, president and general manager of the Rangers, has
discussed trading for Nedved several times in recent months with
Penguins General Manager Craig Patrick. However, Patrick said
Saturday that he did not expect any deal soon. Nedved is playing
with Las Vegas of the International Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers increased their lead to 2-0 on the power play at
4:50 of the second period when Wayne Gretzky, standing to the left
of Skudra, scored his first goal of the season. Key to the play was
Harvey, who took up space in the low slot and deflected a shot by
Brian Leetch.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after that goal, Kevin Stevens rammed Skudra, a
provocative tactic with Barrasso already injured. Skudra seemed
stunned for a moment by the collision, but soon righted himself and
continued.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins tied the score with two goals 85 seconds apart late
in the second period. Jagr assisted on both goals, the first of
which was scored by Patrick Lebeau at 16:36.Robert Lang scored the
second at 18:01.
</P>
<P>
   The defenseman Mathieu Schneider, playing in his second game as
a Ranger since his trade from Toronto, accidentally turned over the
puck creating a two-on-one involving Jagr, whose heavy wrist shot
was stopped by Richter but not controlled. Lebeau knocked in the
rebound.
</P>
<P>
   On the second goal, Hatcher blasted a long shot wide to the left
of the net that bounced of the end boards. Lang beat everyone to
the rebound on the right side of the net and put it in the net.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
