<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-OILERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH BRODEUR STRUGGLING, THE DEVILS FALTER AGAIN  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The last thing the punchless Devils need
now is for Martin Brodeur to allow soft goals.
</P>
<P>
   After winning their first game of the season Friday night
against the Rangers, the Devils returned home Saturday and fell to
the Edmonton Oilers, 4-2, before a crowd of 15,737 at Continental
Arena. It was the third loss in four games for New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Guerin, who was traded by the Devils to Edmonton last
season, scored two goals for the Oilers. Ryan Smyth and Andrei
Kovalenko had the other goals for the Oilers, while Petr Sykora
scored for the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to do well against your former team,'' said
Guerin, who was involved in a contract dispute with the Devils last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Guerin was jeered when he touched the puck early in the game,
but was booed with 1 minute 41 seconds left in the first period
when he picked up a rebound from a shot by Josef Beranek, waited
for Brodeur to commit, then beat the goalie with a rising shot for
his second goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes things get a little sour,'' Guerin said of his trade
to the Oilers, ``but this is the nature of the business. I had some
good times here, but I'm happy where I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   Guerin saw plenty of ice time. Playing right wing on a line with
Beranek and Kovalenko, Guerin used his speed and strength to cause
problems for the Devils. He has been made alternate captain by the
Oilers, and he said he was happy to be in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   With three forwards who didn't play in the victory over the
Rangers a night earlier, the Devils showed plenty of enthusiasm and
spank.
</P>
<P>
   With Brendan Morrison, Sergei Brylin and Vadim Sharifijanov, who
took the place of Dave Andreychuk, Bob Carpenter and Scott Daniels,
the Devils searched for goals from the outset.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils looked dangerous in the offensive zone and
capitalized on their first manpower advantage of the night, scoring
their first power-play goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After failing on seven advantages in the first three games, they
scored 6 minutes 52 seconds into the game. They probably didn't
care that Edmonton was 23nd in the league in killing penalties
coming into the game.
</P>
<P>
   Sykora scored the power-play goal when he beat Mikhail
Shtalenkov through the pads from the bottom of the left circle
after a pass from Denis Pederson, but the Oilers tied it behind
Guerin.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took more than twice as many shots as Edmonton (15-7)
in the second period, but it was the visitors who scored the only
goal to take the lead going into the third.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came at 5:07 from the stick of Smyth, who found himself
unattended at Brodeur's right door step for his first of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Brodeur, who allowed what appeared to be ``soft'' goals in the
losses to Chicago and Pittsburgh, had a clear view of the third
goal, scored by Kovalenko, 11:15 into the last period.
</P>
<P>
   Kovalenko's shot came from the high slot and hit Brodeur in the
chest before bouncing behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek said he was not concerned about Brodeur
having allowed three soft goals in four games. ``To me, every shot
on net is a good save,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
