<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON RETURNS TO MIDEAST SUMMIT IN MARYLAND  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ Trying to force the pace of a Middle East
agreement, President Clinton returned to Maryland's Eastern Shore
Saturday, meeting in turns with the Palestinian and Israeli
delegations sequestered here.
</P>
<P>
   Details were scarce, and so was official optimism. The two sides
were said to be biding their time on serious commitments, and
officials suggested that if the usual pattern of Middle Eastern
summit meetings holds, there will be tantrums, threatened walkouts
and finally, possibly, a breakthrough at the last minute.
</P>
<P>
   But the State Department spokesman, James Rubin, said in an
evening briefing that ``a lot has gone on, and the work has been
constructive.'' He said he expected talks with the leaders to go on
late into the night with special intensity after the Jewish Sabbath
ended at sundown and the Israeli delegation could resume normal
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The American plan, Rubin said, remained the same, with the idea
of reaching an agreement here by Sunday night, presumably with a
White House ceremony or announcement on Monday. But he did not rule
out an extension of the talks.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is an interim accord by which the Israelis will
withdraw from 13 percent more of the West Bank, in return for
specific, phased actions by the Palestinians to fight terrorism.
The land issue, after nearly 19 months of squabbling, is largely
agreed. But the specifics of Palestinian security cooperation _ and
how Palestinian efforts are judged sufficient by the Israelis, with
American mediation _ are intricate and unresolved, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   But the advantage of a secluded meeting like this one is that
concessions can be offered quietly without embarrassing the side
that makes them, American officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton came here by helicopter from Washington with his
national security adviser, Samuel Berger, and had lunch with the
American team, led by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and the
special envoy Dennis Ross, before they began an 80-minute
discussion with Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, and his
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton then telephoned the Egyptian president, Hosni Mubarak,
to bring him up to date on the talks, before beginning a similar
session with Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of Israel and his
advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin said that while the Israelis could not work normally
because of the Sabbath, it was possible to discuss important
questions. While they were doing so, some of the Palestinians
repaired to a mall of outlet shops here to pursue the offerings of
American discount capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the president, with ``a
strong reservoir of trust'' from both sides ``has a unique role
here to help both sides understand each side's position.'' Clinton
is expected to return here on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2318EDT &QL; 
