<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-PETTY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KING RICHARD TAKES STOCK  
 PETTY STILL WEARS THE CROWN IN THE KINGDOM OF NASCAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once a King always a King.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, six years after he last nestled into the cozy belly of
a stock car, ``King'' Richard Petty remains permanently atop the
NASCAR Winston Cup throne.
</P>
<P>
   The view is breathtaking. And, sometimes, bothersome.
</P>
<P>
   Petty retired following the 1992 season and now owns the
familiar blue and red STP Pontiac that John Andretti will drive in
next Sunday's Dura Lube 500 at Phoenix International Raceway. He
had this to say about NASCAR's season-long 50th Anniversary
celebration: ``We always thought (NASCAR) was a big deal because we
were part of it. But now that it has 50 years behind it, it has
some history where everybody can look at it being a pretty big
operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all started with nothing in a basket, kind of like starting
a farm with one acre. Then, every year you add an acre to the farm
and the first thing you know you have 50 acres. No one knew it
would get this big.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty on restrictor plate races, one of which was Saturday night
at Daytona International Speedway: ``The way I look at it, you got
40 (drivers) that all of a sudden have become good race car drivers
with a fast car. If you didn't have (the restrictor plates), cars
would be going 215 (mph instead of 195), but you'd have drivers
separating themselves from the crowd pretty dadgum quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (NASCAR) did it for safety, but all they did was cause
more trouble. I just don't like them, never liked to drive them and
don't even like to watch them. It's just sort of going out on the
interstate and watching 40 cars go by.''
</P>
<P>
   Petty on Jeff Gordon and Mark Martin dominating the circuit this
season: ``I've seen better racing, put it that way. You got too
many cars that are basically the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the competition is too good. When the competition gets too
good, you got a first place guy and a 20th place guy on the same
straightaway with you. That makes it stale. In order to have
racing, you've got to have somebody passing. That means you have to
have fast cars, medium cars and slow cars.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, NASCAR doesn't have that.
</P>
<P>
   What it does have is Jeff Gordon, Mark Martin and little else.
</P>
<P>
   In Petty's prime, however, all NASCAR seemingly had was Petty.
</P>
<P>
   Petty's 200 victories, 172 of which came during a 13-year span
between 1962-75, may be as unapproachable as Joe DiMaggio's 56-game
hitting streak or Wilt Chamberlain's 100-point game.
</P>
<P>
   Petty, 61, also won seven driving titles, a crown he shares with
Dale Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon may be the driver to one day surpass Petty's legendary
feats, but even NASCAR's present-day Sir Lancelot realizes no one
ever will dethrone the King.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's (Petty) been the one who set the standards for all of
us,'' Gordon said in a telephone interview. ``He set the standards
on the racetrack by his performance and off it by the way he
handles himself with the fans and the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that's sort of the benchmark I look at. It's what being
a NASCAR Winston Cup driver is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershel McGriff, 70, whose first NASCAR race was in 1950, said
the sanctioning body couldn't have hand picked a better
representative.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's important for NASCAR is having a really good image, not
like the NBA right now with their bickering and fighting,'' said
McGriff, who was Petty's driving teammate for a few races during
the 1970s. ``And Richard is probably more responsible for that than
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a big booster for NASCAR. He's signed
thousands and thousands of autographs, and always has had time for
the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually everyone ever associated with the sport has a kind
word to reflect upon Petty, whose father, Lee, ranks No. 7 on the
all-time winning list with 55, and son, Kyle, has eight career
victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's contributed more to the sport than any other
individual,'' said retired driver Junior Johnson, chosen by
``Sports'' ``Illustrated'' the top driver in NASCAR history. ``And
even though he's been one of the highest people ever in the history
of racing, he's never let his attitude get out of hand. He's given
to the sport a lot more than he's took from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ditto Bill Elliott, a 12-time winner of NASCAR's Most Popular
Driver award.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes, when it gets a little hard for me to deal with
people, I think of how Richard would act in the same situation,''
Elliott said. ``He's been a role model for every driver, sponsor
and for NASCAR.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what you would expect from a King. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-17-98 2320EDT &QL; 
