r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-AZR &LR;      10-17 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-DAFOE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES LEERY OF BRUINS' DAFOE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - ``Da foe'' for the Phoenix Coyotes Monday night at
America West Arena is ``Lord Byron,'' and don't think for a moment
the Coyotes aren't aware of it.
</P>
<P>
   Bad puns aside, the man in question is actually Byron Dafoe, the
27-year-old Boston Bruins goalie who made a big name for himself in
the NHL last season. Twice he had the Coyotes eating out of his
hand, posting a 3-2 overtime win in Phoenix and a 5-2 victory at
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very good goalie,'' Coyotes goaltending coach Benoit
Allaire says. ``He's very quick and he's tough on the second and
third shots. He always keeps himself between the puck and the net
and he never gives up.''
</P>
<P>
   That assessment comes as no big surprise for fans of the former
Phoenix Roadrunners of the International Hockey League. Dafoe has
long been big in their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   In a 49-game stay with the Roadrunners during the 1994-95
season, Dafoe set franchise records for wins, minutes and shutouts,
as he posted a 25-16-6 record while on loan from the Washington
Capitals organization.
</P>
<P>
   So popular was the 5-foot-11, 190-pound netminder, that he was
afforded the rarest of honors any minor-league player can receive _
his own official fan club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always enjoy coming back to Phoenix,'' Dafoe said Saturday,
a day after suffering his first defeat, a 2-1 setback to the Los
Angeles Kings in overtime. ``I still have a lot of friends and
great memories there. I'll still probably have some fans who will
be pulling for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I own a house there, and it's the city where I plan on
retiring.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dafoe was on loan to Phoenix, the brain trust of the Los
Angeles Kings, the Roadrunners' NHL affiliate, were so impressed
with him that they packaged Alexander Volchkov and Justin Davis to
trade for him and Dimitri Khristich.
</P>
<P>
   He had two solid years as a part-time starter for the Kings
before he and Khristich were sent to Boston for Jozef Stumpel,
Sandy Moger and a fourth-round draft pick just weeks before the
season started last year.
</P>
<P>
   It was only fitting that his 100th career victory came in the
overtime win in Phoenix last season.
</P>
<P>
   Just as his performances with the Roadrunners made him a wanted
commodity, that win helped propel him to a season record of
30-25-9. He became the first Bruins' goalie since Jon Casey to win
30 games (1993-94) and his six shutouts were the most since famed
backstop Pete Peeters had eight in 1982-83.
</P>
<P>
   His 2.24 goals-against average was the best he's posted at any
level of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, (last season) didn't come as that big of a surprise to me
because I always thought I had it in me,'' said Dafoe, who is 2-1-1
with two shutouts entering tonight's game at San Jose. ``I had a
couple of good years in Los Angeles, but I'd start four or five
games and then I'd go to the bench and be forgotten about for
awhile.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bruins Coach) Pat Burns came in last year and gave me a
chance to play. He played me for four or five games early and I did
pretty well, so he stayed with me. It was really the first time in
the NHL that I've been the main guy and I worked hard to keep it.
His faith in me really helped my confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns' close to the vest defensive style received most of the
credit for the Bruins' rebound from a 26-47-9 season two years ago
to make the playoffs last season, where they exited in six
first-round games to eventual Stanley Cup finalist Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk, however, said he believes it's
Dafoe who deserves most of the credit for the Bruins turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston as a whole had a great year, but it all starts with
your goaltender,'' Tkachuk said. ``Him stepping up and already
having back-to-back shutouts this year just shows how much he has
become their main guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had an unbelievable year. He's just tough to beat. He's so
quick. I'm glad we don't play him more often. We knew he was good
from Los Angeles, but it was a big jump for him. He got a chance to
start and just turned it up another level. He was their MVP last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   No Coyote better knows Dafoe's value to the Bruins than center
Mike Sullivan, who played for Boston last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just terrific for us,'' Sullivan said. ``He's a guy who
really works hard and makes a lot of second-effort saves. Some guys
think they have him beat, or he seems to be down and out, and
somehow he gets a glove or a pad on the puck for a second or third
save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because he played so well he gave our team that much more
confidence and he's certainly a big part of the Bruins right now.''
</P>
<P>
   While Dafoe's 1.97 goals-against average against Phoenix last
season suggests differently, he said he is bringing a healthy
respect into Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phoenix is a very talented team with guys like Tkachuk,
(Jeremy) Roenick, (Greg) Adams and (Rick) Tocchet,'' he said.
``We're going to have to play a conservative style because we can't
run and gun with them because they probably have more guns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll play tight defensively and take care of the
puck against them.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
