<SLUG> BC-BBM-FALL-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALL LEAGUE OFFERS BIG NAMES TO LURE FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Last week wasn't the greatest for  &UR; Steve Cobb,
executive vice-president of the Fall League.
</P>
<P>
   He picked up a case of food poisoning, and while attempting to,
uh, alleviate the condition, passed out in his bathroom. He smacked
into a door and wound up with 11 stitches in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks I got into a fight with  &UR; Mike Tyson,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he suffered a recurrence of the problem, but it was
nothing a bottle of Mylanta couldn't cure.
</P>
<P>
   He also felt better because of a big turnout at HoHoKam Park on
Friday night. The United Way of Mesa bought and distributed most of
the tickets, and former Chicago Cubs star  &UR; Ryne Sandberg was there
autographing baseballs. The crowd of 2,241 was the Fall League's
largest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So far, attendance averages 340 a game. Not great, but better
than last year. Cobb is encouraged about a promotional campaign
that brings Diamondbacks and Hall of Famers (present and future) to
the ballparks to sign some baseballs and generally be a presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to pick certain games and make them special
events,'' he said. ``We try to increase (the crowds on) those
nights rather than worry what we're going to do on Tuesday
afternoon at 1 o'clock. Frankly, I'm not sure what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks such as  &UR; Andy Benes and  &UR; Matt Williams have
participated in Wednesday night games. The roster of Hall of Famers
who have come out for Saturday night games includes  &UR; Bob Gibson and
 &UR; Lou Brock, with many more scheduled. Among them are  &UR; Tom Seaver,
Jim Palmer, Gaylord
 &UR; Perry, Joe Morgan, Brooks Robinson, Rod Carew, Don Sutton and
 &UR; Robin
 &UR; Yount.
</P>
<P>
   Future Hall of Famer (and Diamondbacks pitcher?)  &UR; Randy Johnson
was just added to the list. He's scheduled to sign autographs at a
playoff game Nov. 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fly them in, and not one player has received compensation,
nor asked for it,'' said Cobb, who credits the work of Director of
Baseball Operations  &UR; Frank Robinson, a Hall of Famer himself, for
making it happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to fill the stadiums, we realize that,'' Cobb
said. ``We're trying to take a special-event approach and build up
20 or 30 of the games. We're also offering name-recognition. While
we have good players, people don't know who they are. One year ago
exactly, if you said the name,  &UR; David Dellucci, what would it mean?
One year later, you say David Dellucci, you have a lot of females
saying, `Where?' '' &QL; 
New Scorpion &QL; 
The decision to add  &UR; Julius Matos to the Diamondbacks contingent on
the Scottsdale Scorpions, replacing the injured  &UR; Danny Klassen,
wasn't that difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Like Klassen, Matos is a shortstop. And he's good. Matos was the
only position player from the Class-A High Desert club to make the
postseason California League All-Star team (pitcher  &UR; Brad Penny
also was selected).
</P>
<P>
   Purchased from Sioux City of the independent Northern League in
1997, Matos, 23, hit .301 with 19 stolen bases last season. He was
a 16th-round draft pick of the Cleveland Indians in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a nice year in High Desert, and he's somebody we think
will benefit from this level of competition,'' Diamondbacks General
Manager  &UR; Joe Garagiola Jr. said. ``It's also a chance to find out a
little more about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks seem to have an abundance of proven and
promising middle infielders. There are  &UR; Jay Bell and  &UR; Tony Batista
with the big club, plus Klassen,  &UR; Junior Spivey and Matos. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
