<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PITY THE PENGUINS, NOT THEIR OWNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Rick Tocchet remembers the good times. In a lot of ways, they
were some of the best moments of his hockey career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the Stanley Cup,'' the Coyotes veteran forward said,
``isn't something you forget.''
</P>
<P>
   But oh, how far the mighty have fallen. The Pittsburgh Penguins,
whom Tocchet helped lead to the second of back-to-back
championships in 1991-92, have gone from the glory years to the
sorry years faster than the pet-rock fad of the '70s fell out of
style.
</P>
<P>
   Bellbottoms, platform shoes and (gulp) even disco have made a
recovery, but the once-proud Penguins might never be able to make
it back after the incredible financial mess brought on by unethical
co-owners  &UR; Howard Baldwin and  &UR; Roger Marino, who might be the two
biggest frauds in the history of the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Their incompetence, lack of foresight, and incredible string of
bad business deals have led the franchise to complete shame and
shambles. They owe money _ millions of dollars _ to hundreds of
people and the line of lawsuits stacked against them is longer than
the lines outside the ticket office at the Civic Arena. The city
has sued them. The county has sued them. Television networks have
sued them. Duped investors have sued them.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, it finally caught up to them. Baldwin and Marino, who
have been feuding over control of the club, jointly agreed to file
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy. And NHL Commissioner  &UR; Gary Bettman let
them. How pathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real disheartening to me,'' Tocchet said. ``Just the
other day, (teammate)  &UR; Mike Sullivan was asking me where my
favorite place to play was and I told him Pittsburgh. Not just
because I won a Cup there. But because it's a great hockey town. To
think all this crap has happened, that there's a possibility they
might even move, I just can't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bettman and the league were strong, Baldwin and Marino would
be stripped of their ownership, and the NHL would step in
immediately and operate the franchise until a suitable owner could
be found, which wouldn't take long.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin and Marino, who claim they have lost $37 million the
past two seasons, don't just owe retired superstar  &UR; Mario Lemieux
$28 million in back pay. According to sources, they also owe  &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Stevens, who hasn't played for the Pens since 1995, an estimated
$600,000. What's more, Marino borrowed $2.5 million just so the
team could meet payroll on Thursday and pay its players. &QL; 
Just curious, but what person in his right mind would give that
kind of a loan to a guy who filed for bankruptcy just 48 hours
earlier? Bettman, maybe?
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin and Marino, despite their dishonesty and shady deals,
are probably going to get away with running this franchise into the
ground. If they get their wish, they'll get a new arena built, soak
more investors for all they're worth, and be absolved of most of
their debts. What a travesty, should that be the case.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble in Tampa &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The truth behind the firings last week of Tampa Bay Lightning
General Manager  &UR; Phil Esposito and his brother, assistant  &UR; Tony
 &UR; Esposito, really had nothing to do with on-ice performance from the
Dead Bolts.
</P>
<P>
   Quite frankly, new Owner  &UR; Art Williams didn't like the Esposito
brothers' work ethic and he was livid that Phil was already $5
million over budget. The team's payroll now stands at $33 million,
among the top-third in the league. Williams also sought the advice
of other executives around the NHL. The prevailing response was to
get rid of the Espo boys and move on.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Jaques Demers, who already had been promoted to director
of player personnel, will run the show on his own until a new
management type can be found. There is speculation that  &UR; Jack
Ferreira, the vice president of hockey operations for the Mighty
Ducks of Anaheim, will be offered the assistant GM job.
</P>
<P>
   Though many in the NHL didn't find the Esposito firings a huge
surprise, the timing of it _ just two games into the regular season
_ is a bit of shock. Williams, though, indicated there's never a
bad time to correct a bad situation. Translation: He waited until
Phil finalized the rest of the player contracts, including that of
rookie
 &UR; Vincent Lecavalier, the No. 1 overall draft pick.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, Phil Esposito said he would have glady accepted a
lesser role to remain with the organization. Williams wouldn't
offer him one, prefering to make a clean break and start over. &QL; 
Told you so
</P>
<P>
   Remember last week's item about tough-as-nails new Coach  &UR; Dirk
Graham in Chicago? Well, it only took a couple of losses for the
former Blackhawk to start cracking the whip. And he wasn't afraid
to snap it at a few of the club's veterans.
</P>
<P>
   After getting flattened by Dallas and Anaheim, Graham threatened
to make wholesale changes and even suggested he might bench a star
player or two. ``Certainly from some of the guys, I haven't liked
what I've seen,'' he said. ``I think we're at a stage where we need
to make some decisions.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at 602-444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
