<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO? POS? CHOICES SPELL CONFUSION FOR EMPLOYEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAX JARMAN AND JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Across the state, Arizonans are studying materials perplexing
enough to give even scholars a headache: their employee benefits
packets.
</P>
<P>
   Which health plan to select from an alphabet soup of
possibilities: HMO, PPO, POS? Which insurer to choose? What happens
if you are given only one choice?
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time for many of the 1.2 million Arizonans covered by
HMOs to do their health-care homework as their employers offer the
annual chance to change benefits or choose new plans.
</P>
<P>
   Considering managed-care's turbulence over the last year,
enrollees have plenty of brain-busting subjects to consider when it
comes to picking a plan:
</P>
<P>
   Math: What's worth more _ lower premiums or more choice?
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in several years, enrollees are bracing
themselves for double-digit premium increases. The trade-off, say
experts, is that there are more choices available as employers
offer less restrictive programs, such as point-of-service and
preferred provider plans, which allow enrollees to go outside their
plan's network of physicians, although at greater cost.
</P>
<P>
   Geography: Where's my doctor? Mergers, contract disputes and
financial fallout have made health-care delivery as complicated as
Balkan politics. With more pressure by employers to offer a wider
variety of care at a lower cost, look for even more upheaval,
analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Political science: Which candidate is right? HMO reform is a
1998 campaign hot button in state and national elections.
</P>
<P>
   As Arizonans select plans, they are hearing advertising
campaigns with horror stories of people denied life-saving
procedures by pencil-pushing insurance adjusters.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, the state Insurance Department has a
grievance plan so people can complain about plans' arbitrary
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it may be home economics that is the most
important subject when it's time to choose, said Mary Rybka, owner
of MR Consultants, a Mesa business that helps people figure out and
fight their health-care bills.
</P>
<P>
   It's essential that people understand their own health-care
situation and how the fine-print insurance rules affect them, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're younger, look at how it covers pregnancy. If your
child is older, you should think about emergency-room visits. What
does the book say about this?''
</P>
<P>
   Rybka suggests people take yellow highlighting pens to their 12-
to 15-page benefits book and dissect them. A dictionary may come in
handy as well, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the terminology is very sophisticated. I just had a
client whose ER visits are covered only if they are `emergent.'
What the heck does `emergent' mean?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, what seems like an emergency at the time may not end
up being one. It's important to know how they (the plans) handle
that. How do they define emergent?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patients also need to consider future needs as well, said Dr.
Michelle May, an Ahwatukee physician and president of the Arizona
Academy of Family Physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people think since there is no medical crisis going on in
their lives and they only see the doctor once a year, they may as
well save a few bucks,'' May said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then something happens and they are unhappy to learn that
there are restrictions on who they see and what drugs they get.
They perceive the doctors as restricting their care, when it's
actually their choice of plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are sick, that is the last stress that you want to
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Patients already living with chronic conditions also need to
delve into the details, said Sunny Carpenter, director of program
operations for the National Multiple Sclerosis Society.
</P>
<P>
   MS patients frequently complain to Carpenter that their plan
will take them but not cover their condition, labelling it
pre-existing. Or they will deny treatment for as long as a year
after they enroll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Another question is if they will pay for the current
treatments on the market. These are big deals, costing $15,000 a
year,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But there are certain things plans must have.
</P>
<P>
   If a plan brags about offering yearly mammograms for women 50
years and older or paying for 48-hour maternity stays for vaginal
deliveries, don't be overwhelmed _ state statute requires them to
do that, said Vista Brown, state Insurance Department spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   More and more, however, plans are going beyond the basics.
</P>
<P>
   Employers who want to keep and attract workers are asking
insurers for more variety, said Gay Ann Williams, executive
director of the Arizona Association of Health Maintenance
Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   That means HMOs are now compelled to add services at a time
while they are struggling to think of additional cost-cutting
measures, creating an uneasy mixture of higher rates and increased
competition. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Industry instability could trigger additional mergers and
acquisitions, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona consumers already have seen a revolving door of changes:
</P>
<P>
   Locally owned HealthPartners Health Plans this year was bought
by Minneapolis-based United HealthCare, a relative newcomer to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   FHP Health Care was sold last year to Pacificare of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Intergroup of Arizona was bought by California's Foundation
Health Corp. in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   There may be even more changes from the fallout from the July
bankruptcy of San Diego-based FPA Medical Management Inc., which
acted as an intermediary between doctors and HMOs such as
Intergroup and Pacificare.
</P>
<P>
   FPA's bankruptcy left more than 300 doctors holding the bag for
millions of dollars in services they provided and were never paid
for. It also rocked the 187,000 patients who received care from
doctors and staff at Thomas-Davis Medical Clinics operated by FPA.
</P>
<P>
   All this instability means that you may not end up with the
insurer or doctor you signed up with in the beginning, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   It also indicates the importance of also doing your homework on
your potential insurer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowing what I know, it's just hell behind the scenes when
they do those mergers,'' Rybka said. ``People are a lot better off
avoiding being in the middle of that and going with someone who is
stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Carpenter of the MS society tells her clients to ask their
current insurers about their prospective insurer's financial
health.
</P>
<P>
   May suggests getting a doctor's opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some physicians will not sign up with the plans because they
pay so poorly and in the end that has to impede good care,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other times, the plans are just not accepting new physicians.
Patients need to ask to find what they are getting themselves
into.''
</P>
<P>
   May argues that one of the first things an enrollee should
consider is who will be their doctor under the proposed plan.
</P>
<P>
   Although studies have shown that patients will change their
physicians to save $5 on a co-pay, they may regret that when they
try to get extra services, May said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patient needs to understand that the trade-off for lower
costs for themselves and their employers is some restriction on
access.''
</P>
<P>
   As family physicians have greater say-so on whether their
patients see specialists or get certain prescriptions, it's
important to have doctors that you trust, May said.
</P>
<P>
   During this campaign year, politicians as well as physicians are
talking as much about managed care.
</P>
<P>
   As Congress debates measures to rein in managed care, Democratic
gubernatorial candidate Paul Johnson has tried to make HMO reform a
campaign issue, saying HMOs should be held accountable for
decisions that kill or injure patients; offer greater accessibility
to specialists; and protect doctors who report quality problems.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull's campaign has said that there may be a general
sense of dissatisfaction with managed care, but that the state has
a system in place to protect patients, including a new state law
that allows people who have claims or services denied by their HMOs
to go through an informal review. If the matter isn't resolved,
they go through a formal appeal. If necessary, they then can have
the case reviewed by a doctor with the state Insurance Department.
</P>
<P>
   Rybka, who works with health-care consumers daily, is taking a
wait-and-see attitude on the new grievance plan.
</P>
<P>
   She does strongly suggest that people brush up on their civics
and complain to their state legislators if they aren't getting
proper care.
</P>
<P>
   But when they select a managed care plan, what they may need the
most is a crash course in assertiveness, Rybka said.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, one of her clients was told by her HMO that her
headache medicine was covered. When she tried to fill the
prescription, however, she was denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took her three months of pushing but she got what she
needed,'' Rybka said. ``You've just go to learn to push for
things.'' &QL;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
