<SLUG> BC-DAILYLIFE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS THAT LITTLE PRESSURES ADD UP IN DAILY LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MAUREEN WEST  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Researchers are providing the first wide-angle view of America's
daily rat race, and you're likely to spot yourself in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The most common causes of stress aren't muggings, traffic
tickets or money woes, but the little things that add up each day:
burning dinners, hunting for parking spaces, running late, dealing
with rude neighbors. And a lot of the strain comes from the very
same people who enrich our lives _ friends, relatives, children,
co-workers and spouses.
</P>
<P>
   Called the National Study of Daily Experiences, the project's
11,000 telephone interviews with 1,500 people in 48 states _ mostly
people at midlife _ chronicle loss, danger, disappointment and
frustration, along with simple pleasures and unselfish service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The daily lives that Americans endure are disturbingly
stressful,'' said David Almeida, 34, the lead investigator and an
assistant professor of family studies at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if you're a graduate student trying to juggle
studies with a social life, a parent shuttling kids between school
and soccer games or an executive dealing with an unruly staff;
stress affects practically everyone. Only 8 percent in the Daily
Experiences study said they didn't experience stress.
</P>
<P>
   To better understand life in the '90s, researchers called the
same people for eight consecutive days and asked them about their
routines and the stresses they experienced.
</P>
<P>
   The results: The top two sources of stress involved arguments or
tensions with others at work or home. Together they made up more
than 16 percent of the reported stresses. Worrying about someone
else's health was third, followed by work overload _ not having
enough time at work or home.
</P>
<P>
   Being concerned about relatives or friends in trouble was fifth
in line as a major stress.
</P>
<P>
   Money, stress No. 6, didn't rank as high as many might expect,
perhaps because a strong economy prevailed during the survey
period.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the eight days, many people, having grown used to
a daily telephone call from someone who was interested in their
problems, expressed sadness that the calls would stop.
</P>
<P>
   According to Almeida, they didn't have anyone call them up every
night to talk about job promotions, changing relationships,
computers crashing, or partners who wanted too much or too little
sex.
</P>
<P>
   That unexpected response made Almeida and other researchers
realize the profound isolation many people feel in today's culture.
</P>
<P>
   The study of daily stress is part of a larger National Survey of
Midlife in the United States, which is focusing on people ages 40
to 60. Midlifers are being studied because far less is known about
them than seniors and children. People as young as 25 and as old as
74 also were included for comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding more about the everyday tensions of life is
important, Almeida said, because of their frequency daily stresses
are thought to affect physical and psychological health as much as
big events such as a divorce or the death of a spouse.
</P>
<P>
   The findings have implications for future public policies,
workplace decisions, health programs and family counseling.
</P>
<P>
   We experience tension at home, at work, even in our cars, said
Almeida, who lives close to the UA campus so he can walk to the
office.
</P>
<P>
   About 9 percent of reported stressful events happen in
automobiles, from not being able to find a parking spot to a family
pet falling out. Drivers get lost, get to work late, get stuck in
traffic and have angry run-ins with other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The study found direct connections between stress and health. On
days when people reported having significant daily stress they were
two or three times more likely to report stomach pains, headaches
or muscle pains.
</P>
<P>
   Even though being connected _ having a stable social life _ is a
sign of health, the study confirmed that women have different daily
lives than men.
</P>
<P>
   Women are more distressed by a son or daughter having a bad day
at school, a sister stuck in a bad relationship or a friend having
a tough time at work. Men are more affected by work stresses, such
as overload or pending deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   It feeds the stereotypes of women being nurturers and men being
providers, Almeida said. But it also could be that men aren't
reporting someone else's problems as their stress.
</P>
<P>
   The frequency of daily stress declines as people get older.
Women ages 35 to 45 had stressful days 50 percent of the time. By
age 60, women report daily stresses on 30 percent of the days.
</P>
<P>
   Men's peak stress years are between 25 and 34, when they report
almost half of their days as being stressful. By age 60, it's only
about one in five.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the interview period, people were asked how they
viewed the stresses of the week.
</P>
<P>
   Younger and older people had the same number of days when they
were feeling sad, angry or agitated. But young people were more
likely to say the whole week was stressful, while older people
tended to give credit to the good moments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is part of the wisdom of growing older _ part of
maturing,'' Almeida said. ``We eventually learn to deal with
irritations and put them in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   For many people, relationships aren't working or aren't there.
Single people talked about beginning new relationships or resuming
old ones. They described difficult first dates, breaking dates and
being dumped or stood up.
</P>
<P>
   They talked about the compromises: ``We're getting married, and
he's arguing about the amount of money for the honeymoon,'' said
one bride-to-be. ``I had to call a travel agent to try to find
something cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   Another woman allowed researchers to interview her throughout
the stressful week before the wedding. In the last phone
conversation, the researcher could hear the band playing at the
reception in the background as the new bride reported on the flood
of little problems that describe a modern wedding.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding is just the beginning. Married couples said the
stresses of their schedules don't give them enough time with each
other, and they described a lack of truthfulness and mutual
respect, an uneven division of responsibility for cleaning the
house, and stresses arising from political, religious and
philosophical differences.
</P>
<P>
   Separations, breakups and divorces sometimes swept over the
normal daily stresses.
</P>
<P>
   A man talked about the stress of trying to understand his wife's
decision to proceed with a divorce: ``She just wants a single life.
That's what I am hearing so far. I'm trying to rationalize that
there is something I did, but she says nothing. That's stressful.''
</P>
<P>
   Several families on vacation took part in the study by calling
an 800 number, confirming that vacations often are more stressful
than working, especially for young families with children. Almost
every day on the road included some major conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Frictions and jealousies, even among friends, were in the daily
reports. A woman, proud to have received an award for her volunteer
work, said that an envious friend tried to downplay it by saying it
was no big deal and that she knew of somebody else who had
volunteered for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first instinct was to get angry and lash out, but it's not
worth it,'' she said, proud that she had managed to control her
emotions. ``This lady is just that way.''
</P>
<P>
   School and work present major stresses. Parents worry about
getting their kids into college, and adult students worried about
how to balance class demands with other needs of life. At work, the
computerized cubicle office is seen as a life-numbing assembly
line, sometimes full of boredom and conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women talked about the problems associated with changes
in their workplaces, often described as unfair overwork. They
talked about starting new jobs, quitting, demotion, dismissal and
downsizing. Stress came from missed deadlines, boredom, lack of
challenge and relentless interruptions.
</P>
<P>
   Said one man: ``It seemed like everybody all day today had
questions. I hardly had 10 minutes to think before somebody would
come in with another question.''
</P>
<P>
   Some complained about computers crashing, work vehicles breaking
down, threats of eviction, hassles of moving and problems with rude
neighbors. They complained about not accomplishing enough at home,
work or school.
</P>
<P>
   With more people working at home now, the line between home
stress and work stress is fuzzier, Almeida said. For home office
workers, the problems of home can no longer be escaped for nine
hours in the middle of the day, and work problems can't be avoided
after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A suicide attempt, a major accident, a heart attack, a daughter
having an abortion were in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   But the news isn't all bad.
</P>
<P>
   To the daily interview question ``Did you help anybody out
today?'' came answers that describe Americans as a generous people.
In general, older people give money, midlifers give emotional
support, and young people give practical, hands-on help.
</P>
<P>
   Interview subjects also shared the good moments, especially
where they felt appreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent about an hour with my wife discussing her yearly
review at work, including how she's going to approach some of the
problems she has to deal with,'' one midlife husband said. ``It
makes me feel good that she values my opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   And to the question ``Were you productive today at work and at
home?'' came surprisingly positive answers. A day that one person
might find anxiety-ridden might stimulate another person.
</P>
<P>
   One mother, for example, described an incredibly busy day of
opening and closing her store and running her children and assorted
other people all over town, only to conclude that, ``I feel good
about myself for being able to get it all done today.''
</P>
<P>
   The information from the interviews is so rich and complex that
Almeida says he will be mining it for several years in research
papers and possibly a book. The results may suggest additional
lines of research that will be useful to sociologists,
psychologists, business planners and others.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, it will help counselors, ministers and others
identify people who may be at risk for stress that could be
damaging to their health, Almeida said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our stresses are self-imposed, but others are from
survival,'' Almeida said. Some causes are genetic; others depend on
how much money you make or how old you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't make intelligent changes in our lives unless we can
objectively see what's going on,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot more to learn, he said, and he is just beginning
to look deeper and share his findings.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web site for the UA family studies home page, Almeida
chose a photo of himself cruising a sidewalk on a skateboard.
Putting a little more fun in your day and organizing your life away
from cars and commuting are among the important lessons he has
learned from listening to 1,500 people's daily stresses. &QL; 
 &UR; Maureen West can be reached at 444-8167 or at maureen.west &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
